1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. Nh3 Nf6 7. Nf4 Nbd7 8. c3 Qc7 9. h4 {This is the main move with the idea to provoke a kingside weakening using pressure on the b1-h7 diagonal.} O-O-O $5 {This interesting move gained popularity in GM-level play in 2017. The idea is to gain some useful kingside space with ...h4 after White castles short. Also the normal g3 is discouraged as it can be met by ...h4.} (9... e5 10. dxe5 Qxe5+ 11. Qe2 Bc5 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. Bf4 Qxe2+ 14. Bxe2) 10. h5 e5 11. Nh3 (11. hxg6 exf4 12. Ne2 fxg6 13. Bxf4 Bd6 14. Qd2 Bxf4 15. Qxf4 Qa5 16. a3 Qa4) (11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Qb3 Nd3+) 11... Be4 $132 {Black will follow with ...e6 and advance the queenside pawns.} 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bd3 Nef6 14. O-O exd4 15. cxd4 h6 (15... Nd5 16. Qf3 N7f6 17. Ng5 Kb8) 16. Qf3 Nb6 17. Be3 Nbd5 $11 {The position is approximately equal.} 18. a3 Bd6 19. b4 Kb8 20. Rac1 Rhe8 21. Rfe1 Nxe3 22. fxe3 Qd7 (22... Bh2+ {is the main move and also playable.} 23. Kh1 {can be strongly met by} Qg3 $1 {with the idea h4-h5 and a dangerous initiative for White on the kingside.} 24. Re2 Re7) 23. Nf2 Bc7 24. b5 cxb5 25. Rb1 a6 26. a4 Bb6 27. axb5 a5 28. Ne4 Nxe4 29. Bxe4 Re7 30. Re2 Qd6 31. Kh1 Rc8 32. Rbe1 Rc3 33. Rc2 Bc7 34. Kg1 Rxc2 35. Bxc2 Re6 36. Qh3 Qb4 37. Rd1 Qc3 38. Bd3 a4 39. Qf3 f6 (39... Bb6 $1 40. Qxf7 Rxe3 $1 $15 {Closes the kingside. Black intends ...e6 and will develop queenside play.} 41. Qf4+ {This is the most popular and is analysed in other games..} Ka7 {is a positional approach and will be checked in other games.}) 40. Kf2 a3 41. Qd5 Rd6 42. Qc4 Qxc4 43. Bxc4 Rd8 44. g4 Ka7 45. Ke2 Kb6 46. Kd3 Bd6 47. Kc3 Ka5 48. Kb3 Re8 49. Re1 Re4 50. Bd5 Rxg4 51. Bxb7 Rg5 52. Bf3 Rxb5+ 53. Kc4 Rb2 54. Ra1 Rh2 55. Bg4 Rh4 56. Be2 Rh3 57. e4 Bb4 58. Ra2 Rc3+ 59. Kd5 {with a double edged position.} Rc1 60. e5 fxe5 61. dxe5 $1 Ka4 62. Bc4 $132 Rd1+ {A normal developing move.} 63. Kc6 Rh1 64. Bf7 Re1 $132 65. e6 Rd1 66. Re2 $11 Be7 67. Bg6 $1 $15 Kb4 $6 68. Kc7 Kc3 {Manukian,A (2196)-Vidit,S (2718) chess.com INT 2018} 69. Be4 $1 {This normal developing move improves on the game and gives Black the better chances:} Bf6 70. Kc6 Be7 71. Kc7 Kb4 72. Bg6 $15 {with a more pleasant position for Black.} Rd5 73. Kc6 Rd6+ 74. Kc7 Rd1 75. Kc6 Rd6+ 76. Kc7 Ra6 77. Bb1 Ra7+ {Intending g2-g4 and Black must be very precise now:} 78. Kc6 $5 Kc3 79. Kb6 $1 Ra8 80. Kb7 Ra5 81. Kc6 $1 Rxh5 82. Kd7 Bf6 $1 83. e7 Bxe7 84. Kxe7 Rd5 85. Rc2+ Kb4 86. Ba2 Rc5 87. Rh2 Rc6 88. Bd5 $11 {with perpetual.} Rb6 $2 89. Rc2 $3 g5 90. Kf7 h5 91. Rh2 Rb5 92. Be6 g4 93. Rg2 Ra5 94. Ba2 Kc3 95. Kg6 Kd3 96. Kh6 $19 Ke3 97. Rc2 g3 98. Rc3+ Kf2 99. Rc2+ $19 Kg1 $6 100. Rd2 h4 101. Bd5 h3 102. Kg5 $15 {0-1 (36) Vignesh,B (2287)-Hansen,T (2408) London ENG 2017} g2 $6 103. Kg4 Rxd5 {1/2 (20) Moen,A (2330)-Hansen,T (2443) Oslo 2017} 104. Rxd5 $1 {improves on the game} Kh1 0-1


