{[%evp 0,107,10,-23,19,8,8,11,11,11,6,6,23,12,21,21,23,26,26,24,24,16,23,6,24,-29,-40,-37,6,-1,1,1,1,-38,-23,-3,76,57,100,39,69,64,124,133,131,131,127,127,124,122,122,127,130,133,140,148,126,104,115,125,140,122,198,163,198,205,183,187,177,114,175,182,159,127,126,95,212,180,155,123,138,67,108,107,86,81,144,123,119,120,113,113,113,122,134,156,127,127,127,114,361,200,461,395,470,490,486,499,501,522]} 1. c4 {David Cummings} Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 (3. g3 d5 (3... b6 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. d4 (5. b3)) 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 d4 (6... c5 7. Bb2 Nc6 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. d4) (6... b6 7. Bb2 Bb7 (7... c5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. d4 Bb7 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. a3 a5 12. Nbd2 Nd7 (12... Qe7 13. Ne5 (13. b4 axb4 14. axb4 Bxb4 15. Rxa8 Bxa8 16. Qa1) 13... Rd8 14. Nd3 Nc6 15. Nxc5 bxc5 16. e3) 13. Ne4 Be7) 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. d4 Nd7 10. Re1 c5 11. e4 N5f6 12. Nc3 cxd4 13. Nxd4 Bc5 14. Re2) 7. e3 c5 8. exd4 cxd4 9. Bb2 Nc6) 3... b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. Bb2 {David Cummings: 'A well-known attempt to sharpen the game, this move has also scored best for White (around 60%) in my database.'} O-O 7. O-O c5 (7... d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. d4) 8. Nc3 d5 {David Cummings: 'Black goes for a setup where he holds an IQP. The position is reminiscent of a Tarrasch QGD, except that Black's dark-squared bishop has been fianchettoed, rather than being developed on the a3-f8 diagonal. Instead:'} 9. e3 (9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Bxd5 11. d4 Nd7) 9... Qc8 (9... dxc4 10. bxc4 Nc6 11. Qe2) (9... Nc6 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 12. d4) 10. Rc1 (10. Ne5 {(David Cummings) in Melkumyan-Sivuk and a couple of earlier games in the Archives.} Nc6 {(David Cummings) is a sharper alternative, for example} (10... dxc4) 11. Nxc6 (11. f4 d4 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. exd4 cxd4 14. Nb1 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Rd8 16. Qf3 b5) 11... Bxc6 12. cxd5 Nxd5 {is the continuation of Mamedov-Aravindh in the Archives.} 13. Nxd5 {(David Cummings) is a significant alternative, analyzed in Harika-Lahno in the Archives} Bxd5 14. Qg4 g6 15. e4 Bc6 16. h4 Rd8 17. Rfd1 Bf8) (10. Qe2 Rd8 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Rfd1 Nc6 13. d4 Ba6 (13... Nxc3 14. Bxc3 cxd4) 14. Nb5 Bf6 15. Rac1 (15. a4) 15... Qd7 16. a4 Ndb4 17. dxc5) 10... Rd8 11. cxd5 {David Cummings: 'Slightly unusual. We have previously looked at:'} (11. a3 Nc6 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 exd5 $14 {½-½ (46) Goczo,M (2276)-Farago,S (2262) Budapest 2005} 14. d4 a5 15. h4 Qf5 16. Kh2 Ba6 $14 {0-1 (43) Kudryavtsev,V (2147)-Rensch,D (2356) Agoura Hills 2006}) 11... Nxd5 12. Nxd5 {David Cummings: 'Artemiev tries to create some play by transitioning to a hanging pawns structure. Here:'} (12. d4 Nxc3 13. Bxc3 Be4 14. Ne5 Bxg2 $14 {1-0 (33) Dizdarevic,E (2481)-Kosanovic,G (2383) Stara Pazova 2011} 15. Kxg2 Qb7+ 16. Qf3 Qxf3+ $14 {0-1 (42) Faizrakhmanov,R (2426)-Sychev,K (2415) Minsk 2015} 17. Nxf3 Nc6) 12... Bxd5 13. d4 (13. Qe2 {/= ½-½ (28) Valdes Romero,L (2398)-Munoz Pantoja,M (2471) Sabadell 2018} Qb7 {David Cummings} 14. Rfd1 Nd7 15. d4 Bf6 {is only symbolically better for White, Valdes Romero,L (2398) -Munoz Pantoja,M (2471) Sabadell 2018 1/2-1/2 (28)} 16. Ne1 Bxg2 17. Nxg2 cxd4 $11 {½-½ (30) Zaragatski,I (2486)-Babula,V (2581) Teplice 2013} 18. Bxd4 Bxd4 19. Rxd4 Ne5 20. Ne1 Rxd4 21. exd4 Nc6 22. Qf3 Rc8 $14 {½-½ (107) Haast,M (2381)-Nasuta,G (2516) Karlsruhe 2019} 23. d5 Nd8) 13... a5 $6 {David Cummings: 'This allows White to get a grip on the dark squares. Instead:'} 14. dxc5 $1 {David Cummings: 'White had to calculate the consequences of Black grabbing the a2-pawn, but satisfied that this works for him, plays the most active move. Instead:' White can sacrifice the a2 pawn. Exchanging the dark-squared bishops is unfavourable for Black.} bxc5 $6 {David Cummings: 'This wasn't forced, but after normal moves White will be slightly better with play against the hanging pawns.' Accepting the challenge, but it's very risky.} 15. Nh4 (15. Qe2 {David Cummings: 'and now' White does have a better bishop, but everything else is symmetrical, so the game is very likely to end in a draw.} Qa6) 15... Bxg2 16. Qg4 Bf8 {David Cummings: '?!' David Cummings: 'Trying to hold on to the c6-pawn but leaving the knight passively placed. Here:'} 17. Nxg2 Rd2 18. Bd4 {Suddenly White achieved a strong initiative almost out of nothing.} (18. Bc3 Rxa2 19. Nf4) 18... Nd7 {David Cummings: 'Alternatively:'} (18... Qb7 19. Bxc5 Bxc5 {David Cummings: '!' David Cummings: 'is fine for Black. As is often the case, if Black can advance the IQP to the 5th rank with impunity, he gets pressure against the e2-pawn which balances out his own pawn weaknesses.' blocking the diagonal. Black has nothing to complain about.} 20. Rxc5 Nd7 21. Rg5 {David Cummings: 'allows Black to go for exchanges and symmetry with'} g6 22. Ra1 Rc8) 19. a4 Qb7 20. Bc3 $16 {David Cummings: 'White will soon win the d5-pawn, restoring material equality. His pieces are also much more active than their counterparts, leaving White clearly better.'} Rd6 (20... Ra2 {would lead to a balanced game}) 21. Rfd1 Rxd1+ 22. Rxd1 Nb6 23. Nf4 (23. Rc1 c4 24. Qd1 {was played in Oboladze,L (2340) -Nasuta,G (2517) Skopje 2019 1/2-1/2 (45), and now}) 23... Qe4 24. h3 c4 25. bxc4 Nxa4 26. Ba1 {David Cummings: 'White is now a pawn ahead, but the conversion is not trivial with all the heavy pieces, and only a few pawns, left on the board.'} Nc5 27. Rd4 Qb1+ 28. Rd1 Qe4 29. Rd4 Qc2 30. Nh5 Qg6 (30... f5 31. Nf6+ (31. Qg5 {David Cummings} Qb1+ 32. Kg2 Qxa1) 31... Kh8 32. Qh5 gxf6 33. Rh4 Qb1+ $16 {[%cal Gd4h4]} 34. Kh2 Qb7 $14 35. Bxf6+ {David Cummings: 'is slower. Now'} Kg8 $11 {½-½ (45) Oboladze,L (2340)-Nasuta,G (2517) Skopje 2019}) 31. Qf3 Rb8 32. Bc3 f5 (32... h6 {David Cummings} 33. Rg4 {gives White a strong initiative} Qf5 {(David Cummings) is preferable, although after} 34. Rf4 Qb1+ 35. Kh2 f5 36. g4 {White is slightly for choice.} Nd3 $6 {is even worse.}) 33. Bxa5 Qf7 (33... Nb3 {White is favourite to win this endgame with the better minor piece and better pawn structure.} 34. Rd8 {(David Cummings) activating the rook, was more resilient}) 34. Rd1 Ne4 {David Cummings: '?!' David Cummings: 'A better chance was to go for activity with:'} 35. Nf4 h6 (35... e5 36. Nd5 Rb2) 36. Qe2 Kh7 37. Qh5 {David Cummings: 'More accurate was:'} Qxh5 {David Cummings: '?!' David Cummings: 'Missing an opportunity for counterplay with:'} 38. Nxh5 Rb2 39. Be1 e5 40. g4 fxg4 41. hxg4 {David Cummings: 'White's outside passed pawn should be decisive.'} Rc2 42. Rd8 {David Cummings: 'Allowing some opening of the position, although White doesn't spoil anything.'} Bc5 43. Kf1 Rxc4 44. Rc8 Rc1 45. Rc7 Kh8 46. Ke2 Bxe3 47. Rxg7 Bg5 48. Rg6 Kh7 49. Rg7+ Kh8 50. Ra7 Bh4 51. Rf7 Nd6 52. Rf8+ Kh7 53. Bb4 Rc6 54. f3 Bg5 {(David Cummings) is no help due to} 55. Ra8 Nb5 56. Kd3 {picking up the loose h4-knight} Rc7 $1 {(David Cummings) keeps full control} 57. Ba5 $1 {(David Cummings) for example} Rf7 58. Ke4 Nd4 59. Kxe5 Nxf3+ 60. Ke6 Re7+ 61. Kd6 {with some drawing chances} Ne5 {David Cummings} 62. Bc3 Nf7+ {and Black struggles to defend all his weak pawns.} 63. Kd5 {(David Cummings) and if} Rd7+ $2 64. Ke4 $1 {puts Black right back in the game} Re7+ {(David Cummings) was also very strong. After} 1-0


