1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 {Long semi-condemned by theory, but as we've seen before, this version of the Torre may have been slightly underestimated.} e6 4. O-O Be7 {Vidit responds in a critical manner, but this is by no means forced, of course. See Eric's coverage for details of the alternatives.} (4... c5 5. d3 Nc6 6. e4) 5. d3 O-O (5... c5 6. e4 Nc6 (6... O-O 7. e5 Ne8 8. Re1 Nc6 9. a4) 7. Qe2 O-O 8. e5 Nd7 9. c4) 6. Bf4 $1 (6. Nbd2 c5 7. e4) (6. e4 dxe4 7. dxe4 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Nxe4) 6... c5 $6 (6... b6 7. e4 dxe4 8. dxe4 Bb7 9. e5 Qxd1 10. Rxd1 Nd5 11. Bg5 Bxg5 12. Nxg5 h6) (6... Nc6 7. d4 b6 8. c4 Bb7 9. Nc3 Na5 (9... dxc4 10. Ne5 Nd5) 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Bxd5 12. Qc2 Rc8 13. e4 Bb7 14. Rad1) 7. e4 (7. Na3 Nc6 8. e4 d4 (8... a6) 9. e5 (9. c3) 9... Nd5 10. Bd2 b6) 7... Nc6 (7... dxe4 8. dxe4 Nxe4 9. Qe2 Nf6 10. Rd1 Qb6 11. Na3 $1 Nc6 {when the position continued to remain pretty level.} (11... Qxb2 12. Nb5) 12. Nc4 Qa6 13. a4 Nd5 14. Qe4 Nf6 15. Qe2 Nd5) 8. Ne5 ({Instead, no less a game than Artemiev-Caruana, Internet (rapid) 2020, continued} 8. e5 Nd7 9. h4 b5 10. c4 bxc4 11. dxc4 Nb6 $5 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Nc3 Bf5) 8... Nxe5 $6 9. Bxe5 {Back to base, but White is a clear pawn to the good.} Nd7 10. Bf4 ({Eric also looked at} 10. Bc3 $5 d4 11. Bd2 Rb8 12. a4 b6 13. Na3 {, which he thought was unclear, but after} Bb7 $1 {the position should open to White's advantage} 14. Nc4 a6 {is now fine for Black} {This just doesn't really work after White's last, so Black should settle for} 15. f4 b5 16. Ne5 Bd6 {when the issue is how small (or large) is White's edge - see Yusupov-Wirthensohn, Hamburg 1991, in the Archive.} {Earlier in the competition Artemiev had preferred} 17. Nxd7 {when it would be very interesting to know how he intended to counter} Qxd7 $1 {- see the Archive for detailed coverage.}) 10... d4 11. a4 e5 12. Bd2 Nb8 (12... b6 13. Na3 Rb8 {is probably a better try when White might go} 14. f4 $5 a6 15. Nc4 f6 ({prospective white players might also look into} 15... b5 $5) 16. f5 {when at least he has the two bishops} {Eric's suggested improvement over} b5 $6 {which is likely too slow, as shown in the notes to Von der Loo-Nurbekoglu, correspondence 1998}) 13. Na3 Nc6 $2 {Vidit was far from his best in this event and here rather than trying to seize the initiative, allows White to do just that.} 14. f4 $1 exf4 15. gxf4 f5 16. Nc4 $1 {Returning the extra pawn to obtain a strong attack. White can manage just fine without his rook no h1.} Be6 (16... fxe4 17. Bxe4 (17. dxe4 Be6 {followed by picking up e4.} 18. Qe2 $5 Qc7) 17... Bf5) 17. a5 Qd7 (17... Rc8) 18. exf5 Bd5 (18... Bxf5 19. Qf3) 19. Ne5 {White's pieces continue to flow to good squares.} Nxe5 $2 20. Bxd5+ $1 (20. fxe5 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Rxf5 $1 {, since the king will be quite safe after f2-f4 or}) 20... Qxd5 21. fxe5 {White intends Qb1 followed by Ba6. There's simply no good defence, in part because Black cannot move his knight.} Qxe5 22. Qf3 $1 {Finishing crisply. Mate is forced.} (22. Qg4 Bf6 {I would only now improve over Eric's generally excellent analysis with} 23. Rae1 $5 {, and if}) 22... Rad8 (22... Bh4 23. Qxb7 $1 Rae8) 23. Qxb7 (23. Rae1 $1 Qc7 24. Re6) 23... Rxf5 (23... Bd6 {also looks quite effective, again so long as White quickly breaks with f2-f3.} {Black also suffered after} 24. Bf4 Qf6 25. Qd5+ Kh8 26. Bxd6 {in Vlasov-Bejnerovich, St. Petersburg 1998, when} Rxd6 {would have been logical, and strong.} 27. Qe4 {is a better try when after}) 24. Rfe1 Qf6 25. Rxe7 $1 Rf8 26. Ree1 Qg6+ $5 {was arguably worth a try, not that Black has anything good after} (26... h6 $1 27. Rad1 (27. Kh1 Rf2) 27... Rf2 {followed by ...e5 would at least have given Black a bit of Grünfeld-like compensation.} {Vidit wants his bishop safe inside his pawn chain.} 28. Qe4 $5 Kh8) 27. Kh1 $1 {.} {Missing a straightforward tactic.} Rf2 28. Qd5+ ({or} 28. Rg1 Rxh2+ 29. Kxh2 Qh5+) 28... Kh8 {was necessary when after} 29. Rg1 Qe8 30. Rg2 (30. Rg2 R2f5 31. Qe4 Qf7 32. Rag1 {Black would at least have been fighting, albeit two pawns down.}) 1-0


