[EventRounds "5"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 b6 4. g3 Ba6 5. b3 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 Be7 {Black holds back his c-pawn for the time being.} 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Bg2 d5 9. cxd5 exd5 {By no means obligatory just yet, but Vidit can't resist invading the hole.} 10. O-O Re8 11. Rc1 Bb7 12. Bf4 c6 (12... Na6) 13. Ne5 {The standard Stonewall plan to improve the potentially bad bishop, but Black too can improve his pieces.} Nbd7 $1 {The knight prepares to eye e3 as Vidit rightly doesn't fear losing the bishop-pair.} 14. e4 Nf8 15. exd5 cxd5 16. Bh3 a6 ({Of course, there's nothing wrong with} 16... Ba3 {or} 17. Rc2 {here, but the text is both fairly tempting and quite critical.} a6 18. Na4 Ne6 19. Bc1 Bd6) 17. Na4 Bd6 18. Be3 {White has managed to hold e3 and his own on the queenside, but is clearly too tied down to ever pretend to any advantage. Already a draw is looking rather likely.} Ne6 (18... b5 19. Nc5 {might be met by} Bc8 {,} {but notably leading Colle authority Artur Yusupov has preferred} 20. Bg2 {here, returning play to Colle-Zukertort waters.}) 19. Nc6 Bxc6 20. Rxc6 b5 (20... Rb8 {still seems very sensible, as given in a certain Starting Out work} {Instead,} 21. Qd3) 21. Nc5 Bxc5 22. dxc5 d4 23. Rd6 {Now White even has the c-file and after Black's next the draw becomes inevitable.} dxe3 24. Rxd8 Raxd8 25. Qc1 (25. Qb1 exf2+ 26. Rxf2 Nxc5 {I quite like White and now}) 25... Nd4 26. Kg2 e2 27. Re1 Re7 28. c6 (28. Qc3 Nc6 (28... Ne4 $1 29. Qa5) 29. Qb2 {took aim at d5 and f7, with a pleasant edge.} (29. b4 Rd1) 29... Nd4 {is quite critical, but after Yusupov's line}) 28... Rc7 29. Qd2 Rxc6 {followed by a4-a5 will liquidate yet further.} {Vidit was clearly happy with a solid half as Black, but many would have been sorely tempted to try} 30. Rxe2 $5 Rcd6 31. Re7 (31. Re5 $1 {(White strives to undermine the intruder and to generate some pressure)} Nc6) (31. Re3 Nf5) (31. Re1 $1 Nf3) 31... Nc6 32. Qe3 Nxe7 33. Qxe7 {, hoping to gradually grind White down with good knight against bad bishop. I suspect Bakre would have held (Black does lack great pawn breaks and White is very solid), but the defence could have been a lengthy one.} {and not} Nd5 $2 34. Qa7 Nc3 35. a3 $1 {Going for the bishop, but had he been playing a lower-rated opponent, I suspect Bakre would have played more gently, perhaps beginning with} g6 36. Bg4 Nb1 $5 {.} {A possible improvement on his game from the very previous round (clearly they're well prepared in this chess version of the IPL), where} 37. a4 h5 38. Be2 Nc3 39. Bf3 bxa4 40. Qc5 $1 Nd1 $1 41. bxa4 Rd2 42. Bxd1 Rxd1 {had been pretty level, eventually drawn in Bakre-Karavade, Pune (rapid) 2014.} {Before Bakre White had generally moved his queen here, but} 43. h4 R1d2 {doesn't really give him a huge amount to write home about.} {Standard, but} 44. Qc7 $5 {is more ambitious, fighting for the e4-square. Still, after} (44. Qa5 {Black had absolutely no reason to complain in Abergel-Kryvoruchko, German Bundesliga 2013. I'm quite a fan of an early Qf3-h3 in both the Colle-Zukertort and the London, but it rarely seems to cut the mustard in a Stonewall formation. I guess a question one might ask is how often do you see Black's queen appear on h6 in the Dutch Stonewall?} R8d6 {and ...Ba6 is a thematic alternative} {A common reaction to the Stonewall at all levels is} 45. Qb4 {followed by ...f5. This was actually seen in another Yusupov game, Yusupov-Drasko, Sarajevo 1984, where}) 44... Re8 (44... Re8 45. Qa7 Ree2 46. Qxa6 $1 Rxf2+) 1/2-1/2


