{This game was played in the 4th round of the very strong Isle of Man Chess Open. Benjamin and I are good friends and it was a little uncomfortable to prepare against him as we knew many of each other's openings! So I decided to surprise him by playing a line which I had never played before.} 1. c4 {Vidit,S} e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 c6 4. Nf3 e4 5. Nd4 Qb6 {Already at this point, he started thinking. In last few games I had played the Open Spanish so I was pretty sure he wouldn't expect me to play the Classical Ruy Lopez.} 6. e3 d5 7. Nc3 Be7 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. d3 exd3 10. Qxd3 O-O (10... Be6) 11. Qb5 {I was a bit surprised by this move. Is he really going to repeat this way and make a draw?} Rd8 (11... Nc6 12. Qxb6 axb6 13. O-O Bc5 14. Rd1 Bg4 15. Nde2) 12. Qxb6 axb6 13. O-O {I was glad in a way that he didn't repeat and we would have a big fight. On the other hand, I was worried as I couldn't remember all my lines in this variation. A problem shared by many of my colleagues :)} Nc6 14. Rd1 (14. Bd2 Bd7 15. Rfc1) 14... Bg4 15. Nde2 {I was surprised by this move. Although over the board it seemed quite sensible. Usually, in such lines white tries to play with more flexibility.} Bb4 (15... Na5 16. h3 Bxe2 17. Nxe2 Nb3 18. Rb1 $1 $19 Rxa2 19. Bd2 Nxd2 20. Rxd2 $19 g6 21. Nf4) 16. h3 Bf5 (16... Bh5 17. g4 Bg6 $19 18. Bd2 Rac8 19. Rac1 {was also possible but less clean:} h6 20. a3 Bf8 21. Be1 $1) 17. Bd2 d4 {Not the best. In hindsight, I feel that ...c8 is the most harmonious.} (17... h6 18. Rac1) 18. exd4 {Inaccurate as the ideal place for the knight would be on e3 after Black eventually plays ...c6.} Nxd4 $1 {After this, I realized that Black is completely fine as, after the opening up of the centre, his pieces will be ideally placed.} 19. Nxd4 Rxd4 20. Be1 Rxd1 21. Rxd1 h5 (21... Rb8 22. g4 Be6 23. a3 {of course I can't give up the pride of my position!}) 22. a3 {It looks like White has the d5-square and the position is reminiscent of a Najdorf variation. White would be better if he could get his knight to e3 but as the game shows Black has active counterplay} Bxc3 23. Bxc3 Be4 24. Bxf6 {Obvious but slow! Benjamin underestimated Black's initiative after the opening of the center. I felt a rush of excitement after this move as my hands were itching to push the d-pawn!!} Bxg2 $1 {Thematic! This reminded me of a Najdorf game Caruana-MVL.} 25. Kxg2 gxf6 $1 26. Rd6 b5 27. Rxf6 (27. Rb6 Ra5 28. h4 Kf8 29. Rxb7) 27... b4 $1 28. axb4 Kg7 {Now it becomes clear that once the knight comes to d3 the white pieces will start to suffocate.} 29. Rb6 Ra2 30. Rxb7 Rxb2 $1 31. b5 (31. Rb5 Kg6 32. h4 f6 33. Kf3 $19 Rb3+ 34. Ke4 Rb2 35. f3 Rb3 {is the point.} 36. Rb8) 31... Rb3 32. b6 Kg6 33. Rb8 Kg7 34. b7 Rb2 35. g4 {Tricky, but not good enough! I had seen this try when I played ...c5.} hxg4 36. hxg4 Rb5 37. f4 f6 38. f5 Rb2+ 39. Kf3 Rb3+ $1 40. Ke2 Rb2+ 41. Kd3 Rb3+ 42. Kc2 Rb6 43. g5 {was the quickest :)} fxg5 44. f6+ Kxf6 45. Rf8+ Ke5 46. b8=Q+ Rxb8 47. Rxb8 Ke4 48. Kd2 Kf3 $19 49. Ke1 0-1


