1. d4 {Sagar Shah/Amruta Mokal Ding Liren wants to begin with a positional game, perhaps?!} Nf6 2. c4 $5 {Change of plan! The Caro-Kann is avoided and Ding Liren switches to 1.e4!} e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bf4 O-O {Vidit works as a second of Anish Giri. Hence, it doesn't come as a surprise that he goes for the Najdorf.} 6. e3 b6 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Nxd5 (8. Bg3 c5 9. Bc4 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Bb7 11. O-O Nd7 12. a4 Nf6 13. Qb3 Bd6 $13 {with a complicated opposite coloured bishop position.} 14. Bh4 {is the main move} Rc8 $2 15. Rac1 $1 Qc7 16. Bxf6 $16 {and White is clearly better.} gxf6 17. Rfd1 cxd4 18. cxd4 f5 19. Qb2 Qd7 20. Bb5 Qe7 21. Qe2 Rxc1 22. Rxc1 Rc8 23. Rxc8+ Bxc8 24. Ba6 Bd7 25. Bb5 Bc8) 8... exd5 9. Bd3 c5 (9... Bb4+ 10. Ke2 Bd6 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. Rc1 c5 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Qa4 Ba6 15. Rhd1 Bxd3+ {1-0 (32) Quesada Perez,Y (2624)-Li,R (2571) Philadelphia 2017} 16. Rxd3 {is possible to delay 0-0 a bit longer} Nc6 17. Rd2 {is not as strong because the b7-bishop is already blocking the b-file so it will be a slow process to increase pressure on b2.} Rab8 18. Kf1 Ne5 $14 19. Nxe5 {is a possibility} Qxe5 20. Rxc5 Qxh2 21. g3 Qh1+ 22. Ke2 Rfd8 23. b3 Qh5+ 24. g4 Qg5 25. Qf4) 10. b3 (10. O-O $14 {White can claim a small edge thanks to his bishop pair.} c4 11. Bc2 $1 $14 Nc6) (10. dxc5 bxc5 11. O-O Be6 12. Ne5 c4 13. Be2 (13. Bc2 Bf6 14. Rb1) 13... Bf6 14. Bf3 Na6 15. b3 c3 16. Qd3 Qa5 17. a3 Nc5 18. Qc2 Rac8 19. b4 Qa4) 10... Nc6 (10... Bb7 11. O-O Nd7 12. Rc1 Nf6 $19 13. Bg5 Nd7 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 $16 {There are too many scattered weaknesses which cannot be taken care of by Black} 15. Qc2 g6 16. Qb2 Rac8 17. Rc2 Rc7 18. Rfc1 $11 Rfc8 19. Bb5 Bc6 20. Be2 {double defence} Bb7 21. Qa3) 11. O-O Be6 (11... Bg4 $1 {A move which follows the simple principle - when an opponent is underdeveloped, open the centre.} 12. Bb5 Na5 {With White's 0-0-0 this would not be possible as Black would lose his d6-pawn! But here it's completely fine.} 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. h3 Be6 15. Rc1 Qb6 $11 {Just like the game, but a better version, as Black has been able to get rid of his passive dark-squared bishop.} 16. Bd3 c4 17. Bc2 Nc6 18. Ng5 Bxg5 {White loses a pawn for no substantial compensation.} 19. Bxg5 Nb4 20. Bb1 h6 21. Bf4 {Here White is pretty quick.} Qa6 22. Be5 Nd3) (11... Nb4 $14 {Though still complicated, White has more attacking prospects than his opponent.} 12. Be2 Bb7 {It is not so easy to see how Black will continue his attack on the queenside.} 13. Ne5 Rc8 $1 $16 {Eliminating the key defender of Black's kingside.} 14. dxc5 {this natural move doesn't seem to be the best here because of} bxc5 15. a3 Nc6 {with immediate counter-attack by Black.} 16. Bg4 $5 {It is said that in the Sicilian if Black is able to execute the move d5, he should be doing fine.} f5 17. Bf3 Nxe5 18. Bxe5 Qd7 {if White tries to win the pawn, then} 19. Ra2 $1 {is the saving grace!} Qe6 20. Qa1 $1 Rf7 21. Rd2 $11 Bg5 $4 {Trying to save the pawn would land up in disaster on the dark squares.}) 12. Rc1 {White's idea is to support the g5-pawn and prepare h5 and g6. Also he gets the rook off the long diagonal of the b7-bishop.} a5 (12... g6 {and White will be in trouble} 13. h3 a6 $17 14. Qe2 {Although this might be objectively fine, this is not a pawn that you want to be taking. Especially when the g8-square is covered by the bishop on d5.} Qc8 15. Rfd1 Re8 16. Bb1 Bf8 $16 17. dxc5 {is not at all possible because of} bxc5 $16 18. Ng5 {with the idea of h6. White has some real pressure on the position.} Qb7 19. Qf3 $16 Rad8 $142 20. Qg3 Bc8 21. h4 Ne7 22. Bc7 Rd7 $132 {and the position opens up for Black's bishop pair.} 23. Be5 Nc6 24. Bf4 Nd8 $11 25. h5 $1 $14) 13. h3 (13. Qe2 $16 {A very unpleasant position to defend for Black.} h6 14. Rfd1 $18 Qc8 15. Bb5 Qb7 16. dxc5 bxc5 {was a possiblity} 17. h3 Qb6 18. Rd2 Na7 19. Ba4 Rac8 20. Ne5 $6 Rfd8 $3 {An important idea for the rest of the game} 21. e4 d4 22. Nc4 Qa6 23. Rd3 Nb5 $1 $18 24. Bd2 $1 $11 Nd6 25. Nxa5 $13 Bh4) 13... g6 {Vidit is brave and doesn't fear the pawn storm against his king.} 14. Bb5 {The first new move of the game.} Qc8 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Nd4 $6 Nxd4 (16... Bd7 17. Ne2 Be6 18. Nc3 $3 $17 {Going for the same principle which White had on move 42: eliminating the back rank defender! Quite a difficult move to find.} Rd8 $1 {Exchanging this rook would have helped White because it gets rid of an important defender and the a-pawn can start thinking of moving towards becoming a queen.} 19. Qf3) 17. exd4 Qb7 $6 {A common logical move to limit the activity of White's bishop. It also releases the pressure on the d6 weakness, and one must not forget the knight maneouvre via e6. But because White has delayed 0-0-0, Black could have taken advantage of this fact that at the moment there is no pressure on d6 by playing...f5!} 18. a4 (18. Qe2) 18... Rfc8 {This time the move is not as well timed as the previous move, but still needed as it gives Black counterplay down the f-file.} 19. Re1 cxd4 (19... Bf8 20. dxc5 $19 (20. Qd2 c4) 20... Rxc5 $4 21. Qd4) 20. Qxd4 {It's a complicated position. How do we assess ?t. Let's try to make a simple comparison of the pieces. White's knight is excellently placed on c3 looking at the d5-square. White's bishops are also quite active. The f1-bishop can go to h3 and look at an important diagonal. On the other hand I am not so sure about Black's bishops. The f6-bishop is passive, and the b7 one is limited by the f3-e4 pawns. Black has a weakness on d6, but it is compensated for by White's weakness on f3. Overall, the position is complex, but there is no doubt that Ding Liren is better.} Rxc1 (20... Ba3 21. Bh6 $1 Bf8 22. Bxf8 {is just winning.} Rxf8 23. b4 (23. h4 $17 {is also a pleasant endgame.})) 21. Rxc1 Rc8 (21... Qa7 $17 {and Black has chances to win this.}) 22. Rxc8+ Qxc8 23. Bd2 $5 {This exchange is quite counter-intuitive as it opens up the bishop on f6 and places it on a powerful diagonal. However, concretely White is also able to get his light-squared bishop activated. Ding Liren assessed that as an improvement over the current position. But I am not so sure about that. Somehow Black's play becomes easier from this point onwards.} Qc7 (23... Bc5 24. Qc3 Bb6 25. b4 (25. Qf6)) 24. Bc3 f6 25. b4 axb4 26. Bxb4 {Which bishop is better? The bishop on d5 looks great, but so does the bishop on f6. As of now, somehow the white king looks much safer, but things can turn 180 degrees pretty soon in such sharp positions.} Bxb4 27. Qxb4 Kg7 $1 {Good play by Vidit. His queen will come to e5 and target the weakest point in White's camp.} 28. a5 d4 29. a6 Qb6 $1 {This weakens the light squares, but White is not able to make use of it because of the pressure on the b2 point.} (29... Qa7 30. Bc4 Bc8 (30... Bxc4 31. Qb7+) 31. Qd6) 30. Qe7+ {Planning to play d5.} Kh6 {Now the f3-pawn is hanging so there is no time for h1.} 31. a7 Bd5 32. Bc4 Bb7 33. a8=Q Bxa8 34. Qf8+ Kg5 35. Qxa8 f5 36. Qd5 $1 Kh6 37. g3 Qf6 38. Kg2 Qb6 39. h4 Qf6 40. Qe6 Qd8 41. Qe5 Qb6 42. Qd5 Qf6 43. Bd3 Qb6 44. Qf3 Kg7 45. Qf4 Qc6+ 46. Kh2 $2 {The pawn is moving too fast, without any backup from its pieces.} Qc5 $1 47. h5 Kf6 48. h6 g5 49. Qb8 Kg6 50. g4 Kxh6 51. gxf5 g4 {Vidit doesn't risk it and the game ends in a draw. A typical Najdorf game - complex and full of interesting moments.} 52. Kg3 $1 {would have given Vidit a chance to continue playing for a win.} Qd5 53. Qf8+ Kh5 54. Qe8+ $1 {A strong move opening up the rook on f6 to look at the a6-pawn.} Kg5 55. Qe7+ 1/2-1/2


