{Ding Liren was in great form in the World Cup and he had a splendid tournament. As they say, in such tournaments you need some luck and here is where I played my part! After playing a great game and reaching a winning position I gifted him a half point.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. O-O Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. c3 a6 7. a4 O-O 8. Re1 h6 {Tadic,Branko: 'N' Here he started thinking. Not so surprising as this hadn't been played before. ...h6 and ...g7 have been played quite often.} 9. h3 a5 10. Nbd2 Be6 11. b3 (11. Bb5) 11... d5 (11... Re8 12. Nf1 (12. Bb5 Bd7 (12... d5 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Nxe5 dxe4 15. d4) 13. Nf1) 12... d5 13. exd5 Nxd5 (13... Bxd5) 14. Bd2 Nf4 (14... Qf6) 15. Bxf4 Bxc4 16. bxc4 exf4 17. d4) (11... Bxc4 12. bxc4 Nd7 13. Nb3 (13. Nf1) 13... Bb6 14. d4) 12. exd5 (12. Bb5 dxe4 13. dxe4 Na7 14. Bf1 Nc6) 12... Nxd5 {After a series of logical moves, we reached this position. White has the c-file and some play on the queenside. Whereas Black has two bishops and more space.} 13. Ne4 (13. Qc2 Re8 14. Ne4 (14. Nxe5 Bxh3 15. Ndf3 Bf5) 14... Bd6 (14... Bf8) 15. Bd2 f5 16. Nxd6 Qxd6 17. Bb5) (13. Nxe5 Nxc3) 13... Bb6 $1 {Controlling the c5-square and limiting the scope of the e4-knight.} 14. Ra2 (14. Bd2) (14. Qc2) 14... f5 {Here Ding went into deep thought.} 15. Ng3 {He played this and offered a draw. It was clear by his time management and body language that he didn't like his position. And in any case, I liked my position so I decided to continue.} Qf6 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Nh5 Qf7 {This looked a bit weird. Leaving the rook on a8 under the pin and leaving the f7 undefended. Although it didn't look natural, I played this for concrete reasons.} (17... Qg6 18. Rxe5 Nxc3 19. Rxe6) 18. Rxe5 $6 {I was shocked by this move. I expected him to take on d5 and try to save the slightly worse endgame.} Nxc3 19. Rxe6 (19. Bxe6 Nxd1 20. Bxf7+ Rxf7 21. Rd2 Nc3 22. Bb2 Bd4 23. Re6 b5) 19... Nxd1 20. Re7 {Tadic,Branko: '?!' '!?' Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#]' White does have clear control of the c-file and a powerful bishop but probably Ding underestimated the only but important factor which is in Black's favour, 'Weak king'! It was probably wise to go back and ask me to show my cards!} Rad8 $1 {Tadic,Branko: '!'} 21. Rae2 (21. Rd2 Nc3 22. Nf4 c6 23. Be6 g5 $5 $36 24. Rxb7 {- 88/22} Bd4 25. Rxf7 Rxf7 26. Ne2 Nxe2+ 27. Rxe2 Kg7 28. Bxf7 Kxf7) (21. Rxf7 Rxf7 22. Rc2 f4 (22... Re8 23. Kf1) 23. Bxf4 (23. Kf1 Rdd7 24. Ke1 Nxf2 25. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 26. Kxf2 Kh7) 23... c6 24. Bg3 Re8) 21... Nc3 22. R2e5 c6 $1 $17 {Getting rid of the pin. Now White can't stop Black from landing a knight on f4.} 23. Rxb7 {Tadic,Branko: '?!' This was a big surprise. I was only expecting h2 which at least temporarily prevents ...f4} (23. Nf4 {was my original plan but I didn't like the possibility of him exchanging the light-squared bishops.} Qxc4 24. bxc4 Bd4 25. Rxa5 Rde8 {with some play on the queenside.} 26. Ng6 Rxe7 $5 27. Nxe7+ Kf7 28. Ba3 Rd8 29. Nxf5 Bb6 $36 30. Re5 Kf6 $36 31. d4 Rxd4 32. Nxd4 Kxe5) 23... Nd5 {Tadic,Branko: '!'} 24. Rxf7 Rxf7 25. Re6 Kh7 $1 (25... Rc8 26. Bd2 Bd8 {and it's not so easy to progress. It will probably be a draw after the eventual exchanges in the center.} 27. g3 Kh7 28. Nf4 Re7 (28... Nxf4 29. Bxf4 {Now the a7-pawn is undefended.}) 29. Rd6 Nxf4 30. gxf4 Bb6 31. Be6 Rf8) 26. Rxc6 Re7 27. Bxh6 (27. Nxg7 $19 Kxg7 (27... Re1+ 28. Kh2 $15 Rxc1 (28... Bxf2 {It was probably wise to go back and ask me to show my cards!} 29. Nxf5 {Tadic,Branko: '!' This seemed very strange. To put the bishop on b8 and box in the rook on a8 voluntarily? Although the pieces are awkward, it disrupts White's kingside.} Rxc1 30. Rxh6+ {Tadic,Branko: ''} Kg8 31. Rd6 Rxd6 32. Nxd6 Ba7 (32... Rxc4 33. dxc4 Nf4 34. Ne4 Be1) 33. Bxd5+ Kg7 34. Ne4 Bb8+ $5 35. g3 $2 Rc2+ $18 36. Kg1) 29. Nxf5) 28. Bxh6+ Kh7 29. Bg5 Re1+ $19 30. Kh2 Bxf2 (30... Rd7 $1 {Tadic,Branko: ''} 31. Bxd5 Bc7+ $1 {desperate counterplay!} 32. Rxc7 Rxc7 33. Bc4) 31. Bxd8 $19 f4 $19 { Kg7} 32. h4 $2 Ne3 33. Rc7+ Kh6 $13 (33... Kg6 34. Bf7+ Kg7 35. Bd5+ Kg6 36. Be4+ Kh5 37. Rc5+ {Even the simple inclusion of the last piece in the game was giving a decisive advantage.} Kh6 38. Bg5+ Kg7 39. Rc7+ Kf8 40. Bxf4 $19) 34. Bg5+ Kh5 $18 35. Bf7+ (35. Bxf4 Ng4+) 35... Kg4 36. Be6+ Kh5 37. Bxf4 Ng4+ 38. Bxg4+ Kxg4 39. Rg7+ (39. g3 Re2 $19) 39... Kxf4 40. Rf7+ $19 Ke3 41. h5) 27... gxh6 $4 {Tadic,Branko: '?' Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#]' An inexplicable blunder! I hallucinated and didn't play the best move, even after seeing it.} 28. Bxd5 Rd6 {Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#]'} (28... Re1+ 29. Kh2 $1 {Bringing another piece into the attack. Now Black simply plays d6-e6 or g7-h8. Black is winning in multiple ways as you can see from the lines.} Bxf2 30. Rc7+ (30. g3 $1 Bd4 31. Rc7+ Kh8 32. Nf4 Rd6) 30... Kg6 31. Bf3 Bd4) 29. Rxd6 $1 {I was shocked to see this! Black has not even a hint of advantage after this as his pride, the knight on d5, is exchanged!} (29. Rc2 Re1+ 30. Kh2 Bd4 $11 31. Bc4) 29... Re1+ 30. Kh2 Bc7 31. g4 Bxd6+ 32. Kg2 Kg6 33. Ng3 Bxg3 34. Kxg3 Rd1 35. Bc4 Kf6 (35... fxg4 36. hxg4 Rg1+ 37. Kf4) 36. f3 Rg1+ {I offered a draw here but Ding seemed optimistic to maybe even win this game.} 37. Kf2 (37. Kf4 Rh1 38. Kg3) 37... Rh1 38. Kg2 Rd1 39. Kg3 {Eventually, he decided to be objective and take a draw. Needless to say, this game gave me many sleepless nights, but it was a good lesson :) I hope to come back to the next World Cup even stronger.} Rg1+ 40. Kf2 1/2-1/2


