{[%evp 0,66,29,-14,14,2,9,9,9,9,10,-6,8,12,14,6,7,8,20,12,8,10,10,11,18,12,29,13,41,4,70,-9,-22,34,10,18,15,22,22,22,-12,15,13,24,60,40,53,29,38,42,30,6,4,0,11,8,21,21,7,2,0,-6,11,-12,-1,-3,11,-12,0]} 1. d4 {David Cummings} d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 {David Cummings: 'A rare move - White's 7th most common try - and new to this site. Ding uses this as a precursor to the new idea he brought to this game. In the Archives, you can find many games with the mainline 5 Nf3 as well 5 e3, 5 a3, 5 e4, 5 d3 and 5 Rb1.'} h6 {David Cummings: 'Vidit goes for the Fischer setup with ...e7-e6 and ...Ng8-e7, which has proven to be a very reliable approach for Black in the Symmetrical English. Instead another logical response is to construct a dark-squared pawn chain with ..d7-d6 and ... e7-e5:'} 6. Bh4 $5 {David Cummings: 'And this is the novelty. Other players were quick to explore this new line, with Giri and Vachier-Lagrave trying 5 b3 White in games played soon after this one (see the notes above and below).'} dxc4 {David Cummings: 'By forcing Black to defend his c5-pawn, White is aiming to get an edge in the battle for the centre by inhibiting the ...d7-d5 break.'} 7. e4 g5 8. Bg3 b5 9. Ne5 {Usually in the e6-line Black´s plan is to play ...d5, but here it is not possible due to the attack on c5. Vidit deals with the issue and forces ...d5 through. If he had done nothing White would have played d4 himself with good play. Or he could have prevented d4 with ...Nf5 as van Foreest did.} Nbd7 {David Cummings: 'Black comes up with a sharp idea which enables him to get the d5-break in, although this comes at the cost of a slight lag in development. In a later round at Wijk aan Zee, another game saw:'} 10. Nxd7 (10. Nxc6 Qb6 11. d5 Bb7 $6 {too slow} 12. a4 a6 13. Be2 Bxc6 (13... Bg7) 14. dxc6 {Now Black's f5-bishop doesn't have any squares, and Black gets pushed back.} Qxc6 15. e5 Nd5) (10. Be2 Bb7 {and White is better co-ordinated, with pressure in the centre, Vachier-Lagrave,M (2780)-Tari,A (2625) Gibraltar Masters 2019 1-0 (36)} 11. O-O $1 {following through with the bishop trade leaves Black with a position that it perfectly fine for him}) 10... Qxd7 11. Be5 Bg7 {David Cummings: 'The pin on the c3-knight means the d5-pawn cannot be captured.'} 12. Qf3 Qe7 {David Cummings: 'Black can also play:'} 13. h4 Rg8 14. hxg5 {David Cummings: 'Black has a space advantage and is only one or two moves away from completing development, so White must quickly apply pressure to the vulnerable c5-pawn.'} hxg5 $1 {David Cummings: 'Black pushes forward, further heightening the complications. Instead:' A dynamic solution.} 15. Qg3 $1 {David Cummings: 'A far from obvious, but excellent move. White threatens to open the e-file with e3xd4, after which the e1-rook will be powerfully placed. As a result, Black is obliged to trade on the e3-square, giving White an improved grip on the centre.'} (15. Be2 Bb7 16. b3 {White tries to counter Black's plan of ...Qd8-d7 and ...Bf5-h3 by hitting Black's central pawns.} cxb3 17. axb3 a6) 15... Bf8 (15... b4 16. Na4 {and White's better pawn structure give him an advantage, Predojevic,B (2614)-Ostenstad,B (2464) Norway 2015 1-0 (28)} Nxe4 {followed by ...Qd8-d7 is called for} 17. Qe3 f5 18. Bxc4) 16. O-O-O (16. Rd1 {Black needs to play more actively in this line} Bb7 17. Be2 b4 (17... Nd7 18. Bc7 {Black's last 3 moves don't fit together very well, and now White take over in the centre with} Rc8 19. a3) 18. Na4 Nxe4 19. Qe3 Nf6 20. Nc5) (16. a3) 16... Bb7 $1 17. d5 (17. Kb1 $5 b4 18. Na4 Nxe4 19. Qe3 {White sacrifices a pawn to mix things up, Savchenko,B (2655) -Dominguez Perez,L (2721) Havana 2009 1/2-1/2 (48), and now} Nf6 20. Bxc4 Ng4 21. Qe2 {when White's two bishops give him compensation for the pawn.} Nxe5 22. dxe5) 17... cxd5 18. exd5 Nxd5 {David Cummings: 'Another critical moment.'} 19. Nxb5 {David Cummings: 'After this move, the queens and some minor pieces are traded, and Black manages to solve his problems. Instead, White has good chances after keeping the tension with:' White simplifies too soon.} Qb4 20. Nd6+ (20. Nc3 {This is Black's most straightforward plan, and Black has generally not had problems in games where he got in ...Be6-h3.}) 20... Bxd6 21. Bxd6 Qa4 (21... Qb6 {David Cummings: 'followed by ...Qd8-d7 is called for'}) (21... Qa5) 22. Rh4 (22. Ba3 O-O-O {and now:} 23. Rd4 Nb6) 22... Qxa2 $1 {Black keeps defending actively.} (22... Rc8 23. Ba3 Nb4 24. Bxb4 {and Black is no worse.} Qxb4 {was played in the game} 25. Rhd4 {David Cummings} Bd5 26. Be2 Kf8 {leads to a typical closed English battle. Some examples of how play can proceed:}) 23. Ba3 {David Cummings: 'The pressure on the weak b3-pawn causes White to jettison it in search of activity. Instead after:'} Rc8 24. Qd6 Rc6 (24... Rd8 25. Qc5 Qa1+ (25... Rc8 26. Qd6 {Giri,A (2783)-Van Foreest,J (2612) Tata Steel Masters 2019 1/2-1/2 (30), and now after} Rd8) 26. Kd2 (26. Kc2 Ne3+) 26... Nf4+ 27. Kc3 $1 Nd5+ 28. Rxd5 Qc1+ $5 {White sacs the queen to create some imbalance.} 29. Kb4 Rxd5) 25. Qb8+ Bc8 26. Rxd5 {David Cummings: 'White has good play for the pawn, but only enough to hold the balance.'} Qa1+ 27. Kc2 exd5 (27... gxh4 28. Qb5 $1 Bd7 $5 {David Cummings} 29. Rg5 Rxg5 30. Qxg5 Rd6 {with compensation for the pawn due to White's "Swiss cheese" pawn formation.} 31. Bxd6 $5 {was an intelligent waiting move with the idea} (31. Qg8+ {and White "wins" the centre. The tactics from Giri-Van Foreest now don't work for Black since the d1-rook now protects White's queen.} Ke7 32. Qg5+) 31... Ba4+ 32. Kc3 $1 {with good play.} Qe1+ {David Cummings} 33. Kxc4 (33. Kd4 Qxf2+) 33... Qe4+ {Black maintains the symmetry for now. Here:} 34. Kc3 $1 {is White's most accurate, since he will be the first to get in the d-pawn thrust, for example} Qe1+) 28. Rh6 (28. Qa8 Rc7 (28... Kd7 {and the knight gets to c4.} 29. Rd4 {David Cummings: 'is much less effective. After'} Qe1 (29... Qxf1 30. Qxa7+ Rc7 31. Rxd5+ Ke6 32. Qb6+ Kxd5 {leads to some kind of dynamic equality.} 33. Qd6+ Ke4 {is also very messy} 34. f3+ $5 {Even here this was possible. Again}) 30. Qxa7+ (30. Rxd5+ {David Cummings: 'Black has at least enough for a pawn.' and Black gets out.} Kc7 {David Cummings: '?!' David Cummings: 'defending the c5-pawn doesn't work well because of'} 31. Qxa7+ Bb7 32. Rd7+ {David Cummings: 'for example' with initiative.} Kxd7 {David Cummings} 33. Qxb7+ Rc7 34. Qd5+ {and Black's offside queen gives White good attacking prospects in the centre and on the kingside.} Kc8 $5 {(David Cummings) is the engine's suggestion, dislodging the well placed f4-knight. Now} 35. Qa8+) 30... Ke8 31. Rxd5 Qe4+ 32. Kc1) 29. Qxd5 {David Cummings} gxh4 30. Qe5+ Kd8 31. Qf6+ Ke8 {White is more actively placed than in the game, and retains a slight edge.} 32. Qe5+) 28... f6 (28... Qxf1 29. Rxc6 Qd3+ $5 30. Kc1 Qf1+) 29. Qa8 Rc5 (29... Rc7 30. Qxd5 {(David Cummings) Black's knights give him sufficient counterplay.} ({The little move} 30. Be2 $1 {David Cummings: 'depriving the c8-bishop of squares makes it difficult for Black to unravel. If now' was very strong. It is hard for Black to ease the tension:})) 30. Bxc5 Qa4+ {David Cummings: 'Chances are level, and the players now go for a repetition.'} 31. Kc1 Qa1+ 32. Kc2 Qa4+ {White has enough compensation for a pawn but nothing more.} 33. Kc1 Qa1+ 34. Kc2 1/2-1/2


