{[%evp 0,99,80,16,61,8,62,20,45,-92,-38,-147,-95,-63,-51,-55,9,7,75,70,75,-54,62,-20,6,-11,-28,0,-24,43,31,32,21,26,24,26,32,28,27,21,10,10,14,7,5,10,3,9,9,7,7,9,19,26,5,13,13,2,33,26,17,13,9,16,10,0,38,61,71,70,144,104,95,0,72,25,100,-44,369,411,497,497,497,495,505,505,505,505,505,893,901,893,893,938,938,952,982,982,29995,29996,29997,29998] 'FIDE WORLD CUP 2021 – RETURN OF THE OTB CHESS The Chess World Cup 2021 was the 9th edition of the World Cup that took place in Sochi, Krasnaya Polyana, Russia, beginning 12 July and ending 6 August 2021 with the participation of 206 players. It marked the return of over-the-board chess on a global scale after the COVID-19 pandemic forced the cancellation of many sporting events. Elite players from all over the world competed for the $1, 892,500 prize fund and two spots in the 2022 Candidates Tournament. The top seeds were: Magnus Carlsen (World Champion), Fabiano Caruana (World Championship finalist), Sergey Karjakin (World Championship finalist), Levon Aronian (two times Winner of the World Cup), Anish Giri, Alexander Grischuk, Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, Maxime Vachier-Lagrave and Alireza Firouzja. However, the winner of the tournament was the Polish GM Jan-Krzysztof Duda, who won without losing any games either in classical chess or in the rapid tiebreakers. Duda, and the tournament runner-up Sergey Karjakin thus qualified for the FIDE Candidates Tournament 2022. In this volume of Informant we bring you a detail coverage of this prominent event with the contributions by Jan-Krzysztof Duda, Velimir Ivic, Miodrag Perunovic, Rafael Leitao and Milos Perunovic. *** Jan-Krzysztof Duda wins the FIDE World Cup and qualifies for the Candidates The Polish chess superstar finished the tournament undefeated and knocked out none other than World Champion Magnus Carlsen in the semifinals. Eventually, Carlsen beat Vladimir Fedoseev in the match to claim the third place.  Jan-Krzysztof earned his title the hard way, knocking out top class opposition: Alexander Grischuk, Vidit Gujrathi, Magnus Carlsen and Sergey Karjakin in the final four rounds of the marathon event. Right after the final game against Karjakin Duda called this the tournament of his life "at least in classical chess", being both excited and exhausted, but also extremely gracious and modest. World Champion Carlsen provided perhaps the best description of Duda's magnificent performance in Krasnaya Polyana: "Huge congratulations to Duda for winning the World Cup. Considering the line of opponents he beat in the last four rounds, never losing a game - then obviously never being in a must-win or desperate situation - is a massive achievement. So, he is a richly deserved winner." Jan-Krzysztof won a generous $110.000 first prize and 18.2 rating points, but also gained a spot in the next edition of the Candidates Tournament. He now stands as a worthy contender to become the next challenger to the world crown. When asked about his ambitions and chances to win the Candidates, always confident Duda responded: "Yeah, why not? If I have such a good form like here, I'm probably unstoppable in such case." Indeed, why not?! Dear readers, here we present you two of the most interesting games analysed by the Tournament Champion himself, with exclusive annotations for this edition of Informant. Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'FIDE WORLD CUP 2021 – RETURN OF THE OTB CHESS The Chess World Cup 2021 was the 9th edition of the World Cup that took place in Sochi, Krasnaya Polyana, Russia, beginning 12 July and ending 6 August 2021 with the participation of 206 players. It marked the return of over-the-board chess on a global scale after the COVID-19 pandemic forced the cancellation of many sporting events. Elite players from all over the world competed for the $1, 892,500 prize fund and two spots in the 2022 Candidates Tournament. The top seeds were: Magnus Carlsen (World Champion), Fabiano Caruana (World Championship finalist), Sergey Karjakin (World Championship finalist), Levon Aronian (two times Winner of the World Cup), Anish Giri, Alexander Grischuk, Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, Maxime Vachier-Lagrave and Alireza Firouzja. However, the winner of the tournament was the Polish GM Jan-Krzysztof Duda, who won without losing any games either in classical chess or in the rapid tiebreakers. Duda, and the tournament runner-up Sergey Karjakin thus qualified for the FIDE Candidates Tournament 2022. In this volume of Informant we bring you a detail coverage of this prominent event with the contributions by Jan-Krzysztof Duda, Velimir Ivic, Miodrag Perunovic, Rafael Leitao and Milos Perunovic. *** Jan-Krzysztof Duda wins the FIDE World Cup and qualifies for the Candidates The Polish chess superstar finished the tournament undefeated and knocked out none other than World Champion Magnus Carlsen in the semifinals. Eventually, Carlsen beat Vladimir Fedoseev in the match to claim the third place.  Jan-Krzysztof earned his title the hard way, knocking out top class opposition: Alexander Grischuk, Vidit Gujrathi, Magnus Carlsen and Sergey Karjakin in the final four rounds of the marathon event. Right after the final game against Karjakin Duda called this the tournament of his life "at least in classical chess", being both excited and exhausted, but also extremely gracious and modest. World Champion Carlsen provided perhaps the best description of Duda's magnificent performance in Krasnaya Polyana: "Huge congratulations to Duda for winning the World Cup. Considering the line of opponents he beat in the last four rounds, never losing a game - then obviously never being in a must-win or desperate situation - is a massive achievement. So, he is a richly deserved winner." Jan-Krzysztof won a generous $110.000 first prize and 18.2 rating points, but also gained a spot in the next edition of the Candidates Tournament. He now stands as a worthy contender to become the next challenger to the world crown. When asked about his ambitions and chances to win the Candidates, always confident Duda responded: "Yeah, why not? If I have such a good form like here, I'm probably unstoppable in such case." Indeed, why not?! Dear readers, here we present you two of the most interesting games analysed by the Tournament Champion himself, with exclusive annotations for this edition of Informant.'''} 1. e4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof'' Jan-Krzystztof Duda is not known to be going down long forcing lines, but in this game it was exactly what happened. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Jan-Krzystztof Duda is not known to be going down long forcing lines, but in this game it was exactly what happened.''} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6 5. c3 g6 6. O-O Bg7 {Vidit has previously shown a few of his weapons against 1.e4 and the Archangelsk was the latest and the most succesful one, as he managed to beat Vasif Durarbeyli with it, in the previous round. It obviously wouldn't come as a surprise any longer and JKD goes on to blitz out the next few moves.  Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Vidit has previously shown a few of his weapons against 1.e4 and the Archangelsk was the latest and the most succesful one, as he managed to beat Vasif Durarbeyli with it, in the previous round. It obviously wouldn't come as a surprise any longer and JKD goes on to blitz out the next few moves. ''} 7. Re1 {Clever to start with this and not after 7.c3 d6, because now 8.a4 allows the option of 8...Bg4 as well. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Clever to start with this and not after 7.c3 d6, because now 8.a4 allows the option of 8...Bg4 as well.''} O-O 8. h3 {Durarbeyli, who is a very experienced and a very strong Grand Master, with an excellent track record, went for the 8.Nxe5 variation, which also shows up at the highest level a lot. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Durarbeyli, who is a very experienced and a very strong Grand Master, with an excellent track record, went for the 8.Nxe5 variation, which also shows up at the highest level a lot.''} (8. Nbd2 a6 9. Ba4 h6 10. Nf1 b5 $18 11. Bb3 $2 Na5 12. Bc2 c5 13. d4 exd4 14. cxd4 Bg4 15. d5 Nc4 16. Ne3 Nxe3 17. Rxe3 Re8 18. h3 Bxf3 19. Qxf3 Nd7 20. Rb1 Qh4 $13 21. Re2 $2 c4 $1 22. Qf4 $140 Qe7 23. Bd2 a5 24. Qg3 Nc5 $17 25. b3 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'was another attempt, where I had seen a following line: Giri,Anish: '(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) was another attempt, where I had seen a following line:''} cxb3 26. Bxb3 Nxe4 27. Qd3 f5 28. Qxb5 Bd4 29. Be1 Qf7 30. Qd3 Qf6 31. Rd1 Be5 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'is winning, as after 43...h2 there is 44.a8Q protecting h1-square, and after Giri,Anish: 'is winning, as after 43...h2 there is 44.a8Q protecting h1-square, and after''} 32. Qf3 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'there is'} a4 $18 33. Bc4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) Duda,Jan Krzysztof'} Rec8 34. Bb5 Nc3 35. Bxc3 Rxc3 36. Re3 Rc2 37. Re2 Rxe2) 8... Bd7 9. a4 Re8 10. Bg5 {This has been very trendy for a while. The point is that 10...Nxa5? loses to 11.Rxa5! Bxa5 12.dxe5!, while if Black goes 10...Ba7, then after 11.h3 0-0 12.Be3, Black has to deal with some tactics as the a7 bishop is under protected. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'This has been very trendy for a while. The point is that 10...Nxa5? loses to 11.Rxa5! Bxa5 12.dxe5!, while if Black goes 10...Ba7, then after 11.h3 0-0 12.Be3, Black has to deal with some tactics as the a7 bishop is under protected.''} (10. a5 a6 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof'} 11. Bc4 $1 Be6 12. Bxe6 $18 Rxe6 13. Bg5 h6 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof} 14. Bh4 $1 Qd7 15. Qb3 Rb8 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Nbd2 $18 {or} Bg7 18. Nf1 $1 Kh7 19. Ng3 Ree8 20. h4 $18 {with an easily won position.} Nd8 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) Duda,Jan Krzysztof'} 21. d4 $18 Ne6 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof} 22. Rad1 Nf4 23. dxe5 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '+-' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'and there is no stopping the a-pawn.'} Bxe5 {Diagram [#] Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) (Duda,Jan Krzysztof) Diagram [#]'} 24. c4 $1 Qe6 25. Nxe5) 10... h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '!?''Vidit had played the Neo-Archangelsk in the previous match, and in the most trendy 10.a5 variation he played this interesting sideline. It wasn't a big surpise for me though, as his friend Anish Giri had played it in Zagreb GCT before, the tournament I had participated in as well. I decided to play in the most forcing way, and test my opponent's memory, even if objectively the very line is probably close to the so-called "forced draw". Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '!?' '!?' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Vidit had played the Neo-Archangelsk in the previous match, and in the most trendy 10.a5 variation he played this interesting sideline. It wasn't a big surpise for me though, as his friend Anish Giri had played it in Zagreb GCT before, the tournament I had participated in as well. I decided to play in the most forcing way, and test my opponent's memory, even if objectively the very line is probably close to the so-called "forced draw".''' This is the latest trend, intending to go for the direct complications with 12.Be3 Nxe4!?. On the black side we have games of Grischuk, Dubov, Caruana, Aronian and the last one before this game, was actually played by myself against Grischuk in the Zagreb rapid.  Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'This is the latest trend, intending to go for the direct complications with 12.Be3 Nxe4!?. On the black side we have games of Grischuk, Dubov, Caruana, Aronian and the last one before this game, was actually played by myself against Grischuk in the Zagreb rapid. ''} 12. Nbd2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'This move was introduced by the young Russian player Gregory Oparin in 2011, but only gained popularity recently. The ideas behind the move are simple-13.d5 and 13.dxe5.''' White could also start with 12.Re1, which is what Harikrishna did against Fabiano in Wijk aan Zee this year. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'White could also start with 12.Re1, which is what Harikrishna did against Fabiano in Wijk aan Zee this year.''} a6 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'Black accepts the challenge. This move leads to a complex unbalanced position by force.''' That's the point. These complications have existed for a few years already, but it was only this year that the line has exploded and people stopped avoiding this with both colours. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'That's the point. These complications have existed for a few years already, but it was only this year that the line has exploded and people stopped avoiding this with both colours.''} 13. Bc4 {The most direct test, but 13.Re1 has been played here too. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'The most direct test, but 13.Re1 has been played here too.''} Nd8 14. Nf1 Ne6 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'The only move, since two pieces were hanging.''' Forced complications. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Forced complications.''} 15. a5 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'A contribution of the Indian GM Adhiban, who presented the move in 2013.''' The consensus is that this is the best. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'The consensus is that this is the best.''} Nf4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'Black has no choice due to the two hanging pieces.'''} 16. Ne3 c6 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'All Black's moves are forced.'''} 17. h4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'White has no choice either.'''} Rad8 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'We have arrived at a junction. White can choose which bishop to capture.''' And here White is at a principled crossroad. There are two attempts, as there are two bishops that can be captured. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'And here White is at a principled crossroad. There are two attempts, as there are two bishops that can be captured.''} 18. g3 $5 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Diagram [#]''Diagram [#] Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'Concrete play continues after' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Diagram [#]'''} Nh5 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'N!' 'N!''- and of course he knew about this radical solution. Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'N!' 'N!' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '- and of course he knew about this radical solution.''' In 2013, in the game betweed Adhiban and Ashwin, Black wasn't aware of this forced line just yet and played 18...Bc8?. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'In 2013, in the game betweed Adhiban and Ashwin, Black wasn't aware of this forced line just yet and played 18...Bc8?.''} 19. Nh2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!'''} Bc8 $1 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '!' Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'The only move again.''' The crucial intermezzo, intending to throw out the d8 queen with a check. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'The crucial intermezzo, intending to throw out the d8 queen with a check.''} 20. Ba2 $1 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '!' Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'White also has no choice again.''' Forced as well. Now Black has no checks. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Forced as well. Now Black has no checks.''} Rf8 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'One of a few equalisers.''' After the game JKD said that he expected Vidit to follow a correspondence game with 20...0-0 which leads to a draw. There seems to be nothing wrong with Vidit's solution either. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'After the game JKD said that he expected Vidit to follow a correspondence game with 20...0-0 which leads to a draw. There seems to be nothing wrong with Vidit's solution either.''} 21. Qe2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!''' The best. Now we reach an endgame by force. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'The best. Now we reach an endgame by force.''} Kh8 22. Rad1 Qe7 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'The most accurate.'''} 23. Rd2 Nf6 24. Ng2 Qc7 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'I'm pretty sure both players analysed this position at home. Black has three pawns for a piece, but only two extra pawns on the kingside.''' This is an endgame both players went for. White has a knight for 3 pawns which is a very fine material allocation for the second player, but he does have to watch out a little bit, as the a6 pawn is fixed by the a5 pawn and if the knight is ever to land on b4, Black could get under pressure.  But that will never happen... or will it?  Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'This is an endgame both players went for. White has a knight for 3 pawns which is a very fine material allocation for the second player, but he does have to watch out a little bit, as the a6 pawn is fixed by the a5 pawn and if the knight is ever to land on b4, Black could get under pressure.  But that will never happen... or will it? ''} 25. b4 {'- and so after a forced variation we have the ensuing endgame. Objectively it's level, but in practical terms I think only White can pull it off. Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '- and so after a forced variation we have the ensuing endgame. Objectively it's level, but in practical terms I think only White can pull it off.'''} d5 {I didn't like this particular solution, although it is not a bad move objectively, as the game stays well within the drawable margin. It felt more practical to include 25...b4 26.c4, to get some counterplay with Re8-Re5, or alternatively go for 25...g5!?, giving the king a nice square on g6 behind the pawns and not in front of them.  Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'I didn't like this particular solution, although it is not a bad move objectively, as the game stays well within the drawable margin. It felt more practical to include 25...b4 26.c4, to get some counterplay with Re8-Re5, or alternatively go for 25...g5!?, giving the king a nice square on g6 behind the pawns and not in front of them. ''} 26. Nf1 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'A clever intermediate move, which tries to force Black's king to the g-file''' An annoying check. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'An annoying check.''} Bg4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!''' Allowing the rook trade and going for a very concrete knight vs pawns endgame is not something you want to be dealing with this early in the game, but now the king is somewhat awkwardly placed in front of its pawns. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Allowing the rook trade and going for a very concrete knight vs pawns endgame is not something you want to be dealing with this early in the game, but now the king is somewhat awkwardly placed in front of its pawns.''} 27. f3 $1 {'The combination of my last two moves looks a bit weird, but at least now Black can't play g5 anymore. From now on, both sides could deviate in several moments, but what we did certainly made sense. Giri,Anish: '!' Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'Now Black's king is in front of the g-file and so the advance of the kingside pawns is slowed down.' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'The combination of my last two moves looks a bit weird, but at least now Black can't play g5 anymore. From now on, both sides could deviate in several moments, but what we did certainly made sense.''' Strong. The g-file is free for the rook and the king takes it upon himself to stop the invasion of the rook. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Strong. The g-file is free for the rook and the king takes it upon himself to stop the invasion of the rook.''} Bc8 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!''' Black wants to slowly start pushing his kingside pawns.  Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Black wants to slowly start pushing his kingside pawns. ''} 28. Kh2 d4 29. Rc1 $5 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '!?'' 29.Nf3 may seem automatic at first, but this is a much more clever way to stop the pawns, intending Ne4+. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '29.Nf3 may seem automatic at first, but this is a much more clever way to stop the pawns, intending Ne4+.''} Qe7 30. Rb2 Nh5 {'Diagram [#] Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Diagram [#]'''} 31. c4 $1 {'Directing to the green b4-square. Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'The knight is heading to d3 from where it can get to either f4 or b4.' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Directing to the green b4-square.''' Duda makes one nasty move after the other. Here already I started feeling the heat for Vidit, but the engine still pointed out a cleacut solution- 31...Kh6! 32.Nd3 g5!. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Duda makes one nasty move after the other. Here already I started feeling the heat for Vidit, but the engine still pointed out a cleacut solution- 31...Kh6! 32.Nd3 g5!.''} f5 $6 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '?!'' Fishing for a move repetition is tempting, but it just doesn't bring Black the desired result. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Fishing for a move repetition is tempting, but it just doesn't bring Black the desired result.''} 32. exf5 Rxf5 $2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '?' Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '?!''' Continuing with the wrong intention. White doesn't have to take the draw and this only gives White more time. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Continuing with the wrong intention. White doesn't have to take the draw and this only gives White more time.''} 33. b5 $1 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' Now Black is suddenly in serious trouble. He has to allow either Nb4 or Nf4. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Now Black is suddenly in serious trouble. He has to allow either Nb4 or Nf4.''} Rdf8 {Correct, as 33...c5 34.Nf4! was just losing, with Kf3 coming next and Black's kingside pawns not able to move. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Correct, as 33...c5 34.Nf4! was just losing, with Kf3 coming next and Black's kingside pawns not able to move.''} 34. bxa6 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Diagram [#]''Diagram [#] Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Diagram [#]''' Black has to answer very hard questions, but objectively this seems to still be within the drawing margin of the game. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Black has to answer very hard questions, but objectively this seems to still be within the drawing margin of the game.''} bxa6 $2 {'A very natural and tempting check, but at the same time the losing mistake! Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'This is the decisive mistake.' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'A very natural and tempting check, but at the same time the losing mistake!''' Very tempting, but Vidit has missed JKD's strong sequence. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Very tempting, but Vidit has missed JKD's strong sequence.''} 35. Nd2 $1 {'Now White is winning in a forcing way, and I managed to calculate it almost to the end. Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '+-!' Mikhalevski,V: 'Surprisingly, after this retreat Black is in trouble. White wins the a6-pawn and creates a strong passed pawn.' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Now White is winning in a forcing way, and I managed to calculate it almost to the end.''' The king is now not in the way of any checks, neither by the pawns nor by the rook. A very aesthetically pleasing solution. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'The king is now not in the way of any checks, neither by the pawns nor by the rook. A very aesthetically pleasing solution.''} Qc7 36. Qe4 $1 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' Grabbing the a-file before collecting the a6 pawn. The a5 pawn is now unstoppable and Black is just losing by force. Note that with the king on f3 Black would now have counterplay thanks to g4+ and Rb3-xc3 check, but now that the king is on h1, the counterplay is much too slow. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Grabbing the a-file before collecting the a6 pawn. The a5 pawn is now unstoppable and Black is just losing by force. Note that with the king on f3 Black would now have counterplay thanks to g4+ and Rb3-xc3 check, but now that the king is on h1, the counterplay is much too slow.''} R5f6 37. g4 Nf4 {The last attempt, but JKD is merciless.  Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'The last attempt, but JKD is merciless. ''} (37... Rxf3 38. Nxf3 Nf6 $18 39. Qxg6 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) is also enough for a win.'} e4+) 38. Rcb1 $1 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' Leads to a major piece endgame in which White gets to check first and Black's king has nowhere to hide. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Leads to a major piece endgame in which White gets to check first and Black's king has nowhere to hide.''} Nxd3 39. g5 Re6 40. c5 Nxc5 41. Qc2 e4+ 42. f4 Nd3 {'Tragicomedy Black has three extra pawns at the moment, but an extremely poor placement of his pieces means he is getting checkmated by force. Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'It seems that Black did as much as he could, but White's attack is decisive.' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Tragicomedy Black has three extra pawns at the moment, but an extremely poor placement of his pieces means he is getting checkmated by force.''' All forced so far. Now White starts checking and the king just ends up getting mated. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'All forced so far. Now White starts checking and the king just ends up getting mated.''} 43. Bxe6 Nxf4 44. gxh6 Be5 45. Kh1 Bxe6 46. Rb7 Qd6 47. Nxe4 Qd5 (47... Qa3) 48. Ng5 (48. Qa4) 48... d3 49. Qf2 Bc8 50. Re7 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'A well-played game by Duda! Strong opening preparation and good endgame technique made their deal. Black's main mistake came on move 34, when Vidit played 34...Re2?, instead of the correct 34...c5. Black's play can also be improved by means of 31...Kh6. Also 25...b4 and 29...Re5 make sense.''' A crucial win, for the eventual World Cup winner. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'A crucial win, for the eventual World Cup winner.''} d2 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) (Giri,Anish) doesn't save Black.} (50... Be6 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof''}) 51. Rxe5 Qxe5 52. Qa7 Bb7 53. Qxb7 1-0


