{[%evp 0,76,5,27,40,40,39,13,8,-17,-22,-63,-36,17,17,-40,9,-13,37,13,67,70,63,-55,-4,-23,13,13,37,-1,-1,-18,8,13,11,-6,2,-42,-29,-29,-17,-34,-39,-39,-40,-40,-25,-31,-26,-54,-18,-63,-49,-71,-66,-71,-62,-62,-155,-207,-202,-204,-266,-279,-158,-229,-108,-223,-228,-265,-301,-301,-361,-545,-621,-675,-328,-429,-397] This was the 1st time in my World Cup experience that I had gone beyond Round 3. All the matches so far had been quite hard fought and this one was no exception. In the 1st game, after I missed a winning chance, I was lost for the most part but Durarbeyli hadn't been able to finish it off.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d6 {I hadn't played the Archangelsk before, but that didn't seem to surprise my opponent too much. He blitzed out his next moves anyways.} 7. Nbd2 Ne7 8. d4 {Mikhalevski,V: 'The third most popular move in the position. This line was tested by Svidler in two recent games, but probably what inspired the Azeri player was Nakamura's win over Carlsen in 2020.'} (8. Re1 c6 9. Ba4 Bb6 10. d4 Ng6 11. h3 exd4 12. cxd4 $11 {leads to a crazy draw.} d5 $1 $17 13. e5 Nh5 14. Nf1 Nhf4 15. Bc2 f6 16. Ng3 fxe5 $17 17. Bxg6 {with the same idea of e5-c4 was more effective.} Nxg6 $1 {was better, with the idea of} 18. Bg5 Qc7 19. Nxe5 Nxe5 20. Rxe5 h6 21. Bh4 Qf7 $19 {with a technically won position.} 22. Nh5 Be6 $19 23. Re3 Bd8 $1 24. Rf3 Qxf3 $1 {and the pin is really annoying.} 25. gxf3 Bxh4 26. Kg2 Rf7 27. Rc1 Raf8 28. Rc3 Bg5 29. Ng3 {would win a piece, but it's not so clear.} Re7 {was another way to keep the bishop tied in. In some lines the queen ends up on a1, which seemed a little odd to me.} 30. b4 {Mikhalevski,V: '?' Mikhalevski,V: 'loses to' now loses a piece to} a6 $1 $19 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'with a double attack on a2 and e2.'} 31. a4 {Mikhalevski,V: 'looks suicidal, as the light-squared bishop can never get out of b1.' is a type of move which is extremely difficult to make! Just look at the bishop on b1 :)} Bd7 $1 {was the only way to avoid the trick in the game} {Unfortunately for White} 32. Qb3 $2 {is strongly met by} Kh8 33. b5 cxb5 34. axb5 Bxb5 $1 35. Qxd5 Rd7 36. Qe4 Bc6 37. Rxc6 bxc6 $1 $17 {The key move, which secures Black's advantage thanks to the strong position of the knight on e5.}) 8... exd4 9. cxd4 Bb6 {Mikhalevski,V: 'Black has to part with this bishop.'} 10. Bd3 Bg4 11. h3 {Mikhalevski,V: 'This line doesn't score well for White lately.'} Bh5 12. Qb3 ({or} 12. Nb3 d5 13. e5 Ne4 14. Qc2 Nc6 $19 15. Bxe4 dxe4 $1 16. Qxe4 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Nxd4 $1 18. Qxb7 Nxb3 19. axb3 Qd3 20. Qf3 Rad8 21. Ra3 Qxf3 $19 22. gxf3 $1 $19 {was also strong. Mikhalevski,V: '-+'} {Mikhalevski,V: 'After the correct'} f6 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'Black would have to retreat the knight to g6 instead of c4.'} 23. exf6 {Mikhalevski,V: '?' Direct.} Rxf6 24. b4 {[%cal Gc4d2] doesn't lead to much} Rd4 $3 {Mikhalevski,V: '!'} 25. Rb3 {It looks like the bishop on b1 is lost, but White gets unexpected counterplay on the kingside.} Rc4 $1 {Mikhalevski,V: 'and the bishop on b1 is untouchable.'} 26. f4 $1 {Keeping an eye on the king.} Rg6+ 27. Kh1 Bxf2 $1 28. Rxf2 Rxc1+ $1 {Mikhalevski,V: '=!' Mikhalevski,V: 'and the bishop suddenly escapes from a2.'} 29. Kh2 Kf7 $1 $11 {And finally with a series of accurate moves, the white bishop gets a second life :)} 30. Rc3 Rc6 $3 {followed by either Rd7 or f6.} 31. Rxc1 $2 Rxc1 32. b3 Kf6 33. Ra2 Kf5 $1 34. Rxa7 Kxf4 $1 35. Ra2 Ke3 36. Kg2 h5 $1 $18 37. h4 {White has an unexpected resource here as well. Chess is full of amazing ideas, sadly they usually are left behind the scenes as humans can't yet play like Stockfish!} Kf4 38. Ra5 Rc2+ $3 {Black has bank rank problems!} 39. Kf1 g6 40. Rg5 Kf3 41. Kg1 $1 Rc6) 12... d5 {Mikhalevski,V: 'Although Black created a backward pawn on d6 and weakened the d5-square with his last two moves he also restricted White's light-squared bishop, which later became White's main problem.'} 13. e5 Nd7 $5 $146 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'A strong novelty from the Indian Grandmaster. Black forces an exchange of the dark-squared bishop.' An interesting direct approach to target the dark-squared bishop. Also, a move which made my opponent finally stop and have a think.} 14. Qc2 {Mikhalevski,V: 'This provocative move looks a little risky, but playable.'} h6 15. b4 a5 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'A safe move. Now White has to solve the problem of his bishop.'} 16. bxa5 Rxa5 17. Bb2 Bxf3 {Mikhalevski,V: '!?' A slight inaccuracy. Starting directly with b4 would avoid some options.} 18. Nxf3 {Mikhalevski,V: 'White's idea is to move the knight and play c3 in order to free the bishop.'} c5 19. Bc3 {Mikhalevski,V: '?' Mikhalevski,V: 'If the previous move was slightly inaccurate, the text is a serious mistake.' The position felt fairly equal. So far, I had played all my moves at a fast speed. I realized that if White manages to play c2-c3 and remove the bishop, he would be quite comfortable.} Ra8 $1 {A very tricky move, which I feel made me win the game! Vasif thought that e6-g4 was the only threat in the position. But, I had a cunning idea up my sleeve.} 20. e6 $6 {Mikhalevski,V: '!'} fxe6 $1 {Mikhalevski,V: 'Nice play against the light-squared bishop.'} 21. Qe2 Rf7 $1 22. Qxe6 Nf8 23. Qe2 c4 {Mikhalevski,V: '' Mikhalevski,V: 'The bishop is trapped on b1 and White is in trouble.' Now we see the point of b6. I could have reached the same position without h3 & b6 included, but then White could have played a2 and freed the bishop.} 24. Bc2 Nc6 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'Vidit stops 25.Ba2 and reaches a virtually winning position.' It's important to keep the bishop on b1 boxed in! Now if I manage to get my knight to c4-d2, it would just be winning. Although, it's not easy as my c3 pawn is constantly under pressure.} 25. a4 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'The Azeri GM is trying to create counterplay on the kingside. Unfortunately for him he doesn't have enough resources.'} Qe7 $1 {Important decision. Initially I was trying all the queen moves to protect c3 and then bring the knight to d2. But, in all the lines White gets some sort of counterplay.} 26. Qd1 {In order to play f4.} Ne6 {Mikhalevski,V: '?!' Mikhalevski,V: 'This move is inaccurate.' Defending the pawn in order to play c4-d2. Surprisingly, White had an unexpected defensive idea here.} 27. Rb1 $6 {Mikhalevski,V: '?' Mikhalevski,V: 'White misses a chance to set some problems.' Missing the only chance in the game.} Ba7 $1 {Mikhalevski,V: 'The Indian player protects the c3-pawn in order to bring the knight to c4.' Now everything is secure. There is no way for White to stop the idea of e5-c4-d2.} 28. Bg6 Rf6 29. Bh5 Nf4 30. Ne5 Nxh5 31. Qxh5 {The attack on the kingside looked dangerous, but it's harmless. The key for Black is not to hurry in capturing the bishop on b1, it's dead anyways. Once he brings back his  in defense, White is doomed.} Nxe5 {Mikhalevski,V: '-+!' Mikhalevski,V: 'Black wins the b1-bishop.'} 32. dxe5 Rf4 $1 $19 {Mikhalevski,V: '!'} 33. e6 d4 34. Qd5 dxc3 35. Rxb7 Qc5 36. Qd7 Qd4 $1 {Finally the poor soul is captured!} 37. Rd1 Qxd7 38. exd7 Bxf2+ {Mikhalevski,V: 'A nice positional achievement for the Indian Grandmaster. 13.. .Nh5 looks like a strong novelty, which promises Black equal chances. Probably 11.f4 is a better attempt to fight for an opening advantage.' My opponent resigned and I was through to Quarterfinals! I received many nice messages after the game, but the message of my coach Alon Greenfeld stood out: " Congrats,Vidit for the win, in my long career, I have never seen a pawn on the 1st rank!" That aptly summarizes the game! :)} 39. Kh2 Rd4 $19 0-1


