{[%evp 0,119,25,29,36,5,5,4,17,8,35,38,15,14,14,11,2,-6,2,0,72,53,38,-3,-11,-2,-5,-27,-24,-34,-33,-40,-33,-28,-44,-58,-14,-24,-40,-63,31,53,36,58,32,22,72,74,77,54,76,46,51,58,59,77,77,71,71,49,70,26,32,12,41,15,30,26,38,61,55,53,63,17,34,35,48,48,48,21,47,56,56,-3,76,89,76,81,94,85,91,87,87,92,97,104,113,95,104,93,113,120,120,121,115,127,131,131,133,145,150,150,176,176,302,306,312,294,317,317,1094,1115]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Vienna Variation} Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 $5 {Not the main move, but interesting.} 5. Bxc6 dxc6 $1 {Now the idea behind 4...b4 is clear} 6. Nbd2 Nd7 7. Nc4 f6 $1 8. Bd2 $1 {I find this the most challenging for Black here.} Nf8 9. b4 Be7 $1 {Mikhalevski,V: 'An obvious improvement, which has already been seen in modern practice.' A very cool reaction by Black. The point of this move is to delay short castling for a bit!} 10. Nh4 g6 11. O-O $5 {Mikhalevski,V: '?!' Mikhalevski,V: 'A dubious novelty. It was unnecessary to leave Black with the bishop pair.' Trying too keep some chances.} Ne6 {Mikhalevski,V: '?!' Mikhalevski,V: 'Black shouldn't be afraid of the few active moves White could make after the correct 11...Bf7!'} 12. g3 O-O 13. Ng2 b6 {Mikhalevski,V: ''} 14. Kh1 c5 15. a3 {Mikhalevski,V: 'Firouzja is looking for activity and transfers the queen to g3.' So here I was optimistic about my attacking chances. In this position the idea is to bring the queen to g3, the bishop to b2 and put pressure on the pawn on f6!} Bb7 16. Bh6 Rf7 $5 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' Planning to attack the weaknesses of White's queenside structure by ...a4!} 17. c3 {First preventing the queen trade on g4!} Qd7 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'Vidit attacks White's pawn weaknesses.'} 18. Qe2 $5 {Mikhalevski,V: 'Alireza prefers activity over a pawn.' White should be careful to not lose the c2-pawn because after that the whole position would collapse.} Rd8 {Mikhalevski,V: '!'} 19. Rad1 $5 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'A clever move, which shocked the Indian player.' A very tricky move both targeting the f6-pawn and maybe trapping the queen on a2!} cxb4 {Mikhalevski,V: '?' Mikhalevski,V: 'Black panics.' Here my opponent thought the queen was more important than the f6-pawn!} 20. axb4 {Mikhalevski,V: 'After winning back the f6-pawn the dark a1-h8 diagonal will also be weak.'} c5 {Mikhalevski,V: '?'} 21. bxc5 $16 {Now the bishop on b2 will be just a monster!} Nxc5 22. f3 {Mikhalevski,V: '' Mikhalevski,V: 'The advantage changed hands quickly.'} Nxd3 $1 {Mikhalevski,V: 'Vidit is looking for an escape in an endgame.' With the queens on the board Black will probably get mated on g7!} 23. Nb2 Qh3 24. Nxd3 {So now there still is a target on g7, and one on d6!} Qxh6 {Mikhalevski,V: '?!' Mikhalevski,V: 'Passive defence. Black's idea is to cover the f5-square.' Stopping f5} 25. Qa2 a5 26. Nb2 {Mikhalevski,V: '!'} Qf8 27. Qe6 {Mikhalevski,V: '' Mikhalevski,V: '28.Nf5 is a threat again.'} Bc5 28. Na4 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' Now all of my pieces are in the game.} Bc8 29. Qc4 {Mikhalevski,V: 'Too soft.'} Rxd1 30. Rxd1 Kg7 31. Nxc5 {Still trying to put pressure on the kingside.} Qxc5 32. Qxc5 bxc5 {Mikhalevski,V: '?!'} 33. Ra1 Ra7 34. Ne3 Be6 35. Kg1 a4 36. Ra3 f5 $1 37. Kf2 f4 38. Nd1 Bb3 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'Black has to counter attack White's pawns.'} 39. Ke1 Bxd1 {Mikhalevski,V: '?!'} 40. Kxd1 {So here we both were under time pressure, and Black still has to solve some problems.} c4 41. g4 g5 42. Kc2 Ra6 43. Kb1 Rb6+ $2 {Mikhalevski,V: 'This is an obvious mistake. Black had to force White's pawns to dark squares in order to blockade them.' A very big mistake. After this things just get tougher for Black.} 44. Kc2 $18 Rh6 45. Rxa4 Rxh2+ 46. Kd1 Rf2 47. Ra7+ Kg6 48. Ra6+ {And now this is just a technical win.} Kf7 49. Ra7+ Ke6 50. Ra6+ Kd7 51. Ra7+ Kc6 52. Ra6+ {Mikhalevski,V: '+-' Mikhalevski,V: 'Now White wins thanks to the kingside pawn on g3, as Black can give up the bishop for two connected passed pawns.'} Kb5 53. Re6 Ka4 54. Rxe5 h6 55. Re6 Kb3 56. Rxh6 Rxf3 57. Rg6 Rd3+ 58. Ke2 Kxc3 59. Rxg5 Re3+ (59... f3+ 60. Kf2 Kd4 61. Rd5+ (61. Rf5 c3 62. g5 c2 63. Rd5+ $11 {or} Kc4) 61... Kxe4 62. Rc5 Rd2+ {and Black shouldn't have problems to hold.} 63. Kf1 $1 {Once again Black had to choose an active defence.} Kf4 64. Rxc4+ Kg3 65. Rc1 Rh2) 60. Kf2 Rxe4 61. Rg8 Kd3 62. g5 $18 {The dubious opening experiment with 11.Nf4?! Can't be recommended. Instead 11.Nxd5 is equal. Moreover, the entire line promises White no advantage, after 11...Bf7! Black is better.} c3 63. Rd8+ Kc2 $1 {giving up the a7-pawn for a very nice blockade on the light squares.} (63... Rd4 64. Rxd4+ $11 {or} Kxd4 65. g6 c2 66. g7 c1=Q 67. g8=Q {with a dead draw.} Qe3+ $1 68. Kf1 Qf3+ 69. Kg1) 64. Kf3 Re7 65. Kxf4 Rg7 66. Rc8 Kb2 1-0


