{[%evp 0,71,58,42,26,-29,-22,-14,0,-16,45,46,101,42,75,-26,81,82,82,81,82,59,67,34,51,22,78,60,73,94,138,58,126,101,164,145,145,58,117,72,64,62,62,68,72,132,132,117,123,137,140,130,159,34,871,42,286,286,219,253,247,248,322,322,340,316,316,308,308,308,408,439,438,423]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 {This system, popularized largely by Wesley So, has been played in some high level games recently. Black is trying to force matters to the maximum and in the main line the queens come off very quickly.} 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. e4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ng5 Be6 {The endgame is obviously very equalish, but Black does have some development issues and has to somehow find a good spot for the king and get his rooks connected.} 10. Bb5 $5 $146 {A new idea, which could be not so easy to meet, for an unprepared opponent, if he either hasn't seen this move, or doesn't recall how to react to it. Black has a few ways to play, but sometimes having options can also be an issue. The clock is ticking.} a6 11. Ba4 Nbd7 {This is a reasonable way of playing, especially if followed up well.} 12. O-O b5 $2 {[%csl Ra8,Rd8,Rh8] The right move here was Nc5, though Black would still need to spend some time arranging his pieces. At the end of the day, he's got that king on d8 and rooks are yet to get connected.} (12... Nc5 {is fine, an example line could be:} 13. Rd1+ Ke7 14. Bc2 Rc8 $1 {Useful move, bringing the rook into the game.} 15. Be3 h6 16. Bxc5+ Rxc5 17. Ngxe4 {and now if xe4 xe4, Black still has some small problems, so the easiest is to just drop back the rook.} Rc7 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7] Intending g6 followed by g7. White gave up the dark squared bishop for some tempi, but in the long run that is not ideal. Black has fully equalized here.}) (12... Bb4 $5 {[%cal Gd8e7] is also not bad, intending Ke7.}) 13. Bb3 $1 {A very unpleasant move to face. Suddenly there is a real threat and Black is not in time to get the f8 bishop out, before going Ke7.} Ke7 14. Be3 $1 {[%csl Rc5,Rf8] Controlling the c5-square and stopping c5. The opening clearly hadn't worked out for Black. White is fully mobilising, while Black has yet to finish his development.} h6 15. Ngxe4 {Taking on e6 was also possible, but I didn't feel the need to create pawn weaknesses, instead I wanted to keep the e-file open and try and use it to trouble the black king, while Black will be busy developing his f8 bishop.} Ke8 $2 {This is way too slow. Black still needs two moves to connect his rooks- b4 and e7 and even when he does, the king on e7 will still be vulnerable.} (15... Nxe4 $1 16. Nxe4 Bxb3 17. axb3 Ke6 {This would be a strong sequence. Black king is vulnerable out there in the open, but at least the position is very simplified and there is hope to escape with just a scare.} 18. Rad1 Bb4 (18... Ne5 19. Ng3 $1 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5] intending f4-f5 would still be very nasty.}) 19. Rd4 a5 20. Bd2 {Black is facing some concrete issues here. Not pleasant, but the material is limited and there are some drawish tendencies, after for example} Nf6 $1 {leading to a drawish pawn down rook endgame.}) 16. Bd4 {There were many ways to exploit White's huge superiority in piece activity and king's safety.} Bb4 17. Rae1 $5 {Of course the 'normal' 17.fe1 is also good, but I was very happy with this fancy idea, especially as I managed to calculate what happened in the game all the way till move 23.} Ke7 18. f4 $1 {The point of keeping the f1 rook behind the pawn.} Rhd8 $2 {Black is hoping to connect his rooks, with tactical means, but I was fortunate enough to have anticipated well in advance that this clever defence doesn't work. There was no real good move at this point, but as the text move is losing, I have to attach a question mark. xe4 or f8 were objectively less lost.} 19. f5 Bxb3 20. Nxf6+ Kf8 {and now the point.} 21. Nh5 $1 {The bishop on b3 is still hanging and the g7 pawn is falling.} Bc4 22. Bxg7+ Kg8 23. Rf4 {White is winning here. Besides being up a pawn, I have also got the attack.} Kh7 (23... f6 {was a tougher defence.} 24. Rg4 Kf7 25. Rg6 $1 {White is still winning, but it is a little more messy than the game.}) 24. Rg4 Rg8 25. Ne4 {The rest is straightforward and the only remarkable thing that happened from now onwards was a beautiful mate in 6 that I missed.} Be7 26. Rd1 Be2 27. Rxd7 {I saw a forced win a few moves ago, so I just went for it, but I missed an insanely pretty finish.} (27. Rd6 $3 {deflecting the bishop and setting up a Rxh6 checkmate.} f6 28. Rxd7 $1 {and now it's just checkmate, as there is no pawn on f7 in the way.} Bxg4 29. Nexf6+ Bxf6 30. Nxf6#) 27... Bxg4 28. Rxe7 Bxh5 29. Be5 {I was aiming for this position. Black is completely hopeless.} Rad8 30. h3 {Everything wins, but this is the cleanest.} Rd1+ 31. Kh2 Rc8 32. Nf6+ Kg7 33. Nxh5+ Kf8 34. Ra7 Rd5 35. Bg7+ Kg8 36. Nf6+ {You don't often get to score such clean victories in a rapid game, so I was certainly happy with this one.} 1-0


