1. d4 {[%emt 0:00:00] Fernandez,D} f5 {[%emt 0:00:31]} 2. g3 {[%emt 0:02:48]} Nf6 {[%emt 0:00:13]} 3. Bg2 {[%emt 0:00:05]} g6 {[%emt 0:00:16]} 4. Nd2 {[%emt 0:09:42] A slightly rare line and maybe one which indicates a degree of fear. White is trying to get e4 in and swap pieces quickly. Normal are c4 or f3:} (4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 {is the main position of the Leningrad Dutch and now Black chooses between ..c6, ...c6 and ...e8.}) (4. Nh3 $5 Bg7 5. Nf4 {is a creative path chosen a few times by Kamsky when forced to play against his own system!}) 4... Bg7 {[%emt 0:13:20]} 5. e4 {[%emt 0:01:25]} fxe4 {[%emt 0:00:16]} 6. Nxe4 {[%emt 0:00:36]} Nxe4 {[%emt 0:00:11]} 7. Bxe4 {[%emt 0:00:04]} d5 {[%emt 0:00:12]} (7... O-O 8. Ne2 e5 $5 9. dxe5 Nc6 10. f4 d6 {is a more adventurous way for Black to play, probably getting dynamic equality}) 8. Bg2 {[%emt 0:13:23]} Nc6 {[%emt 0:00:25]} 9. Ne2 {[%emt 0:08:35]} (9. c3 e5 10. Be3 exd4 11. cxd4 O-O 12. Ne2 Bg4 {was already really comfortable for Black in Arkell,K -Pruijssers,R chess.com INT 2017} 13. Qb3 Bxe2 14. Qxd5+ Kh8 15. Qxd8 Raxd8 16. Bxc6 Ba6 17. Be4 Bxd4 18. Bxd4+ Rxd4 19. f3 Rfd8 20. Kf2 Rd2+ 21. Ke3 Rxb2 22. h4 Re2+ 23. Kf4 Rf8+ 24. Kg4 b6 25. h5 gxh5+ 26. Kxh5 Rg8 27. g4 Bc8 28. g5 Bd7 29. Rad1 Be6 30. Kh6 Rxe4 31. fxe4 Bg4 {0-1 (31) Arkell,K (2438)-Pruijssers,R (2502) chess.com INT 2017}) 9... Bg4 {[%emt 0:07:07]} (9... e5 $5 {is a bit sharper, and makes White commit to a central structure change of some kind, otherwise we just end up with the previous note.} 10. dxe5 (10. O-O exd4 11. Nf4 O-O 12. Bxd5+ Kh8 $132) 10... Nxe5 11. Qxd5 Qxd5 12. Bxd5 c6 13. Be4 Bg4 (13... O-O $5 $44) 14. h3 Bf3 $6 {Now in my personal experience with this line- from the White side- I was able to slowly neutralise the compensation and go on to win:} 15. Bxf3 Nxf3+ 16. Kf1 O-O 17. Kg2 Rae8 18. Be3 $14 {Fernandez,D-Sanders,I London 2016}) 10. f3 $6 {[%emt 0:02:50] Blunting the bishop cannot be clever and now White has no chance of an opening edge.} (10. c3 $1 e5 (10... O-O 11. h3 {is not really independent, because now the bishop on g4 needs to think of something to do other than take the knight.}) 11. h3 Bxe2 12. Qxe2 O-O 13. Qb5 {Reaching a position which has been played twice from the White side by Croatian grandmaster Nenad Sulava.} exd4 14. Qxd5+ Kh8 15. O-O Qxd5 $1 (15... dxc3 $6 16. bxc3 (16. Qxd8 Raxd8 17. bxc3 Bxc3 18. Rb1 $14) 16... Qxd5 17. Bxd5 Nb4 18. Bg2 $14 {Sulava,N-Vallejo Pons,F Toscolano 1997, White even managed to win in 7 further moves here.}) 16. Bxd5 Rad8 17. Bg2 (17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. cxd4 Bxd4 $11 {Sulava,N-Santo Roman,M Saint Affrique 1998}) 17... Rf7 $5 {Black doesn't take the pawn yet, and just improves. It is not clear to me whether White has some way to continue pressing.}) 10... Bf5 $146 {[%emt 0:01:06]} (10... Be6 11. c3 Qd7 12. O-O Bh3 13. Bxh3 Qxh3 14. Nf4 Qd7 15. Re1 Nd8 16. Qe2 Bf6 17. Nd3 O-O 18. Nc5 Qh3 19. Bf4 c6 20. Bc7 b6 21. Nd3 Nf7 22. g4 Ng5 23. Rf1 Rf7 24. Bg3 Raf8 25. Nf2 Qh6 26. Kg2 Bh8 27. f4 Rxf4 28. Bxf4 Rxf4 29. Qxe7 Bg7 30. Rad1 Bf8 31. Qe8 Nf3 32. Qe6+ Kh8 33. Nh3 Qxh3+ 34. Kxh3 Ng5+ 35. Kg3 Nxe6 36. Rxf4 Bd6 37. Re1 Nxf4 38. Re8+ Kg7 39. Rd8 Ne2+ 40. Kf3 {Gerusel,M-Henningsen,J Voelklingen 1970 1-0}) 11. O-O {[%emt 0:16:20]} Qd6 {[%emt 0:23:19]} 12. c3 {[%emt 0:08:33]} (12. Bf4 Qb4 {was presumably what White was afraid of, but the machine informs us that the pawn sacrifices are fully playable for White.} 13. c3 Qxb2 14. g4 Bd7 15. Rb1 Qxa2 16. Rxb7 $132) 12... e5 $6 {[%emt 0:03:13]} (12... O-O-O {first was a more stable order.}) 13. Be3 {[%emt 0:03:26] Not leading to a disadvantage, but not particularly incisive either.} (13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nd4 O-O-O {Else f4 and e1 motifs come into play.} 15. Nxf5 gxf5 16. Qc2 $14) 13... O-O-O {[%emt 0:03:34]} 14. Qd2 {[%emt 0:06:31]} h5 {[%emt 0:04:41]} 15. Rae1 $6 {[%emt 0:05:03]} (15. Bg5 {was worth considering, but if Black had wished to emulate the play of his countryman, then in addition to normal moves leading to a slightly more pleasant position (...f6, etc) there was also the violent} h4 $5 $44) 15... h4 {[%emt 0:01:47]} 16. g4 {[%emt 0:01:01]} h3 $1 {[%emt 0:00:13] Else White consolidates by playing h3 herself.} 17. Bh1 {[%emt 0:00:04]} Bd7 {[%emt 0:01:02]} 18. Rd1 {[%emt 0:08:41]} Rde8 {[%emt 0:12:58]} 19. dxe5 $2 {[%emt 0:04:57]} (19. Rfe1 {still asks the question of how Black is going to try and break in, although the obvious choices like} Rhf8 $17 {still leave Black quite obviously better}) 19... Qxe5 {[%emt 0:05:42]} 20. Bd4 {[%emt 0:00:05]} Nxd4 {[%emt 0:00:15]} 21. Nxd4 {[%emt 0:00:03]} Bxg4 $2 {[%emt 0:08:19] Maybe marring the victory a bit.} (21... Qd6 $19 {or similar left White with essentially no moves}) 22. Rde1 {[%emt 0:10:45]} (22. fxg4 Bh6 $19) (22. Rfe1 $1 {was the better rook move, leaving White's king a flight square.} Qh5 23. Rxe8+ Rxe8 24. fxg4 Qxg4+ 25. Kf2 (25. Kf1 Rf8+ 26. Nf3 Rxf3+ 27. Bxf3 Qxf3+ 28. Ke1 Bf6 $15 {Black is better, with his adequate number of pawns for the exchange plus continuing attack, but he has to win again.}) 25... Bh6 26. Qxh6 Qxd1 27. Qxh3+ Kb8 28. Bf3 {Here White seems to be surviving with some machine precision, though in a game you would still take Black.}) 22... Qh5 {[%emt 0:00:46]} 23. Rxe8+ {[%emt 0:01:24]} Rxe8 {[%emt 0:00:02]} 24. fxg4 {[%emt 0:01:40]} Qxg4+ {[%emt 0:00:08]} 25. Kf2 {[%emt 0:00:17]} Qh4+ {[%emt 0:01:08]} 26. Kg1 {[%emt 0:00:55]} ({After} 26. Kf3 Bh6 {also wins trivially}) 26... Bh6 {[%emt 0:00:14] Not a completely flawless game by Black (moves 9, 12 and 21) but a very nice finish nevertheless. Meanwhile, both sides- and most Dutch players for that matter - should probably pay a bit more attention to this sideline.} 0-1


