1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 b5 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Kb1 Qb6 {Both players decide not to deviate from a theoretical discussion in the line which occurred in their last encounter.} 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. f5 h5 14. fxe6 fxe6 15. Qe1 $1 {Sergey did his homework, and now he comes up with a different approach. White's setup is now quite flexible, so many tactical ideas like Nc3-d5 are at his disposal.} (15. Bd3 {is what he played last time.}) 15... Kf7 {Santosh Gujrathi again prefers to host his king in the centre.} ({After} 15... O-O-O 16. Bd3 Qc5 17. Ne2 Rg8 18. Qa5 Bb7 19. a4 $36 {Black's king was rather unsafe in Ragger,M - Georgiadis,N Switzerland 2019}) 16. Bd3 Bh6 $6 {This innovation was nicely refuted by Sergey.} (16... Be7 {was mostly tested in corr. games. However, the plan with ...Rag8 and h5-h4 doesn't look attractive enough, in my opinion.} 17. Rf1 Rag8 18. Ne2 $1 Rxg2 19. Nf4 {looks scary to the second player. The g-file is open in White's favor, while the Kb1 is absolutely safe. Indeed, the following corr. game demonstrates White's attacking possibilities:} Rg5 20. h4 Rgg8 21. Be2 $1 Bxe4 22. Bxb5 ({Weaker is} 22. Bxh5+ Rxh5 23. Qxe4 d5 $132) 22... Qb7 23. Bc4 d5 24. Rd4 $36 {Black's king feels very unsafe. Fedorov,S - Churkina,N ICCF email 2015}) 17. Rf1 Qe3 ({The standard} 17... Qc5 $2 {runs into} 18. Nd5 $1 exd5 19. e5 {with a decisive attack:} Bg7 20. exf6 Bf8 21. Qg3 $18) (17... Raf8 18. e5 dxe5 19. Qxe5 Ke7 20. Qg3 Rhg8 21. Qh4 $36) 18. Ne2 $1 Bxe4 $2 {A blunder.} ({After} 18... Rac8 19. Rf3 Qc5 20. c3 Qe5 21. Nd4 Bb7 22. Rf2 {Black's setup is dicey, but there is still plenty of play.}) 19. Bxe4 $2 ({Strangely enough, both players missed} 19. Qh4 $1 $18 {, and Black's position collapses.}) 19... Qxe4 20. Qf2 {Still, White's initiative outweighs the pawn.} f5 21. Rd3 $6 ({Stronger was} 21. Ng3 $1 Qe3 22. Nxf5 Qxf2 23. Nxd6+ Ke7 24. Rxf2 Rhf8 25. Ne4 $16) 21... d5 $6 ({In turn Black should have played} 21... Bg7 $1 22. Nd4 Bxd4 23. Rxd4 Qe5 $132 {the queen's centralization makes it possible for Black to secure his king.}) 22. Nd4 Rae8 23. Re1 ({It made sense to play the 'quiet'} 23. a3 $1 {, leaving Black under big pressure.}) 23... Qf4 24. Rf3 $6 {This turns out to be ineffective since the piece sacrifice on f5 doesn't work.} ({More to the point was} 24. Nf3 Bg7 25. Qb6 Re7 26. g3 $36) 24... Qd6 25. a3 Bg7 26. c3 Bf6 {Obviously, Black's setup is much more harmonious than before.} 27. g3 Rhg8 (27... Qb6 $5) 28. h3 {Sergey's strategy at this point was to maintain the tension until Black loses his sense of danger.} Be5 29. Qe2 ({Deserving of serious attention is} 29. Qe3 $5) 29... Bxd4 $2 {A big concession - now the dark squares in Black's camp are very exposed.} ({Black should have continued:} 29... Bxg3 30. Ref1 f4 31. Rxg3 Rxg3 32. Qxh5+ Rg6 33. Qh7+ Kf6 {, and he is out of danger.}) 30. cxd4 Rxg3 $2 {Alas, GM Vidit doesn't stand the pressure.} ({After} 30... Re7 31. Rc3 Rg5 {White also has a powerful initiative, but he still has to find a way to break through.}) 31. Rxf5+ exf5 32. Qxe8+ Kf6 33. Qxh5 ({Simpler was} 33. Rc1 $1 $18) 33... Qf4 34. Qh8+ $2 {This move offers Black some hope.} (34. h4 $1 Re3 35. Qg5+ $18) 34... Kg6 $2 ({It was necessary to play} 34... Kg5 35. Qd8+ Kh5 36. Qxd5 Kh4 $16 {, and Black is still in the game.}) 35. Re6+ Kf7 36. Qe8+ (36. Qf6+ $1 Kg8 37. Re8+ Kh7 38. Rh8#) 36... Kg7 37. Qe7+ Kg8 38. Qd8+ Kg7 39. Qf6+ Kg8 40. Re8+ Kh7 41. Rh8# 1-0


