1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 {By choosing the Classical GM Vidit shows his aggressive mood, the unfavorable match situation forced him to push for a win with both colors.} 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 (9. f3 {is a relatively quiet choice, but Sergey rarely deviates from the main theoretical paths.}) 9... b5 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Kb1 Qb6 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. f5 {Again, the most common. White immediately starts to put pressure on the weak spot in Black's camp.} (13. Bd3 b4 14. Ne2 h5 15. f5 Bh6 {is fine for Black, as was demonstrated in Kryvoruchko,Y (2678)-Ivanchuk,V (2731) FIDE World Cup, Tromso 2013 [Richard Palliser]}) (13. Qe1 $5 {was covered in detail in many old games, but recently it went out of fashion.}) 13... h5 {This prophylactic move is the latest fashion.} ({The main alternative -} 13... b4 14. Ne2 e5 15. Ng3 h5 16. Bc4 $1 {This isn't that clear, but the potential danger of Black's setup was well illustrated in Timofeev,A (2570)-Eliseev,U  (2582) Moscow RUS 2016 [Roiz, M]}) 14. fxe6 {The most consistent.} (14. Qe1 {can be well met by} b4 15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. exd5 e5 17. Rd3 Ke7 {Black's king feels quite safe in the centre. This position was tested in a dozen corr. games, and the results are great for Black.}) 14... fxe6 15. Bd3 ({In case of} 15. Qf4 {Black can ignore the obvious threat:} Qc5 16. Qxf6 Qe5 17. Qxe5 dxe5 18. a3 Bc5 $44 {The bishop pair fully compensated for the pawn in Volokitin,A - Kozul,Z Sarajevo 2005}) (15. Qe1 {is covered in Karjakin,S (2752)-Vidit,S  (2726) Chess.com INT 2020}) 15... b4 $1 ({Weaker is} 15... O-O-O 16. Ne2 Qc5 17. Rhf1 $14 {Black didn't have real counterplay, while his king is unsafe and the pawn structure is somewhat dicey. Anand,V - Caruana,F Paris 2019}) 16. Ne2 ({Dubious is} 16. Nd5 $2 exd5 17. exd5 Bd7 18. Rhe1+ Kd8 $17 {, and White doesn't have anything special for the piece.}) 16... Bh6 {A standard way of activating the dark-squared bishop in this line.} 17. Qe1 Qc5 {A decent consolidating move. The Pd6 is covered now, and the queen is heading to e5.} ({It also makes sense to connect the rooks at once:} 17... Ke7 $5 18. Bc4 Qc5 19. b3 Bb5 20. Rd4 Rhg8 21. Qh4 Qe5 {Black had an acceptable position with good counter-attacking chances. Muzychuk,M - Rapport,R Caleta 2016}) 18. Rf1 {The most natural move - White activates the king's rook.} (18. g3 {was employed too, but it looks less threatening} a5 19. Nf4 Kf7 20. Rf1 Rag8 21. e5 $5 {This is the most attractive try} (21. Nxe6 Kxe6 22. Rf5 Qe3 23. Bc4+ Ke7 $132 {Collins,S - Vovk,A Escaldes 2016}) 21... dxe5 22. Nxh5 Bg5 23. Qe2 Ke7 {White had sufficient compensation for the pawn, but hardly more. Ploscaru,S - Zinoviev,P ICCF email 2017}) 18... Ke7 19. b3 {By making this new move Sergey definitely doesn't pretend to refute Black's setup. White makes c4 vacant for his bishop, but it also seriously weakens his king.} ({Harmless is also} 19. Nf4 Bxf4 20. Rxf4 a5 21. Qh4 Raf8 22. Rdf1 Qe5 {The Pf6 is comfortably covered, and Black had no other worries. Gupta,V - Trivedi,K ICCF email 2015}) ({The most challenging seems to be} 19. g3 $5 a5 20. Nf4 Bxf4 21. gxf4 Rhg8 {, though even then Black seems to have enough counterplay along the g-file. For instance,} 22. h3 Raf8 23. Qh4 Rg2 24. e5 Bb5 25. Qxh5 fxe5 26. Qh7+ Rf7 27. Qh4+ Kd7 $11 {Kuna,H - Tellier,B ICCF email 2015}) 19... Bb5 {GM Vidit is aiming to exchange the bishops in a favorable version.} ({There was also nothing wrong with} 19... Rhg8 $5 20. g3 a5 21. Bc4 Rg4 $132) 20. Qh4 {Naturally, White's hopes are mainly connected to attacking Black's weaknesses on the k-side.} ({The other continuations are:} 20. Bxb5 axb5 21. Nd4 Rhc8 22. Qf2 Qe5 $132) (20. Qg3 Qe5 21. Qf3 Bc6 22. Qf2 Rhc8 $132 {In both cases complex, double-edged play is ahead.}) 20... Bg5 21. Qh3 Rhc8 {In turn Black mobilizes all his forces for the counter-attack on the opposite side of the board.} ({Worthy of attention is} 21... Rac8 $5 {, keeping the king's rook on its initial spot for a while.}) 22. Nd4 {A somewhat inaccurate move.} ({After} 22. Nf4 Bxf4 23. Rxf4 Rc6 24. Rdf1 Rf8 {the dynamic balance would have been kept.}) 22... Qxd4 23. Bxb5 Qxe4 {GM Vidit decides to unbalance the position by sacrificing the exchange.} (23... Qe3 $5 24. Qxe3 Bxe3 25. Be2 h4 {offers Black a small advantage, but a top player should be able to hold such an endgame with bishops of opposite colors.}) 24. Bc4 Rxc4 {This was practically forced.} 25. bxc4 Rc8 26. Qxh5 ({Safer was} 26. Qd3 $5 Qxd3 27. cxd3 a5 28. Kc2 d5 29. Kb3 {White's chances are by no means worse in this interesting endgame.}) 26... Rxc4 27. Rf2 Rd4 $2 ({Better was} 27... Rc3 28. Re2 Be3 29. Qf3 Qxf3 30. gxf3 {, but then Black doesn't have any winning chances.}) 28. Rdf1 $2 ({After} 28. Rxd4 Qxd4 29. Qh7+ Kf8 30. Qh8+ Kf7 31. Rf1 {White has every chance to convert his advantage into a full point.}) 28... Qh4 29. Qxh4 {The endgame looks comfortable for Sergey,} ({but after} 29. Qg6 $1 Qe4 30. Qg7+ Kd8 31. g3 Qg4 {Black would have to struggle hard for a draw.}) 29... Rxh4 30. g3 Rh3 31. Kb2 ({Stronger was} 31. Re2 $1 {, preventing Black from activating his bishop} e5 32. Kb2 Ke6 33. Kb3 $14 {Black is gonna be the defending side here.}) 31... Be3 $1 {An important resource. From now on Black can advance his central pawns.} 32. Re2 Bc5 33. Kb3 e5 34. Ka4 Ke6 35. g4 $4 {An extraordinary case where a player of such a high calibre puts his king into a mating net!} ({After} 35. Ka5 f5 36. Kxa6 Rh8 37. Kb7 {the result of the game would still be unclear!}) 35... Ra3# 0-1


