{The World Cup is a very special tournament. It simply can't be compared to any other event. The pressure and schedule of such an event are gruelling. Therefore I was very glad that I had managed to play good chess and advance until round 3. In round 2 I played against Le Quang Liem who had made an impressive showing in Saint Louis a couple of days back.} 1. d4 {Paunovic,Tomislav} (1. Nf3 {Paunovic,Tomislav} d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 {0-1 (70) Le,Q (2739)-Vidit,S (2693) Tbilisi 2017 [Paunovic,Tomislav]}) 1... Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 O-O 8. e3 Bf5 9. Qb3 {My opponent was blitzing out his moves which alerted me a little. Thankfully my memory was working fine that day and I managed to recollect my analysis.} Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3 (10. bxc3 {(Paunovic,Tomislav) - 131/146}) 10... Nbd7 11. Be2 (11. Nd2 {this line was more fresh in my mind as I had seen this game} Rc8 12. Be2 c5 13. O-O Qb6 14. Rfc1 Rfe8 15. Kf1 Ne4 {½-½ (40) Karjakin,S (2783)-Harikrishna,P (2755) Shamkir 2017}) 11... c6 (11... Rc8 {Paunovic,Tomislav} 12. O-O c5 13. dxc5 $1 g5 (13... Nxc5 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Qxf6 gxf6 16. Nd4 $16) 14. Bg3 Nxc5 (14... Ne4 15. Qa3 Ndxc5 16. Rac1 $14) 15. Qa3 $14) 12. Nd2 Ne4 {My opponent was taken aback when I played this. Here I probably realised that he maybe wasn't expecting me to play this.} 13. Bxd8 (13. Nxe4 Qxh4 14. Nd6 {is another way to play.} Bg4 {Paunovic,Tomislav} (14... Be4 {Paunovic,Tomislav} 15. O-O Rab8 $13) 15. g3 Qf6 16. Bxg4 (16. Nxb7 $6 Bxe2 17. Kxe2 Rab8 18. Na5 Nc5 $1 $15) 16... Qxd6 $13) 13... Nxc3 14. bxc3 Rfxd8 {I thought Black is quite comfortable here. He can play ...c5 and maybe double up on the c-file. Whereas White's plan isn't that clear.} 15. f3 c5 16. Kf2 Rac8 17. Rhc1 Rc7 18. e4 {I was very surprised to see this. I was under the impression that White's centre is more of a burden than a strength.} (18. g4 Bh7 19. h4 {expanding on the kingside made sense. Although Black is completely fine.} Rdc8 20. Nb3 Kf8 $11) 18... dxe4 19. fxe4 Bg6 20. Bf3 (20. Ke3 Nf6) 20... Ne5 $5 {I played this after considerable thought. I was confused between various tempting plans.} (20... Rdc8 {reduces the pressure on the d4-pawn.} 21. Nb3 a5 $5 (21... cxd4 22. cxd4 $14) 22. a4 $11) (20... b6 {Paunovic,Tomislav} 21. a4 f5 22. exf5 Bxf5 23. Nb3 Nf6 $36) 21. Ke3 (21. dxe5 {was maybe a concrete way to solve the issue.} Rxd2+ 22. Ke3 Rcd7 23. Rd1 R7d3+ 24. Kf4 Rxd1 25. Rxd1 Rxd1 (25... Rxc3 26. Rd8+ Kh7 27. g4 {and White is better due to the bad bishop on g6}) 26. Bxd1 b5 27. h4 Kf8 28. g4 Ke7 29. Bb3 a5) 21... Nc6 22. Nb3 {Somewhere around here he offered me a draw. With such a comfortable position it would be shameful to accept it!} (22. d5 Ne5 23. c4 Re7 24. g4 f6 {The knight has a fantastic blockade and White's position doesn't inspire much.}) 22... cxd4+ 23. cxd4 Re7 {With the threat of ...xe4 followed by ...f5.} 24. g4 $6 {I was very surprised to see this. White should probably already start his play on the queenside:} (24. e5 {was the only other move I considered} Nb4 (24... f6 25. Bxc6 bxc6 26. Rxc6 Bf7 27. Rc5 Bd5 {looks nice, but fizzles out} 28. Kf2 fxe5 29. dxe5 Rxe5 30. Rac1 $11) 25. Be4 Bxe4 26. Kxe4 f6 27. Rc4 Nc6 28. Rac1 {Here ...fxe5/d5 looked scary but Black has the luxury to prepare this capture!} Ree8 $1 29. g3 fxe5 30. d5 Ne7 $1 $17 {The point!}) (24. Rc5 $1 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '' I must admit that I hadn't seen this resource.} f5 25. e5 f4+ 26. Kf2 $1 (26. Kxf4 Nxd4 27. Nxd4 Rxd4+ 28. Kg3 b6 {looks practically annoying}) 26... Nxd4 27. Rd1 $132) 24... f6 25. Re1 {Again, a very surprising move. It looked a bit slow.} ({Maybe White has to go for active counterplay:} 25. Rc5 Bf7 26. Rd1 Nb4 27. Rd2 b6 $15 {Black is better but compared to game his pieces are more active.}) 25... Bf7 {Most logical, but probably not the best.} (25... Nb4 26. Kd2) (25... Rde8 26. Nd2 a5 $1 {is the computer's suggestion! Black now threatens to play ...d7 and then kick away the knight on b3. Isn't playing ...a5 after the knight has been kicked back to d2 a little too counter-intuitive for a mere human?} 27. Rac1 Rd7) 26. Rad1 Nb4 {I have to act fast!} 27. Rd2 Rc7 28. Kf2 (28. Rc1 Rxc1 (28... Rdc8 {Paunovic,Tomislav} 29. Rxc7 Rxc7 $15) 29. Nxc1 Rc8 30. Ne2 Bxa2) 28... Nxa2 {Inaccurate.} (28... Rc2 $1 29. Ree2 Rc3 {is a sophisticated way to keep the domination} 30. Re3 Rxe3 31. Kxe3 Rc8 32. d5 Rc3+ 33. Ke2 Be8 $1 34. Nd4 Bd7 35. Rb2 a5 {and Black's active pieces suffocate White.}) 29. d5 (29. Rxa2 Bxb3 30. Ra3 $1 {We both missed this intermediate move.} (30. Rxa7 Rxd4 {Paunovic,Tomislav: ''} 31. Rb1 Rd3 $17) 30... Bf7 31. d5 {Apparently It's not easy for Black to advance his queenside pawns.}) 29... Nc3 {I wanted to get my knight to d6.} (29... Nb4 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '!?'} 30. Re3) 30. Nd4 Rc4 (30... b5 31. Rb2 (31. Rc2 $1)) 31. Re3 (31. Ra1 {Paunovic,Tomislav}) 31... Be8 $6 (31... a5 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '!' Just advance your passed pawns!}) 32. Bg2 {I was relieved to see this. While my opponent was thinking, I realised that I had thrown away my advantage as I didn't see how to react after the simple breakthrought in the centre.} (32. e5 fxe5 (32... Nxd5 33. Nf5 $1) 33. Rxe5 a5 34. d6 $1 (34. Ne6 Rd6 $15) 34... Bf7 35. Nb5 a4 36. Nxc3 Rxc3 37. Bxb7 $11) (32. Ne6 $1 {Paunovic,Tomislav} Rdc8 33. e5 $132) 32... Nb5 (32... b5 33. Bf1 Rcc8) (32... Bd7 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '!?' was maybe better, but I wanted to solve the problem of the c3-knight.}) 33. Nxb5 (33. Ne6 {Paunovic,Tomislav} Rdc8 34. e5 Rc2 35. Rxc2 Rxc2+ 36. Kg3 fxe5 37. Rxe5 Rc3+ 38. Kf2 Rc8 $17) 33... Bxb5 34. Bf1 (34. Rb2 Rc5 35. h4 {apparently is more resistant! The presence of bishops creates more problems to realise the extra pawn.}) (34. e5 $5 {Paunovic,Tomislav} fxe5 35. Rxe5 Rxg4 36. d6 Bc6 37. Bxc6 bxc6 38. Re7 $15) 34... Rc5 35. Bxb5 Rxb5 $17 {Now Black has a clear advantage. Although White still has counterplay due to the d-pawn. After a few earlier inaccuracies, I am proud to say that in the next phase of the game I showed some talent! :)} 36. Rc3 (36. h4 $5 {Paunovic,Tomislav}) 36... Rd7 (36... a5 $5 {Paunovic,Tomislav}) 37. Ke3 Kf7 38. Rdc2 (38. h4 a5 39. Rc8) 38... a5 39. Rc7 Ke7 40. Rc8 a4 41. Ra8 Rb4 $1 {Cutting of the king!} (41... Rb3+ 42. Kd4 Rb4+ (42... a3 {looks tempting but pawn is way too advanced to defend} 43. Rc3 $1 $11) 43. Rc4 Rxc4+ 44. Kxc4 Rc7+ 45. Kb5 Rc2 46. Rxa4 Rxh2 47. Kb6 $11) 42. Kd3 (42. Rcc8 {visually looked scary but I correctly understood that I can safely take my king to the queenside.} Kd6 $1 43. Re8 Kc5 $1 44. h4 g5 45. h5 Rb3+ $19) 42... Rd8 $1 {The move I am most proud of in the game! I found this simply because I couldn't find another way to keep the pressure!} (42... Kd6 43. Rc4 $1 (43. Re8 Re7 44. Rd8+ Ke5 45. d6 Rd4+ $17) 43... Rxc4 44. Kxc4 Rc7+ 45. Kd4 b5 46. Ra6+ Kd7 47. Ra5 {and my pawns are a little stuck.}) 43. Ra7 (43. Rc7+ Kd6 44. Rxb7 Rxa8 45. Rxb4 {with a classic rook behind the pawn scenario} a3) 43... Kd6 44. Rc4 Rxc4 (44... Rb3+ 45. Kd4 a3 46. h4 (46. Rc3 Rxc3 47. Kxc3 Ke5) 46... h5) 45. Kxc4 Ke5 $1 {Another very strong move! It was important to understand that Black has to give away the material rather than to hang onto it.} (45... Rc8+ 46. Kd4 b5 47. Ra6+ Kd7 48. Ra5 Rc4+ 49. Kd3 Rc5 50. Kd4 {Black has practical problems!}) 46. Rxb7 (46. Kd3 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '!?'} b5 {is similiar to above line but here Black is so much more active.} 47. Rxg7 b4) 46... Ra8 $1 47. Rb2 a3 48. Ra2 Kxe4 49. d6 Ke5 $1 (49... Rd8 50. Kc5 {would be anti climactic!}) 50. Kc5 (50. d7 {Paunovic,Tomislav} Rd8 $1 51. Rxa3 Rxd7 $19) 50... Rc8+ $1 51. Kb4 Kxd6 52. Rxa3 Rc7 53. Re3 (53. Ra5 Rc2 54. h3 Rh2 $19) 53... Kd5 54. h3 g6 $1 $19 {Black just prepares a passed pawn as White's king is safely cut off. My good friend Erwin l'Ami who is a master of such rook endgames congratulated me and told that he found this endgame 'sweet'! What better compliment can I ask for?} 55. Re8 f5 56. Rg8 (56. Rh8 {Paunovic,Tomislav} f4 $1 57. Rxh6 f3) 56... Rc6 (56... f4 $1 {Paunovic,Tomislav} 57. Rxg6 Rf7) 57. Kb5 Rf6 58. gxf5 gxf5 59. Rd8+ Ke4 60. Re8+ Kf3 61. Kc4 Rd6 62. Kc5 Rd1 63. Rh8 f4 64. Rxh6 Kg3 65. Rg6+ Kxh3 66. Rf6 Kg3 67. Rg6+ Kf2 68. Kc4 f3 69. Kc3 Kf1 70. Kc2 Rd5 0-1


