{After a slow start I managed to win two games before this round and was eager for a fight.} 1. e4 {Vidit,S Vidit,S} c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 {This came as a slight surprise. Before this game, Ly had exclusively played 9.xf6.} Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c3 Rb8 {A move popularized by Boris Gelfand, 11...0-0 was the old main line.  Vidit,S: 'A move popularised by Boris Gelfand, 11...0-0 was the old main line. '} 12. Nc2 Bg5 13. a4 bxa4 14. Ncb4 Nxb4 15. cxb4 {Although this was a theoretical position my opponent had already spent a considerable amount of time on his last two moves.} O-O 16. Qxa4 $6 {This is a rather dubious move. It is very important to keep control over the key d5-square.} (16. Rxa4 {is considered the main theoretical move. The opening debate is still wide open. Some believe in White's control over the d5-square while some in two bishops! Whose side are you on :) ?}) 16... Bb7 (16... f5 {is another way to play the position. But I wanted to attack the d5-square right away.} 17. exf5 Bxf5 18. Bxa6 Be4 19. Qb3 Kh8 20. O-O Bxd5 21. Qxd5 Rxb4 $11) 17. Rd1 $6 {Now White's position is very unpleasant.} (17. Bc4 Qc8 $1 {A very important move and now ...g4 is a very annoying threat.} 18. Qb3 Qg4 19. Qf3 Qxf3 20. gxf3 Rfc8 {Black still has a very nice position but the possibility of opposite coloured bishops gives White good drawing possibilities.}) (17. Bxa6 {looks like the best} Bxd5 18. exd5 e4 19. O-O f5 $36 (19... Bd2 20. b5)) 17... Qc8 $1 {An important move. Black has ideas like xd5-c1 and also ...g4.} (17... Bxd5 $5 {was the alternative but it looked somewhat too naive.} 18. Rxd5 Qc7 19. Bxa6 Qc1+ 20. Rd1 Qxb2 21. b5 Qc3+ 22. Kf1 Bd8 23. h4 $1 Bb6 24. Rh3 Qc7 $15) 18. Qb3 $1 {The most resilient move.} (18. Nc3 f5 $40) 18... Bxd5 $5 {This looked like the most direct to me.} 19. Rxd5 a5 {The most energetic!} 20. b5 a4 $1 {The a4-pawn continues on its epic suicide journey.} 21. Qb4 (21. Qxa4 {is probably better. Although during the game I was more worried about 21.b4.} Qc1+ 22. Rd1 Qxb2 23. Bc4 Qc3+ $1 24. Kf1 Rfc8 25. Bd5 Bd8 $15 {Black has a dream Sveshnikov. White still needs a lot of time to coordinate the rooks.}) 21... Qc2 $1 {My opponent missed this move. It's not easy to defend the b2-pawn.} 22. Be2 (22. h4 {It looks stupid to provoke the  to c1, but it has its pluses.} Bd8 $1 (22... Bc1 23. Bd3 Qxb2 24. Qxa4 Ra8 25. Qc2 Qb4+ 26. Kf1 Bb2 27. g3 {White can still hold on}) 23. Be2 Bb6 $15 {White still struggles to castle.}) 22... Rfc8 23. b6 $6 (23. Bd1 {was the main line in my calculations.} Rc4 24. Bxc2 Rxb4 25. O-O Rc8 $1 26. Bd1 Be7 $17 {and White has to give up one of the pawns.}) 23... Qc1+ $1 {I thought for a long time over this move. I was afraid to end up into some sort of opposite coloured bishop endgame. Vidit,S: 'I thought for a long time over this move. I was afraid to end up in some sort of opposite coloured bishop endgame.'} (23... Qc6 24. O-O Rxb6 25. Bb5 $1 {is the extra alternative with the direct ...c6:} Rcb8 26. Bxc6 Rxb4 27. g3 {and the game still goes on.}) 24. Rd1 Qc6 {Now White doesn't have b5!} 25. O-O (25. Qxd6 Qxe4 $19) 25... Rxb6 26. Qa3 Rb3 $6 {An inaccuracy} (26... Qxe4 {was another option but I didn't want to allow the  to d5.} 27. Bf3 Qb4 28. Bd5) (26... Rcb8 $17 {is probably the cleanest win.}) 27. Rxd6 $1 {I underestimated this move, but luckily I had a nasty trick up my sleeve!} Qxe4 28. Bf3 Qh4 (28... Qf4 {was my original intention but I missed 30.d4 in my calculations.} 29. Qa2 e4 (29... Rb4 $17) 30. Rd4 $1 $11) 29. Qa2 $2 (29. g3 $1 {White could still offer some resistance with this move.} Rxa3 30. gxh4 Rxf3 31. hxg5 Rf5 (31... g6) 32. h4 g6 33. Kg2 Rb8 34. Ra6 Rb4 35. Kg3 Kg7 $19 {should win slowly.}) 29... Rxf3 $1 {My opponent missed this thematic move. Now White is just lost.} 30. gxf3 Bf4 $19 31. Rfd1 Qxh2+ (31... e4 $1 {was quicker but xh2+ seemed clearest during the game.}) 32. Kf1 Qh1+ 33. Ke2 Rc2+ 34. R1d2 Rxd2+ 35. Rxd2 Bxd2 36. Qxa4 {Finally the brave a4-pawn meets its doom but it did a brave job, Wouldn't you agree :)?} Qe1+ 37. Kd3 Bb4 0-1


