1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. b3 {A comparatively rare continuation, which is 5th in popularity after 3 Nc3, 3 d4, 3 g3 and 3 e3. Notably, it is Demuth's recommendation in his Reti repertoire book. This line is new to Chess Publishing, so I've included an overview of some of the main options as seen in recent games} Nf6 {Another key try is to immediately occupy the centre:} (3... e5 4. Bb2 {and now Black has:} d6 {is more circumspect. Now} (4... e4 $5 {is ambitious, but gives White chances for an edge by striking against the advanced e4-pawn.} 5. Ng1 Nf6 6. Nc3 {when Black has tried:} Bd6 (6... Be7 7. Qb1 {[%emt 0:00:07] a common theme in this variation. White hits the e4-pawn but leaves the queen less exposed to ...Nc6-b4 ideas that it would be after 7 Qc2. After Qb1} O-O {and here:} 8. e3 {is Demuth's choice. After} (8. Nxe4 d5 (8... Nxe4 9. Qxe4 Bf6 10. Qb1 d5 {is simpler and gives Black good compensation}) 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Ng3 f5 11. Nf3 (11. e3 {activating the f1-bishop, is an improvement}) 11... f4 12. Ne4 Bf5 13. g4 Bg6 {and Black has reasonable compensation for the pawn due to White's lagging development, Travadon,L (2456) -Tomasi,A (2283) Cergy Pontoise 2019 0-1 (38)}) 8... Re8 {White can take the pawn since} 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Bf6 $2 {fails to} 11. Bxf6 {with a winning advantage for White}) 7. Qb1 Qe7 {and now:} 8. e3 (8. g4 $5 Nxg4 $6 (8... h6 {was called for}) 9. Qxe4 Nce5 $2 10. Nd5 Qe6 11. h3 f5 12. Qc2 Nf6 13. Bg2 Nh5 14. Nf3 O-O 15. O-O-O Nc6 16. e3 b6 17. Rhg1 {with a big advantage for White, Gonzales,J (2367) -Karthik,V (2514) Barbera del Valles 2018 1/2-1/2 (60). White has strong pressure on the g-file while Black's forces are uncoordinated.}) 8... O-O 9. Nge2 Re8 10. Ng3 {gives White an edge according to Demuth}) 5. Nc3 g6 6. g3 Bg7 {leads to a battle between White's double fianchetto setup and Black's Botvinnik structure.} 7. d3 Nge7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O h6 {and now White has tried two routes for his f3-knight:} 10. Ne1 (10. Nd2 Be6 11. a3 Qd7 {and now:} 12. b4 $5 (12. Nd5 {is a typical (reversed) Botvinnik system with two practical examples:} Bh3 (12... f5 13. f4 Rab8 14. Rb1 Kh7 15. b4 {A bit premature.} (15. e3 b5 16. Qc2 {maintains the tension, with roughly balanced chances}) 15... cxb4 16. Nxe7 Nxe7 17. axb4 b5 {and Black has sufficient counterplay against White's queenside pawns, Nguyen,P (2427)-Gopal,G (2589) Budapest 2019 0-1 (38)}) 13. Bxh3 Qxh3 14. b4 cxb4 (14... Qd7 $1 15. Qa4 Rad8 16. e3 {is Demuth's mainline}) 15. Nxe7+ Nxe7 16. axb4 f5 17. Qa4 f4 18. Qb5 b6 19. Ne4 {and White's play, with pressure on the d6- and a7-pawns, is further ahead than Black's kingside ambitions, Gonda,L (2524)-Korpa,B (2505) Hungary 2018 1-0 (54)}) 12... cxb4 13. axb4 Nxb4 14. Ba3 a5 15. Rb1 {gave White Benko-style queenside pressure in return for the pawn, Kramnik,V (2800) -Gelfand,B (2695) Moscow (Rapid) 2018 1/2-1/2 (56)}) 10... Be6 11. Nd5 Rb8 12. Nc2 b5 13. e3 bxc4 14. dxc4 f5 {was a quick draw in Maghsoodloo,P (2666) -Alekseev,E (2639) Bandar e Anzali 2019 1/2-1/2 (14), although with} 15. Nxe7+ Nxe7 16. Na3 {White can continue by building pressure on the d-file.}) 4. Bb2 d5 {Black goes for a reversed Maroczy-bind structure. Instead:} (4... e6 {is more common. Now} 5. g3 (5. e3 {is also possible, of course}) 5... d5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bg2 {and now:} d4 (7... Bg4 8. O-O Be7 (8... d4 {grabs space, and is similar to the next line}) 9. d4 {Now White gets a QGD Tarrasch setup which is fairly comfortable for him. After} O-O 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Nc3 a6 12. h3 Bh5 13. Na4 Ba7 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Rc1 {White was better thanks to his superior pawn structure, Demuth,A (2542) -Marcelin,C (2462) Brest 2018 1/2-1/2 (29)}) 8. O-O Be7 9. Na3 O-O 10. Nc4 Be6 11. e3 Rc8 12. exd4 cxd4 13. Re1 Bd5 14. Nce5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Re8 {was played in Giri,A (2777)-Ding,L (2778) Shamkir 2018 1/ 2-1/2 (69), and now} 16. Bxd5 Qxd5 17. Qf3 {leaves White slightly for choice due to Black's exposed d4-pawn.}) 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nc3 {An important move in the fight for the centre. Alternatives give Black too much influence:} (6. e3 $6 Ndb4 7. d3 Bf5 8. e4 Bg4 9. a3 Bxf3 10. gxf3 Na6 {and Black has spoiled White structure and stands a little better, Sadorra,J (2553)-Le,Q (2715) Batumi 2018 0-1 (51)}) (6. g3 {is not challenging enough, for example} f6 7. Bg2 e5 8. O-O Be7 9. d3 O-O 10. Nbd2 Bg4 11. a3 Qd7 {with a very good Maroczy for Black, Nyzhnyk,I (2638)-Xiong,J (2663) Saint Louis 2019 1/2-1/2 (39)}) 6... e5 {The most principled. Black has also tried:} (6... Nf6 7. e3 a6 8. Na4 e6 9. Rc1 Nd7 10. Be2 b5 11. Nc3 Bb7 12. a4 b4 {Nyzhnyk,I (2666)-Fernandez,D (2466) Orlando 2019 1-0 (52), and now} 13. Ne4 Na5 14. d3 {gives White the more harmonious position, with pressure against the c5- and g7-squares, plus control of the c4-square.}) (6... Bg4 7. e3 e6 8. Be2 (8. Nxd5 $1 Qxd5 9. Bc4 {is more to the point}) 8... Ndb4 9. Qb1 Bf5 10. e4 Bg4 11. a3 Bxf3 12. gxf3 Na6 {with another example of this structure which favours Black, Swapnil,S (2488) -Bogdanovich,S (2536) Moscow 2019 0-1 (33)}) 7. e3 Nxc3 {Black trades a pair of knights to speed up his development. Alternatively:} (7... f6 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. Bc4 Qd6 $6 (9... Qe4 $1 {is unusual, but after} 10. d3 Qg6 {Black has counterplay on the kingside}) 10. d4 {White has a big lead in development. After} cxd4 11. exd4 e4 12. Qe2 Qe7 13. Nd2 f5 $6 14. O-O Bd7 15. d5 Nd8 16. d6 Qxd6 17. Nxe4 {Black was crushed in Nyzhnyk,I (2666)-Sarkar,J (2357) Orlando 2019 1-0 (24)}) (7... Ndb4 $6 {is now answered by} 8. Qb1 $1 {and the b4-knight will be kicked back next.}) (7... Nc7 8. Rc1 f6 9. Ne4 b6 (9... Qd5 10. Qc2 Nb4 11. Qb1 Nxa2 12. Bc4 Qc6 13. Qxa2 Qxe4 14. O-O {favours White  (Demuth)}) 10. d4 {and White is better after blasting open the centre} (10. Bc4 {is less precise. Now} Be6 11. O-O Bxc4 12. Rxc4 Qd3 {was much less clear in Gregori,G (2280)-Aghayev,M (2433) Brixen Bressanone 2019 1/2-1/2 (53)})) 8. Bxc3 {In view of Black's possible improvement on the 9th move below, it is worth considering:} (8. dxc3 $5 {for example} Bf5 9. Qxd8+ Rxd8 10. Bb5 {aiming for pressure in the queenless middlegame}) 8... Bd6 9. Bb5 {White also has:} (9. Qb1 Qe7 10. Bd3 h6 11. O-O O-O 12. Re1 Bg4 13. Be4 {this is an awkward setup for White} f5 14. Bd5+ Kh8 15. d3 {Vokac,M (2465)-Rehorek,M Karvina 1989 1-0 (60), and now} Nb4 {secures the two bishops and leaves Black better.}) (9. Qc2 {is a better square for the queen, for example} Qe7 (9... O-O {can be met by} 10. Bb5) 10. Bd3 h6 11. Be4 Bd7 {with an approximate balance}) 9... Qe7 {Not a bad move, but it gives White the chance to play against a static weakness. It was better to go for:} (9... Bd7 $1 {and now:} 10. d4 {is critical, but after} (10. Bxc6 $6 Bxc6 11. Nxe5 $2 {grabbing the pawn doesn't work} (11. O-O O-O {is a bit better for Black, however}) 11... Bxe5 12. Bxe5 Qd5 $1 {and White is in huge trouble, for example} 13. Bg3 Qxg2 14. Rf1 Bb5 15. d3 Rd8 {and White collapses}) (10. d3 Qe7 {when it is not obvious what the b5-bishop is doing - Black is at least fine}) 10... cxd4 11. exd4 exd4 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 (12... Qe7+ {is a safe choice}) 13. Bxd7+ Qxd7 14. Qxd4 O-O-O $5 {when the engine likes Black. White cannot grab the a7-pawn since} 15. Qxa7 $2 Rhe8+ 16. Kf1 Bc7 {gives Black a winning attack}) 10. Bxc6+ {An improvement over:} (10. O-O {Giulian,P (2133)-Stebbings,A (2281) Rhodes 2019 0-1 (27) and now simplest is} e4 11. Ne1 O-O {with a decent space advantage for Black}) 10... bxc6 11. d3 Ba6 12. Qc2 Rd8 {It was more accurate to keep White's bishop out of the a5-square:} (12... Bc7 $1 {and now} 13. Nd2 f5 {and both sides have their trumps. White can press on the c-file, while Black can target the d3-pawn and potential kingside play.}) 13. Ba5 {A nice move which helps White to improve his coordination. Now when the knight gets to the c4-square, the queen can recapture in the event of ...Ba6xc4.} Rd7 14. Nd2 O-O 15. Nc4 f5 {Instead:} (15... Bc7 16. Bxc7 Rxc7 17. O-O {is also slightly better for White}) 16. e4 $1 {A strategically important move. White doesn't want to live with less space on the kingside in a line such as:} (16. O-O Bb8 {when White will probably need to play e3-e4 sooner or later}) 16... Qg5 $6 {This queen excursion doesn't achieve anything concrete. Better was:} (16... Qe6 {which keeps the queen in contact with the c4-square, making it harder for White to castle queenside. After} 17. Rd1 (17. O-O-O $6 fxe4 18. dxe4 Bxc4 19. bxc4 Rb7 {leaves White in trouble}) (17. f3 fxe4 18. fxe4 Be7 {is also fine for Black}) 17... Be7 18. exf5 Qxf5 19. O-O {white keeps a slight edge}) 17. f3 {Engines like White after:} (17. O-O f4 18. f3 {when Black isn't in time to launch a kingside attack, for example} Rf6 19. Nxd6 Rfxd6 20. Qxc5 {and White is on top}) 17... Rf6 18. h4 {White is aiming to castle long.} (18. O-O {is similar to the previous note.}) 18... Qg3+ 19. Qf2 Qg6 {Black should perhaps trade queens here:} (19... Qxf2+ 20. Kxf2 Bxc4 21. bxc4 Be7 22. Ke2 {although White can press in this better endgame.}) 20. h5 Qf7 21. Qc2 Rh6 22. O-O-O {With his king now castled safely, White has achieved a clear advantage, since Black doesn't have pressure to compensate for his inferior pawn structure.} Rxh5 23. Nxd6 Rxd6 24. Rxh5 Qxh5 25. Qxc5 Qh6+ $6 {This leaves Black a clear pawn down. A better chance was:} (25... Rxd3 {for example} 26. Qxa7 Rxd1+ 27. Kxd1 Qh1+ 28. Kc2 Qxg2+ {with some counterplay, although White is still on top}) 26. Kc2 fxe4 27. fxe4 Qf6 28. Qxa7 c5 29. Bc3 Qf2+ 30. Rd2 Bxd3+ 31. Kb2 Qf1 32. Qb8+ {Here:} (32. Qxc5 {is very strong, since after} Qb1+ 33. Ka3 Qc1+ 34. Kb4 {the king is safe and Black is lost}) 32... Qf8 33. Qxf8+ Kxf8 34. Bxe5 Rd7 35. Kc3 Bb5 36. Rxd7 {Maghsoodloo is not afraid to enter an opposite coloured bishop endgame where he accurately calculates his way to a win.} Bxd7 37. Kc4 Bc6 38. Kxc5 Bxe4 39. Kd6 Bxg2 40. b4 Ke8 41. Kc7 Ke7 42. b5 Ke6 43. Bd6 h5 44. b6 h4 45. a4 g5 46. a5 Bb7 (46... g4 {is way too slow} 47. a6 g3 48. b7 {and White promotes first}) 47. Kxb7 Kxd6 48. Kc8 1-0


