1. d4 {Grigoriants,Sergey} Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 {Grigoriants,Sergey: 'The Russian system. White's bringing more pressure against Black's central outpost on d5; White typically forces ...dxc4, gaining an immense center; however, their queen will often be exposed.'} dxc4 6. Qxc4 Be6 {Grigoriants,Sergey: '!?' Grigoriants,Sergey: 'A tricky sideline. Black immediately attacks the queen, trying to chase it from c4, after which Black can play c7-c5.'} (6... O-O {Grigoriants,Sergey The main line.} 7. e4 {And now black has different paths:} a6 {The Hungarian Variation} (7... Bg4 8. Be3 Nfd7 {The Smyslov Variation}) (7... Na6 {The Prins Variation}) (7... Nc6 {The Byrne Variation})) 7. Qd3 (7. Qb5+ {Grigoriants,Sergey The main move, which we will cover in the next games.}) 7... c5 {Grigoriants,Sergey: '!' Grigoriants,Sergey: 'Black has to counterattack in the center as quickly as possible to prevent White from obtaining a massive center with e2-e4 followed by d4-d5.'} 8. e4 (8. Qb5+ $6 {Grigoriants,Sergey} Nc6 9. Qxc5 Nd7 $1 10. Qb5 Nxd4 11. Nxd4 Bxd4 $36) (8. dxc5 $6 {Grigoriants,Sergey Simply a strategic mistake as it weakens the pawn structure.} Qxd3 9. exd3 Nd5 $1 {An important move. The point is to prepare Nb4 or trade the knights and empower the g7B by freeing up its diagonal.} 10. d4 (10. Nxd5 {Looks less dangerous than allowing black to jump his knight to b4.} Bxd5 11. d4 Nc6 $1 (11... Bxf3 {This is also possible, but White has sufficient compensation for the destroyed pawn structure due to the bishop pair.} 12. gxf3 Bxd4 13. Be3 Nc6 14. O-O-O O-O-O 15. Bc4 e6 $13) 12. Be3 O-O-O 13. Be2 Rd7 $5 $15 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yh8d8]}) 10... Nb4 $1 11. Bb5+ N8c6 12. O-O O-O-O $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yb4c2] The d4 pawn is very weak. Black clearly has an edge.} 13. Ng5 Nxd4 14. Nxe6 Nxe6 15. Ne4 {(Maghsoodloo-Abdusattorov, Chess.com 2022)} Nd4 $17 {Black's domination is evident, let alone the extra pawn.}) 8... cxd4 {Grigoriants,Sergey: '!' Grigoriants,Sergey: 'A crucial capture. Otherwise, White would keep his strong center.'} 9. Nxd4 Bd7 $146 {Grigoriants,Sergey: '!' Grigoriants,Sergey: 'It's practical to prevent xe6, which would have spoiled the pawn structure. Surprisingly, the engine suggests leaving the bishop on e6, which is highly counterintuitive, so I won't consider analyzing it any deeper. When the dust settles, it's a symmetrical pawn structure, resulting in a balanced and equal position. At this point, Black solved all opening problems.'} (9... O-O 10. Nxe6 fxe6 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Bc4 $14) 10. f3 (10. e5 Ng4 11. f4 (11. e6 fxe6 12. Be2 Qb6 $1 13. Bxg4 Qxd4 $15) 11... Nc6 12. h3 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Nh6 14. g4 f6 $132) (10. Be2 Nc6 11. Be3 (11. Nxc6 {Grigoriants,Sergey} Bxc6 12. Qxd8+ Rxd8 13. f3 Nh5 (13... O-O 14. Be3 a6 {just transposes back to the game.}) 14. Be3 Bd4 15. Kf2 Nf4 $1 16. Bxd4 Rxd4 17. Rhd1 e5 18. Bf1 Ke7 $11 {Najer-Deac, Chess.com 2021}) 11... O-O $11 12. Rd1 {Grigoriants,Sergey} Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Bc6 14. O-O Qa5 $1 {Logical square of the queen, then putting the rooks to the d and c-files. Black's position is adequate.} 15. Qe3 Rfd8 $11 {Ibrahimli-Corrales Jimenez, Chess.com 2022}) 10... Nc6 11. Nxc6 Bxc6 12. Qxd8+ (12. Be3 Qa5 13. Be2 O-O 14. O-O Rfd8 $11) 12... Rxd8 13. Be3 a6 14. Be2 O-O {Grigoriants,Sergey: '=' Grigoriants,Sergey: 'The calm after the storm has descended.' Grigoriants,Sergey: 'just transposes back to the game.'} 15. Kf2 {Diagram [#]} (15. O-O {Grigoriants,Sergey (Milekic-Tancik, Vrnjacka Banja 2022)} Nd7 {One the most logical way to go for me. Future plans include playing e7-e6 and, at some point, f7-f5.} (15... Ne8 {Transferring the knight to d6 is just as fine.} 16. Rfd1 Nd6 $11) 16. Rfd1 e6 $11) 15... Ne8 $1 {Grigoriants,Sergey: '!?'} 16. Rhd1 (16. Bb6 $6 Rd2 $36) 16... Nd6 (16... Nc7 {Grigoriants,Sergey Also possible. There are no significant differences between some logical, standard moves because the position is pretty harmless.} 17. Bb6 Rxd1 18. Rxd1 Rc8 19. Rd2 e6 20. g3 Na8 21. Be3 Nc7 $11 {Volkov-Iljiushenok, Kazan 2018}) 17. a4 (17. Bb6 Rd7 18. Rac1 f5 19. exf5 Rxf5 $13) (17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. Rxd5 Bxb2 19. Rb1 Bg7 20. Bc5 $44) 17... f5 {Grigoriants,Sergey: '!'} 18. exf5 gxf5 19. Ke1 Kf7 20. Bd4 Bf6 {Grigoriants,Sergey: '='} 21. b4 Rc8 22. Ra3 (22. Bxf6 Kxf6 23. Rac1 Kf7 24. Kf2 Rfd8 $13) 22... b5 23. axb5 axb5 24. Bxf6 Kxf6 25. Ra6 (25. Nd5+ Bxd5 (25... Kf7 26. Ra7 Bxd5 27. Rxd5 $14) 26. Rxd5 Rc1+ 27. Kf2 Rfc8 28. Bd3 R8c3 29. Rxc3 Rxc3 $11) 25... Bxf3 26. Nxb5 Bxg2 (26... Bxe2 27. Kxe2 Rc2+ 28. Rd2 Rxd2+ 29. Kxd2 Ke5 30. Nxd6 exd6 $11) 27. Nxd6 exd6 28. Rdxd6+ Ke5 29. Bd3 Be4 30. Kd2 (30. b5 $11) 30... Rcd8 {Diagram [#]} 31. Rxd8 $4 {Grigoriants,Sergey: '?' Grigoriants,Sergey: 'It's just a fatal mistake. White is heading directrly for a losing pawn endgame. Perhaps he missed 35...f2!.'} (31. Re6+ Kf4 32. Rad6 {Grigoriants,Sergey: '='} Rxd6 33. Rxd6 Rb8 34. Bxe4 fxe4 35. Rf6+ Ke5 36. Rh6 Rxb4 37. Rxh7 $11) 31... Rxd8 32. Ra3 (32. Ra5+ Kf4 33. Ra3 Kf3 34. b5 f4 35. b6 Kg2 36. Rb3 (36. b7 Bxb7 $19) 36... Bxd3 37. Rxd3 Rb8 $19) 32... f4 $19 {Grigoriants,Sergey: '!'} 33. Ke2 f3+ {Grigoriants,Sergey: '!'} 34. Ke3 Bxd3 35. Rxd3 f2 {Grigoriants,Sergey: '!'} 0-1


