1. b3 e5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. e3 Nf6 4. Bb5 e4 {Black gains space and aims to probe the light squares in White's setup. This is a modern alternative to the mainline:} (4... Bd6 {which is covered in many games in the PGN Archives.}) 5. Ne2 {It appears that Hikaru has switched to this move from his earlier choice:} (5. f3 a6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. Qe2 {which is analyzed in Nakamura-Shankland in the Archives.}) 5... a6 {Another part of Black's plan, forcing the exchange of the b5-bishop and opening the d-file for Black's major pieces} 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. Ng3 {White's usual choice, although practice has also seen:} (7. Nbc3 Bf5 8. Ng3 Bg6 9. h4 h5 10. Nce2 {Rapport,R (2707)-Saric,I (2669) Riadh 2017 1/2-1/2 (67), and now} Bd6 {is natural and looks pleasant for Black}) 7... h5 {Black presses against the awkwardly placed g3-knight} 8. Nc3 Bg4 {A later game (on the same day) in the same tournament instead saw:} (8... Qe7 {and now} 9. h4 Rh6 10. Qe2 Bg4 $6 {White is now well prepared to meet this sortie, and trade off the advanced e4-pawn.} (10... Rg6 {allows} 11. O-O-O {to be met by} Rxg3 $1 12. fxg3 Bg4 {and Black is at least fine.}) 11. f3 exf3 12. gxf3 Bd7 13. O-O-O O-O-O 14. Qf2 Kb8 15. e4 {when White has taken control of the centre and went on to win in Nakamura,H (2736)-Ding,L (2791) chess24.com INT 2021 1-0 (52)}) 9. f3 {A clear improvement over the alternative:} (9. Nge2 $6 {White has lost two tempi with his knight. Now} Qd7 10. h3 Bf5 11. Ng3 Bg6 12. h4 O-O-O 13. Qe2 Bd6 {and Black is for choice, Karjakin,S (2773)-Caruana,F (2807) Saint Louis  (blitz) 2017 1-0 (39)}) 9... exf3 10. gxf3 Be6 {The first new move. Black has also played:} (10... h4 11. Nf1 {Not a great posting for the knight.} (11. fxg4 hxg3 12. h3 g2 13. Rg1 Rxh3 14. Qe2 {holds the balance, Perez,E (1647)-Mendoza, B (1653) Batangas 2019 1/2-1/2 (32)}) 11... Bh5 12. Qe2 Qd7 13. d3 O-O-O 14. O-O-O {Granda Zuniga,J (2652)-Naroditsky,D (2622) Benasque 2015 1/2-1/2 (63) and now} Bc5 {keeps White's pawn centre under pressure}) 11. Qe2 Qd7 {Black is relying on piece play to keep White's centre under restraint. A more energetic approach was:} (11... h4 {for example} 12. Nf1 (12. Nge4 {allows Black to improve his position by trading a pair of knights}) 12... Nd5 13. O-O-O Qe7 {with a roughly balanced game.}) 12. O-O-O {Instead:} (12. Qf2 h4 13. Nge2 {was a useful regrouping which allows White to get coordinated and enjoy a slightly more comfortable position.}) 12... O-O-O 13. Rhg1 h4 14. Nge4 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 {After the knight trade, Black has enough space for his pieces and his bishop pair balances out White's central pawn majority.} f6 16. Kb1 Kb8 17. d4 Qf7 18. Qf2 Be7 19. Nc5 Bc8 20. e4 g5 {Black starts to mobilize the kingside pawns, while White's e- and d-pawns aren't really going anywhere.} 21. Nd3 Qh7 22. Qe2 Rhe8 23. a4 Qf7 24. Rdf1 Bd6 {Alternatively after:} (24... f5 $5 25. Ne5 Qh5 26. Rf2 h3 {Black is pressing slightly although White's setup is solid.}) 25. Qf2 Qh7 26. Re1 Qf7 27. f4 {Now it is White that gets to make the first pawn break.} gxf4 28. Nxf4 h3 29. d5 cxd5 30. Nxd5 f5 31. Rgf1 Rg8 32. Ne3 $6 {Losing time. Instead:} (32. Rd1 {maintains the balance since} Rg2 {can be met by} 33. Qh4 {hitting the d8-rook and h3-pawn.}) 32... f4 33. Nc4 {Suddenly White is in trouble as the h2-pawn is dropping to ...Rg8-g2xh2} Bb4 34. Rc1 Rg2 35. Qf3 Rxh2 36. Be5 Rg2 37. Bxf4 Qh7 {Black's passed h-pawn is the most important factor in the position.} (37... Rf8 {is more accurate, pinning the f4-bishop}) 38. Ne3 Rgg8 $2 {Blundering an exchange and turning the game on its head.} (38... Rg6 {keeps Black's advantage.}) 39. Nd5 {[%emt 0:00:40] With the double threat of 40 Nxb4 and Nf6} Rxd5 40. exd5 Ba3 41. Rce1 Bb4 42. Qe4 Qxe4 43. Rxe4 Bc5 44. d6 $6 {Allowing Black some practical chances. Instead:} (44. b4 Bd6 45. Bxd6 cxd6 46. Rh4 {should win for White as, unlike in the game, he keeps the d-pawn.}) 44... Bxd6 45. Bxd6 cxd6 46. Rh4 Kc7 47. Rf6 Rg7 48. Rhh6 Bd7 49. Rxd6 h2 50. Rd1 Rg1 51. Rc1 Rg2 52. Kb2 Bf5 53. Rh1 Rxc2+ 54. Ka3 Be4 55. R1xh2 Rxh2 56. Rxh2 a5 57. Kb2 b6 {Black should be holding this since his pawns are on the opposite coloured squares to his bishop.} 58. Rh4 Bd5 59. Rh7+ Kc6 60. Kc3 Kc5 61. Rh3 Be6 62. Rh6 Bd5 63. Rh8 Be6 64. Re8 Bd5 65. Re7 Kd6 66. Rg7 Kc5 67. Rg4 Be6 68. Rf4 Bd5 69. Rf6 Be4 70. Rf8 Bd5 71. Rc8+ Kd6 72. Kb2 Kd7 73. Rc3 Kd6 74. Rc1 Be6 75. Rc2 Bd5 76. Ka3 Bc6 77. Rh2 Kc5 78. Rh5+ Bd5 79. Rg5 Kd6 80. Rg1 Kc5 81. Rd1 Bc6 82. Rd8 Bd5 83. Kb2 Bc6 84. Kc2 Bd5 85. Kc3 Kc6 86. Re8 Kc5 87. Rc8+ Kd6 88. b4 {White finally tries the only pawn break but it leads to a Tablebase draw which Black indeed manages to hold.} axb4+ 89. Kxb4 Bc6 90. Rg8 Bd7 91. Rh8 Kc7 92. Rh7 Kd6 93. Rg7 Bc6 94. Ra7 Bd7 95. Rb7 Kc6 96. Rb8 Kc7 97. Rh8 Kd6 98. Ra8 Bc6 99. Ra7 Bd7 100. Kc4 Bc6 101. Ra6 Kc7 102. a5 bxa5 103. Kc5 Bg2 104. Ra7+ Kd8 105. Kd6 Ke8 106. Rg7 Bf1 107. Re7+ Kf8 108. Ke6 Kg8 109. Kf6 Bd3 110. Rg7+ Kh8 111. Kf7 a4 112. Rg4 a3 113. Rh4+ Bh7 114. Ra4 Bg8+ 115. Kf8 a2 116. Rh4+ Bh7 117. Rh1 a1=Q 118. Rxa1 Bg8 119. Rg1 Bh7 120. Kf7 Be4 121. Rg8+ Kh7 122. Rg4 Bd5+ 123. Kf6 Kh8 124. Rh4+ Kg8 125. Rd4 Ba2 126. Rd2 Bb1 127. Rb2 Bd3 128. Rb3 Bc2 129. Rb8+ Kh7 130. Rb2 Bd3 131. Rg2 Kh8 132. Kf7 Bh7 133. Rg7 Bd3 134. Kf8 Bh7 135. Rc7 Bg8 136. Rc8 Kh7 137. Rc3 Kh8 138. Rc2 Bh7 139. Rg2 Be4 140. Rg8+ Kh7 141. Rg4 Bf5 142. Rf4 Bc2 143. Rf2 Bd3 144. Rd2 Be4 145. Kf7 Kh8 146. Rd8+ Kh7 147. Rd4 Bg6+ 148. Kf6 Bc2 149. Rc4 Bb1 150. Rc1 Bd3 151. Rd1 Bc2 152. Rg1 Kh8 153. Ra1 Bh7 154. Re1 Bg8 155. Rh1+ Bh7 156. Kf7 1/2-1/2


