{[%evp 0,114,28,34,29,-9,4,-15,-2,4,33,1,10,10,10,-33,-24,-26,-19,-16,-1,-36,-34,-30,-23,-5,0,-6,4,-13,7,-20,-20,-9,0,16,17,11,10,-5,-10,3,7,-14,-14,2,4,-30,-30,-103,-110,-117,-116,-118,-118,-113,-116,-116,-118,-111,-118,-119,-118,-134,-122,-123,-118,-123,-121,-118,-118,-123,-129,-140,-134,-129,-124,-119,-119,-120,-119,-115,-119,-119,-123,-119,-121,-121,-121,-121,-121,-121,-108,-113,-111,-111,-98,-121,-121,-114,-121,-121,-121,-214,-206,-240,-231,-224,-239,-238,-214,-213,-207,-203,-204,-204,-203]} 1. d4 {Vidit, Santosh Gujrathi} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qb3 {I wasn't expecting this variation. This line was supposed to be quite easy for Black, so I was intrigued to see what idea David had in mind.} c5 6. dxc5 Na6 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3 Nxc5 9. cxd5 Qxd5 10. Be3 Nce4 11. Qb4 $5 {This was played only once before. I was out of the book and decided to play the most natural moves.} a5 (11... Bd7 12. Rd1 a5 13. Qb6 Qa2 {is the engine's first line. Don't ask me why!}) 12. Qd4 O-O 13. Ne5 {White's main trump is the pair of bishops. Although he lacks a bit in development, if he manages to get f3-e4, kicking my knights, he would stand better.} a4 14. Nd3 ({In the previous game Black surprisingly blundered with} 14. f3 $4 Qa5+ 15. Qb4 Qxe5 16. fxe4 Bd7 $19 {0-1 (25) Moranda,W (2599)-Tregubov,P (2592) Germany 2018}) 14... Rd8 {I saw this move instantly, but I was looking to find something more forcing.} ({I was attracted to the sophisticated idea of} 14... Qa5+ $5 15. Qb4 Qf5 {The point is that now f3 is met with Nd5. But sadly I couldn't find anything after} 16. Bc1 $1 {It looks ridiculous to bring one of the only developed pieces back to its initial position. But now that the threat of Nd5 isn't there, there isn't an easy way to stop f3-e4.} (16. f3 Nd5 $1)) 15. Qxd5 {Until now David had been blitzing, but surprisingly he took half an hour to play this move.} (15. Qb4 {was the only other alternative. It didn't work due to some beautiful lines.} Qf5 {threatening Nd5} 16. f3 (16. g4 $5 Nxg4 17. Bb6 Rxd3 $1 18. exd3 Nef6 $1 {Black has fantastic compensation for the exchange.} (18... Nexf2 $6 19. Rg1 Qe5+ 20. Kd2 Qg5+ 21. Kc2 {and the king runs})) 16... Nd5 17. Qd4 e5 $1 18. Nxe5 Ng5 19. g4 Qf6 $132) 15... Nxd5 16. Bc1 b5 {I wanted to have a firm grip on c4 as my knights will eventually end up there.} (16... Bd7 $1 17. f3 Nd6 18. e4 Nb6 {followed by Bb5 seems to solve all the problems.}) 17. f3 Nd6 18. e4 Nb6 19. Bd2 $6 {A surprising move as it allows the exchange of the light squared bishop.} (19. Bf4 $5 Nbc4 20. Be2 f6 21. Bxd6 Nxd6 22. Nb4 {White has a very pleasant endgame, although it's quite close to equal.}) 19... Ndc4 20. Bc3 Ne3 21. Ke2 (21. Nb4 Nxf1 22. Rxf1 $11 {is probably a less clumsier way of exchanging.}) 21... Nbc4 22. Ne5 Ba6 (22... Nxf1 {Initially I wanted to simply a force a draw with} 23. Nxc4 bxc4 24. Rhxf1 Rd3 {but then later I realized that I can try to pose some more problems. Although it's still completely equal, of course.}) 23. Nxc4 Nxc4 24. Rc1 $4 {David hallucinated. He told me after the game that he simply missed the idea of Nd2.} (24. Kf2 Nxb2 {Black wins a pawn, but still the endgame should be completely equal, as the bishop on a6 is nothing more than a pawn.} 25. Be2 Nd3+ 26. Ke3 Rdc8 27. Bd4 Nc5 28. Bxc5 Rxc5 29. Rhc1 Rac8 30. Rxc5 Rxc5 31. Rd1) 24... b4 25. Bxb4 Nd2+ 26. Ke3 Nxf1+ 27. Rhxf1 Bxf1 28. Rxf1 Rac8 $17 {The endgame should be completely winning for Black, but there are still some technical difficulties as it's not easy for Black to find an entry into White's camp.} 29. Bc3 f6 30. h3 {Another strange move, unnecceasarily weakening the g3 square.} Kf7 31. Rg1 Rd7 {I decided to shuffle around till move 40 before taking any concrete measures.} 32. Ke2 Kg6 33. Ke3 Kg5 34. Rc1 {Cheeky.} Kg6 {I didn't want to take any big committal decisions before move 40. I decided to simply improve my position to the maximum.} 35. Kf2 h5 36. Kg3 Rd3 (36... Rcd8 {is slightly careless as it would free the rook on c1.} 37. Bb4) 37. Kf2 h4 38. Ke2 Rd7 39. Ke3 Kh5 40. Rf1 Rcd8 {There are two main plans in this position: 1) To push the king back to e2 and try to enter with the king via g5-f4-g3. 2) To block the kingside and manoeuvre the king all the way to b3. The 1st plan was shorter and more tempting. The lazy person that I am, I decided to go for the shorter route.} 41. Ke2 Rb8 (41... Kg5 {is the natural follow up but I couldn't see how to procede after} 42. Rc1 Kf4 43. Be1 {Preventing Kg3.} Rb7 44. Rc2 Rdb8 {Initially, I thought this was winning for Black as it seems that the bishop has to prevent both Kg3 and support the b2 pawn.} {But then I spotted the idea of} 45. Kf2 (45. b4 $3 {The computer spots the brilliant idea of mating the black king!} axb3 46. Rc5 $1 {The idea of g3 hxg3/Bd2# is impossible to parry.} Rd7 47. Bxh4 $18 {1-0 Bruzon Batista,L (2659)-Vidit,S (2651) FIDE World Cup 2015 (1.3) Ironically, once I had trapped my king exactly this way in the World Cup.}) 45... Rxb2 46. Bd2+ Ke5 47. Bc3+) 42. Rc1 Rb3 43. Rf1 Kg5 44. Ke3 Rb6 45. Rc1 Rbd6 46. Ke2 Rd3 47. Be1 Rb3 48. Rc2 e5 {As I couldn't make any progress on the kingside, I decided to opt for the second plan of transferring the king to the queenside.} 49. Bc3 Kg6 50. Ke3 $6 {Allowing the rook to the 1st rank can't be right. He probably got tired of defending and started making mistakes.} Rd1 $19 51. f4 $2 {Whoever said mistakes come in pairs was a wise man.} Re1+ 52. Kd2 Rxe4 53. fxe5 fxe5 54. Kd3 Rd4+ 55. Ke3 Kf5 56. Rf2+ Rf4 57. Rd2 Rc4 {It's funny how the last round makes or breaks your tournament. With a win, I managed to finish second making an average event into a good one.} 0-1


