{[%evp 0,133,36,0,15,15,28,20,48,21,34,33,54,48,36,35,35,44,49,22,27,27,27,35,31,31,47,22,22,29,2,13,23,20,30,34,30,32,50,33,41,57,54,75,82,26,63,55,59,72,66,53,72,53,59,42,42,41,42,30,44,54,60,54,54,44,58,56,67,50,42,38,70,42,69,52,61,22,38,12,63,56,46,47,34,42,63,54,60,16,24,29,55,0,30,-12,-12,25,26,23,24,30,33,28,71,28,22,11,45,24,63,84,64,64,89,58,101,66,104,104,109,90,94,75,136,145,161,178,210,210,237,499,500,500,973,178]} 1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 g6 4. e3 Nf6 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qb3 Nxc3 9. Bc4 Nd5 10. Bxd5 e6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. O-O Qd5 13. Be3 f6 14. Rfc1 (14. Nd2 Ba6 15. Rfc1 Qxb3 16. Nxb3 Kd7 17. Nc5+ Bxc5 18. Rxc5 Bd3 19. f3 $14 {½-½ (70) Nepomniachtchi,I (2723)-Inarkiev,E (2693) Poikovsky 2013}) 14... Bd6 15. Nd2 (15. Ne1 Kf7 16. Nd3 Ba6 17. Qc2 Rhd8 18. Nc5 Bxc5 19. Qxc5 Qxc5 20. Rxc5 {This endgame is also unpleasant for Black, although the presence of opposite coloured bishops indicates strong drawish tendencies.} Bb7 21. Rac1 Rd5 22. Rxd5 exd5 23. Rc3 Ke6 24. Ra3 Kd7 25. Bd2 $14 {½-½ (70) Sokolov,I (2642)-Darini,P (2524) Guilan 2016}) 15... Kf7 (15... Bd7 16. Nc4 Be7 17. Bf4 O-O 18. Qg3 Be8 19. Bd6 Bxd6 20. Nxd6 {Exchanging dark-squared bishops is a strategic dream for White. The knight is so much superior to Black's remaining bishop, although Black will have a pawn, as a slight reward for his suffering.} Qxd4 21. Qa3 Rb8 22. Rd1 Qxb2 23. Qxa7 Bf7 24. Qe7 $36 {1-0 (43) So,W (2773)-Maghsoodloo,P (2447) Baku 2015}) (15... O-O 16. Qc2 Bd7 17. Ne4 Be7 18. Nc5 Be8 19. Qb3 ({It is more ambitious to keep the queens on the board. For instance:} 19. f3 {[%cal Ge3f2,Gc1e1]}) 19... Bxc5 20. Rxc5 Qxb3 21. axb3 Rf7 {White has very little in this ending.} 22. h4 h5 23. b4 Rb7 {/= ½-½ (37) Diamant,A (2505)-Quintiliano Pinto,R (2487) Goiania 2016}) 16. Qc2 Bd7 (16... Rd8 17. Qxc6 ({I would advise White not to grab the pawn, but to play} 17. Ne4 $1 {in the same way as Nepomniachtschi in the current game.}) 17... Bb7 18. Qxd5 Bxd5 {Black has decent compensation for the pawn. His bishops are excellent.} 19. f3 (19. Nc4 Be7 20. f3 g5 21. Nd2 Rdc8 22. Ne4 Rxc1+ 23. Bxc1 Rc8 24. Nc3 Bb4 25. Bd2 Rc4 $11 {½-½ (43) Kreisl,R (2404)-Erdos,V (2645) Vienna 2012}) 19... Rab8 20. b3 Rbc8 21. Nc4 Be7 22. Rc2 Rc6 23. Rac1 Ra6 24. Nd2 g5 25. Kf2 Ba3 26. Rc7+ Kg6 27. R1c2 Bd6 28. R7c3 h5 $11 {½-½ (31) Cordova,E (2629)-Oliva Castaneda,K (2497) Linares 2017}) (16... Rb8 17. Ne4 $14 {1-0 (32) Xu,M (2302)-Bu,X (2725) China 2018}) 17. Ne4 Rhb8 18. f3 Be7 19. Qf2 Kg7 (19... h5 20. Nc5 a5 21. b3 Bc8 22. Rc2 Qf5 23. Rac1 $16 {½-½ (41) Belov,I (2407)-Alekseev,E (2653) Sochi 2015}) 20. b3 Be8 21. Qg3 a5 22. Nc5 Rd8 23. Rc4 Ra7 24. Rac1 {White has a pleasant advantage, but it's difficult to achieve progress. A lot of manoeuvres followed until Ian finally managed to break through.} Kg8 25. Ra4 Rda8 26. Qe1 g5 27. Bf2 Bf7 28. Rac4 Kh8 29. h3 Rb8 30. Ne4 Ra6 31. Nc5 Ra7 32. R1c2 h6 33. Ne4 Ra6 34. Nc5 Ra7 35. Kh1 Rba8 36. Bg1 Bg8 37. Re2 Bf7 38. Qc1 Rc8 39. Rc3 Bf8 40. Rc4 Be7 41. Qc3 Kg7 42. Qe3 Kg8 43. Re1 Re8 44. Qe2 Raa8 45. Rec1 Rec8 46. Ne4 Kg7 47. Ra4 Rcb8 48. Rac4 Rc8 49. Bf2 Ba3 50. R1c2 Be7 51. Nc5 Kg8 52. Be1 Ra7 53. Ra4 Rca8 54. Qe3 Bd6 55. Ne4 Be7 56. Rc5 Qd8 57. Rxc6 Be8 58. Rxe6 Bf7 59. Ng3 Bxe6 60. Qxe6+ Kh8 61. Nf5 Bf8 62. d5 Qe8 63. Qxf6+ Kh7 64. Bc3 Qf7 65. Qh8+ Kg6 66. Nh4+ Kh5 67. Qe5 1-0


