1. e4 {Tadic,Branko} e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nd3 Nxe4 5. Qe2 Qe7 6. Nf4 {Continuing a bizarre fashion from the World Championship match, though it must be said that trying to find an advantage in this position is a thankless task. Therefore, you have to respect Nepomniachtchi (also a pioneer of the 5.Bd3 Petroff) for trying.} Nc6 {Likewise. I'm not certain what's wrong with ...Nf6 or ...c6.} (6... Nf6 7. Nc3 (7. d4 Qxe2+ 8. Bxe2 Bf5 $11) 7... c6 {would be my choice.} 8. f3 {and now one high-level game went} g5 $5 (8... Qxe2+ 9. Bxe2 d5 10. d4 Bd6 $11) 9. Nd3 Be6 10. b3 Bg7 11. Bb2 Nbd7 12. O-O-O h6 13. Qf2 Ne5 $16 {with an extremely original mess in Ganguly,S-Abasov,N Ulaanbaatar 2018}) 7. c3 {Tadic,Branko: 'N!?'} (7. Nd5 {(Tadic,Branko) - 138/132}) 7... Nc5 8. d4 Qxe2+ 9. Bxe2 Ne6 10. d5 {Usually something has gone wrong if White has gained tempi and achieved d5 in such positions. The Petroff is so solid that Black is fine anyway, though. The problem, rather, lay in what happened if White didn't rush d5.} (10. O-O {doesn't leave Black many good options for development. The main one that makes sense is} Nxf4 11. Bxf4 Be6 12. Bf3 $14 {but here I would award White a little something, mostly because he does still have ways to force through the d5-break, at a moment of his choosing.}) 10... Nxf4 11. Bxf4 Ne5 {Black is fine now.} 12. Na3 Bf5 13. Nb5 O-O-O $5 {Sacrificing this pawn does not seem to have been entirely needed, though it is in principle fine.} (13... Kd7 {Tadic,Branko: ''} 14. O-O-O a6 15. Nd4 Be4 $11) 14. Nxa7+ Kb8 15. Nb5 Nd3+ 16. Bxd3 Bxd3 17. a4 (17. Nd4 Bc4 {regains the pawn.}) 17... Bc4 (17... Re8+ 18. Be3 Bc4 19. O-O-O Bb3 20. Rd2 g6 {is probably no worse a version than the next note.} (20... Re5 $5)) 18. O-O-O Bb3 19. Rd2 $1 {Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#]'} Bxa4 {Tadic,Branko: '?!'} ({Bizarrely, the key to Black's position probably lay in the classy} 19... Re8 $1 20. a5 g6 $44 (20... Re4 {Tadic,Branko} 21. Rd4 (21. Bg3 $2 Ra4 $1 22. Re2 (22. Kb1 Rxa5 23. Nd4 Ba2+ 24. Kc2 Bxd5 25. Re1 Kc8 26. Rde2 b6 $17) 22... Kc8 23. Rhe1 Rxa5 $17) 21... Rxd4 22. Nxd4 Bxd5 23. f3 Be7 $13)) 20. Nd4 {Now this is a little hard to play for Black, mostly because of the imminent mate threats.} Be7 $1 {Black recognises that the priority is to exchange off the knight on d4.} 21. b3 Be8 $1 ({In the similar line} 21... Bd7 22. Ra2 Bf6 23. Kd2 Bxd4 24. Rha1 $16 {Black's king lacks a flight-square on d7 and probably perishes.}) 22. Ra2 {Tadic,Branko: '!?'} Bf6 23. Rd1 (23. Be3 $14) 23... Bxd4 24. Rxd4 Bd7 25. c4 b6 26. b4 Kb7 $2 {Tadic,Branko: '?!' Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#]'} ({The even calmer response} 26... Rhe8 {Tadic,Branko: '!?'} 27. c5 (27. Rd3 {Tadic,Branko} Bf5 28. Rda3 Kc8 29. c5 (29. Be3 Re4 $132) 29... bxc5 30. bxc5 dxc5 31. Ra8+ (31. Ra7 Re1+ $1 32. Kd2 Re7 33. d6 Red7 34. Ra8+ Kb7 35. R2a7+ Kb6 36. Rxd8 Rxd8 (36... Kxa7 $11) 37. Rxc7 Rd7 $11) 31... Kd7 32. R8a7 Rc8 33. d6 g5 34. Bg3 Bd3 $1 35. dxc7 f5 36. f3 f4 37. Bf2 Kc6 $13) 27... Bb5 $1 {Tadic,Branko: '' was needed in order to fully neutralise White's advantage. White cannot give mate with a single rook, and there isn't time to keep both rooks AND double them.} 28. Be3 dxc5 29. bxc5 bxc5 30. Rf4 Bd3 31. Rxf7 Rxd5 $13 {Black's pieces have acheived a measure of co-ordination.}) 27. c5 {Tadic,Branko: '!'} dxc5 28. bxc5 c6 (28... bxc5 {Tadic,Branko} 29. Rb2+ Kc8 30. Rc4 Rde8 31. Rxc5 Kd8 32. Rxc7 Ke7 33. Kd1 $1 (33. Rbb7 Rc8) 33... Rd8 34. Rbb7 h5 35. Bd2 Ke8 36. Bb4 Rh6 37. Rc3 Ra8) 29. cxb6 cxd5 30. Be3 $1 $16 {Tadic,Branko: '!' When playing Kb7, Black must have underestimated this quiet move.} (30. Rxd5 {Tadic,Branko: '?!'} Be6 31. Rxd8 Rxd8 $14 {is dangerous, but nowhere near as dangerous as the game.} 32. Rb2 $14 {Tadic,Branko}) (30. Rb4 {is just misguided:} Ra8 $11) (30. Bc7 $6 {Tadic,Branko} Ra8 31. Rxa8 Rxa8 32. Rxd5 Be6 33. Rd4 $14) 30... Ra8 {Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#]'} 31. Ra7+ {Tadic,Branko: '!'} Rxa7 32. bxa7 Bc6 33. Rg4 ({Engines start speaking of wins which begin} 33. Rf4) 33... Rg8 34. Kd2 Kc7 $2 {Now the position becomes definitely lost, due to immediate Rb8 and Bb8-type tactics.} (34... Ka8 {Tadic,Branko}) 35. Rb4 $1 {Tadic,Branko: '+-!'} Bb7 (35... Ra8 36. Bf4+ Kc8 37. Bb8 $18 {is not really worth playing on}) (35... Kd7 36. Rb8 Rc8 37. Bd4 g6 38. Ke3 Re8+ 39. Kd3 Rc8 40. f3 Re8 41. Bb2 $18 {Black can prevent White's king from reaching the kingside, but cannot simultaneously prevent tactics based on Kc5 and perhaps Rb6xc6.}) 36. Bb6+ Kc6 (36... Kd7 {Tadic,Branko} 37. Ba5 Bc6 38. Rb8) 37. Ba5 {The bishop is lost.} Ra8 {Tadic,Branko} 38. Rb6+ Kc7 39. Rf6+ {1-0 (39) Nepomniachtchi,I (2763)-Vidit,S (2695) Wijk aan Zee 2019 CBM 188 [Fernandez,Daniel Howard]} 1-0


