1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. a3 Bd6 8. Qc2 (8. Nge2 {Chernin,Alexander 2570 - Kavalek,Lubomir 2560, Subotica (izt) 1987 - 43/713}) 8... a6 ({A bit earlier this year Vidit managed to reach equality by going for} 8... c6 9. Nge2 Re8 10. Bd2 b6 11. O-O Ba6 12. Kh1 c5 (12... Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nbd7 14. f3 Qe7 $11) 13. Rad1 (13. f3 Qc8 14. g4 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Nc6 16. Rad1 Qe6 $11) {Better is} 13... Bb7 (13... g6 $6 14. Bxa6 (14. Qb1 Bb7 $11 {Aronian,Levon 2772 - Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi 2727, Berlin 2022 - 151/183}) 14... Nxa6 15. f3 Qe7 16. Be1 $1 Qxe3 17. Bh4 Qh6 18. g3 $14 {}) 14. f3 Nc6 $11 {Vidit assumed that Rapport was prepared for this continuation so he changed his game plan a bit.}) 9. Nge2 Re8 10. O-O b6 11. b4 Nbd7 $146 (11... Bb7 12. Rb1 Qe7 13. h3 Nbd7 14. b5 a5 15. a4 Rac8 16. Qb3 Nf8 17. Nf4 Rcd8 {Diagram [#]} 18. Ra1 $1 {Excellent move! White is preparing Ba3.} Bxf4 19. exf4 Ne4 20. Be3 $14 {Milov,Vadim 2680 - Riff,Jean Noel 2474, Kemer 2007}) 12. Nf4 ({The very same day the following game took place:} 12. b5 Nf8 13. f3 Ne6 14. Kh1 Bf8 15. Bb2 axb5 16. Bxb5 Bd7 17. a4 {(1/2 : 1/2 Nisipeanu,Liviu Dieter 2652 - Lodici,Lorenco 2537, Cattolica 2022) and Black could have been slightly better after} c6 18. Bd3 c5 $15) 12... Bb7 ({Black should avoid} 12... Bxf4 13. exf4 Bb7 14. Be3 h6 15. h3 Ne4 16. Rfe1 $14 {Because White is able to gain a big advantage thanks to his bishop pair.}) 13. Rb1 Nf8 14. f3 Ng6 {Diagram [#]} 15. Nfe2 $1 {White avoids the exchange of knights. Rapport is intending to push e4 and make a strong break in the centre, so he keeps as many pieces on the board as possible.} Qe7 16. Ng3 Qd7 17. Nf5 $14 {White has a more promising position.} Bf8 18. Kh1 Ne7 19. Ng3 $1 {Staying focused and consistent!} Rad8 20. Nce2 {Black cannot prevent e-pawn advance, and it is very difficult to suggest any improvement for Vidit.} Ng6 ({Maybe, Black could have put stronger resistance after} 20... h5 21. Nf4 h4 22. Nge2 $14 {with somewhat more pleasant position for White.}) 21. e4 dxe4 22. fxe4 Re6 23. Bb2 ({Maybe better is} 23. d5 Re5 (23... Ree8 {Diagram [#]} 24. Rxf6 $1 gxf6 25. Nh5 $18) 24. Nd4 Rde8 25. Nf3 $16) 23... Ng4 24. Qb3 b5 (24... Rf6 25. Bc2 $16) 25. Bc2 Rc6 26. Nf5 Re8 27. Neg3 a5 28. Bd3 ({Also, White obtains a better position after} 28. bxa5 Ra6 29. Bd3 Rxa5 30. h3 Nf6 31. Nh6+ gxh6 32. Rxf6 $18) 28... Rce6 29. bxa5 c6 30. e5 {White has a winning position, and Rapport brings the victory hope.} Be7 31. Nh5 Bf8 32. h3 Nh6 33. Nxh6+ gxh6 34. Nf6+ Rxf6 35. Rxf6 Bg7 36. Rf2 Rb8 37. Be4 c5 38. Bxb7 c4 39. Qf3 Rxb7 40. Bc3 {Most likely this was the most significant win in the group stage for Richard Rapport.} 1-0


