{[%evp 0,40,20,27,60,18,21,-9,-9,-9,9,22,4,-1,-1,-18,-18,-30,-30,-32,-32,-47,-57,-59,-59,-189,-208,-208,-192,-203,-209,-225,-225,-269,-272,-283,-325,-353,-354,-464,-464,-464,-512]} 1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Qb6 (4... Nf6 {was the original move order.} 5. Nc3 e6 6. g3 Qb6 7. Nc2 {- transposes to the game}) 5. Nc2 Nf6 6. Nc3 e6 7. g3 {In this variation the knight on c2 is a bit passive and also does not control the important c5-square.} Bc5 8. e3 (8. Ne3 d5 $1 {This an important move that allows Black to immediately equalise.} 9. cxd5 Nxd5 $1 10. Ncxd5 exd5 11. Bg2 Bxe3 $1 12. Bxe3 d4 $1 (12... Qxb2 13. O-O O-O 14. Qxd5 $14) 13. Bf4 O-O 14. Qb3 Qa5+ 15. Bd2 Qe5 $132) 8... d5 (8... O-O {likely transposes to the game, for example after} 9. Bg2 d5 10. cxd5 exd5 {- 8...d5}) 9. cxd5 (9. b3 $6 {(Lubczynski-Gritsak, Legnica 2013)} dxc4 $1 {improves on the game for a couple of reasons. Black wants to use the open d-file (intending ..0-0, d8). Also after xc4 the light squared-bishop is misplaced, as normally the bishop would go to g2.} 10. Bxc4 (10. Na4 Bb4+ 11. Nxb4 Qxb4+ 12. Bd2 Qe7 13. Bg2 (13. bxc4 b6 $15) 13... O-O 14. bxc4 e5 $15) (10. bxc4 {This recapture leaves a White with a weak c4 isolated pawn which is high price to play to get in the natural g2.} O-O 11. Bg2 Rd8 12. Qe2 Qa6 13. O-O e5 $17) 10... O-O 11. O-O Rd8 12. Qe2 Ne5 $17) 9... exd5 $1 {The isolated d-pawn structure is fine for Black who leads in development and controls d4 which stops White from establishing a blockade with d4. White is developed passively and after the aggressive development ...g4, Black has a slightly better position.} (9... Nxd5 10. Bd2 $1 (10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Bg2 O-O 12. O-O Rd8 13. b3 {Followed by b2, the position is roughly equal.} (13. a3 $6 Be7 14. b4 Bf6 15. Rb1 Bf5 16. Bb2 d4 $1 17. e4 Be6 18. Qd2 Ne5 $17 {Wei Yi-So Wesley, Internet 2018}) 13... d4 {Black makes the thematic advance which liquidates the isolated pawn and after a long forcing computer variation, the position fizzles out to a draw.} 14. exd4 Nxd4 15. Bg5 $1 f6 16. b4 $1 Nxc2 17. Qxc2 Bd4 18. Bf4 Bxa1 19. Bc7 Qxb4 20. Bxd8 Be6 21. Rxa1 Rxd8 22. a3 Qb3 23. Qxb3 Bxb3 24. Rb1 Be6 25. Bxb7 $11) 10... Nxc3 11. Bxc3 O-O 12. Bg2 e5 $11) 10. Bg2 Bg4 $1 (10... Be6 {is a slightly passive move.} 11. O-O Be7 {(Moroni-B.Szabo, Gabicce Mare 2013)} 12. b3 $1 O-O 13. Bb2 $14) (10... O-O {Avoiding the complications that would arise from giving up the d-pawn after 10...g4 11.xd5} 11. O-O (11. Nxd5 $2 Nxd5 12. Qxd5 (12. Bxd5 Bh3 $17) 12... Bb4+ 13. Nxb4 Nxb4 $19 {[%csl Rc2,Rd3]}) 11... Bg4 12. Qd2 (12. Nxd5 $2 {Taking the d-pawn fails because White is left with too many hanging pieces after} Bxd1 13. Nxb6 Rad8 $1 $19 {This is the nice tactical point, the rook escapes the attack and defends the d1, while White is left with two hanging knights.}) 12... Rfe8 13. Na4 Qb5 14. Nxc5 Qxc5 $132) 11. f3 $6 {A bad move. White now has several weak pawns and the bishop on g2 is blocked by the f3-pawn.} (11. Nxd5 $1 {This is the only move, but eventually Black will have a slight advantage in the endgame.} Bxd1 (11... Qa5+ $2 12. Qd2 $1 $16) 12. Nxb6 Bxc2 13. Nxa8 Kd7 14. Bd2 Bd6 $1 (14... Rxa8 $2 15. Rc1 $18) 15. O-O Rxa8 $15 {Two minor pieces are usually better than a rook and a pawn and this position is no exception.}) 11... Bf5 12. Kf2 $2 {The losing move.} (12. O-O {This was the way to prolong the game but Black will still have a better position, with an extra pawn.} Bxc2 13. Qxc2 Bxe3+ 14. Bxe3 Qxe3+ 15. Qf2 Qxf2+ 16. Rxf2 O-O-O $17) 12... Bxc2 $1 13. Qxc2 d4 $1 {Black makes the thematic advance to open the position and start a direct attack. The position is hopeless for White.} 14. exd4 Bxd4+ 15. Kf1 O-O 16. Bh3 Rfe8 $19 17. Ne4 Nb4 18. Qe2 Qc6 19. Bg2 Nc2 20. Rb1 Nd5 0-1


