{I had my first encounter with Sethuraman back in 2005. And, funnily enough in 12 games I have played 11 Blacks! :)} 1. e4 {Szabo,Krisztian Szabo,Krisztian} e6 {I always have had the craziest games with the French and I was very much in a fighting mood that day.} 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 (3... Bb4 {I have played this from time to time. In fact I had played this against Sethuraman in last year's Indian ch. Sadly it was an uneventful draw after ed.}) 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 Be7 8. Qd2 O-O 9. dxc5 (9. h4 {Szabo,Krisztian} a6 10. dxc5 Nxc5) 9... Nxc5 10. O-O-O a6 11. h4 {Szabo,Krisztian: 'see 9.dxc5.'} Qa5 $146 (11... b6 {Szabo,Krisztian} 12. Kb1 f6 {(Inarkiev-A.Schenk, Germany 2016)} 13. exf6 {if Black plays ...f6 in the French Steinitz usually White should take there, otherwise his e5- might become a weakness in the future.} Bxf6 14. g4 $36) 12. Kb1 (12. Bd3 Nxd3+ 13. Qxd3 Nb4) 12... b5 13. Bd3 b4 {My opponent was blitzing out moves till this point. But from now on he started to use a lot of time for each move.} 14. Ne2 ({Szabo,Krisztian: 'After'} 14. Bxh7+ {leads to a crazy draw! leads to a crazy draw! Szabo,Krisztian: 'Vidit gives a nice drawish variation:'} Kxh7 15. Ng5+ Kg8 16. Bxc5 bxc3 17. Qd3 g6 18. Bxe7 Nxe7 19. h5 d4 $1 20. hxg6 Qb4 21. Rh8+ $1 Kg7 $1 (21... Kxh8 $4 {Szabo,Krisztian} 22. Qh3+ $18) 22. Rh7+ Kg8 $11) 14... Nxd3 15. Qxd3 (15. cxd3 d4 $1 16. Nexd4 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Bb7 $11) 15... Qb5 {An important move! Before White can play g5 and provoke some weaknesses, it is better to get rid of the queen from the diagonal.} 16. Qd2 (16. Qxb5 {Szabo,Krisztian: '!' '!' I was slightly concerned by this during the game. But I thought counterplay on the a-file would be sufficient for the doubled pawns.} axb5 17. g4 $14 {Szabo,Krisztian}) 16... a5 17. Ned4 (17. g4 {with the same idea as in the game, but not giving the extra option of f6.} a4 18. Ned4 Nxd4 19. Nxd4 Qc4 {Szabo,Krisztian: '!' '!' Szabo,Krisztian: 'Vidit'} 20. f5 b3 (20... f6 $1 {This looks much safer than b3} 21. fxe6 (21. Nxe6 Bxe6 22. fxe6 b3 $132) 21... b3 22. Nf5 Re8 23. Nxe7+ Rxe7 24. exf6 Rxe6 {Szabo,Krisztian: '' '' And the line ends with 0.00!}) 21. Rc1 (21. cxb3 axb3 22. a3 exf5 23. gxf5 Bxa3 $1 24. bxa3 Rxa3 $19) 21... Bb4 22. c3 Bc5 23. f6 $1 {Engines due to the advanced pawn and the bishop pair seem to support Black, but the position looks extremely scary.} Ba6 24. Rhd1 $40) 17... Nxd4 18. Nxd4 Qc4 {The queen at least appears to be doing something here!} (18... Qa6 19. g4) 19. g4 f6 $6 {I didn't want to give White the freehand of f5-f6. I thought the activity will compensate for the e6-weakness.} ({Black is probably fine after} 19... a4 $142 20. f5 f6 {transposing to 17.g4}) 20. exf6 {A very normal move, but for some reason my opponent took 40 minutes to play this!} (20. Nf3 {Maybe he was considering this move, but Black seems fine after} Qe4 $132) 20... Bxf6 21. h5 ({I was only expecting the natural} 21. g5 Be7 (21... Bd8 $1 {The engine says this is better. I couldn't understand for a long time why, but it has a deep point. Compared to e7 in the lines with h5-g6 h6 xh6.. Black has an extra defence with a7! :)}) 22. h5 (22. Rhe1 Bd6) 22... a4 23. f5 $1 {I missed this neat trick during the game!} exf5 24. g6 $40 {White has a strong attack whereas Black's attack seems very slow. which transposes to 21.g5}) 21... a4 (21... e5 {I was trying to make this work desperately, but the d5-pawn is too fragile.} 22. fxe5 Bxe5 23. b3 Qa6 (23... Qc3 24. Qxc3 bxc3 25. Nc6) (23... Qc7 24. Nf3) 24. Nf5 $16) 22. h6 $6 {This turns the tables!} (22. g5 {Szabo,Krisztian: '!' I thought it was better to play this, as it kicks the bishop off this important diagonal.} Be7 23. f5 $1 (23. h6 g6) 23... exf5 24. g6 $40 {which transposes to 21.g5}) 22... g6 23. Rhe1 Bd7 {I played this almost instantly.} (23... e5 {leads to fascinating lines!} 24. fxe5 Bxe5 25. Nf5 $3 {strictly the only move to keep the game level} gxf5 (25... Bxf5 26. gxf5 Rxf5 27. Qxd5+ Qxd5 28. Rxd5 $11) 26. Bc5 $1 Qxc5 27. Qg5+ Kh8 28. Rxe5 Ra7 29. Rexd5 Qe7 30. Rd8 Qxg5 31. Rxf8+ Qg8 32. Rxg8+ Kxg8 33. Rd8+ Kf7 34. Rxc8 fxg4 35. Rc4 {And it's 0.00!}) 24. Bf2 {Here I was very confused regarding which rook to play to e8. Surprisingly either of the moves isn't in the top 3 choices!} Rfe8 (24... Rae8 25. Bg3) (24... Rac8 {Stockfish says this is better, but it is too deep for me to understand :)} 25. Nxe6 $6 (25. Rc1 $142) 25... Rfe8 $1 (25... Bc3 26. Qd3 Bxe1 27. Nxf8 $11)) 25. Nf3 b3 (25... Bc3 {fails to the cool} 26. Qe3 $1 (26. Qe2)) (25... a3 26. b3 Qc3 27. Bd4 $1 $14) 26. Bd4 e5 $1 (26... bxc2+ 27. Qxc2 Qxc2+ 28. Kxc2 {This endgame is potentially very dangerous for Black.}) 27. fxe5 Bxg4 $2 {Now the crazy complications start!} (27... bxc2+ $142 28. Qxc2 Qxc2+ 29. Kxc2 Bd8 $1 $15 {I was so tempted by bxc2+ that I completely forgot about this retreat} (29... Bh8 30. Rg1 $14)) 28. exf6 bxc2+ 29. Qxc2 (29. Ka1 cxd1=Q+ 30. Rxd1) 29... Bf5 (29... Qxc2+ 30. Kxc2 Bxf3 31. f7+ $18) 30. Qxf5 gxf5 31. Rg1+ $2 {Played very quickly, now the position is objectively drawn, although still complicated.} (31. Ng5 $1 {we both missed this simple move. White's pieces co-ordinate perfectly and f7 is a strong threat. we both missed this simple move. White's pieces co-ordinate perfectly and f7 is a strong threat. Szabo,Krisztian: 'Vidit'} Re4 32. f7+ Kf8 33. Nxh7+ Kxf7 34. Ng5+ Kg6 35. Nxe4 dxe4 36. h7 $1 f4 37. h8=Q Rxh8 38. Bxh8 e3 39. Rd4 $1 Qc7 40. Rd5 $1 $18) 31... Kf8 32. Ng5 Re2 $1 33. Nxh7+ Ke8 {We both were under time pressure here. My opponent had 3 minutes whereas I had a little bit more.} (33... Kf7 34. Rg7+ Ke6 35. Ng5+ $11) 34. a3 {Stopping a4-a3.} (34. Ka1 $2 {I was worried about this move for a moment, but it fails to nice tactic} a3 35. Rg8+ Kd7 36. Rxa8 Qxd4 $1 $19) (34. Rg8+ $2 Kd7 35. Rg7+ Kd6 $19) (34. Bc3 a3 35. Rg8+ Kd7 36. Rxa8 Qe4+ 37. Ka1 axb2+ 38. Bxb2 Re1 $11) (34. f7+ {was the easiest way to draw} Kxf7 35. Rg7+ Ke6 36. Ng5+ Kd6 37. Nf7+ $11) 34... Rb8 35. Ka1 $2 (35. Rg8+ Kd7 36. Rxb8 Qc2+ 37. Ka2 Qxd1 38. f7 Qxd4 {We both thought Black is winning here but} 39. Rb7+ Kc6 40. Rb4 $1 $11 {this move saves the game!}) (35. f7+ {Szabo,Krisztian: '=' '=' again was the easiest way to draw.}) 35... Rb3 $1 36. f7+ Kxf7 37. Rg7+ Ke8 $1 38. Nf6+ (38. Rg8+ Kd7) 38... Kd8 39. Rg8+ $4 {Szabo,Krisztian: '?' '?'} (39. Bb6+ $1 {was the only move to survive.} Kc8 40. Rc7+ Qxc7 41. Bxc7 Kxc7 42. Nxd5+ Kb7 {Szabo,Krisztian: '' ''} 43. h7 Rh2 $17) 39... Ke7 40. Nxd5+ Qxd5 $4 {The famous 40th move blunder! I panicked when I saw few seconds remaining on the clock.} (40... Kf7 {would have won} 41. Rg7+ Kf8 {Szabo,Krisztian: '-+' '-+'} 42. Nb4 {I thought White has defended everything and h7 is coming next and I prematurely stopped my calculations here.} Re1 $3 {After this pretty move, White is just lost.} 43. Rxe1 Qxd4 44. Rb1 Rxa3+ 45. Na2 Rb3 $19) 41. Bf6+ Kxf6 (41... Kf7 42. Rxd5 Kxg8 43. Rxf5 $11) 42. Rxd5 Rexb2 43. Rg1 (43. Rd1 $142) 43... Rh2 44. Rf1 Rxa3+ 45. Kb1 Rb3+ 46. Ka1 Ra3+ 47. Kb1 Rb3+ 48. Ka1 Ra3+ {An exciting game! Had I taken my chances, the tournament would have had a different winner :)} (48... Rh5) 1/2-1/2


