1. e4 {Sagar Shah} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. Bd3 $5 {In simple words this is not a theoretically challenging move. However, there are some tricky lines and if you are not prepared, you can fall into some sort of trap or prepared line.} (6. e5 {It goes without saying that this move has been played on almost every occasion that this position has been reached at the top level.}) 6... d5 7. Qe2 (7. e5 Ng4 8. O-O Bc5 9. Bf4 (9. h3 Nxe5 10. Re1 Qf6 $17 {and Black is better.}) 9... O-O 10. h3 Nxf2 11. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 12. Kxf2 Qh4+ 13. Bg3 Qd4+ 14. Kf1 Qxb2 {with a complicated position.}) 7... dxe4 8. Nc3 (8. Bxe4 Nxe4 9. Qxe4+ Qe7 {gives Black a long lasting advantage of two bishops in a completely open position.}) 8... Bb4 9. Bxe4 {Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#]'} O-O {Tadic,Branko: 'N!' Black's position already looks very sound. True, his pawns are weak. But he has castled and got his king to safety. The white king is still in the centre and the queen is awkwardly placed on e2. The only upside for White is that he is going to win a pawn on c6, at the same time stopping ...e8.} (9... Nxe4 10. Qxe4+ Qe7 {Tadic,Branko: '=''Sagar,Shah: 'Tadic,Branko: '='''} 11. O-O Qxe4 12. Nxe4 Bf5 {should be around even.}) (9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Nxe4 11. Qxe4+ Qe7 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7 13. Bf4 Be6 {This should end in a draw.}) 10. Bxc6 Rb8 {Tadic,Branko: '*'} 11. Be3 $6 (11. O-O {was a good move for White. It is difficult to say what Aryan was worried about. Because d1 is quite a big threat now.} Qd6 $1 {Theoretically Black is fine.} 12. Bb5 Ng4 13. g3 Ne5 14. Bf4 Bxc3 15. bxc3 Rxb5 16. Qxb5 Nf3+ 17. Kg2 Qe6 18. Kxf3 Bd7 19. Qe5 Qc6+ 20. Ke3 Re8 $11) 11... Qd6 (11... Ng4 {was also strong} 12. Bxa7 Qf6 {[%cal Gf6c3,Gf6c6]} 13. Qf3 Qe5+ 14. Kd1 Bc5 15. Bxb8 Nxf2+ $19) 12. Bf3 Ba6 $6 (12... Ba5 $1 {Attacking b2 makes it very difficult for White to meet this move.} 13. O-O (13. Qd2 Rxb2 $19) 13... Ba6 14. Bf4 Bxe2 15. Bxd6 Bxf1 16. Bxf8 Kxf8 17. Kxf1 Rxb2 $17) 13. Qd2 {Now Black has to either exchange the queens or let White castle long.} Qe7 14. O-O-O Ba3 $1 {Vidit is in his element! I would be very afraid if I was White here. First of all Black's king is safe and I already have four black pieces looking at my king.} 15. Na4 Bxb2+ $1 {Now for a second, let's leave the engines aside and try to look at this game from a practical point of view. The bishop has taken the pawn on b2 and opened up the white king. As Kasparov says, in an attack there are no pieces or pawns. There are units of attack and units of defence. Here b2 is a unit of defence that is destroyed by a unit of attack!} 16. Nxb2 Qa3 17. Bd4 $6 (17. c4 {might have been better, but I am already quite cynical after Tadic,Branko: 'Sagar,Shah: 'might have been better, but I am already quite cynical after''} Qxa2 {Tadic,Branko: '''Sagar,Shah: 'Tadic,Branko: '''' I have a feeling that Black should have decent compensation here, and any human player over the board would feel the same. However, the engines are not convinced. Tadic,Branko: 'Sagar,Shah: 'I have a feeling that Black should have decent compensation here, and any human player over the board would feel the same. However, the engines are not convinced.''} 18. Qc2 $1 Qa1+ 19. Qb1 Qa5 20. Rd4 Rb3 21. Bd2 Qc5 22. Bd1 Qxd4 23. Bxb3 Qxf2 24. Rd1 $14 {and although White is losing pawns, his king is safe and he can surely claim an advantage here.}) 17... Qxa2 18. Qc3 Rfd8 $1 {Tadic,Branko: '' Bringing the last piece into the game. Black's threat is ...a1 followed by taking the piece on b2.} 19. Bc6 Bb5 $3 {The Indian GM finds a great resource. The idea is to simply deflect the bishop from the control of the e4 square so that the knight can jump in.} (19... Qa1+ 20. Kd2 Qxb2 21. Qxb2 Rxb2 22. Kc3 {and even though White is a pawn down, he is better here because of his active bishops.} Rbb8 23. Bxa7 $16) 20. Bf3 (20. Bxb5 Ne4 $19) (20. Nd3 Bxd3 21. Rxd3 (21. Qxd3 Rb4 $1 22. Bxf6 Rxd3 $19) 21... Qb1+ 22. Kd2 Qxh1 $19) 20... c5 $5 (20... Be2 $3 {Following the same theme this move would have won the game.} 21. Bc6 (21. Rde1 Bxf3 22. gxf3 c5 $1 23. Qxc5 Qa1+ 24. Kd2 Qxb2 $19) (21. Bxe2 Ne4 $19) 21... Bxd1 22. Rxd1 Qa1+ 23. Kd2 Qxb2 24. Qxb2 Rxb2 {The rest is just matter of technique.}) 21. Qxc5 Qa1+ 22. Kd2 Qxb2 {Once again, though this looks completely winning, the white king manages to survive. Now this is not something that you can blame a player for. Vidit's evaluation ended somewhere here saying the material is even, and white king is disastrously placed, while the black king is great. It should be better for Black. But the tragedy is that it is not! White's king feels really safe on e3.} 23. Ke3 $1 Qa2 (23... Re8+ 24. Kf4 $1 $16 {The king is afraid of no one!}) 24. Bxf6 gxf6 $2 (24... Qe6+ 25. Be5 Re8 $11 {was how Black could have survived.} 26. Kf4 Qh6+ 27. Kg4 Qe6+ $11) 25. Rxd8+ Rxd8 26. Qxb5 {Black is just a piece down now with no compensation.} Qxc2 27. Rd1 $2 (27. Be4 $1 {Not such a difficult move to find for Aryan.} Qd2+ (27... Qc3+ 28. Kf4 $18 {Once again the king is safe.}) 28. Kf3 $18) 27... Rxd1 28. Qb8+ Kg7 29. Bxd1 Qxd1 {Now the game is drawn. Vidit tries to push it as much as possible, but there is nothing much he can do here.} 30. Qxa7 Qg1 31. Kf3 Qxh2 32. Qd7 h5 33. g3 Qh1+ 34. Ke3 Qe1+ 35. Kf3 Qe5 36. Kg2 f5 37. Qd2 Qe4+ 38. Kh2 Qg4 39. Qc3+ Kh7 40. Qc7 Qg6 41. Qf4 Qf6 42. Kh3 Kg6 43. Qb8 Kg7 44. Qf4 Qg6 45. Kh4 f6 46. f3 Kh7 47. g4 hxg4 48. fxg4 fxg4 49. Qc7+ Kg8 50. Qd8+ Kf7 51. Qd7+ Kf8 52. Qd8+ Kg7 53. Qc7+ Qf7 54. Qxf7+ Kxf7 55. Kxg4 Ke6 56. Kf4 {Tadic,Branko: '½-½ (56) Tari,A (2593)-Vidit,S (2692) Khanty-Mansiysk 2017 CBM 179 [Sagar,Shah]'} 1/2-1/2


