1. d4 {Marin,Mihail Marin,Mihail Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 c6 {Flear,Glenn: 'A solid choice, but one that looks somewhat unambitious.' Marin,Mihail: '!?' '!?'} 6. cxd5 (6. Bf4 {was featured in Potkin, V - Kamsky, G Moscow 2010, which can be found in the archives.}) ({I always thought that} 6. Bg5 {was a good antidote as there is additional pressure on the d5-square, but Black can complicate matters, for example with} dxc4 7. Qxc4 Qb6 $5 8. e4 Qxb2 9. Rb1 Qa3 10. e5 Be6 11. Qb4 Qxb4 12. Rxb4 Nd5 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 14. Rxb7 Nd7 {Crouch, C - Gormally, D British league 1999, and it seems that Black has good chances, noting that ...c5 is threatened.}) 6... Nxd5 {Marin,Mihail: '!?' '!?' Marin,Mihail: 'An interesting opening experiment. As Black will soon play ...c6-c5, he basically loses a tempo with respect to the normal Exchange System lines. His main aim is proving that b3 is not so useful, as it weakens the defence on d4 and exposes the queen to ...e6 or ...c6-a5. On the other hand, the queen defends c3, so White can play an early d4-d5 as a reaction to Black's typical centre undermining. So far, this line has been mainly used by lower rated players and this is a first high level practical test. '} ({After} 6... cxd5 {then this time} 7. Bg5 {is fairly effective e.g.} Nc6 8. e3 e6 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O h6 {(Black has to do something, as otherwise White's much smoother development is annoying)} 11. Bh4 g5 12. Bg3 Nh5 13. Rac1 Nxg3 14. hxg3 Bd7 15. Rfd1 g4 $5 16. Nd2 h5 17. Ne2 Rb8 18. Nf4 Qg5 19. Bb1 Rfd8 20. Qd3 f5 21. Nb3 {with the easier game for White, Bu Xiangzhi - Andriasian, Z Riyadh Blitz 2017.}) 7. e4 {Flear,Glenn: 'So we have a type of Exchange Variation with the additional moves Qb3 for White and ...c6 for Black.'} Nxc3 ({Flear,Glenn: 'As a rule, the retreat to b6 isn't 'dynamic' enough for my taste e.g.'} 7... Nb6 {- 7/561 Marin,Mihail: '(Perunovic,Milos) - 7/561'} 8. Be3 O-O 9. Rd1 Be6 10. Qc2 N8d7 11. Be2 Bg4 12. O-O {Mamedyarov, S - Areshchenko, A Eilat 2012, and White's central grip ensures an enduring pull.}) 8. bxc3 O-O 9. Be3 {Diagram [#] Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: 'Diagram [#]'' Marin,Mihail: 'A natural developing move, but possibly not the strongest.'} ({Practical examples are few and far between, but so far it seems that Marin,Mihail: 'Intuitively I would say that the queen's development to b3 suits the plan based on'} 9. Ba3 $5 {is White's best chance of an edge: Marin,Mihail: 'as Black will need some time to prepare ...c6-c5, thus ensuring the prolonged stability of the queen on b3. Here are a few examples:'} Qc7 (9... Nd7 10. Bd3 ({A very old game went} 10. Be2 {Marin,Mihail} c5 11. O-O cxd4 {and now} 12. Nxd4 $2 $11 {Bogoljubow,E-Saemisch,F Lueneburg 1947 (½-½, 47) was clearly not what White should play,}) 10... c5 {Marin,Mihail: 'Black has carried out his thematic break, but with the knight on d7 the queen has no worries.'} 11. O-O b6 12. Rad1 e6 13. Bc4 Qe7 14. Rfe1 {(White's development is more rapid and threatening)} Bb7 15. Bc1 $1 {and now that White is fully mobilized, the bishop is redeployed to a more useful diagonal, Leitao, R - Toth, Chr Joao Pessoa 2013 Marin,Mihail: '' '' Marin,Mihail: 'Leitao,R (2636)-Toth,C (2365) Joao Pessoa 2013 (1-0, 46)'}) 10. Be2 Be6 {Marin,Mihail: 'is not likely to offer Black enough counterplay:'} 11. Qb2 Rd8 12. Ng5 Bc8 13. Qb3 {Marin,Mihail: '' '' Marin,Mihail: 'Ivanisevic,I (2665)-Bitici,G (2068) Skopje 2016 (1-0, 36)'} Rf8 {(another return to starters, but now White is ready to go for sharp play)} 14. Bc4 $1 Bxd4 $5 15. cxd4 Qa5+ 16. Kf1 Qxg5 17. h4 $1 {Ivanisevic, I - Bitici, G Skopje 2016, with a promising initiative (and in addition, Black can't even hold onto his e7 pawn).}) 9... c5 $146 {Flear,Glenn: 'Black has lost a tempo (...c6 followed by ...c5) over a 'Be3 Exchange Variation', but this extra tempo is Q-b3, an unusual choice. However one advantage of this bonus move (that doesn't escape Vidit's attention) is that it defends the c3-pawn, thus enabling White's next...' Marin,Mihail: 'Obviously the critical continuation. In games between lower rated players Black has delayed his counterplay, allowing White to keep his space advantage. '} (9... Nd7 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'}) 10. d5 {Flear,Glenn: '!' Marin,Mihail: 'The most logical way of justifying b3.'} ({But} 10. Be2 {Marin,Mihail has no obvious refutation.} cxd4 11. cxd4 Nc6 (11... Qa5+ $5) 12. Rd1 Bg4 13. d5 {Kumaran,D (2310)-Rojas Keim,L Guarapuava 1991 (½-½, 34)} Ne5 $5 14. Nxe5 Bxe2 15. Kxe2 Bxe5 {White's space advantage remains impressive but due to the slightly exposed king's placement on e2 Black has chances for counterplay.}) 10... Nd7 {Marin,Mihail: 'Defending c5 with a developing move and creating a threat which White failed noticing.'} 11. Bd3 {Flear,Glenn: '?!' Marin,Mihail: '?!' '?!'} ({Flear,Glenn: 'With hindsight, I think that' Marin,Mihail: 'Therefore, the critical move is'} 11. Rc1 {Flear,Glenn: '!' Flear,Glenn: 'was the correct move, keeping control for now.' Marin,Mihail: '!' '!' Marin,Mihail: 'defending and unpinning c3, when Black still needs to struggle finding a constructive plan.'} Nf6 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} 12. Qc2 Qa5 (12... e6 13. Bxc5 exd5 14. Bxf8 Qxf8 15. e5 Ng4 16. Be2 Nxe5 17. O-O $14) 13. Be2 e6 14. d6 Bd7 15. O-O Bc6 $13) ({Following} 11. Be2 {Black could consider} Nf6 12. Nd2 b6 {intending ...e6 to counter the white centre.}) ({Abstractly, it makes sense preparing to consolidate the centre with c3-c4 by unpinning the c-pawn. But} 11. Rd1 {Marin,Mihail still allows} b5 {for instance} 12. Bxb5 Rb8) 11... b5 $1 {Flear,Glenn: 'Creative play. Artemiev notices a negative side of the queen's position on the b-file, as either capture on b5 will give White some problems.'} 12. Qc2 (12. Bxb5 $2 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: '?''} Rb8 {Flear,Glenn: '!' Flear,Glenn: 'and the threat of ...a6 along with the pressure along the long diagonal gives Black the advantage.' Marin,Mihail: '' '' Marin,Mihail: 'leaves White hanging to ...a7-a6 and ...xc3.'} ({this is more to the point than} 12... Qa5 13. Bd2 Rb8 14. c4 Qc7 {as after} 15. Bc3 {White would have chances to keep control}) 13. Bf4 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} Rb7 $17) (12. Qxb5 $2 Bxc3+ {and Black will be able to safely take on a1.}) 12... b4 {Marin,Mihail: '!' '!'} (12... f5 $5 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} 13. exf5 $140 c4 14. Be2 Ne5 (14... Rxf5 $13) 15. fxg6 Bf5 16. gxh7+ Bxh7 17. Qd2 Nd3+ 18. Bxd3 Bxd3 $44) ({The slow approach} 12... c4 {Marin,Mihail} 13. Be2 Nb6 14. Nd4 a6 {offers White a free hand to start a typical attack.} 15. h4) 13. Bd2 ({Had White anticipated what was going to happen in the game, he might have sacrificed the pawn with} 13. O-O {Marin,Mihail , when his strong centre and good development might have offered reasonable compensation for the pawn.}) 13... c4 {Flear,Glenn: '!' Flear,Glenn: 'More activity to rattle his opponent.' Marin,Mihail: '!' '!'} 14. Bxc4 (14. Be2 {Marin,Mihail} Nc5 15. Bxc4 bxc3 $15 {leaves the e4-pawn hanging, offering Black the initiative partly based on the enemy king's presence in the centre.}) 14... Qc7 15. Be2 bxc3 {Marin,Mihail: '' '' Marin,Mihail: 'The opening has ended in an obvious fiasco for White. His centre is immobile and the c3-pawn is very strong. '} 16. O-O {Diagram [#] Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: 'Diagram [#]''} Ne5 $1 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: '!''} 17. Rfc1 {Flear,Glenn: 'Vidit is in the process of completing development, but it has come at the cost of allowing Black's c-pawn to cramp his prospects.'} (17. Nxe5 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} Qxe5 (17... Bxe5 18. Rac1 Bd7 19. Be3 Bxh2+ 20. Kh1 Be5 21. f4 Bg7 22. e5 $44) 18. Be3 f5 19. Bc4 f4 (19... Kh8 $15) 20. Bc5 Kh8 21. f3 Bd7 $15) (17. Rac1 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} Nxf3+ 18. Bxf3 Ba6 19. Rfd1 Rfc8 20. d6 (20. Be3 Rab8 $17) 20... exd6 21. e5 Rab8 22. Qxc3 Qxc3 23. Bxc3 Bxe5 24. Bxe5 dxe5 $17) ({The knight exchange favours Black, as he can coordinate his pieces better for sustaining the passed pawn, but White has no favourable way of avoiding it:} 17. Nd4 {Marin,Mihail} Ng4 18. Nf3 Bd7 $15) 17... Nxf3+ 18. Bxf3 Bd7 $1 {Diagram [#] Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: '!' Perunovic,Milos: 'Diagram [#]''} 19. Bxc3 {Flear,Glenn: '!?' Flear,Glenn: 'Sacrificing the exchange in order to avoid being 'worse without play'. The engine doesn't think much of this but, in practical terms, having a powerful dark squared bishop certainly offers White something for his sorrows.' Marin,Mihail: 'A desperate attempt to save the game. White has to eliminate the dangerous pawn at any cost.'} (19. d6 $142 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} Qxd6 (19... exd6 20. Bxc3 Rac8 (20... Rfc8 21. e5 Rab8 22. Qd2) 21. Bxg7 Qxc2 22. Rxc2 Rxc2 23. Bd1 $1 Rd2 24. Bxf8 Kxf8 25. Bb3 $15) 20. Bxc3 Rac8 21. Qb2 Rxc3 22. Rxc3 Rb8 23. Qc2 Qd4 24. Rd1 Qxc3 25. Qxc3 Bxc3 26. Rxd7 Rb2 27. g3 (27. a3 e5 $17) 27... Rxa2 28. Rxe7 Bd4 $17) (19. Bg5 {Marin,Mihail} Rab8 20. Bxe7 Rb2 $19) (19. Rab1 {Marin,Mihail} Rfc8 20. Bg5 Rab8 $19 {[%cal Gb8b2]} 21. Bxe7 Rb2 22. Rxb2 cxb2 23. Qxc7 bxc1=Q+) 19... Rfc8 $17 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: '''} 20. Bxg7 (20. e5 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} Bxe5 21. d6 Qxc3 22. Qxc3 Bxc3 23. Rxc3 Rxc3 24. Bxa8 exd6 $17) 20... Qxc2 21. Rxc2 Rxc2 22. Bd4 a5 ({Marin,Mihail: 'Now or on the next move it would have been simpler to force White into passivity with'} 22... Rac8 23. Be3 {Marin,Mihail: 'White cannot allow the exchange of rooks.'} f6 24. h4 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} (24. g4 {Marin,Mihail} a5 $17) 24... a5 $17) 23. h3 Rb8 {Flear,Glenn: 'The rooks are great but, in such open positions, bishops aren't too bad either!'} 24. a3 (24. e5 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} Rb4 25. Be3 Rcb2 26. Kh2 Rb1 $17) 24... f6 $6 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: '?!''} (24... Rc4 $1 $17 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'}) 25. e5 {Flear,Glenn: '!' Flear,Glenn: 'Open lines are going to be necessary to keep the white bishops going.'} Rc4 26. Rd1 Ba4 ({Marin,Mihail: 'White's saving chances are not obvious after'} 26... fxe5 27. Bxe5 Rb3 28. d6 e6 $17 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: ''' Marin,Mihail: 'either, as the rook has no open files available, but of course it is not easy to allow him to have such an advanced passed pawn.'}) 27. Rd2 Rc2 ({Artemiev decides to trade White's rook at the cost of a pawn. Instead,} 27... Kf7 28. exf6 exf6 29. d6 {looks reasonable for White.}) 28. Rxc2 ({If} 28. Rd3 {Black could be insistant with} Rb3) 28... Bxc2 29. exf6 exf6 30. d6 {Marin,Mihail: 'Possibly fruit of a misscalculation.'} ({Flear,Glenn: 'For the record,' Marin,Mihail: 'But Black's winning chances remain intact after'} 30. Bxf6 Kf7 31. Be5 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} (31. Bc3 a4 {Marin,Mihail: '' ''} 32. Bd4 $15 {doesn't look too bad either.}) 31... Rb3 32. Bd6) 30... Kg7 31. d7 $2 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: '?''} (31. Bc3 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} Rd8 32. Bxa5 Rxd6 33. Bb4 Rd4 $17) 31... Ba4 $19 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: '-+''} 32. Bg4 {Diagram [#] Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: 'Diagram [#]''} Bxd7 $1 {Flear,Glenn: 'Safe, but perhaps not strong enough to win.' Marin,Mihail: 'Probably this is what White missed. But if so, this was a brilliant blunder from a practical point of view.'} 33. Bxd7 Rd8 34. Bb6 Rxd7 35. Bxa5 {Flear,Glenn: 'Without the a-pawn, such positions are considered to be book wins (I remember a Speelman-Kasparov endgame). However, now winning attempts are more problematic as, for example, Black can't threaten to head into a pure king and pawn endgame. In the game Vidit successfully uses his a-pawn as a decoy.'} Rd1+ 36. Kh2 Rd3 37. Bb4 Kf7 38. Bc5 Rd5 39. Bb4 Ke6 40. g3 {Flear,Glenn: 'Setting up his desired kingside fortress while he still has time.'} f5 {Marin,Mihail: 'Black's position is simply won. The a-pawn does not really count and with the actual pawn display White would have needed the light-squared bishop to retain saving chances.'} 41. Kg2 Rd3 42. Bf8 Kd5 43. Be7 Ke6 {Diagram [#] Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: 'Diagram [#]''} ({The typical plan in the positions without the a-pawn would be a massive invasion starting with} 43... Kc4 {Marin,Mihail It would work perfectly fine here, too.} 44. Bb4 Kb3 45. g4 ({Passive defence would not do either:} 45. Bf8 Kc2 46. Bb4 Kd1 {Planning ...e2, ...f3 followed by preparing the pawn break ...f5-f4.} 47. Kf1 f4 $19) 45... Kc2 46. gxf5 gxf5 47. Bc5 Kd1 48. a4 Ke2 49. a5 Rc3 50. Be3 Ra3 51. Kg3 (51. Bb6 f4 $19) 51... Rxa5 52. Kf4 Rb5 {Putting White in some sort of zugzwang.} (52... Kf1 53. Kf3 {slightly complicates matters.}) 53. Ba7 (53. Kg3 Rb4 54. Bc5 Rb3+ 55. Be3 Rxe3+ 56. fxe3 Kxe3 $19) 53... Kf1 {[%cal Gf1g2]} 54. Kf3 Rb4 55. Bc5 Rc4 56. Bb6 h5 57. Ba7 h4 58. Be3 Kg1 $19) 44. Bf8 $1 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: '!''} g5 {Flear,Glenn: 'This turns out to be committal, but I'm not confident enough to know if it's actually a mistake. What else could he try anyway, I'm thinking?' Marin,Mihail: '?!' '?!'} 45. Bc5 Rc3 46. Be3 {Flear,Glenn: '!' Flear,Glenn: 'Oh, a surprise choice. The a-pawn is abandoned in order to trade some kingside pawns.' Marin,Mihail: '!' '!' Marin,Mihail: 'Obviously underestimated by Black.'} (46. Bb4 $17 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} Rb3 $140 47. Bf8) 46... h6 (46... Rxa3 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} 47. Bxg5 Kd5 48. Bf4 $11) ({One idea is Marin,Mihail: 'I failed to find a winning plan for Black after'} 46... g4 47. hxg4 fxg4 48. a4 (48. Bb6 {Marin,Mihail} Rxa3 {½-½ Cebalo,M (2515)-Nedev,T (2415) Cannes Martinez op 1996 (7) which seems to be a fortress. Please refer to}) 48... Ra3 49. a5 Rxa5 50. Bb6 Ra2 51. Be3 {and I can't see how Black will make progress.}) 47. h4 $1 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: '!''} gxh4 48. Bxh6 hxg3 49. f3 {Marin,Mihail: '!' '!' Marin,Mihail: 'The saving move. White will win the g-pawn and keep the favourable kingside structure.'} (49. fxg3 $2 {Marin,Mihail leaves the light squares undefended.} Rxa3 50. Kh3 Ra7 51. Kg2 Ke5 52. Bf4+ Ke4 53. Bb8 Ra2+ 54. Kh3 Kf3 55. Kh4 Ra8 56. Be5 Rg8 57. Bd6 Kg2 58. Be5 Rg4+ 59. Kh5 Rxg3) 49... Rxa3 50. Kxg3 $11 {Flear,Glenn: 'A book draw it seems.' Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: '='' Marin,Mihail: 'This is a theoretical draw already, as the bishop and the pawn complete their actions. The main thing White should avoid is pushing his pawn to f4.'} Ra4 51. Bg5 Ke5 52. Bh6 Rc4 53. Bg7+ Kd5 54. Bh6 Kc6 55. Bg5 Kb5 56. Bh6 Kb4 57. Bg5 Kc3 58. Bh6 Kd3 59. Bg5 Ke2 60. Bh6 Rc3 {Flear,Glenn: 'Artemiev has done all he can do, but Vidit's reaction shows why he can't win.'} 61. Kf4 {Flear,Glenn: '!' Marin,Mihail: '!' '!'} Rxf3+ 62. Ke5 {Flear,Glenn: 'Threatening Bf4 and then Kxf5.'} Rh3 63. Bg5 $1 Rh5 64. Kxf5 1/2-1/2


