1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Bxc6 bxc6 $5 {The most fashionable move recently. Black is provoking a double-edged position, as we will see later in the game.} (4... dxc6 {is the more 'solid' approach. One of the typical positions is this one:} 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 Nf6 7. Nc3 Nd7 8. Be3 e5 9. Qd2 {[%cal Re3h6,Gh7h6,Gd7f8,Gf8e6,Rf3h2,Rf2f4] White intends to exchange the bishops, and at the same time will think about preparing the move f4, to achieve better control in the centre. Meanwhile, Black has the option to play ...h6 to stop h6, and also to play ...f8-e6, placing the knight on an excellent square.}) 5. O-O Bg7 6. Re1 Nh6 $1 {Gelfand himself is a big defender of this variation, according to my database he has played it 15 times in official games (classical and other time controls)} (6... e5 $6 {now this move is supposed to be slightly inferior for black:} 7. c3 $1 Ne7 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 exd4 10. Nxd4 O-O 11. Nc3 {White is somewhat more comfortable, with a better pawn structure and nice pieces. On the other hand, Black has the bishop pair, but he has to be watching all the time for weaknesses with the hanging c6-d7 pawns.} Rb8 12. Nb3 Qc7 13. Bg5 d6 14. Qd2 Be6 15. Nd4 $14 {/, 1-0 (47) Delgado Ramirez,N (2611)-Matsuura,E (2485) Foz do Iguacu 2018 Even though the game wasn't convincing later, White msnsged to achieve a better position out of the opening.}) (6... Nf6 {allows yet another different setup from White:} 7. e5 Nd5 8. c4 Nc7 9. d4 cxd4 10. Qxd4 $1 {bringing the queen over to h4} Ne6 (10... O-O 11. Qh4 {threatening the simple h6, followed by c3, with a huge advantage} f6 $1 12. Bd2 Ne6 13. Bc3 $14 {1-0 (32) Svetushkin,D (2574)-Hirneise,J (2315) Hofheim 2017}) 11. Qh4 d6 12. exd6 Qxd6 13. Nc3 Bf6 14. Ne4 {looks drawish} (14. Qe4 $5 $146 {keeping the game going} O-O 15. Bh6 Re8 16. Rad1 $36) 14... Bxh4 15. Nxd6+ exd6 16. Nxh4 f6 $1 {avoiding Bg5-f6} 17. Nf3 Kf7 18. Rd1 Rd8 $11 {½-½ (40) Hasangatin,R (2502)-Grachev,B (2647) Sochi 2018, and Black equalised comfortably.}) 7. c3 O-O 8. d4 (8. h3 {is more popular recently.} f5 (8... d5 {is also possible, preparing a pawn sacrifice.} 9. d3 c4 $5 10. exd5 cxd5 11. dxc4 dxc4 12. Qxd8 (12. Qe2 $5 Nf5 13. Bf4 Bb7 14. Nbd2 Rc8 15. g4 e5 $2 (15... Qd5 $1 16. gxf5 Qxf5 $44) 16. Bxe5 Nh4 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Nxh4 Qxh4 19. Qe7 $1 $16 {1-0 (33) Areshchenko,A (2675)-Hracek,Z (2594) Hungary 2017}) 12... Rxd8 13. Na3 Bb7 (13... Nf5 $5 14. Nxc4 Bb7 $44 {It seems like Black is always able to sacrifice a pawn somehow in this variation!}) 14. Bxh6 Bxh6 15. Nxc4 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Rac8 $44 {½-½ (25) Smirin,I (2644)-Moiseenko,A (2671) Jerusalem 2017}) 9. e5 Nf7 {preparing d6 with a clearly better position if White does nothing} 10. d3 (10. d4 cxd4 11. cxd4 Bb7 12. Na3 (12. Nc3 c5 13. d5 e6 $1 $132 {0-1 (40) Haria,R (2441)-Sankalp,G (2374) Stockholm 2018}) 12... c5 $1 {with very good counterplay for Black} 13. dxc5 Rc8 14. Be3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Nxe5 16. Qd5+ e6 $13 {½-½ (29) Wang,H (2702)-Gelfand,B (2729) Tbilisi 2017}) 10... d6 11. Bf4 Ba6 12. Na3 (12. Nbd2 $5 Bxd3 13. e6 Ne5 14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. Bxe5 Bxe5 16. Rxe5 c4 17. Qe1 Qb6 18. b4 $1 a5 19. a3 $14 {1-0 (41) Zhigalko,S (2620)-Meribanov,V (2396) Minsk 2018}) 12... Rb8 13. b3 g5 14. Nxg5 Nxg5 15. Bxg5 dxe5 16. Nc4 e4 $1 $132 {½-½ (44) Khismatullin,D (2632)-Gelfand,B (2695) Sochi 2018}) 8... cxd4 9. cxd4 d5 10. e5 f6 11. Qc2 $5 {Vidit comes up with a novelty in a popular position where many moves are possible.} (11. e6 Qd6 $1 {is the precise move here, Black immediately attacks the pawn and creates direct counterplay.} (11... Nf5 $6 12. Bf4 $1 (12. Nc3 Qd6 $1 13. Qe2 c5 $5 $132 (13... Qb4 14. a3 Qb3 15. h4 a5 16. Bf4 Ba6 17. Qd2 h5 18. Rac1 $13 {1-0 (34) Saric,I (2677)-Saric,A (2541) Pozega 2018})) 12... g5 13. Qc2 Nd6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Qf5 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Rb1d2,Rd2b3,Rb1c3,Rc3a4] trying to achieve a blockade on the c-file with c3-a4, or bd2, c1} Rb8 16. b3 $16 {½-½ (21) Solozhenkina,E (2230)-Kovalevskaya,E (2405) Moscow 2017}) 12. Qe2 Nf5 13. b3 Qb4 14. Ba3 Qa5 15. Qb2 Bh6 $132 {1-0 (54) Antipov,M (2550)-Ganguly,S (2672) Monzon 2016}) (11. Nbd2 $5 fxe5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. dxe5 Qb6 14. Nf3 Nf5 15. Qc2 c5 16. b3 Bb7 $132 {1-0 (77) Karthikeyan,M (2585)-Mamedov,R (2709) Moscow 2018}) (11. exf6 $5 exf6 12. Nbd2 Re8 13. h3 Nf7 14. Nb3 Bf5 15. Bf4 g5 16. Bh2 Qb6 17. Qd2 Bf8 $1 $11 {½-½ (42) Gharamian,T (2637)-Cornette,M (2581) Agen 2016}) 11... Bg4 (11... Qb6 $5 {has to be tested here}) 12. Nbd2 Qb6 13. h3 fxe5 {Gelfand accepts the challenge!} (13... Bf5 $6 {would allow White to achieve the dream position controlling the c5-square} 14. Qc3 Nf7 15. Nb3 $16 {[%cal Gb3c5]}) (13... Bxf3 $5 14. Nxf3 Nf5 {[%cal Rf5d4] threatening on d4. White has many interesting moves here, simply reinforcing the fact that 11.c2 has to be explored in future games.}) 14. hxg4 Nxg4 15. Nc4 $5 (15. Qd3 $5 {a very hard move to conceive - White wants to avoid ...d3 after Black plays ...exd4. And there is an idea to place the queen on e2.} e4 (15... exd4 16. Rxe7 $16) (15... Rae8 16. Qe2 {[%cal Rd4e5]} e4 17. Nxe4 dxe4 18. Qxe4 Nf6 19. Qe6+ Kh8 20. Re2 $16) 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Rxe4 $16) 15... dxc4 16. Qxc4+ Kh8 17. Qe6 {[%csl Rg4]} Rf5 (17... Nxf2 18. Kxf2 Qxd4+ (18... exd4 19. Kg1 $16) 19. Kg3 $16) (17... Rxf3 18. gxf3 $16) 18. Re4 {[%csl Rg4]} Nf6 (18... Nxf2 $5 19. Kxf2 exd4 {wasn't good enough} 20. Rb1 $1 $16 {preparing to develop the c1-bishop without losing the b2-pawn.}) (18... Rxf3 19. gxf3 Nf6 20. Rxe5 {transposes to the game -- 18...f6.}) 19. Rxe5 Rxf3 20. gxf3 Qxd4 (20... Nd5 $5 21. Re2 Rf8 $132) 21. Be3 Qxb2 22. Rc1 Rf8 23. Rxc6 Ng4 {[%csl Re5]} 24. Re4 Nxe3 25. Rxe3 Bf6 {Suddenly the position has calmed down, and White maintains a big advantage, but it's not that easy to convert. Exchanging rooks looks natural.} 26. Rc8 Rxc8 27. Qxc8+ Kg7 28. Qe6 Qc1+ 29. Kg2 Qc5 30. Re4 a5 31. f4 Qc2 32. f5 {trying to open up the black king as much as possible.} g5 33. a4 Qd1 34. Rc4 h5 $1 {White is not threatening much, but Black is looking for active counterplay, that seems like a good idea.} 35. Qe4 g4 (35... h4 $1 {this counter-intuitive move was good enough to balance the game. The idea is to put the king on a safe square (h6) and force White to be careful with moves like ...h3+.} 36. Qg4 $6 h3+ 37. Kxh3 Qh1+ 38. Kg3 Be5+ 39. f4 Qg1+ {with a forced draw} 40. Kf3 Qd1+ 41. Kg3 Qg1+ 42. Kf3 $11) 36. Rc7 (36. Rc5 $1 {attacking a5, and now if Black plays ...h4, then 37.d5! wins right away.} h4 $2 37. Rd5 $1 $18) 36... Qd6 (36... h4 $1 37. Rxe7+ {there was no need to defend against this, Black has enough counterplay against the white king:} Bxe7 38. Qxe7+ Kg8 $1 39. f6 (39. Qxh4 Qf3+ 40. Kg1 Qxf5 $11) 39... Qd5+ 40. Kh2 Qf7 $1 41. Qd8+ Kh7 42. Qxa5 Kg6 43. Qe5 Qc4 44. a5 Qc2 $1 $11) 37. Ra7 Qc5 38. Rd7 Qa3 39. Rd3 Qc5 40. Rd8 Qc3 41. Qe6 $6 (41. Qd5 $1 $18 {threatening checkmate in two moves with g8+ and g6#. At the same time, White keeps an eye on the f3-square} Kh6 42. Rg8 {[%cal Rg8g6,Rd5g8]} Bg7 {is the most stubborn defense} (42... Kh7 43. Rg6 $18 {forcing Black to play ...f3+, losing the endgame easily}) 43. Qe6+ Kh7 44. Rd8 $1 {the most precise, so Black will not have ...d1+ after ...f3+} Qf3+ 45. Kg1 $18) 41... Kh6 $1 42. Rg8 Qf3+ 43. Kg1 Qd1+ $5 (43... h4 $1 {once again good enough for equality - now Black has a very good flight square on h5, and also wants to play ...h3 at some point.} 44. Rh8+ (44. Rg6+ Kh5 $11) (44. Qe3+ $4 {is even losing for White} Qxe3 45. fxe3 Kh5 $19 {followed by h3 and h4}) 44... Kg5 45. Qg8+ Kf4 $11 {is fine for Black, White has to be careful not to lose here.}) 44. Kh2 h4 45. Rg6+ Kh5 46. Rg7 $1 {[%cal Re6f7]} Kh6 (46... Bxg7 $4 47. Qg6#) (46... Qd6+ $5 {would give Black some drawing chances in the following endgame, but it may be lost anyway:} 47. Qxd6 exd6 48. Ra7 Bc3 {[%cal Rh5g5]} 49. f6 Kg6 50. f7 Kg7 {still, I am not entirely sure what's happening, even with the help of the computer! It says White wins, but the lines are not convincing} 51. Rc7 $1 $18) (46... h3) 47. Rg6+ Kh5 48. Rg7 Kh6 49. Rxe7 Kg5 50. Re8 $2 (50. Qe3+ $1 Kxf5 51. Qe6+ Kg6 52. Rd7 Qf3 53. Kg1 $18 {White wins by a devastating attack, or by exchanging queens.}) 50... Qc2 $2 (50... Qf3 $1 51. Rg8+ Kf4 $1 $11 {a tough move to spot beforehand.}) 51. Qe3+ Kh5 (51... Kxf5 52. Qe6+ Kg5 53. Rg8+ $18) 52. Qf4 $1 Qb3 53. Re3 {Doesn't spoil the win, but there was a beautiful line with 53.e6!} (53. Re6 $1 Qh3+ 54. Kg1 g3 55. Qf3+ $1 Kg5 56. Qe3+ Kh5 57. Rxf6 $1 {with a pretty finish:} Qh2+ 58. Kf1 g2+ 59. Ke2 $18 {and White delivers checkmate first!} g1=Q 60. Rh6+ Kg4 61. Qf3+ Kg5 62. Rg6#) 53... Qd1 54. Re6 Qf1 55. Re4 $1 (55. Rxf6 {allows a forced draw:} g3+ 56. fxg3 hxg3+ 57. Kxg3 (57. Qxg3 Qh1+ $1 58. Kxh1) 57... Qg2+ $1 58. Kxg2 $11) 55... Qd1 56. Qc7 Kg5 $1 57. Qf4+ (57. Qh7 $1 {would demand a lot of courage and precise calculation, but it wins:} Qd6+ (57... g3+ 58. Kg2 $18) 58. Kg2 $3 h3+ 59. Kh1 Qd1+ 60. Kh2 Qd6+ 61. f4+ gxf3+ 62. Kxh3 $18 {a pretty amazing finish! Forcing 58...h3+ to manoeuvre the king and then be able to take the pawn there and hide from the checks.}) 57... Kh5 58. Re6 Qf1 $1 59. Qe3 $2 {Now Black finally escapes.} (59. Re4 $1 $18 {going back to the position after the 55th move.}) 59... Bg5 $1 60. Qd4 g3+ $1 61. fxg3 hxg3+ 62. Kxg3 Bf4+ $1 63. Qxf4 Qg2+ {A nice way to finish this crazy game.} 64. Kxg2 {Stalemate!} 1/2-1/2


