1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 a6 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 Be6 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Qb3 Ra7 9. a3 Qd8 10. h4 c5 $5 {Last month I discussed the moves 10...h6, 10... Be7 and 10...b5 in the game Vidit - Grandelius.} 11. dxc5 ({It is also possible for White to play slowly with} 11. g3 Nc6 12. Qd1 {when play might follow} g6 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Bg2 d4 15. Ne4 Be7 16. O-O O-O $13) 11... Bxc5 12. Rd1 (12. Ng5 b5 13. e3 O-O (13... h6 $6 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. g3 $1 $14 {As will be shown, White gains an advantage with the g3, Bh3 setup if Black has not coordinated all the pieces.}) 14. Rd1 Rd7 {is also interesting territory. Black seems to be holding.} (14... h6 $6 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Nxd5 $1 {is an important point.} exd5 17. Rxd5 Qa5+ 18. Ke2 $14) 15. Be2 (15. g3 d4 $1 (15... h6 $6 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Bh3 Qf6 (17... Kh8 18. Ne2 Rd6 19. Nf4 $16) 18. O-O {is similar to the game. White is better as Black's central pawns are weak.}) 16. Nxe6 (16. Qc2 {also only leads to equality with best play from both sides.} Re8 $1 17. Qxh7+ Kf8 18. Nxe6+ (18. Qh5 $5 Bb6 19. Bh3 dxc3 20. Rxd7 Qxd7 21. Bxe6 Rxe6 22. Nxe6+ fxe6 23. bxc3 $18 Qc6 24. Qh8+ Kf7 25. Qh5+ Kf8 $11) 18... Rxe6 19. Ne4 dxe3 20. Qh8+ Ke7 21. Qxd8+ Kxd8 22. Nxc5 (22. Rxd7+ Nxd7 23. Nxc5 Nxc5 $11) 22... exf2+ 23. Kxf2 Rxd1 24. Nxe6+ fxe6 $11) 16... fxe6 17. Ne4 (17. Bh3 {keeps the game going, but probably to Black's favour.} dxc3 18. Bxe6+ Kh8 19. Bxd7 Nxd7 20. Qxc3 Qe7 21. b4 Bb6 22. Qc6 Bxe3 23. Rxd7 Bxf2+ 24. Kd1 Qe5 $44) 17... dxe3 $1 {After this, Black has very good compensation for the piece, and for engines this means that a draw is made in almost all cases. For human games I think we would all be quite nervous as White! For the record, the line continues} 18. Nxc5 Rxd1+ 19. Qxd1 exf2+ 20. Ke2 Qf6 21. Bg2 Qe5+ 22. Ne4 Nc6 23. Qd2 Nd4+ 24. Kf1 b4 $1 {Introducing the devastating threat of 24...Qb5+} 25. Qxb4 (25. axb4 $4 Qb5+) (25. a4 h6 $1 $44 ({Pure prophylaxis, and it is far too deep, but the idea is revealed by the following line:} 25... Qc7 $4 26. Qxd4 Qc1+ 27. Ke2 Qxh1 28. Nf6+ $1 Rxf6 29. Qd8+ {and Black would love to have the h7-square available for the king.} Rf8 30. Qxf8+ Kxf8 31. Bxh1 $18) 26. h5 (26. Nxf2 Nf5 27. Kg1 Nxg3 28. Rh3 Ne2+ 29. Kf1 Ng3+ $11) 26... Qc7 $1 $11) 25... Rc8 $11) 15... h6 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Bg4 Kh8 $1 18. O-O Rd6 $13 {After 19. g3 this will look very similar to the position after 15.g3. However, the key difference is that Black - by virtue of being a couple of tempi up - is given the time to develop the b8-knight to c6 and immediately to e5 with an active position.}) ({Potentially the most testing move here is} 12. O-O-O $5 b5 (12... Bxf2 13. Nxd5 O-O 14. e4 $36 {Evaluation-wise, I'm not 100% sure what is going on here, but White is definitely having all the fun.}) 13. e4 d4 14. Nd5 O-O 15. Kb1 {Now Black is apparently fine after} Nd7 16. Bd3 b4 17. a4 {though the situation is still far from clear, so I'll leave this with an inconclusive evaluation for now.}) 12... b5 13. Ng5 $6 h6 14. Nxe6 fxe6 {In the aforementioned 11.Ng5 line, White had made the useful pawn move e3 rather than Rd1. In that case, White plays 15. g3! followed by 16.Bh3 with pressure against Black's central construction. Here Black is ready to castle with tempo or play ...Rf7 (depending on the situation) as the f2-pawn will be under fire.} 15. e3 Nd7 $2 (15... O-O $6 {fails to the previously noted} 16. Nxd5) ({If the players understood the subtleties of the position, which is not really possible in a rapid game, they would have realised that Black is better after} 15... Rf7 $1 16. Bd3 ({Now} 16. g3 $6 O-O 17. Bh3 {is too slow!} Rxf2 18. Bxe6+ Kh8 {Now whichever way White captures on d5, Black will have a clear advantage.} 19. Nxd5 (19. Ne4 {is probably White's best option.} Qa5+ 20. Qc3 Qxc3+ 21. Nxc3 Rxb2 22. Nxd5 Bxa3 $15) (19. Rxd5 $2 Qf6 $19) (19. Qxd5 Qb6 $17) 19... Qa5+ 20. Qc3 b4 $1 21. axb4 (21. Nxb4 Qc7 $1 $17) 21... Qb5 22. Qd3 Bxb4+ 23. Nxb4 Qxb4+ 24. Rd2 Rxd2 25. Qxd2 Qe4 $1 26. Bd5 Qb1+ 27. Qd1 Qf5 $17) 16... Qf6 17. O-O O-O $15) 16. g3 $1 O-O 17. Bh3 Qf6 18. O-O Kh8 ({Black would love to be able to play the move} 18... Ne5 {but this of course loses to} 19. Nxd5) 19. Ne2 $1 {Just in time to meet Ne5.} g5 {Some engines indicate that this is overkill, but it seems like a good practical try and, well, it clearly worked!} (19... Ne5 20. Nf4 Re7 21. h5 $16) 20. hxg5 {In some lines the open h-file can be used to Black's advantage, but it was hardly reasonable to expect Vidit to play the strongest move here...} (20. Qc2 $1 Kg7 ({The point is that after} 20... gxh4 21. Nf4 {White will play Ng6+ next and pick up the h4-pawn (or the exchange).}) 21. b4 Bb6 22. Qc6 {and White continues to increase the pressure:} Re8 23. hxg5 hxg5 24. Nd4 Bxd4 25. exd4 $16) 20... hxg5 21. Qc3 $6 {Black is no worse now!} (21. Qc2 Kg7 22. Bg4 {looks like it keeps the most control out of all the possible options, though Black still continues to fight after} Rc7 23. Nd4 $1 Re8 24. Kg2 Bb6 25. Qe2 Ne5) 21... Kg8 $6 {Returning the favour.} (21... Qxc3 22. Nxc3 Rf6 $11 (22... Re8 $11)) 22. Qxf6 {Again, not the best however, White seemed to be happy to exchange queens anyway.} (22. Nd4 $1 Bxd4 23. exd4 $16) 22... Rxf6 23. Rc1 Kf7 24. Nd4 Bxd4 $6 {Somehow I feel that Mamedyarov was generally too happy to execute this exchange, when in reality, the resulting structure is not so pleasant.} (24... Rb7 $1 {hints at liquidation with ...b4 and only after} 25. b4 {does Black play} Bxd4 26. exd4 Nb6 {when the knight will be planted on the c4-square.}) 25. exd4 Ke7 26. Rfe1 Kd6 27. Rc2 $6 {This is too soft.} (27. Rc8 $1 {causes some real problems for Black because of the threat of 28.Re8. If} Nb6 28. Rd8+ $1 (28. Rg8 Rh6 29. Bg4 (29. Bg2 Nc4 30. Re2 Na5 $1 {[%cal Ga5b3]} 31. Rxg5 Nb3 $11) 29... Rah7 $132) 28... Ke7 29. Rg8 {and White will net a pawn.}) 27... Nb6 28. b3 Rh7 $1 29. Bg4 Rfh6 30. Kg2 Rh2+ 31. Kf3 Rf7+ 32. Ke3 Na8 $1 {Brilliant manoeuvring from Mamedyarov. In just a few moves he coordinated his pieces perfectly.} 33. Rec1 Rc7 34. Rc5 (34. Bxe6 $5 {was only enough for a draw, but it's flashy at least!} Rxc2 35. Rxc2 Kxe6 36. Rc8 Rh1 37. Rxa8 Rb1 38. Rxa6+ Kf5 $11) 34... Rxc5 35. Rxc5 ({No doubt Mamedyarov would have responded to} 35. dxc5+ {with the active} Ke5 $1 $13) 35... Nc7 36. Rc1 Ne8 $1 37. Rc8 Nf6 38. Bf3 g4 39. Be2 {It is impressive that the Azeri number one continues to play dynamically even with just a few pieces on the board.} e5 $1 40. dxe5+ $6 {This move in itself does not change the evaluation, but it is already a step in the wrong direction.} (40. Ra8 exd4+ 41. Kxd4 Rxf2 42. Rxa6+ Ke7 43. Ra7+ $11 (43. Bxb5 Rf3 44. Ke5 Re3+ 45. Kf4 Rf3+ $11)) 40... Kxe5 41. Rd8 $6 {Now Black is really better. This does not preclude the possibility that White can hold, but indicates that the defence will not be easy to carry out.} ({Simplest was to exchange a set of pawns with} 41. a4 bxa4 42. bxa4 d4+ 43. Kd3 Rxf2 44. Rc5+ Kd6 45. Ra5) 41... Rh1 42. f4+ gxf3 43. Bxf3 Rb1 44. b4 Rb3+ 45. Ke2 Rxa3 46. g4 Ne4 47. Re8+ $4 (47. g5 $1 {might have been the only defence. Black would then play} Ra2+ {to dismantle the king. White would need to continue with precision here, probably by starting with} 48. Kd1 (48. Ke3 Nd6 $1 {Black threatens ...Nc4+ followed by ... Ra3.} 49. Kd3 Rf2 50. Ke3 Rb2 $15) 48... Kf4 49. Bxe4 Kxe4 50. g6 Rg2 51. Rd6 $1 d4 52. Ke1 Kd3 53. Rxa6 Kc4 54. Rc6+ Kxb4 55. Kf1 {White is just in time to activate the king.}) 47... Kd4 48. Bxe4 dxe4 $19 {This is now a winning rook ending.} 49. Re6 Rg3 50. Rxa6 Rxg4 51. Rc6 Rg2+ 52. Kd1 Rb2 53. Rd6+ Ke3 54. Rd5 Rxb4 55. Kc2 Ke2 56. Kc3 Rc4+ 57. Kb3 e3 58. Rxb5 Rc8 59. Re5 Kd2 60. Rd5+ Ke1 61. Re5 e2 62. Kb2 Rf8 0-1


