{[%evp 0,121,19,31,19,0,4,-10,0,6,38,42,47,27,15,29,19,14,13,13,16,11,8,14,8,-2,6,8,31,27,8,21,21,29,28,19,18,7,5,10,21,14,10,-66,-32,-29,9,-9,31,33,10,11,76,86,79,92,67,49,65,64,62,55,69,73,65,59,77,70,77,77,81,84,84,88,103,88,75,79,83,92,85,85,85,92,111,111,114,114,113,113,108,115,119,108,126,133,137,129,147,161,156,158,158,165,158,155,150,168,316,330,413,399,418,426,475,482,552,764,1056,1092,1131,1156,1192,1186]} 1. d4 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi} d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 c6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. Be2 O-O 8. b3 b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Bb2 Qe7 11. Rad1 Rad8 12. Rfe1 Rfe8 13. h3 {An over the board improvisation. I wanted to play Bf1, but at the same time wanted to avoid Black's ideas with e5.} (13. Bf1 {, with ideas to play e4 or improve the bishop with g3- Bg2, is the most common move. But in this particular position Black has the idea to react immediately in the centre:} e5 $1 14. cxd5 (14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nd4 dxc4 16. bxc4 Bb8 (16... Bb4 17. h3) 17. f4 Ng6 18. g3 $16) 14... e4 $1 {The point.} 15. dxc6 exf3 16. cxb7 Bxh2+ $1 17. Kxh2 Qd6+ 18. Kh3 Re5 $3 19. dxe5 Qe6+ 20. Kh2 Qxe5+ 21. Kg1 Ng4 {with a mating attack.}) (13. e4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Bb4 16. Rf1 Bd6 {has led to many move repetitions.}) 13... a6 {This creates a weakness on the queenside. It's probably better to be less committal.} (13... h6 14. Bf1 c5 $132) 14. e4 dxe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Qxe4 Bb4 17. Rf1 Ba3 $6 (17... Bd6 {I judged that the inclusion of h3-a6 should be in White's favor. However, Black should have played this as he is still quite solid.} 18. Ne5 (18. Bd3 Nf8) 18... f5 19. Qf4 Nxe5 20. dxe5 Bc5 21. Bf3 $14) 18. Bd3 $5 {I played this after a long thought. I wanted to find a way to punish Black's innaccuracy. Objectively it's not the most precise way.} (18. Bxa3 Qxa3 19. Ne5 (19. Rfe1 {Computer's top choice! The idea is to overprotect e2.} Qxa2 20. b4 {followed by c5. White would have enough compensation for the pawn.} (20. Qf4 $1 Qxb3 21. Qc7 Ba8 22. Ng5 {and the engine gives White as better. It was quite tough to judge this during the game.})) 19... Qxa2) (18. Ba1 Nf8 $132 {followed by c5.}) 18... Nf6 19. Bxa3 Qxa3 20. Qf4 c5 21. d5 {The point.} exd5 22. Qc7 Bc8 $6 {Logical, but not the most accurate.} (22... Rd7 23. Qxb6 Re6 24. Qa7 {with ideas like Bf5 and Rfe1, I thought White is doing well. But, Black has sufficient resources:} d4 $1 25. Rfe1 Be4 $1 26. Qb8+ Re8 27. Qf4 Rde7 $1 {and Black consolidates.}) 23. Qxb6 Be6 $6 (23... Qxa2 {During the game I felt that taking the pawn is most accurate.} 24. cxd5 Rxd5 (24... Nxd5 25. Qxc5 Qxb3 26. Bc4 $18) 25. Ra1 {I missed this intermezzo.} (25. Bc4 Rxd1 26. Rxd1 Qc2 $1 {with enough counterplay.}) 25... Qb2 26. Bc4 Rdd8 27. Ng5 $16) (23... h6 $1 {Not an easy move to make. It creates a safe haven for the king and at the same time stops Ng5 ideas.}) 24. cxd5 Bxd5 25. Qxa6 Qxa6 (25... Ra8 26. Qxa3 Rxa3 27. Bb1 c4 28. Nd4 {Compared to the game, Black has more activity.}) 26. Bxa6 Ra8 27. Bb5 Reb8 28. Ba4 {After the game, Sethu confessed that he had apparently missed this idea. Now White remains a pawn up. However, converting the extra pawn is still a task.} c4 29. Nd4 cxb3 30. axb3 Rb6 31. Rfe1 g6 32. Rc1 Rd8 $6 {Allows a favorable exchange of minor pieces.} (32... Rab8 $142) 33. Nc6 $1 Bxc6 34. Rxc6 Rdb8 35. Rxb6 Rxb6 36. Re5 {If I could get my bishop to c4, White would be strategically winning.} Rb4 37. g3 $2 {This allows unnecessary counterplay. Wiser was to play the uglier looking f which restricts the knight on f6.} (37. f3 {looks ugly, but Black cannot take advantage of the weaknesses on the dark squares.} Rd4 38. Bb5) 37... Ne4 $1 38. Rb5 Rd4 39. Rb8+ Kg7 40. Bc6 {I calculated this far. White of course has good winning chances, but Black has some counterplay.} Nc5 $1 41. Rb5 (41. b4 $2 Na6 $1 $11) 41... Nd3 $4 {A complete shocker. Once White exchanges rooks, the extra pawn should be easy enough to convert. For good or worse, Black had to keep the rooks and create some threats around the White king.} (41... Rd1+ $1 42. Kg2 Nd3 43. Be4 f5 $1 {The key move, forcing White to trade the bishop for the knight.} 44. Bxd3 Rxd3 45. h4 Kf6 46. b4 Rb3 {I am not sure about the assesment of this endgame. But definitely, Black has good drawing chances, compared to the game.}) 42. Rd5 Rxd5 43. Bxd5 f5 44. Kf1 Nb4 45. Bc4 (45. Bb7 Nc2 {and it's not easy to bring in the king because of the fork on d4.}) 45... Kf6 46. Ke2 g5 47. Kd2 Ke5 48. Bg8 $1 {Emptying the c4 square for the king, with a tempo.} (48. Kc3 Na2+ $1 49. Kb2 Nb4) 48... h5 49. Kc3 Nc6 50. Bf7 $1 {Precise. It was still possible to blunder away the win.} ({For example,} 50. b4 $2 Nxb4 $3 51. Kxb4 Ke4 52. Bf7 Kf3 53. Bxh5+ Kxf2 54. g4 f4 $11) 50... h4 51. gxh4 gxh4 52. b4 Nd4 (52... Nxb4 53. Kxb4 Ke4 54. Bh5 {stops the king from infiltrating.}) 53. Kc4 Ne2 (53... Nf3 {would require White to be more accurate:} 54. Bd5 Ng5 55. f4+ $1 Kxf4 56. b5 Ke5 57. Kc5 $18 {The b-pawn is unstoppable.} Nh7 58. b6) 54. Kc5 $18 {The rest is easy.} Nf4 55. b5 Nd3+ 56. Kc6 Nb4+ 57. Kd7 Kd4 58. Kd6 Ke4 59. b6 Kd4 60. b7 Na6 61. Bh5 1-0


