1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 a6 4. Nc3 d5 {A popular system nowadays.} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 Be6 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Qb3 {This seemingly strange sequence, with a voluntary exchange of the bishop, contains a nice trap.} Ra7 $1 {8...Ra7 is better than 8...b5.} ({But not} 8... b5 $2 9. a4 $1 b4 10. Nxd5 $3 Qd8 11. e4 c6 12. Qe3 $1 cxd5 13. exd5 Qxd5 14. Rc1 $1 {[%cal Rf1c4] , and amazingly, White regains the piece in all variations, keeping a positional advantage, which was seen in a number of recent games.}) (8... b6 {is a weakening move, of course, and White keeps an edge after, say,} 9. g3 Qd8 10. h4 Be7 11. Ng5 $1 O-O 12. Bg2 c6 {1-0 (93) Nesterov,A (2476)-Enchev,I (2501) Chess.com INT 2021} 13. Nxe6 $5 fxe6 14. e4) 9. a3 $5 {[%mdl 4] An interesting side line. An interesting useful move preventing possible ...Bf8-b4 in future and forcing Black to speak out.} (9. Nxd5 Qd8 10. e4 c6 11. Qb6 {gives Black sufficient counterplay after} cxd5 12. Qxa7 Bb4+ 13. Kd1 dxe4 14. Qxb7 {0-1 (31) Srihari,L (2302)-Gholami,A (2541) New Delhi 2020} O-O $1 $44 {[%csl Rd1]}) (9. g3 {is the main option, tested in a number of games.}) 9... Qd8 10. h4 ({Alternative:} 10. Qc2 $5 {[%cal Ye2e4]} c6 (10... Be7 11. e4 c6 12. e5 Nd7 13. Bd3 h6 14. O-O O-O 15. h3 $14 {1-0 (42) Basso,P (2538)-Druska,J (2494) Tornelo INT 2021}) (10... Bd6 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 h6 13. Bc4 Bxc4 14. Qxc4 Qe7 15. O-O O-O 16. Rfe1 $14 {1-0 (27) Basso,P (2538)-Nilssen,E (2121) Cattolica 2021}) 11. e4 $5 (11. e3 Nd7 12. Bd3 g6 13. h4 Nf6 $11 {1/2 (125) Hakobyan,A (2559)-Jacobson,B (2486) Saint Louis 2019}) 11... dxe4 12. Qxe4 Be7 13. Bd3 Ra8 14. O-O Nd7 15. Rfe1 $14 {0-1 (45) Radovanovic,M (2474)-Yurtseven,M (2385) Montebelluna 2019}) 10... h6 (10... Be7 11. e4 c6 (11... dxe4 $5 12. d5 Bf5) 12. e5 Nd7 13. Qc2 b5 14. Rd1 $14 c5 $6 15. dxc5 Nxc5 16. b4 Nd7 17. Nxd5 $16 {1-0 (53) Vidit,S (2726)-Grandelius,N (2670) Tornelo INT 2021}) 11. Qc2 {The insertion of h2-h4 h7-h6 looks favorable for Black, who has protected the g5 square and controls g4.} Bd6 $6 {This move is probably less fortunate than the following alternatives:} (11... Nd7 $5 12. e4 dxe4 13. Qxe4 Nf6 14. Qe3 Ng4 15. Qd2 Bd6 16. d5 Bf5 $11 {1/2 (20) Moiseenko,A (2620)-Vetoshko,V (2523) Lviv 2021}) (11... Be7 12. e4 dxe4 13. Qxe4 c6 14. O-O-O Nd7 15. d5 cxd5 16. Nxd5 {1-0 (60) Deac,B (2627)-Urazayev,A (2429) Europe-Echecs INT 2021} Bxd5 17. Qxd5 b5 $11) 12. e4 $1 dxe4 13. Qxe4 Qe7 14. O-O-O Bb3 15. Qxe7+ Kxe7 16. Re1+ Kd8 17. Bd3 {Too soft.} (17. Nd2 $1 Bf4 (17... Be6 18. Bc4 $16) 18. Rh3 Nd7 19. Ne2 Bxd2+ 20. Kxd2 Bc4 21. b3 $16 {A lot is going on in the centre, and Black's a7 rook is still out of play.}) 17... Nd7 18. Bf5 g6 (18... c6 $142) 19. Bh3 (19. Bc2 $5 Bxc2 20. Kxc2 $14 {[%cal Yh4h5]}) 19... a5 (19... Nf6 20. g3 c6) 20. g3 {Apparently preparing Nf3-d2...} Nf6 21. Ne5 $6 {...and not playing it. The game move is pseudo-active (the knight doesn't attack anything) and allows Black to consolidate his position.} (21. Nd2 $1 Bd5 (21... a4 22. Nxb3 axb3 23. Bf1 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Yf1c4]}) 22. Nxd5 Nxd5 23. Nc4 $16) 21... Re8 22. Re3 a4 $2 (22... Ra6 $11) 23. Rhe1 $2 {[%mdl 64]} (23. Nxa4 {is not dangerous due to} Bxe5 $1 24. dxe5 Bxa4 25. exf6 Rxe3 26. fxe3 Ra5) ({but both players missed} 23. Rf3 $1 Bxe5 (23... Be7 $2 24. Nb5 {[%cal Rf3b3,Rb5a7]}) 24. dxe5 Nh5 (24... Nd7 25. Rd3 $16) 25. Rd3+ Ke7 26. Rd7+ Kf8 27. Rxc7 Rxe5 28. Bg2 $16) 23... Ra5 24. Nxa4 (24. Rf3 {is not dangerous anymore due to} Bxe5 25. dxe5 Nd7 26. Rd3 f5 $1) 24... Bxe5 25. dxe5 Bxa4 26. exf6 Rxe3 $2 (26... Rc5+ {was the right move order, of course:} 27. Kb1 Bc2+ 28. Ka1 Rxe3 29. Rxe3 Bf5 $1 $11) 27. Rxe3 {[%mdl 4096]} Rc5+ 28. Rc3 {Ups!} Rd5 29. b3 Bd7 30. Bg2 Rb5 {It is not easy for White to convert his extra pawn but losing??? Well, rapid, online...} 31. Rd3 (31. a4 $5 Rb6 32. Bd5 Kc8 $1 33. Rf3 Be6 34. Bxe6+ Rxe6 35. Kd2 $14) 31... Ke8 $6 (31... Kc8 $142 $1 {to protect the b7 pawn and eventually free the rook.}) 32. Bd5 (32. a4 $142 $1 Rb6 33. Bd5 {, as the pawn endgame after} Be6 34. Bxe6 Rxe6 35. Re3 $1 Rxe3 ({or} 35... Kd7 36. Rxe6 Kxe6 37. Kd2 Kxf6 38. Kd3 Ke5 39. Kc4 Kd6 40. b4) 36. fxe3 Kd7 37. Kc2 Ke6 38. Kc3 Kxf6 39. Kd4 Ke6 40. Kc5 Kd7 41. a5 {is winning for White (try to calculate this is a rapid game!).}) 32... Be6 33. Bxe6 fxe6 34. g4 g5 35. h5 $2 (35. hxg5 $1 Rxg5 (35... hxg5 36. Kb2 c6 37. Kc3 Kf7 38. Rd7+ Kxf6 39. a4 Rb6 40. b4) 36. f3 h5 37. gxh5 Rxh5 38. f7+ Kxf7 39. Rd7+ Kf6 40. Rxc7 b5 {- this endgame should be winning for White.}) 35... Rd5 $1 {Now White can't trade rooks, therefore Black recaptures the f6 pawn and equalizes.} 36. Rc3 c6 37. Kc2 Kf7 38. f3 Kxf6 39. Rc4 Ke5 40. Re4+ Kd6 41. f4 c5 42. a4 b6 43. Kc3 gxf4 44. Rxf4 Rg5 45. Rf6 Rxg4 46. Rxh6 Rh4 47. Rh8 Kd5 48. h6 Rh3+ 49. Kc2 Kd4 50. h7 {Why allow cutting off White's king?} (50. Rd8+ {was simpler, of course.}) 50... Rh2+ 51. Kd1 Kc3 52. b4 $4 (52. Rb8 Rxh7 53. Rxb6 {was still a dead draw.}) 52... c4 {This pawn decides the game.} 53. a5 (53. Rb8 Rxh7 54. Rxb6 Kb2 55. Rc6 c3 56. a5 {, and now the simplest way to win is} Ra7 $1 {(stopping White's pawns) followed by the triumphal march of the e-pawn.}) 53... Kb2 54. Rc8 c3 55. axb6 Rxh7 56. Ke2 c2 57. Kd2 Rd7+ 58. Ke3 c1=Q+ 59. Rxc1 Kxc1 60. Ke4 Rb7 0-1


