{[%evp 0,117,27,-10,23,21,27,12,21,18,5,5,12,5,12,7,25,27,4,-1,21,21,23,27,16,22,12,14,47,39,68,32,73,62,71,74,47,91,85,105,105,85,135,122,154,110,192,166,157,157,208,206,206,208,212,216,202,232,213,217,215,204,276,295,295,262,295,200,245,200,188,174,187,169,179,179,242,158,179,177,186,188,217,184,215,216,216,218,216,225,223,219,221,221,218,226,218,217,214,203,184,194,214,214,205,212,236,240,255,257,266,282,374,388,384,345,357,381,381,364]} {Before this game, Peter was leading by one point in the overall standings. Hence, this game was really important for me as it was my best chance to take the lead.} 1. c4 {Vidit, Santosh Gujrathi One month ago, I used a very interesting novelty to win against Peter in a rapid game. This time, I decided to test him in the English opening, as I felt he would be more thoroughly prepared in the Catalan.} c5 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 d6 6. O-O Rb8 $5 {The first interesting point of the game. Earlier they used to play the setup with e6-Nge7 which was considered solid, although recently the trend has been to play Bf5-Qd7 which is a more aggressive approach. The point of Rb8, as I understand, is quite clever. Black waits for White to commit with a plan & accordingly react with either Bf5-Qd7 or e6/e5 Nge7. I expect lot of new theory to develop in this direction.} (6... e6 7. d3 Nge7) (6... Bf5 7. h3 Nf6 8. d3 O-O 9. Be3 a6 10. Qd2 {This was the most recent top level game, where Maxime quite dubiously sacrificed a pawn on the next move and struggled against Carlsen.} b5 $6 11. cxb5 axb5 12. Nxb5 Qa5 13. Nc3 Rab8 14. Rfc1 Rfc8 15. b3 $16 {1-0 (43) Carlsen,M (2845)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2773) Karlsruhe/Baden Baden 2019}) 7. a3 {With hindsight, this a3-b4 idea looks a bit slow.} (7. e3 {might be the more critical approach, directly fighting in the centre.} Nf6 8. d4) 7... a6 8. Rb1 (8. b4 cxb4 9. axb4 Nxb4) 8... b5 $6 {A pleasant surprise! With a clever intermezzo, Black could have won some tempi.} (8... Bf5 $1 9. d3 b5 10. cxb5 axb5 {The point is that as Black has forced me to play d3, I can't continue with my b4 plan as the c3 knight will be left hanging.} 11. Bd2 Nf6 12. b4 cxb4 13. axb4 Qd7 14. Bg5 O-O 15. Qd2 Rfc8 $11 {Black looks completelty fine.}) 9. cxb5 axb5 10. b4 cxb4 11. axb4 $14 Nf6 {A subpar move. Already at this point Peter was thinking for a long period of time, suggesting me that he felt quite uncomfortable.} (11... Bf5 {was more tricky, although White is still slightly better after} 12. Rb3 Be6 13. Ng5 $1 Bd7 14. Nge4 $1 Nh6 15. d4 Nf5 16. e3 $14) 12. d4 $1 {It's really unpleasant to meet the threat of d5.} Bf5 13. Rb3 (13. d5 $1 Bxb1 14. dxc6 Bf5 15. Nd4 O-O 16. Bg5 $16) 13... d5 14. Ne5 $1 {I like this approach of directly putting pressure on Black. In order to meet with the threats, Black has to put his pieces in awkward positions.} (14. Bf4 Rb6 15. Qc1 O-O) 14... Qb6 (14... Rb6 15. Nxb5 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Rxb5 17. exf6 Bxf6 18. Bh6 $16) 15. Be3 $1 Be6 {An ugly looking move. It shows that Black really is in some trouble.} (15... Rd8 {I would have still preferred to move the rook and keep at least the bishop on f5 more active.} 16. Qc1 $1 $14 {With all kinds of threats like Nxd5/Nxb5.}) 16. Nd3 $1 {The key manouevre. Once the knight lands on c5. Black pieces are completely paralyzed.} O-O (16... Nxd4 17. Ne5 $1 $18 {is the clever point. The d4 pawn is poisoned.}) 17. Nc5 Rfd8 18. Ra3 $1 {Using tactical tricks to improve the rook's position. Once White gets control of the a-file, he will have complete domination.} Ra8 (18... Nxb4 {Now the b4 pawn is poisoned!} 19. Qb1 Nc6 20. Ra6 Qc7 21. Bf4 $18 {wins material.}) 19. Rxa8 Rxa8 20. Qb3 Qd8 (20... Rd8 {would cede the control of the a-file:} 21. Ra1 $16) 21. Rc1 $1 {The final precise move in the sequence starting with 14.Ne5! After this, strategically Black's position is lost. He can't avoid losing material as both pawns b5 and d5 are very weak.} Rc8 (21... Rb8 22. Nxe6 fxe6 23. Nxd5 $18) 22. Nxb5 Qb6 (22... Bf5 23. Nc3 e6 24. h3 h5 25. b5 Na5 26. Qb4) 23. Nxe6 fxe6 24. Bh3 $1 {Using tactics to keep my pieces active.} Kf7 25. Rc5 Ra8 {White's position is completely winning. He is a pawn up and has better pieces. I had played really well in the last phase of the game, but I failed to land the final blow. Over the next few moves, I improved my pieces further but didn't make much progress.} (25... Nd7 26. Bxe6+ $1 $18) 26. Bf4 $1 Nd8 27. Bc7 Qb7 28. Qf3 $6 {I wanted to stop the f6 knight from coming to e4. This doesn't lose the advantage, but practically Bxd8 would have won the game on the spot.} (28. Bxd8 $1 {Simplest.} Rxd8 29. Nc7 Rd6 30. b5 $18 {and all of Black's pieces are tied up. Soon White will sacrifice on e6 and push the b-pawn.}) 28... Bh6 29. Be5 Bg7 30. Kg2 (30. Nc7 $1 Ra1+ 31. Kg2 Qxb4 32. Bxe6+ Nxe6 33. Nxe6 {This was a difficult tactics to see in timetrouble.}) 30... h5 31. g4 (31. Nc7 $1) (31. Qf4 Ra4 32. Nc3 Rxb4 33. Rc7 Qb6 34. Bd6) 31... hxg4 32. Bxg4 Ra4 33. Qb3 $6 {Another indecisive move. White was still completely winning, but after this practically the task became tougher.} (33. Bc7 $1 {It was possible to finish the game with brute force!} Nc6 34. e4 $1 {Complete aggression!} (34. Ba5) 34... dxe4 35. Bxe6+ $1 Kxe6 36. Qb3+ $18) 33... Ra6 34. Bxf6 {It's a pity to give the bishop. Already at this point I started to feel that I had lost considerable portion of my advantage and I might have to 'rewin the game'.} Bxf6 35. e3 Rb6 36. Be2 Nc6 37. Qa4 Kg7 38. f4 {Stopping Black's counterplay ideas like ...e5.} (38. Nc3 Nxb4 39. Qe8 Rc6 40. Na4 $1 {is just too brilliant of a win!}) 38... Ra6 39. Qb3 Rb6 40. Bd3 Na7 $2 {So many times the 40th move is the critical mistake!} (40... Qb8 {It made more sense to just wait as it's not easy to remove the knight on b5 and convert the advantage.}) 41. Nc7 $1 {Peter expected me to exchange the knights, but this counter intuitive knight jump practically wins the game.} (41. Rc7 Qb8) 41... Rxb4 42. Nxe6+ (42. Qd1 {was also possible, but simplying to the endgame looked easier.} Rb2+ 43. Bc2 {with Qg4 next.}) 42... Kf7 43. Nd8+ Kg7 44. Qxd5 Qxd5+ 45. Rxd5 Rb3 46. Ne6+ $1 Kh6 47. Nc5 $1 {I had to foresee in advance that I can defend the d3 bishop this way and avoid losing the e3 pawn. The position is winning but still needs precision.} Rb2+ 48. Kg3 Nc6 49. Rd7 Nb4 50. Bc4 $1 (50. Be4 Re2 {Now White has to give up either the e3 or h2 pawn.}) 50... Nc2 (50... Rc2 51. Bb5 g5) 51. Nd3 $1 {The knight danced all the way from b5-c7-e6-d8-e6-c5-d3!} Rb1 52. Kf3 g5 53. fxg5+ Bxg5 54. Ne5 $1 {Again a very important move, using tactics to defend the e3 pawn.} Kg7 {Now taking on e3 is threatened again.} (54... Nxe3 55. h4 $1 $18) (54... Bxe3 55. Ng4+ $18) 55. Rd8 $1 Bxe3 56. Rg8+ Kh7 (56... Kf6 57. Ng4+ $18) (56... Kh6 57. Ng4+ $18) 57. Rg6 {Threatening mate with Bg8+-Nf7++. Black's pieces are too far and not coordinated.} Rb8 58. Bd3 Rf8+ 59. Rf6+ {White will win the piece on c2. Black resigned. After this game I took the lead of the tournament and didn't let it go till the last! I was very happy to win such a prestigious even like the Biel GM, on top of that with a margin of 6 points!} 1-0


