[SourceQuality "1"]

{I have played against Korobov countless number of times. Each game being very fighting but always ending in draw. In the last 4 games, 3 of them were over 80 moves! I was happy to finally break the 'tradition' with this game.} 1. e4 {Vidit,S} c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. f3 h5 9. Nd5 Bxd5 10. exd5 Nbd7 11. Qd2 g6 12. O-O-O Nb6 13. Kb1 Nbxd5 14. Bg5 Be7 15. Bd3 {Nothing new so far, though this is a rare move. Played only once before, by one of the most polite persons I know, Peter Leko.} Rc8 {An 'automatic' move. What does the rook do on c8? Black should either castle long or keep the rook on a8 to prepare b5-a5 ideas.} (15... Qc7 16. Rhe1 O-O-O 17. c4 Nb6 18. c5 dxc5 19. Nxc5 Qxc5 20. Rc1 Nc4 21. Rxc4 Qxc4 22. Bxc4 Rxd2 23. Bxd2 Rh7 24. Rxe5 $14 {½-½ (35) Leko,P (2679)-Areshchenko,A (2645) Schwaebisch Hall GER 2017}) 16. Rhe1 {Preparing ideas like f4.} O-O 17. h3 {For one pawn, I have all the compensation. Perfect pieces plus a very clear plan of breaking through on the kingside.} b5 (17... Qc7 18. g4 Rfe8 {is the engine's stone cold suggestion. White has various possibilites here. I like the look of c3-c2 threatening gxh5.}) 18. g4 h4 {Played after a lot of hesitation. It wasn't easy to parry the threat of gxh5.} 19. Bxh4 $16 {It's hard to say where Black actually went wrong. With a few sub optimal moves he already has a difficult game.} Nf4 20. Bg3 Nxd3 21. Qxd3 Qc7 {White has a couple of plans. h4-h5, preparing f4, or simply re-routing the knight from d2. I was too confused to chose one of them so ended up playing a 4th idea! The luxury of good positions :)} 22. c3 (22. h4 $1 {Objectively this seems the best.} Qc4 23. Qd2 b4 24. h5 $16) 22... Qc4 23. Qd2 Qc6 24. f4 $6 {Although White keeps an edge. It allows some unnecessary complications.} (24. Qe3 $1 {Slowly preparing f4 is more advisable.}) 24... Ne4 25. Qd3 d5 $5 {A typical Korobov move! Anton never misses a chance to muddy the waters.} (25... Nxg3 26. Qxg3 b4 $1 {I had missed this.} (26... Bf6 27. f5 $1) (26... exf4 27. Qxf4 Rce8 28. Nd4 $16) 27. cxb4 Qc2+ 28. Ka1 Bf6 {was a brilliant way out. Suddenly Black has a lot of activity.} 29. f5 e4 30. Rb1 $14) 26. fxe5 b4 27. cxb4 Bxb4 {For a moment I thought that I had messed up. When I dug deeper, I realised that although Black's initiative with ...a5-...b6 etc is scary, it can be parried concretely.} 28. Re2 $1 a5 29. Bf4 $1 {An important move. White threatens to take on d5} Qb6 {Renewing the threat of ...a4.} (29... a4 30. Qxd5 $16) 30. a4 $1 {Probably the most important move of the game. This caught Anton by surprise and he went into deep thought. If White manages to play b5 it's just winning. What should Black do? His entire play was dependent on dislodging the b3-knight.} (30. Qxd5 Rfd8 $1 $19) 30... g5 {A sign of desperation. Now White is completely winning. A normal person would convert this with good technique but I sometimes have a tendency not to do exactly that!} (30... Nc3+ 31. bxc3 Rxc3 32. Qxd5 Be7 {Preparing ...d8 and attacking the b3-knight at the same time} 33. Rd3 $1 {And White protects everything.}) (30... Bc3 $1 31. Qb5 $1 Rb8 $1 {The only move! During the game, we both underestimated this.} 32. e6 Qxb5 33. axb5 Rxb5 34. e7 Re8 35. Rxe4 $1 Rxb3 (35... dxe4 36. Rd8 $18) 36. Rxd5 f6 $1 (36... Rxb2+ 37. Kc1 f6 38. Rd8 Kf7 39. Bd6 $18 {with idea c4-cc8 etc}) 37. Kc2 Rb4 {After a series of only moves Black has some chances to draw this endgame.} 38. Re3 $14) 31. Be3 Qg6 32. Ka2 (32. Nd4 $5 $18) 32... Rfd8 33. Nd4 {Black basically has no 'real' counterplay. He has to survive on some tricks.} Rc4 34. Rc2 $1 {Removing the only active piece.} Qa6 35. Nb5 $6 (35. Rdc1 {would be game over for Black:} Rdc8 (35... Bd2 36. Rxd2 $1) (35... Bc3 36. Rxc3 $1) 36. Rxc4 Rxc4 37. Rxc4 Qxc4+ 38. Qxc4 dxc4 39. Nc6 $18) 35... Be7 $1 {Posing some practical problems.} 36. Rxc4 (36. Na3 $5) 36... dxc4 37. Qc2 Rxd1 38. Qxd1 Qe6 39. Qd4 $1 {Despite messing up the advantage a little, I managed to bring myself back to making good moves.} Nc5 40. Nc3 $1 Nd3 41. Kb1 {Getting myself out of the fork. The main problem of Black's position is that, despite restoring material equality he has a tough time. Every endgame is bad for him due to the weak pawns (a5-c4-g5).} (41. Nd5 Qxd5 {A classic tactic.} 42. Qxd5 Nb4+) 41... Nxe5 42. Qe4 {Planning d5 or d4.} (42. Qd5 $1 {was much more forcing and cleaner. After exchanging queens White can easily collect one of the weak pawns on the queenside.}) 42... Bb4 {Hard to suggest any alternatives. It's not so easy to avoid queen exchanges.} (42... Bf6 43. Qd5 $1) (42... Qd5) 43. Bd4 (43. Qd5 $5) 43... Bxc3 44. Bxc3 f6 45. Qa8+ Kf7 46. Qxa5 $1 {It looks like Black can get some counterplay with d3-e4, but it's all illusory.} Nd3 47. Qb5 $1 Qe4 48. Ka2 $18 {White simply puts the king on a2. Black can't co-ordinate the knight and queen to create any problems. White's simple plan is to just push the a-pawn. The rest is easy.} Nc1+ 49. Ka3 Qe7+ 50. Qb4 Qc7 51. a5 Nd3 52. Qb6 Qe7+ 53. Ka2 Nc1+ 54. Kb1 Qe4+ 55. Kxc1 Qh1+ 56. Kd2 Qh2+ 57. Ke1 1-0


