{[%evp 0,34,20,24,24,4,17,17,27,32,23,23,27,23,28,28,27,30,23,10,26,29,34,56,29,27,27,0,7,-22,-12,-22,-1,-22,-11,-22,0]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd2 d5 6. Nf3 b6 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Rc1 Bb7 9. Bd3 Re8 {Planning ...Bf8 followed by ...c5.} ({Another game at the Opera tournament continued} 9... Be7 10. O-O c5 11. Ne5 Nc6 12. Ne2 $5 ({we've looked at} 12. Be1 {- see the notes to Ponomariov,R-Yilmaz,M/ Douglas 2019.}) 12... Rc8 13. Bc3 Ne4 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. dxc5 Qxd1 17. Rfxd1 Bxc5 $11 {Vidit,S-So,W/chess24.com 2021.}) ({In the past we've also considered} 9... Nbd7) (9... a6) ({and} 9... c5) 10. O-O Bf8 11. Ne5 c5 12. f4 (12. Bb5 Re6 (12... Nbd7 13. f4 a6 14. Bd3 b5) 13. f4 a6 14. Bd3 (14. Ba4 $5 {is an idea, so that after} b5 15. Bc2 Nc6 16. Be1 cxd4 17. exd4 {White can keep the knight on e5}) 14... Nc6 15. Bf5 Re8 $11 {was Shengelia, D-Bosman,M/ Batumi 2018.}) 12... Nc6 $1 {As usual, it's desirable for Black to put pressure on the d4-pawn.} ({After} 12... Nbd7 $6 13. Be1 $1 {White gets exactly what he wants.}) 13. Ne2 $1 {By protecting the d4-pawn, crucially Vidit is able to maintain his powerful knight on e5. It's true that the knight retreat allows Black's knight to enter e4, but Vidit demonstrates that this doesn't have to be a major inconvenience for White.} ({As mentioned before,} 13. Nxd5 {leads to a draw:} Qxd5 $1 (13... Nxd5 $4 14. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 15. Qh5+ Kg8 16. Qxf7+ Kh7 17. Rf3 $1 {wins}) 14. Bc4 Qd8 (14... Qe4 15. Nxf7) (14... Qxg2+ $5 15. Kxg2 Nxe5+ 16. Kg1 Nxc4 17. Rxc4 Ba6 18. Rc1 Bxf1 19. Qxf1 $14 {Bluebaum,M-Karjakin,S/Moscow 2019}) 15. Nxf7 Qc7 16. Ng5+ Kh8 17. Nf7+ Kg8 18. Ng5+ Kh8 19. Nf7+ Kg8 {1/2-1/2 Koneru,H-Girya,O/chess.com 2020.}) (13. Be1 {is the other way to relieve the pressure against the pawn.} cxd4 14. Nb5 $5 (14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. exd4 Ne4 $1 $15 {is just what Black is trying to achieve with ...c5 and ...Nc6}) 14... Nxe5 $6 (14... Rc8 $1 15. Nxc6 Rxc6 16. Rxc6 Bxc6 17. Nxd4 Bd7 {is fine for Black}) 15. fxe5 Rxe5 16. exd4 Re4 (16... Re7 17. Bh4) 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. Bh4 $14 Qd7 19. Rc7 Qxb5 20. Rxf6 $1 Bd5 21. Qh5 $1 g6 22. Qg5 Bg7 $2 23. Rfxf7 $1 Bxd4+ 24. Kh1 a6 25. Qe7 {1-0 Sandipan,C-Torosyan,N/ Yerevan 2017.}) 13... Rc8 14. Be1 $1 {This is actually a novelty, but it's also a typical move and a fairly obvious improvement over what had happened before.} (14. Ng3 cxd4 $1 15. Nxc6 Rxc6 16. Rxc6 Bxc6 17. exd4 Ne4 $1 18. Bxe4 dxe4 19. Be3 Qd5 $17 {with some advantage for Black, Marn,J-Lampert,J/Maribor 2020.}) 14... cxd4 15. exd4 ({More challenging than} 15. Nxc6 Rxc6 16. Rxc6 Bxc6 17. Nxd4 Bd7 $1) 15... Ne4 {The obvious continuation, especially as White was threatening Bh4.} 16. Bb5 $1 Re6 17. h3 $1 {Realising that Black can hardly improve his position, Vidit chooses a useful waiting move in anticipation of Dominguez's next move.} (17. f5 $2 {is premature and met strongly by the exchange sacrifice} Rxe5 $1 18. dxe5 Nxe5 {when White has lost control.}) 17... f6 $6 {It's difficult to avoid playing this move, but that's probably what Black should be trying to do.} (17... a6 {is playable and restricts White to an edge after} 18. Bxc6 ({or} 18. Nxc6 Bxc6 19. Bxa6 Ra8) 18... Bxc6 19. f5 Rh6 20. Ng4 Rd6 21. Bb4) (17... a5 $5 {intending ...Na7 is another idea for Black.}) 18. Nxc6 Bxc6 19. Ba6 $1 Rc7 20. f5 $1 Re8 21. Nf4 {The position has settled somewhat and it's become clear that White is doing well. Black has significant light-squared weaknesses on both sides of the board, and the bishop is unable to simultaneously cover all of them. With the threat of Ne6 looming, Dominguez is obliged to give up his d5-pawn, but this does at least enable him to break the bind.} Ba4 $1 22. b3 Rxc1 23. Qxc1 Bd7 24. Nxd5 Bd6 25. Bd3 Qb8 26. Nc3 Nxc3 27. Bxc3 Bh2+ $6 {Black should keep this check in reserve, as he loses valuable time moving the bishop again.} ({After} 27... b5 $1 {intending ...Qb6 there's still a lot of work for White to do before he can think about converting the advantage of the extra pawn.}) 28. Kh1 Bg3 29. Bd2 Rc8 $2 30. Bc4+ $1 Kh8 31. Qd1 $1 {Planning Qg4. Vidit has reorganised his pieces effectively and White's advantage is now decisive.} Qd6 32. Qg4 Re8 33. Be6 $1 Bxe6 34. fxe6 Rxe6 35. Bb4 $1 Qxb4 36. Qxe6 h6 37. Qc8+ Kh7 38. Qf5+ Kg8 39. Qd5+ Kh7 40. Qe4+ Kg8 41. Rc1 Kf7 42. Qd3 Qd6 43. Rc3 Bf2 44. Qc4+ Kg6 45. Rf3 Bh4 46. d5 Bg5 47. h4 {An excellent game by Vidit and a powerful demonstration of White's chances in this line. Dominguez's ...Re8, ... Bf8, ...c5 and ...Nc6 plan looks entirely logical, but after Vidit's13 Ne2! it seems that Black still has some problems to solve.} 1-0


