1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 d5 7. Bg5 c5 {John Emms: '!?' John Emms: 'Wojtaszek's gambit is a delayed version of Romanishin's invention 4...d5 5 a3 Bxc3+ 6 Qxc3 c5!?. It remains fairly popular and scores well for Black.'} ({The main choice for Black is} 7... dxc4 8. Qxc4 b6 {- see games in the archives.}) 8. dxc5 d4 9. Qf3 {John Emms: '!?' John Emms: 'This move is very rare - there were only four other examples on my database.'} ({Previously we've considered the two most common options} 9. Qg3) ({and} 9. Qc2) 9... Nbd7 {John Emms: '!' John Emms: 'Ganguly targets the c5-pawn.'} (9... Nc6 10. O-O-O e5 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Qxf6 gxf6 13. e3 Rd8 {(Lenic,L-Boruchovsky,A/Batumi 2018) and here} 14. Nf3 {looks good for White.}) 10. e3 {John Emms: '!'} (10. O-O-O {is less accurate, as} e5 11. e3 e4 $1 12. Qf4 d3 $1 {looks very promising for Black.}) 10... h6 ({If} 10... e5 {then} 11. exd4 $1 exd4 12. O-O-O {avoids the problems with the previous note.}) 11. Bxf6 Nxf6 12. O-O-O e5 13. Ne2 {John Emms: '!' John Emms: 'White is willing to give up the exchange.'} d3 {John Emms: 'The first new move.'} ({Earlier, Riazantsev,A-Inarkiev,E/Geneva 2017, had continued} 13... Bg4 14. Qg3 d3 (14... Ne4 15. Qxg4 Nxf2 16. Qf3 Nxh1 17. g4 Qg5 18. Qxh1 Qxe3+ 19. Kb1 $14) 15. f3 Be6 16. Nc3 Qc7 17. Bxd3 Qxc5 18. Kb1 Rfe8 19. Qf2 Bxc4 20. Bxc4 Qxc4 21. e4 {with a small edge for White, Riazantsev,A-Inarkiev,E/Geneva 2017.}) 14. Nc3 Bg4 15. Rxd3 {John Emms: '!'} Qa5 $6 {John Emms: '!' John Emms: 'A wise practical decision by Ganguly, who will regain both the sacrificed pawns.'} (15... Qxd3 16. Bxd3 Bxf3 17. gxf3 a5 $11) ({John Emms: 'After'} 15... Bxf3 16. Rxd8 Rfxd8 17. gxf3 {John Emms: 'White has two pawns for the exchange and his position looks easier to play than Black's.'} a5 $11) 16. Qg3 {John Emms: '!'} ({John Emms: 'Eschewing the pawn grab'} 16. Qxb7 $142 {John Emms: 'which gives Black serious play after'} Rab8 17. Qc6 $14 e4 $1 18. Rd4 Rb3 $1) 16... Qxc5 $11 {Diagram [#]} 17. e4 $146 (17. Rd2 {- 139/(188)}) 17... Be6 18. Rd2 Rfd8 19. Qe3 {John Emms: '!'} Qc6 $6 (19... Rd4 $5 20. f3 (20. b4 Qc7 21. Rxd4 ({or} 21. c5 Rxd2 22. Qxd2 a5) 21... exd4 22. Qxd4 Rd8 {is risky for White}) 20... Rxc4 $1 21. Qxc5 Rxc5 $11) (19... Qxe3 20. fxe3 Ng4 {also looks okay for Black.}) 20. f3 Rxd2 21. Qxd2 Rc8 22. Kb1 Bxc4 23. Bxc4 Qxc4 24. Qd6 {John Emms: '!' John Emms: 'This position is not completely comfortable for Black. The e5-pawn has to be defended, and because of the d5-square White's knight is stronger than its counterpart.'} Qe6 {John Emms: '?' John Emms: 'Ganguly goes for the endgame, but his position becomes worse.'} (24... Qc7 $142 25. Qxc7 Rxc7 26. Rd1 $36) (24... Re8 {minimises White's advantage.}) 25. Qxe6 fxe6 26. Nb5 {John Emms: '!'} Rd8 {John Emms: 'Giving up a pawn.'} (26... a6 27. Nd6 Rc7 28. Rc1 $16 {John Emms: '!'} Rxc1+ 29. Kxc1 b6 30. Kc2 {looks very good for White.}) 27. Nxa7 Rd2 28. Nb5 b6 ({John Emms: 'If'} 28... Rxg2 29. Nd6 {John Emms: '!'} Rf2 (29... b6 30. Nc4) 30. Nxb7 Rxf3 31. Nc5 $16) 29. g3 (29. a4 $16 Rxg2 30. b4 Rf2 31. a5 bxa5 32. bxa5 Rxf3 33. Kb2 {also looks very promising for White.}) 29... Rf2 30. Nd6 Rxf3 31. Rc1 Nd7 32. Rc6 Re3 33. Ka2 Re2 34. Nc8 Rxe4 35. Rxe6 (35. Nxb6 $142 {John Emms: '!' John Emms: 'looks more logical and offers good winning chances. For example,'} Nxb6 36. Rxb6 Kf7 37. Rb4 $1 $16 Re2 ({Black has to try} 37... Rd4 $1) 38. a4 Rxh2 39. a5 Rd2 40. a6 Rd6 41. Rb7+ Kf6 42. a7 Ra6+ 43. Kb1 e4 44. b4 e3 45. Kc2 {and White wins.}) 35... Rd4 $1 36. b4 $6 (36. Kb1 $5) 36... Kf7 37. Rc6 e4 {John Emms: '?!'} (37... Rd2+ 38. Kb3 Rxh2 39. a4 (39. Nxb6 Nxb6 40. Rxb6 Rg2 41. a4 Rxg3+ 42. Kc4 Ra3 43. a5 h5 44. b5 Ra4+ $1 (44... Rxa5 $2 45. Ra6 $1) 45. Kc5 e4 46. a6 e3 47. Rb7+ Kf6 48. Rb8 Kf7 $1 $11) 39... Rg2 $13) 38. Rd6 {John Emms: '!'} Rd3 {John Emms: '?'} ({John Emms: 'And here'} 38... Rxd6 {John Emms: '!'} 39. Nxd6+ Ke6 40. Nxe4 Kd5 $132 {John Emms: 'might well still draw.'}) 39. Kb2 (39. Rxd3 exd3 40. Kb3 $16) 39... Ne5 {John Emms: '?'} (39... Rxd6 $142 40. Nxd6+ Ke6 41. Nxe4 Kd5) 40. Rxd3 {John Emms: '!' John Emms: 'Now White is winning.'} exd3 (40... Nc4+ 41. Kc2 exd3+ 42. Kxd3 Nxa3 43. Nxb6 Ke6 44. Kd4 $18) (40... Nxd3+ 41. Kc3) 41. Nxb6 $18 Ke6 42. Kc3 Kf5 $6 (42... g6 43. a4 Kd6) 43. a4 Ke4 44. a5 g5 (44... Ke3 45. Nd5+ Ke2 46. Nf4+ Ke3 47. Nxd3) 45. Na4 Ke3 46. Nb2 d2 47. a6 1-0


