{[%evp 0,91,19,38,25,16,13,9,21,38,31,34,35,46,28,8,14,-8,9,19,20,22,37,27,57,38,55,30,116,87,73,99,91,85,84,90,83,84,83,83,77,79,91,81,79,76,75,77,79,83,83,68,68,68,67,61,69,52,59,72,57,49,38,43,42,47,62,71,74,74,77,73,67,69,90,83,71,67,83,123,124,118,175,175,179,194,192,205,210,224,234,216,220,222] Last time I played against Gelfand, I missed 100 hundred wins and even got stalemated. So this time I was more determined than ever to win.} 1. e4 {Vidit, Santosh Gujrathi Vidit, Santosh Gujrathi Vidit, Santosh Gujrathi: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Vidit, Santosh Gujrathi''} e5 (1... c5 {The Sicilian has been Gelfand's opening for decades. He used to play Najdorf, and after his match against Anand his pet line became the Sveshnikov.}) 2. Nf3 Nf6 {Expected. In his 1v1 match against GM Markus Ragger, he employed the Petroff regularly, although the results were a bit shaky.} 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Be7 7. Be3 O-O {This is all the rage of 2019. Chess has become extremely concrete nowadays. Previously, Black used to play 'safe' with Nc6, Be6 and castling queenside.} 8. Qd2 Nd7 9. O-O-O Nf6 (9... c6 {No one so far has been able to break Fabiano's defenses in this line with c6-d5}) 10. Bd3 c5 {I first saw this line when GM Motylev played it against GM Anish Giri in the World Cup 2017. My first impression of this system was dubious. Although when Fabiano played it against Magnus at the WCh recently, I started to take it more seriously.} 11. Kb1 {A rare move. Usually White plays Rfe1 but then it is met with Be6, attacking the pawn on a2. The point of Kb1 is that now Be6 can be met with Ng5.} (11. Rhe1 {Gelfand managed to escape by a hair's breadth in the 1st round against David Navara. David found some deep line where Black had to be extremely precise to hold.} Be6 12. Bg5 (12. Kb1 Qa5 13. c4 Qxd2 14. Bxd2 h6 {½-½ (55) Carlsen,M (2835)-Caruana,F (2832) London 2018}) 12... d5 13. Qf4 Re8 14. Re5 Qc7 15. Qh4 h6 16. Bxh6 $1 Ne4 17. Qf4 Nxf2 18. Qg3 Ng4 19. Bf4 Bd6 20. Bh7+ {[#]} Kf8 (20... Kh8 {Walking in the fire with Kh8 was apparently was the only move to survive!}) 21. Rde1 Rad8 22. Qh4 Nxe5 23. Nxe5 Bxe5 24. Bxe5 $16 {½-½ (100) Navara,D (2739)-Gelfand,B (2655) Prague 2019}) 11... b5 {Played instantly.} 12. Rhe1 Rb8 13. Bg5 c4 $6 {The idea of playing c4-d5 etc. is pretty standard in this line, but in this precise position it just doesn't work.} (13... Be6 {is the most logical move.}) 14. Nd4 $1 Bd7 15. Nf5 Bxf5 16. Bxf5 Ne4 {Probably Black's best bet. The attack on the queenside is just too slow.} (16... d5 17. Qd4 b4 18. cxb4 h6 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Qc5 $16) 17. Bxe4 Bxg5 18. Qxd6 Qxd6 19. Rxd6 Rfe8 20. Rdd1 {Although White has a doubled pawn, his chances for winning seemed quite realistic since the Black's queenside pawns were ripely placed on light squares.} Kf8 21. Bc6 Rxe1 22. Rxe1 Bf6 23. a3 $6 {Not a bad move in itself. However, I started to play moves without a plan. Black's pieces are completely stuck, and it was the right moment to create a plan.} (23. a4 $1 {It's usually advisable to keep more pawns when you are on the offensive. But here there were concrete reasons. For example, Black's next moves are obvious. To free his rook from b8, Black will play Be7 & a6 to support b5. After that, I would have to play Bd7, but then it would be met with Rd6. Imagine the same position with a6/axb5 axb5 included. Now the b5 pawn is loose, which ties the rook on b8 permanently.} a6 (23... bxa4 24. Ka2 $1 {is the point of, course.}) 24. axb5 axb5 {Now slowly White can aim to transfer the rook to d5. Techincally this should be winning for White}) 23... g6 24. g3 $6 a6 25. Re2 Be7 {I realized that I had messed up. After a 15min think, I composed myself, went deep into the position and started playing strongly & with high intensity.} 26. Kc1 {Prophylactic move. Black is going to play Bc5, and then I didn't want to play f4 as it would create weaknesses on the kingside. Another point is to have Rd2 whenever Black brings the rook to d6.} Rb6 {Now that his rook is free, Black is back in the game. Now I had to start the endgame grind all over again.} 27. Bd7 Rd6 28. Rd2 Rf6 {Black can only exchange the rooks if his king is protecting the a6-b5 pawns.} 29. Kd1 $1 Bc5 30. Ke1 Ke7 31. Bc8 $1 {The beginning of a sweet manouevre.} Rc6 32. Re2+ $1 Kd8 (32... Kf8 {would allow the rook to enter:} 33. Bd7 Rd6 34. Re8+ Kg7 35. Bc8 $16) 33. Bb7 Rf6 34. Bd5 $1 {All this drama to make the rook awkwardly placed on f6!} Rf5 $6 (34... g5 $1 {It makes sense to put the pawns on the dark squares.}) 35. Bb7 Rf6 36. f4 $1 {freeing the rook on e2 and also restricting Black's pieces even further.} h5 $2 {I was shocked to see this move. After h4 all the black pawns will permanently be on light squares. Also, all bishop endgames are now lost for Black. For better or worse, he had to play h6-g5 or wait passively.} (36... Kc7 37. Bd5 h6 $1 {At least due to the idea of g5 he has some counterplay.}) 37. h4 Rd6 (37... Kc7 38. Bd5 Kd6 39. Re5 {would also slowly lose}) 38. Re5 $1 {The final precise move.} (38. Rd2 Rxd2 39. Kxd2 Kc7 40. Bd5 Bf2 {It looked unneccesary to allow any counterplay.}) 38... Rb6 (38... Ba7 39. Rd5 {Black will drop one more pawn. It looks completely lost.}) 39. Rxc5 Rxb7 40. Rc6 $18 a5 41. f5 Kd7 42. Ra6 gxf5 43. Rf6 Ke7 44. Rxf5 b4 45. axb4 axb4 46. Kd2 1-0


