1. d4 {Vidit,S Vidit,S Vidit,S: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Vidit,S''} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 {My opponent usually plays the Ragozin, but for this game he decided to go with something which is ultra-solid :)} 5. g3 {I usually played f4 or g5, but I decided it was time for a change.} O-O 6. Bg2 dxc4 7. Ne5 c5 {This is the most solid choice. There are two other more complicated lines, Kramnik's creative 7...d6!? and the double edged 7...c6!?} (7... Qd6) (7... Nc6) 8. dxc5 Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 Bxc5 10. Nc3 Rd8 (10... Nc6 11. Nxc4 {is how the games usually went} (11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Na4 Bd4 13. Nxc6 Bb7 14. Nxd4 Bxh1 15. f3 Bg2 16. Kf2 Bh3 17. g4 h5 18. g5 Nd5 $17)) 11. O-O Be7 {By supporting the rook on d8 Black is preparing ...d5.} ({I must confess that the alternative doesn't look so tempting:} 11... Nc6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Bxc6 Rb8 14. Bf4 Rb4 15. Rfd1 Rf8 16. Na4 Be7 17. Bd2 Rb8 18. Rac1 Ba6 19. Be3 $14) 12. Nb5 $6 {A careless move.} (12. Nxc4 Nc6 13. b3 Nd5 14. Bb2 Nxc3 15. Bxc3 Bd7 16. Na5 $14 {still keeps some advantage.}) ({The best way was the counter intuitive f4-fd1 wit the idea of allowing an exchange on f4:} 12. Bf4 $1 Nd5 13. Rfd1 Nxf4 (13... g5 14. Bd2 $14) 14. Rxd8+ Bxd8 15. gxf4 Bc7 16. Rd1 $14 {and because of the undeveloped queenside White retains an edge.}) 12... Nd5 $5 13. Nxc4 ({White could still keep some pressure with} 13. e4 $5 Nb4 $1 (13... a6 14. Na3 $1 {I underestimated this idea!} Nb4 15. Naxc4 Nc2 16. Rb1 $14) 14. Nxc4 (14. Nc7 Bd6 15. Nxa8 Bxe5 $15) 14... N8c6 $11 15. Bf4 e5 16. Nxe5 g5 $1 {although it's still messy!}) (13. Bxd5 exd5 14. Nc7 Bd6 $19) 13... Bd7 14. a4 Na6 $6 {I was relieved to see this as I didn't see a clear way to play after ...c6:} (14... Nc6 $1 15. Bd2 Be8 16. e4 Ndb4 $11) 15. Ne3 $1 {Exchanging Black's best piece!} Bc6 (15... Nab4 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Bxd5 Bxb5 18. Bxb7 Bxe2 19. Bxa8 Bxf1 20. Kxf1 Rxa8 21. Bd2 $14) 16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. Bxd5 (17. Be3 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Bc5 $11) 17... exd5 {This leaves Black with a weak IQP. I was mainly considering ...xd5.} (17... Rxd5 18. Be3 Bc5 19. Bxc5 Rxc5 20. Rfd1 {was my intention during the game. I thought the activity will be unpleasant for Black.} (20. Rfc1 Kf8 (20... Rac8 21. Rxc5 Rxc5 22. Rd1) 21. Kg2 Ke7 22. b4 Rc6 23. Nd4 Rcc8 (23... Rxc1 24. Rxc1 Rd8 25. Rc4 Rd7 26. Nb5 b6 27. Kf3)) 20... Rc2 21. Rd7 Rxe2 22. Rxb7 Rxb2 23. Rc1 h6 24. Rc6 Nb4 25. Rcc7 a6 26. Nd6 Nd3 $11 {And as it is in chess, best moves from both sides results in a draw :)}) 18. Rd1 Nb4 19. Bd2 $1 {It's important to drive the knight.} Nc6 20. Be3 $14 Rd7 (20... Bf6 $5 {would have been better. White doesn't get time to consolidate his position.} 21. Nc7 (21. Nd4 Bxd4 22. Bxd4 Rac8 $11) 21... Rab8 22. Nxd5 Bxb2 23. Rab1 Be5) 21. Nd4 $1 (21. Rac1 d4 $1 $15) 21... Bf6 (21... Ne5 22. b3 (22. Rac1 Nc4 23. Nf5 $5) 22... Bc5 23. Rac1 b6 24. h3 f6 25. Kg2 $14) 22. Nxc6 bxc6 23. Rac1 Rd6 24. b4 h6 $5 {A very nice move. Black now threatens the unpleasant ...a5, liquidating his queenside weaknesses.} (24... a5 $5 25. Bf4 Re6 26. b5 cxb5 27. axb5 a4 28. Rxd5 a3 29. b6 Rxb6 30. Ra5 Re8 31. Rxa3 $16) (24... d4 25. Rc4 $14) (24... a6 25. Rc2) 25. Rc5 (25. Kf1 $5 {Protecting e2 in advance made sense:} a5 26. Bf4 Re6 27. b5 cxb5 28. axb5 a4 29. Bc7 $1) 25... Re6 26. b5 cxb5 27. Rxb5 $6 {Played this quickly and foolishly. As soon as I played this I saw ...e4.} ({Although this leads to a 4 vs 3 this was the best:} 27. axb5 d4 28. Bxd4 Rd8 29. e3 a6 30. bxa6 Rxa6 $16) 27... Re4 $1 {I missed this move.} 28. a5 {With the hope that my opponent's time pressure and the illusion of playing for a win will help me :)} d4 29. Rb4 Rd8 30. Kf1 Re5 $6 (30... g5 $11) 31. Bf4 $1 {Althought it doesn't objectively change the evaluation. White has the easier game now.} (31. Rbxd4 Rxd4 32. Bxd4 Rxa5 33. Bxf6 gxf6 $11) 31... Re6 (31... Rh5 32. g4 Rc5 33. Rb7 Ra8 34. Bd2 Rc2 {Engines with their 0.00 are sometimes annoying, aren't they? :)}) 32. Rb7 a6 33. Rc1 $1 {Now it's already not easy for Black to play.} (33. Bc7 Rde8 34. Rd2 R6e7 35. Ra7 (35. Rc2 Rc8 36. Rc6 Kh7) 35... Rc8 36. Bb6 Rxa7 37. Bxa7 Rc1+ 38. Kg2 Ra1 39. Bb6 Kf8) 33... Rd5 {This just helps White organize his pieces.} (33... g5 34. Bd2 Rde8 35. Rcc7 Rxe2 36. Rxf7 Rxd2 37. Rxf6 Rf8 38. Rbb6 $14) 34. Bc7 d3 (34... Kh7 35. Bb6 Kg6 36. Ra7 Rb5 37. Rxa6 Bd8 38. Rd1 Bxb6 39. axb6 Rbxb6 40. Rxb6 Rxb6 41. Rxd4 h5 42. h4 $16) 35. exd3 Rxd3 36. Bb6 $16 (36. Rb6 Bd4 37. Rxe6 fxe6 38. Rc6 Rc3 39. Rxc3 Bxc3 40. Ke2 Kf7 41. Kd3 Be1) 36... Bc3 37. Ra7 (37. Rc7 Bd4 38. Rd7 {transposes to the next note.}) 37... Bd4 38. Rxa6 $2 {Careless move! Now Black can draw the game} (38. Rd7 Rc3 39. Rxc3 Bxc3 40. Ra7 Kh7 $1 41. Rxf7 {Transposes to 38.c8} (41. Rxa6 Bxa5 $1)) (38. Rc8+ $1 Kh7 39. Rd7 Rc3 {This leads to some amazing lines :)} (39... Bxb6 40. Rxd3 Bxa5 41. Rf3 {I was worried about Black having a fortress here. Now I realize it was just a stupid illusion :) With two rooks Black is going to have a difficult time holding this position.} (41. Rd7 Rf6 42. Rf8 Kg6 43. Rb7 Bc3)) 40. Rxc3 Bxc3 41. Rxf7 Re5 {Looks like Black is going to capture the a5-pawn and it will be an easy draw, but chess isn't that simple, is it? :D} 42. Ra7 Bxa5 43. Bd4 $1 Rg5 44. f4 Rg6 45. Rb7 $1 {Important to stop the black bishop from coming to b6. White now slowly plans to bring his king and push the pawns.} (45. f5 Rg4 46. Ba1 Bb6 47. Rxa6 Rb4 $132) 45... Bd8 $5 {Threatening ...f6. Not the best move, but it does have a deep trick! I would show the rest of the lines just for fun :)} (45... Kg8 46. Kf2) (45... h5 46. Ke2 Kh6 47. Kf3 $18) 46. f5 Rg4 47. f6 $2 {this leads to a theoretically drawn position!} (47. Bc3 $1 {Threat is stronger than execution! Black can't really parry f6.}) 47... Rxd4 48. f7 Rd6 $1 49. f8=Q Rf6+ 50. Qxf6 Bxf6 51. Ra7 h5 $1 52. Rxa6 Bd4 53. Ke2 g6 $1 $11 {and this endgame is theoretically drawn! Black should maintain the bishop on the a1-h8 diagonal. Even after White achieves e6, a7 he can't progress.}) 38... Kh7 $1 {Taking away a8 check possibilities.} 39. Rc4 $6 {I was so upset because of xa6 that I carelessly played this move.} (39. Ra7 {I of course saw this.} Bxb6 40. axb6 Rxb6 41. Rxf7 Rf6 $1 42. Rxf6 gxf6 43. Rc5 Kg6 44. g4 Rh3 45. Kg2 Rb3 {looks tough for White to win.}) 39... Rd2 (39... Rd1+ 40. Kg2 Rd2 41. Rxd4 Rxd4 42. Ra7 Ra4 43. Rxf7 Rc6 $11) 40. Rxd4 Rxd4 41. Bxd4 Rxa6 42. Bb6 {I was optimistic here for some time. Black can't escape the queenside cage!} Kg6 43. Ke2 Kf5 {But here I realized that Black simply invades on the kingside and starts pushing the pawns.} 44. Kf3 $11 {The game was nothing special, but I like the small subtleties in the early endgame and on move 38! Such small finesses show how rich the game of chess is!} (44. Kd3 {is of course the more fun way to draw} Kg4 $1 (44... Ke6 45. Kc4 Kd7 46. Kb5 Ra8 47. a6 Kc8 {I thought this is winning for White, but apparently it's still drawn!} 48. f4 g6 49. g4 f5 50. gxf5 gxf5 51. Bd4 h5 52. h3 Rb8+ 53. Kc6 Rb3 54. a7 Ra3 $11) 45. Kc4 (45. h4 f6 46. Kc4 g5) 45... Kh3 46. Kb5 Ra8 47. Kc6 Kxh2 48. Kb7 Rxa5 49. Bxa5 Kg2 50. Bb6 h5 51. Kc6 g5 52. Kd5 h4 53. gxh4 gxh4 54. Bc7 Kxf2 55. Ke4 $11) 1/2-1/2


