{[%evp 0,85,29,29,28,-11,31,16,21,15,18,10,29,29,41,41,42,30,34,26,26,9,9,7,9,16,7,-1,11,11,11,-3,-3,-3,2,-1,3,-10,43,38,108,100,104,104,129,119,119,126,124,125,125,115,155,176,159,159,159,159,158,149,169,181,153,153,170,157,176,185,188,198,185,186,193,230,220,220,214,225,289,294,304,278,270,278,319,303,372,372] The first game of the 3rd round, I was very excited and was looking forward to a great fight against my fellow countryman and friend Vidit Gujurathi!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 {One of Vidit's patent line.} Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nc3 d6 6. Nf3 Nc6 ({Previously I had a lot of fun in} 6... Nbd7 {which also leads to exciting positions!}) 7. O-O a6 {I felt this might be an interesting choice for this game.} 8. Bf4 {Tomashevsky used this line to beat Iniyan in the same event.} Rb8 9. Rc1 h6 10. d5 (10. b3 g5 11. d5 gxf4 12. dxc6 {with a messy fight with chances for both sides (Tomashevsky-Iniyan World Cup 2021)}) 10... e5 $1 {A nice intermezzo achieving the key break in the centre.} 11. Bd2 (11. dxe6 fxe6 {with a complicated fight.}) 11... Nd4 $1 {I felt that this was stronger than the thematic retreat to e7.} ({Also decent was} 11... Ne7 {[%cal Gb7b5] followed by b5 next.}) 12. Ne1 {White can't afford to take on d4, since that would allow a strong pawn on d4 which can't be targetted.} c5 $5 ({It was probably a better idea to maintain the tension with} 12... Re8) 13. dxc6 bxc6 14. e3 Ne6 (14... Nf5 15. Bxc6 Rxb2 16. Nd3 $14 {[%csl Yf5] The knight on f5 looks misplaced.}) 15. Bxc6 Rxb2 {I felt this should be nothing for White, but I had to be slightly careful to neutralize his pressure.} 16. Nd3 Rb8 (16... Bb7 {was an exciting option which I was considering but runs into} 17. Bd5 $1 Rb6 18. Na4 {[%csl Rb6]} Rc6 19. e4 $16 {with a clear advantage.}) 17. Bg2 ({I felt} 17. Nd5 {was the most promising try though after} Bb7 {It didn't look like much for White.}) 17... Bb7 18. Nd5 h5 {I rushed with this move, It was stronger to immediately play e4!} (18... e4 $1 {Killing two birds with one stone! Activating my KID bishop and at the same time shutting down his catalan bishop!} 19. Nxf6+ (19. N3f4 Nxd5) 19... Qxf6 {with full equality.} (19... Bxf6 20. Nf4 Nxf4 21. exf4 d5 {with full equality.})) 19. Bc3 {I guess the concept of better late than never ... wasn't right here :).} e4 $4 ({When say H .. .you gotta continue it :)} 19... h4) 20. Bxf6 {A complete blackout! The moment I played e4, I saw this coming ... but it was already too late!} Bxf6 21. Bxe4 {After this, it was a matter of technique!} h4 22. Rb1 Bg7 23. Bg2 Re8 24. Qg4 {Forcing a decision about my brave h-pawn!} hxg3 25. hxg3 Qa5 26. Rb3 Bxd5 27. Bxd5 Nc7 28. Bc6 Rxb3 ({It was funny that during this game, I was calculating long pointless lines which would meet one move refutations :)!} 28... Qxa2 29. Nc1 $1 {wins on the spot!} ({I spent lot of time calculating Be8!} 29. Bxe8)) 29. axb3 Rb8 30. b4 Qa3 31. Rd1 {[%csl Gb4,Gc4,Gd3][%cal Gd1d3,Gd3b4] Now everything is protected and I can just wait for the bitter ending...} Qb3 32. Bf3 Qc2 33. Kg2 Bf8 (33... Ne6 {was more stubborn.}) 34. Qd4 {[%cal Gd4a7] Greedy VD going after another pawn...} Ne6 35. Qa7 Re8 36. Qxa6 Ng5 37. Ne1 Qf5 38. Qc6 Re5 39. Nd3 $1 Re8 40. Qd5 $1 {Strong technique, not allowing any chances!} Qh3+ 41. Kg1 Bh6 42. Nf4 Qc8 43. Bg2 {I decided to call it a day, luckily there was still a chance to redeem myself in the next day...} 1-0


