1. Nf3 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi '} Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. g3 d5 6. Bg2 e5 7. Nf3 d4 8. O-O Nc6 9. e3 Be7 10. exd4 exd4 11. Bf4 O-O 12. Ne5 Qb6 13. Re1 Be6 14. Nd2 Rfd8 {A novelty. During the game, I recalled having seeing this somewhere in my notes. Apparently, I had mixed 14...Rad8 with 14...Rfd8.} ({Please go through this line after checking the note on White's 19th move!} 14... Rad8 15. Qb3 Qa6 16. Nxf7 Kxf7 17. Rxe6 Kxe6 18. c5+ Kd7 19. Bf1 $1 {The only move.} (19. Re1 Kc8 {and Black escapes.}) 19... d3 20. Bxd3 Nd4 21. Bxa6 Nxb3 22. Bb5+ Kc8 23. Nxb3 $14) (14... Rac8 {is by far the most common move.}) 15. Qb3 Qa6 $2 {The decisive mistake already! This line requires very precise play from Black and one mistake is enough to lose the game.} (15... Na5 $142 16. Qxb6 axb6 17. Nd3 Re8 18. a3 $14) 16. Nxf7 $1 {I played this after some thought.} (16. Ndf3 {also looked good to me during the game. But 16.Nxf7 is hard to resist!}) 16... Kxf7 (16... Bxf7 17. Bxc6 $1 Qxc6 18. Rxe7 $16) 17. Rxe6 $1 Kxe6 18. c5+ Kd7 (18... Kf5 19. Qf7 {And it will be mate in few moves as Bh3 is hard to avoid.}) 19. Bf1 $2 {White is still winning, but it's a pity to exchange queens. My intuition was screaming at me to play Re1 and continue the attack, but I remembered seeing this idea with Bf1 in my notes. Apparently Bf1 is the only move if Black had played ...Rad8 instead of ...Rfd8 on move 14!} (19. Re1 {Had I not known that Bf1 is the move in my notes, I would have definitely played Re1 as the attack looks irresistable.} Ke8 20. Ne4 $1 {I saw this resource during the game, although I missed some details.} Nxe4 (20... Na5 {leads to a beautiful variation.} 21. Nxf6+ Qxf6 22. Qg8+ Qf8 23. Rxe7+ $3 Kxe7 24. Bg5+ Kd7 25. Qd5+ Kc7 26. Qe5+ $1 Kc8 27. Bh3+ Rd7 28. Qe6 $18 {After a forced series of checks, Black can't defend the rook on d7! What a domination of the bishops!}) 21. Qg8+ {In my calculations I was automatically calculating only the 'forced moves'} (21. Bxe4 $1 {is much simpler} Kf8 {stopping Qg8 ideas.} 22. Bxh7 $1 $18 {A very unique idea, where white plays two non forcing moves after giving a rook. Black is helpless!}) 21... Bf8 22. Rxe4+ $6 Ne7 {I couldn't see a way to continue White's attack. Apparently even this is good for White, if he foresees how to keep the momentum.} 23. Bg5 $1 Rd7 24. c6 $3 {cutting off the Queen.} bxc6 25. Bh3 $18) 19... d3 $1 20. Bxd3 Nd4 21. Bxa6 Nxb3 22. Bb5+ Kc8 (22... Ke6 23. Nxb3 Kf7 24. Na5 $18) 23. Nxb3 Nd5 24. Re1 $1 {I had seen this far. White's bishops completely tie up Black's pieces.} a5 $1 {Black has to activate the rook, somehow.} (24... Nxf4 25. Rxe7 Rd1+ 26. Bf1 Nh5 27. Re8+ Rd8 28. Bh3+ Kc7 29. Re7+ $18) 25. Be5 $1 (25. a4 {looks most logical, but compared to the note on 24th move, Black has additional options after the inclusion of a5-a4} Nxf4 26. Rxe7 Rd1+ 27. Bf1 Ra6 $1 $132 {and the knight on f4 is taboo because of ...Rg6+.}) 25... Bf6 26. Bd6 {All I need is to get the bishop from b5 to h3, and White should be winning.} a4 (26... Bxb2 27. Bf1 $18) 27. Nd2 a3 28. bxa3 (28. Bf1 {unnecessarily complicates things:} axb2 29. Bh3+ Rd7 30. Re8+ Bd8 31. Rg8 g5 $1 32. Rg7 Nf6 $132) 28... Rxa3 29. Bf1 {I was down to around 5-6 minutes at this point.} b5 $4 {The idea is to create space for the king. However, it loses on the spot.} (29... Kd7 {was the most tenacious, although White is still winning.} 30. Ne4 $1 (30. Bh3+ Kc6 31. Bg2 Rd3 $132) 30... Kc6 31. Nxf6 gxf6 32. Rb1 $18) 30. cxb6 $4 {Inexplicable! As soon I played cxb6?? I saw the winning idea. After this blunder, I almost threw away all my advantage.} (30. Bh3+ Kb7 31. Bg2 {During the game, the idea of Bh3 and the Bg2, pinning the knight on d5 was quite common (as you can see in the various variations). Hence, I completely overlooked the simple tactic with c6.} (31. c6+ $1 $18 {wins the rook on a3}) 31... Rd3 $1 {Here it felt that Black can survive.} 32. Nb3 {White is still winning, but this line is irrelevant.}) 30... Rxa2 (30... Rxd6 31. Nc4 {is the point.}) 31. Nc4 Bd4 32. Rb1 $1 {The only way to keep the advantage.} Rxd6 $2 {This allows White to keep the f2 pawn.} (32... Bxf2+ 33. Kh1 Rxd6 34. Nxd6+ Kb8 {Compared to the game, this is of course much better.} 35. Bc4 Ra5 $1 36. b7 Ba7 $1 $16 {Probably Black can survive.}) 33. Nxd6+ Kb8 34. Ne4 $1 Nxb6 35. Rd1 Ra4 36. Ng5 h6 37. Ne6 Bf6 38. Rb1 Ka7 39. Rc1 Re4 $2 {A blunder in time pressure.} (39... Kb8 $1 {indirectly protecting g7. With the king cut off from the kingside pawns, I feel White still has good winning chances. However, it would require a lot of effort to convert.}) 40. Nxg7 $18 {With two extra pawns, White is easily winning.} (40. Nxg7 Bxg7 41. Rc7+ Kb8 42. Rxg7 $18) 1-0


