{[%evp 0,79,25,40,28,-14,6,6,37,28,56,35,14,31,25,16,17,24,15,34,43,31,40,41,48,48,48,48,43,47,63,48,51,46,42,37,46,51,54,59,40,37,84,31,58,50,50,28,35,45,42,42,45,42,42,30,28,46,72,27,45,48,83,81,94,62,152,152,420,442,459,466,1400,1466,1493,1503,1503,1503,1503,1503,1156,1244] The Biel Grandmaster Event this time had a very unique format. It was a combination of classical, rapid and blitz. On the 1st day in the rapid section I didn't start well by losing to Cori Jorge. Eventually I managed to recovere, but was still trailing by 2 points. Hence, this game was extremely important to me from the tournament and personal point of view!} 1. d4 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Vidit, Santosh Gujrathi'} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ {The Bogo Indian! Cori Jorge hadn't played much in the last 6 months, so I wasn't sure what to expect. In fact, his last available game in my database was in December 2018.} 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 O-O (5... Nc6 {is more common.}) 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2 d6 8. O-O e5 9. Nc3 {Black hasn't played the Bogo Indian in the most principled way. White has the centre and the extra space advantage.} Nc6 10. Nd5 $5 {I thought for about 20 minutes to make this decision. I wanted to be precise and increase my advantage.} (10. dxe5 {was the other option that I considered. But it didn't feel right to give up the central control.} dxe5 11. Nd5 Nxd5 (11... Qd6 $5) 12. cxd5 Rd8 13. Rfd1 e4 {I only saw this far. Apparently, Tactically this line works.} 14. Ng5 $1 f5 15. Qc3 Nb4 16. Qb3 $16) (10. d5 {Closing the centre didn't appeal to me as black would play Nb8-a5-Na6 and would have easy play.}) 10... Qd8 (10... Nxd5 11. cxd5 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 exd4 13. Rfe1 Qe5 14. Rac1 Bf5 15. Rc4 $16 {White will collect the d4 pawn and the pile up the major pieces on the c-file. the c7 pawn is a clear target}) 11. Rfd1 Re8 (11... Bg4 $5 {looked more natural but then the pressure along the d-file would be annoying.} 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Qe3 Re8 14. Nb6 axb6 15. Rxd8 Raxd8 16. h3 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 e4 18. Bg2 Nd4 19. Rb1) 12. dxe5 Nxe5 (12... dxe5 13. b4 Qd6 14. b5 Ne7 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. a4 $16) 13. Nxe5 $1 (13. Rac1 {looks normal but runs into} Ne4 $1 {And now the queen doesn't have any good squares!} 14. Qd4 (14. Qf4 Ng6 $1) 14... Ng4 15. Rf1 c6 $132 {Clearly White has lost control.}) 13... Rxe5 (13... dxe5 {During the game this looked more critical. If Black gets c6 in, he will be fine.} 14. Qa5 $1 Nxd5 15. cxd5 Bg4 16. Rac1 $16 {White will exchange the e2 pawn for c7 and the passed d-pawn should give him a healthy advantage. But maybe practically this was a better choice as at least Black has some counterplay. In the game he is left with passive pieces.}) 14. Rac1 Bg4 15. Re1 {Keeping the pressure. Now the plan is simple. Just push e4-f4 and gain more space.} (15. Ne3 $5 {This looks highly tempting and I tried very hard to make the tactics work. In hindsight I feel this is also objectively better.} Qc8 16. Nxg4 (16. c5 $5 {I was mainly trying to use the trick of weak bank rank} Rxc5 $4 (16... dxc5 17. Nxg4 Nxg4 18. Qf4 g5 19. Qf3 c6 {I didn't see a follow up, but engine simply suggests doubling of the rooks on the d-file.} 20. Rd2 $16) 17. Rxc5 dxc5 18. Nxg4 Nxg4 19. Bxb7 $18) 16... Nxg4 17. Qd4 Nf6 18. c5 Rxc5 19. Rxc5 dxc5 20. Qxc5 {I felt that exchaning too many pieces will help ease the defense. Although even here due to bad rook on a8, White keeps a considerable edge.} c6 21. Qe7) 15... Re8 16. Rc3 {Threatening Nf6+ followed by Bxb7.} (16. b3) 16... Rb8 17. e4 Nd7 18. f4 $16 Be6 19. b3 a5 20. Rce3 {The last couple of moves were normal. Both sides just reshuffled the pieces. White has a decent advantage, but it's not easy to get any breaks in the centre yet. Black is quite solid.} Ra8 $6 (20... a4 $1 {Black should have used the opportunity to open up the a-file. During the game he struggled for the very same thing!}) 21. Qd4 Rb8 (21... a4 22. b4 c6 23. Nc3 (23. Bf1) 23... Qb6) 22. Nc3 f6 23. Nb5 {The knight on b5 locks black pieces and also it can re-route to d4.} Ra8 24. Qd2 {A subtle move. I indirectly prevent a4 as it is met with a central breakthrough.} Qc8 (24... a4 25. e5 $1 fxe5 26. Bxb7 Rb8 27. Bc6 $16) 25. Nd4 (25. g4 $5 {Engine's choice! This move didn't come to my mind!}) 25... Bf7 26. Qc3 $1 {This move might not look anything special, but I am quite proud of it. I could have started expanding on the kingside, but Black would have played a4 and got some counterplay. With Qc3 I support the c4 pawn and keep total control. The most important thing is to not allow unnecessary play.} Qb8 27. h4 Qa7 28. Bh3 ({Apparently the direct} 28. g4 {g4 was better}) 28... Rad8 (28... Nf8 {Cori didn't like e5 here. I would have probably played Kh2 preparing e5.}) 29. Kh2 Qc5 30. g4 $1 {Now it's not easy to meet the threat of g5.} Nf8 31. g5 Ng6 32. Rf1 $1 (32. gxf6 Nxf4 {is completely unnecessary!}) 32... Nxh4 33. gxf6 $18 {There are many moves for Black, but nothing satisfactory. It's completely winning for White now.} gxf6 (33... g6 34. Qd3 Kh8 35. Bg4) 34. Rg3+ Kf8 35. Ne6+ Bxe6 36. Qxf6+ Bf7 37. Qh6+ Ke7 38. Qxh4+ Kf8 39. Qh6+ Ke7 40. Rg7 $18 {It felt nice to avenge the loss in rapids!} 1-0


