1. d4 {Vidit,S} Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 Nc6 9. O-O-O f5 {This used to be popular a few years ago but according to current theory it has the reputation of being a bit dubious.} 10. e5 (10. h4 {used to be the main line previously, but has lost popularity lately} fxe4 11. h5 gxh5 12. Rxh5 (12. d5 Ne5 13. Bh6 Nec4 14. Qg5 Rf7 15. Bxc4 Nxc4 16. Rd4 Qd6 17. Bxg7 Rxg7 18. Qxh5 Qf4+ 19. Kb1 Bf5 20. fxe4 Bg4 21. Nge2 Qd2 {0-1 (21) Mamedyarov,S (2724)-Kurnosov,I (2602) Moscow 2009}) 12... Bf5 13. Rg5 (13. fxe4 Bg4 14. Rg5 Bxd1 15. Qxd1 Kh8 16. Nf3 Nxd4 $1 (16... e6 {1-0 (29) Kovalenko,I (2596)-Krasenkow,M (2643) Trzcianka 2013}) 17. Nxd4 Rxf1 18. Qxf1 Bxd4 19. Nd5 Bxe3+ 20. Nxe3 Qd6 $15) 13... Bg6 14. Nxe4 e5 15. d5 Nd4 $11 {Vallejo Pons,F (2702)-Navara,D (2638) Wijk aan Zee 2009}) 10... Nb4 11. Nh3 Be6 (11... Qe8 12. Kb1 a5 13. Be2 c6 14. Rc1 Kh8 15. Ka1 Be6 16. Nf4 {led to a model victory for Carlsen against Li Chao in the Qatar Masters, where White was just a little faster than Black.}) 12. Kb1 Qd7 13. Nf4 Nc4 $6 {A new move in this position.} 14. Qc1 (14. Bxc4 Bxc4 15. h4 Rfd8 {was a possiblity, but I think the text was much simpler and more straightforward.}) 14... Nxe3 15. Qxe3 c6 16. Nxe6 $1 {White has many tempting options here, but this move goes by force to a position in which White has a simple strategic advantage.} (16. h4 Bh6 17. h5 g5 18. Nxe6 Qxe6 19. a3 Nd5 20. Nxd5 Qxd5 {is less clear than the text.}) 16... Qxe6 17. a3 Nd5 18. Nxd5 cxd5 (18... Qxd5 {It seems a little dangerous to keep the a2-g8 diagonal exposed, especially with h4-h5 coming so swiftly.} 19. h4 Rac8 20. Rc1 {[%cal Gf1c4]}) 19. h4 $1 {A very unpleasant move for Black. Black has made no obvious mistakes but his position is already strategically highly dubious.} h6 $6 {looks a bit naive} (19... h5 {I thought this was better, with the idea} 20. Be2 ({But White still keeps the initiative with} 20. Rg1 $1 Kh7 21. g4 Bh6 22. Qb3 $36) 20... Kh7 $1 21. g4 Bh6 {forcing White to play g5.}) 20. Qb3 {The plan that follows is quite straightforward and simple - to break through with g4.} Rfc8 $6 {A sub optimal move. Although It's not easy for Black to play maybe the best was to admit the mistake and play h5.} 21. Bd3 Rc7 22. g4 {White just crashes through on the kingside. Black has no counterplay on the other flank and he won't be able to defend on the light squares either.} fxg4 23. fxg4 $6 {White is still much better but hg1 was just winning} (23. Rhg1 $1 {was much more powerful} Rf8 24. Rxg4 Rxf3 {I prematurely stopped my calculations here but after} 25. Rdg1 {Black has no defence!}) 23... Rf8 24. h5 Qxg4 25. Qxd5+ e6 26. Qb3 Rc6 (26... g5 27. Rhf1 $18) 27. Bxg6 Rf2 {Black tries to struggle for some counterplay. Black's g7-bishop has no squares, and White's king is safe as the light squares are still out of reach for Black's rooks...} 28. Rhg1 Rb6 (28... Qf4 29. Qxb7 {[%csl Rg7]} Rxb2+ 30. Qxb2 Rb6 31. Qxb6 axb6 32. Bc2 $18 {[%csl Rg7]}) 29. Rxg4 Rxb3 30. Rdg1 $1 Rbf3 (30... Rbxb2+ 31. Kc1 {c2 is defended, and g7 is doomed. A typical example of the strategic advantage White has in this position. Also, threats like a2-a1 are simply neutralised by b1.} Rb6 32. Bh7+ $18) 31. Bh7+ Kh8 32. Rxg7 Rf1+ 33. Kc2 Rxg1 34. Rxg1 Kxh7 35. Rg6 Rf5 36. Rxe6 Rxh5 37. d5 Rh4 38. d6 Rd4 39. Re7+ Kg6 40. d7 1-0


