1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 Bg7 8. Bb5+ Nfd7 9. Nf3 a6 10. Bd3 b5 11. O-O O-O 12. a3 Re8 13. Kh1 Ra7 14. Qe1 Rc7 (14... Nf6 {is met by} 15. Qh4 $1 {, as we saw in Edouard, R-Hillarp Persson, T/ Reykjavik 2015. With 14...Rc7 Black makes a useful move and waits to see what White does.}) 15. Bd2 Bb7 {Not always an easy decision for Black. Attacking the d5-pawn means it's more difficult for White to arrange e4-e5, but if White leaves the pawn on e4 the bishop on b7 is hitting a brick wall despite its prophylactic qualities.} ({In any case, Black has to do something, and of course} 15... Nf6 {is again answered by} 16. Qh4) 16. Qg3 Nf6 $1 {Good timing: the knight goes to f6 only after Qg3, so White would lose a tempo if he now plays Qh4.} 17. Rae1 Rce7 (17... b4 18. axb4 cxb4 19. Na4 a5) 18. f5 $1 {It's time for action, for both sides.} b4 $1 {Any further delay, and Black is likely to get squashed after something like Bg5 or Ng5. After 18...b4 the position is critical, very complicated and it's difficult to find the best moves over the board.} 19. axb4 cxb4 20. Na4 Qa5 $2 ({It seems like Black should capture the e4-pawn immediately, e.g.} 20... Nxe4 21. Bxe4 Rxe4 22. Rxe4 Rxe4 23. Ng5 Re2 $1 24. fxg6 fxg6 25. Ne6 Qe8 26. Qxd6 Bxd5 $1 27. Nxg7 Bxg2+ 28. Kg1 Bb7 $1 29. Rf2 (29. Nxe8 Rg2+ 30. Kh1 Rg4+) 29... Re1+ 30. Bxe1 Qxe1+ 31. Rf1 Qe3+ 32. Rf2 Qe1+ $11 {is some computer analysis.}) 21. b3 $2 {Natural, but not best!} ({White gets an advantage after the somewhat paradoxical} 21. Ra1 $1 {with the tactical point} Nxe4 22. Bxe4 Rxe4 23. Nc3) 21... Nxe4 $1 22. Rxe4 Rxe4 23. Bxe4 (23. Ng5 $1 {is stronger, e.g.} R4e7 24. fxg6 hxg6 25. Nxf7 Rxf7 26. Rxf7 Kxf7 27. Qxg6+ Kf8 28. Qf5+ Kg8 29. Qh7+ Kf8 30. Qf5+ $11 {with another perpetual check.}) 23... Rxe4 24. Qxd6 Re8 $2 (24... Qb5 $1 $17 {is a star move which holds everything together for Black, the point being} 25. Qxb8+ $2 (25. Rc1 Nd7 $17) 25... Re8) 25. Re1 $1 Rd8 $2 (25... Rxe1+ 26. Nxe1 {wins for White.}) (25... Rc8 $1 26. Bxb4 Qb5 $1 {is more resilient} ({but not} 26... Qxd5 $2 27. Qxd5 Bxd5 28. Nb6)) 26. Qe7 $1 Ba8 ({If} 26... Nd7 {then} 27. Bg5 f6 28. fxg6 hxg6 29. Qe6+ Kh7 30. Re4 $1) 27. Bxb4 Qxd5 28. Nb6 $1 {Winning.} Qd3 29. Nxa8 (29. fxg6 $1 hxg6 30. Ng5 $1 $18 {is even better.}) 29... Nc6 30. Qe8+ $1 Rxe8 31. Rxe8+ Bf8 32. Bxf8 Qd1+ 33. Ng1 f6 34. Bc5+ Kg7 35. Nc7 gxf5 36. Re6 Nb8 $2 37. Ne8+ Kg8 38. Re7 $1 Qa1 39. Rg7+ Kh8 40. Rf7 1-0


