1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 e6 6. e3 c5 7. Bxc4 Nc6 8. O-O cxd4 9. exd4 Be7 10. Qe2 O-O 11. Rd1 Nd5 12. Bd2 Ncb4 13. a5 {Ramirez,A: a novelty that shouldn't change the character of the position, but one that certainly puts some pressure on Black's queenside. Normally in these positions Black is very solid but he lacks space and an active plan. It's White's task however on how to proceed from here.} ({As an alternative we can examine} 13. Rac1 b6 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Bb3 Ba6 16. Qe3 Nd3 17. Rb1 $1 {This is definitely stronger than 17.c2} (17. Rc2 $6 Bf6 18. Bc3 Re8 19. Ne5 Bc4 20. Bxc4 dxc4 21. Qf3 Bxe5 22. dxe5 Qc7 $15 {Wang,Y (2689)-Zhou,J (2580) Jiangsu Wuxi 2008 1/2 (48)}) 17... Re8 18. Ne5 Bc5 $2 (18... Nxe5 {seems to be the strongest move} 19. dxe5 Bc4 20. e6 Bf6 21. exf7+ Kxf7 22. Qf3 Bxb3 23. Qxb3 Qd7 24. Bc3 Rad8 $14 {I think that Black's position is quite solid and he shouldn't lose the game.}) (18... Bf8 19. Bc3 Bc4 20. Bc2 Nb4 $6 (20... Nxe5 $142 21. dxe5 Qc7 22. b3 Ba6 23. Rbc1 $14) 21. Bxb4 Bxb4 22. Qh3 g6 23. Nxf7 Qc8 (23... Qf6 24. Ne5 $16) (23... Kxf7 24. Qxh7+ Kf8 25. Qh6+ Ke7 26. Bxg6 Rf8 27. b3 Ba6 28. Rbc1 $18) 24. Qh6 $1 (24. Qh4 $143) 24... Bf8 25. Qh4 Re2 26. Rbc1 Be7 27. Qg3 Kxf7 28. b3 Rxc2 29. Rxc2 Qf5 30. Rdc1 Ba3 31. bxc4 Bxc1 32. Rxc1 $16) 19. f4 $2 (19. dxc5 $1 Nxe5 (19... Rxe5 20. Qg3 bxc5 21. Bc2 $18) 20. Bc3 Bc4 21. Bxc4 Nxc4 22. Qf3 $16) 19... f6 20. dxc5 fxe5 $13 {Wang,Y (2736)-Rowson,J (2596) Dresden 2008 1/2 (47)}) 13... Bd7 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Ne5 Rc8 (15... Be8 16. Qf3 f6 17. Nd3 Bf7 18. Qg4 Kh8 19. Nc5 Bxc5 20. dxc5 Qc7 21. a6 bxa6 22. b4 Rfd8 23. Rxa6 $16 {Kramnik,V (2784)-Korobov,A (2720) Tromsoe 2013 1-0 (51)}) 16. a6 b6 17. Rdc1 Bd6 18. Qg4 Bxe5 $1 ({If Black doesn't want to play f5 he can try} 18... Ne7 {but it seems to me that it's dangerous.} 19. Bg5 $1 (19. Bd3 Ng6 20. Bg5 Qe8 21. Rxc8 Bxc8 22. Rc1 f5 $8 (22... Qa4 23. Nxg6 hxg6 24. Bxg6 $1 $16) (22... Bxe5 23. dxe5 Bd7 24. Rc7 Bb5 25. Qe2 $16) 23. Qe2 Bxe5 24. dxe5 h6 25. Bd2 $14) 19... Qe8 ({it is too late to play} 19... f5 $2 20. Qe2 Bxe5 21. Qxe5 $18) (19... Bxe5 20. dxe5 Qe8 21. h4 Ng6 22. Bb3 $1 $16 Nxe5 $6 23. Qg3 Ng6 24. Rc7 $18) 20. Nxd7 Qxd7 21. d5 $1 Nf5 (21... Rxc4 22. Qxc4 Nxd5 23. Qc6 $16) 22. dxe6 fxe6 23. Re1 $16) 19. dxe5 f5 20. exf6 $6 (20. Qd4 Bc6 21. Bb4 Re8 22. Bd6 Qd7 23. Bb3 $14 {I think that Black's position is unpleasant. He can't trade or eliminate the opponent's a6-pawn, so he should wait passively.}) 20... Qxf6 21. Rf1 Nf4 $6 ({I think that Oliver could get an equal position after} 21... h5 $1 22. Qe4 (22. Qe2 Qxb2 23. Rac1 Rf5 24. Rfd1 $44) 22... Qxb2 23. Bxd5 exd5 24. Qxd5+ Rf7 25. Be3 Qb5 $11) 22. Rac1 b5 23. Bxf4 Rxc4 24. Rxc4 bxc4 25. Bd6 $6 (25. Be3 $5 Bb5 26. Bxa7 Bxa6 27. Re1 Qf5 28. Qg3 $14 {White retains some chances to win the game.}) 25... Rc8 26. Re1 c3 $1 $11 27. bxc3 Qxc3 28. Rd1 Qc4 29. Qxc4 Rxc4 30. Bb8 Bc8 31. Bxa7 Bxa6 32. h3 Rc7 33. Bb8 Rb7 34. Be5 Bc4 35. Rd8+ Kf7 36. Kh2 Bd5 37. Kg3 Ra7 38. f3 Rb7 39. h4 h5 1/2-1/2


