{[%evp 0,76,28,28,17,37,17,14,21,4,4,5,10,4,30,-8,6,-4,-3,8,25,22,12,-27,-17,-50,17,47,42,0,-20,-46,-17,-30,10,14,19,0,-50,-5,0,-35,-7,-10,11,-33,14,23,73,74,68,-36,72,-248,-290,-505,-290,-288,-302,-296,-285,-294,-292,-316,-340,-340,-345,-341,-353,-334,-339,-335,-351,-353,-358,-355,-300,-284,-615] Santosh Vidit had an excellent start but (due to blunders) collapsed towards the end of event.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. O-O h6 7. Re1 O-O 8. Nbd2 Bb6 9. h3 (9. a4 {- 147/105}) 9... Ne7 10. d4 {A relatively recent development in this line and (arguably) the most direct one.} ({White players have also tried different "slower" moves here, like} 10. Bb3) ({or} 10. a4) ({or} 10. Nf1) 10... Nc6 {Placing the knight back to c6-square may look somewhat unusual as Black's basic problem in the Italian (and the main reason White has some advantage) is the need to improve his Nc6 development. Here, however, Black has direct reason, because with his last move White has provided Black with a target (d4-pawn).} ({Mamedyarov has experiance in this position and has previously tried a "more standard Italian development".} 10... Ng6 {However after} 11. Bd3 c6 12. Nf1 Re8 13. Ng3 {White had some advantage and went on to win in Karjakin,Sergey 2750 - Mamedyarov,Shakhriyar 2764, Saint Louis (rapid) 2019}) {Diagram [#]} 11. a4 {This is White's idea tried in the last Candidates and can lead to a pawn sacrifice.} ({Black has nothing to worry about if White decides to try a less combative} 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 {as seen in recent top level game Sevian,Samuel 2668 - Oparin,Grigoriy 2659, Riga (blitz) 2021}) 11... exd4 $146 {A novelty. Mamedyarov decides to fight versus the isolated pawn.} ({The mentioned Candidates game went} 11... a5 {and White sacrificed a pawn} 12. Ba2 $5 {after} exd4 13. Nc4 dxc3 14. Nxb6 c2 15. Qxc2 cxb6 {we had a complex position, White having compensation, but perhaps not more. The game ended drawn in Alekseenko,Kirill 2698 - Caruana,Fabiano 2842, Yekaterinburg (ct) 2021}) 12. cxd4 {Now Mamedyarov forces the type of position his was aiming for.} d5 ({Grabbing a pawn is (least to say) risky for Black:} 12... Nxd4 $2 13. Nxd4 Bxd4 14. Nb3 {Black does not have a good retreat for his bishop.} Bc5 15. Nxc5 dxc5 16. Qc2 $16 {White is clearly better here having more than just a compensation.} Qd4 $2 17. e5 Nh7 18. Be3 $18 Qxe5 $140 19. Bxc5) (12... Bxd4 {is a better way to capture on d4, but still playing with fire.} 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Ra3 $44 (14. b4 $5 $44)) 13. exd5 Nxd5 {Diagram [#] Diagram [#] Critical moment (and important one for theoretical assessment on this line). White needs to decide how to develop and I do not think Vidit choose the best way to do it. Diagram [#]} 14. b3 $2 {This move (White voluntarely depriving himself from Ra3 rook lift) does not look natural here and now Black has easy play.} ({The way to put Mamedyarov's idea to more serious test was (in my opinion)} 14. Ne4 {and after} Be6 {Diagram [#]} 15. Ra3 $1 $36 {this standard type rook lift, seems to be working for White here. White's prospects look promising (to me), e.g.} a5 (15... Ne3 $2 16. Bxe3 Bxc4 17. Bxh6 gxh6 18. Qc1 $18) (15... Ba5 16. Bd2 Bxd2 (16... Ne3 $2 17. Raxe3 Bxc4 18. Bxa5 Nxa5 19. Ne5 Bd5 20. Rg3 $18 {White has a winning attack.}) 17. Qxd2 $16) 16. Ne5 $36) 14... Be6 15. Ne4 Re8 16. Bb2 {Diagram [#] Diagram [#] White's set-up we sometimes (certainly not often) see in the isolated pawn positions. However, here it does not seem to be dangerous for Black. Mamedyarov does not choose the best way to arrange his pieces and White indeed gets strong attack. Diagram [#]} Na5 $2 (16... Ba5 $1 {looks to be equalizing on the spot, since it is difficult for White to avoid move repetition.} 17. Re2 ({In case of} 17. Nfd2 $6 {White's pieces look poorly coordinated and only Black can be better after} Bb4 $15 ({Or} 17... Nf4 $15)) 17... Nf4 18. Re3 Nd5 19. Re2 $11) 17. Ne5 $40 {Now White stands better. White has "free hand" to develop kingside attack, while is it difficult for Black to justify his 16...Na5? move - if Black takes on c4, he improves White's pawn structure, while if he does not take the knight on a5 is out of play.} c6 18. Qf3 f6 $2 {Diagram [#] Diagram [#] A risky decision. However, Black wants to chase the white knight of the central square.} ({In case of} 18... Bc7 19. Rad1 {if Black does not want to weaken himself with the ...f6 move, logical looks} Qh4 {Diagram [#] White gets decisive attack after} 20. Bd3 $1 {Black is simply "missing a piece" (terrible position of Na5).} Nxb3 ({Or} 20... Qf4 21. Qe2 $18) 21. Bb1 Na5 22. Bc1 $1 {White is combining different elements - Black exposed his queen and White has a battery threat on the b1-h7 diagonal. For example:} Ne7 23. Qd3 Bf5 24. Nf3 Qh5 25. g4 {and White has winning advantage.} Bxe4 (25... Qxh3 26. gxf5 Qg4+ 27. Ng3 Bxg3 28. fxg3 Qxg3+ 29. Kf1 $18) 26. Rxe4 Qxh3 (26... Qg6 27. Rde1 $18) 27. Rde1 $18) {Santosh Vidit chooses a bit conservative approach -} 19. Nd3 $2 (19. Ng6 $16 {looks promising.}) (19. Ng4 $1 {might be just winning for White!} Nxc4 (19... f5 $2 {loses to} 20. Nef6+ gxf6 21. Nxh6+ Kg7 {Diagram [#]} 22. Rxe6 $1 Kxh6 23. Rae1 {It is not surprising that White has a winning attack here.} Rxe6 24. Rxe6 Nxc4 25. bxc4 Nc7 26. Qe3+ Kg6 27. Re7 $18) 20. bxc4 f5 {Diagram [#] Diagram [#] Now White needs to sacrifice in a different way. Diagram [#]} 21. Nxh6+ $1 gxh6 22. Nc5 Nc7 23. Nxb7 Qh4 (23... Qg5 {loses to} 24. d5 Nxd5 (24... cxd5 25. c5 $18 {wins back the piece with a winning advantage.}) 25. a5 $1 Bc7 {Diagram [#]} 26. Rxe6 $1 Rxe6 27. cxd5 Rg6 28. dxc6 $18 {The material is (technically speaking) equal, but Black's king position is hopeless.}) {Here the most precise for White is} 24. Nd6 Re7 25. Rxe6 $1 Rxe6 26. Nxf5 Qg5 27. a5 $1 Rf6 28. g4 {White wins the black bishop, establishes material equality and has a large advantage because his king is safer than Black's.} Raf8 29. Kh1 $18) 19... Bf7 20. Re2 Bc7 21. Rae1 {Diagram [#]} b6 (21... Bd6 $145 $1 22. Bxd5 (22. Bc1 Bf8 $13) 22... cxd5 23. Nxf6+ Qxf6 24. Rxe8+ Rxe8 25. Rxe8+ Bxe8 26. Qxd5+ Bf7 27. Qxa5 Qg6 $44 {Perunovic,Milos}) ({Perhaps the best defence for Black was} 21... a6 $1 $13 {with ...b5 to follow disturbing the white bishop.}) 22. Bc1 $1 Re6 (22... Nxc4 $145 23. bxc4 Ne7 24. Bf4 $14 {Perunovic,Milos}) 23. Bd2 Nxc4 24. bxc4 Ne7 {Diagram [#] Diagram [#] Vidit goes for (arguably) the most logical continuation.} 25. Bxh6 $5 ({An interesting alternative for White was} 25. Bf4 $5 f5 26. Bxc7 Qxc7 27. Ne5 $1 Rxe5 (27... Ng6 28. Nc3 $1 Nxe5 29. dxe5 $18) 28. Nf6+ gxf6 29. dxe5 $16 {and Black has problems coordinating his pieces.}) 25... Qxd4 {} ({A Computer-type defence and (likely) the way to save the game was} 25... Ng6 $1 26. Bxg7 Kxg7 27. Ng3 {Diagram [#]} Bxg3 $1 28. Rxe6 Bxe6 29. Rxe6 Bc7 $13 {and the position looks very promising for White. However, my engine is surviving as Black.}) {Diagram [#]} 26. Qg4 $4 {Horrible blunder destroys Vidit's tournament. I guess White thought to be winning (on the spot) and somehow (at the end of the long tournament those things happen) missed Black's response.} ({White had to continue with} 26. Bf4 $1 {and after (forced)} Bxf4 27. Nxf4 $16 {White has excellent attacking prospects.}) 26... f5 $19 {Now White loses the piece without any compensation.} 27. Bxg7 Qxg7 28. Qxg7+ Kxg7 29. Ng5 Rxe2 30. Rxe2 Ng6 {Diagram [#] The smoke has cleared and Black is piece up in the ending. Mamedyarov safely brings it home.} 31. Ne6+ Bxe6 32. Rxe6 Rd8 33. Rxc6 Bb8 34. Ne1 Ne5 35. Re6 Kf7 36. Rh6 Rd1 37. Kf1 Nxc4 38. Rh4 Ne3+ 0-1


