1. d4 {Vidit,SG Vidit,SG Vidit,SG: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Vidit,SG''} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d6 5. Bg5 {I was quite inspired to take this line after watching the Kramnik-Yermolinsky game.} O-O (5... Nbd7 6. e3 b6 7. Nge2 Bb7 8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. Nxc3 h6 10. Bh4 O-O 11. f3 c5 12. dxc5 dxc5 13. O-O-O Qe7 14. Be2 Rfd8 15. g4 $36 {1-0 (40) Kramnik,V (2751)-Yermolinsky,A (2597) Wijk aan Zee 1999}) 6. e3 b6 7. Nge2 c5 8. a3 (8. O-O-O {I was considering this move for a while but I wanted to get a better version by pushing the bishop to a5.} Bb7 ({I was mainly considering} 8... cxd4 {but I simply underestimated how strong e4 is. Black's pieces aren't co-ordinated at all} 9. Ne4 $1 Bb7 10. Nxf6+ gxf6 11. Bh6 dxe3 12. fxe3 $44 {White's position looks quite pleasant.}) 9. d5 Bxc3 10. Nxc3 $14) 8... Bxc3+ (8... Ba5 9. O-O-O $36 {and a free initiative for White.}) 9. Nxc3 cxd4 10. exd4 Bb7 11. Be2 $1 {Ideally I would like to have the bishop on d3, but in lot of cases White needs to support the d4-pawn with d1.} (11. Bd3 h6 12. Bh4 Nc6 $132) (11. O-O-O Nbd7) 11... h6 (11... Bxg2 $6 {Taking this pawn is more dangerous than the b2-pawn in Najdorf :))} 12. Rg1 Bb7 13. O-O-O {with a big attack on the kingside.}) 12. Bh4 Nbd7 13. O-O Qe7 14. b4 $14 {The opening is over and White has a dream position without Black committing any mistakes. Apparently all natural looking moves aren't nice :)} Rfc8 15. Qb3 a6 (15... Ba6 16. Rfe1 {The bishop isn't doing much on a6.}) 16. Rfe1 {I love the luxury of making such small moves :)} Qf8 (16... Rc7 17. Bg3) 17. Rac1 {I was basically waiting for my opponent to go ...c7 so that I get g3 with a tempo. Although all alternatives are good.} (17. a4 $14) (17. Bg3 {Here I didn't like} Ne4 $1) 17... a5 {I was a bit surprised by this, but actually I don't see any good alternatives.} (17... Rc7 18. Bg3 $1 Rac8 19. c5 {and now White is creating some concrete problems for Black.}) 18. Bg3 (18. Bxf6 axb4 $1) (18. bxa5 {was also possible} Rxa5 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. Nb5 $16) 18... Ne4 19. Nxe4 Bxe4 20. Qb2 {Maybe a bit slow, but still the position remains quite unpleasant.} (20. d5 $6 {looks too hasty} exd5 21. cxd5 Rxc1 22. Rxc1 Nf6 {and the black pieces were getting some targets.}) (20. Bf1 $1 Bb7 21. c5 $1 $36) (20. Bf4 $14 {with the idea of g3 is also possible.}) 20... Bc6 $2 (20... Nf6 {was better although White still keeps a huge edge after} 21. f3 $16) 21. d5 $1 exd5 22. cxd5 Ba4 (22... Bxd5 $142 23. Rcd1 (23. Qd4 Be6 24. Bxd6 Qd8 25. Rcd1 $16 {I love how centralised the white pieces are :)}) 23... Nf6 (23... Be6 24. Bxd6) 24. Bh4 Be6 25. Bxf6 gxf6 26. Rd3 $40 {was my intention} (26. Qxf6 $16)) 23. h3 $1 $16 {I quite like this move. Although the engine doesn't agree. In lot of lines the back rank was a problem and now Black lacks good counterplay and slowly his position falls apart.} (23. b5 Nc5) 23... axb4 24. axb4 (24. Rxc8 $1 {is more accurate maybe, but I wanted to box Black's pieces in with axb4} Qxc8 (24... Rxc8 25. Qxb4) 25. Qxb4 $16) 24... Ne5 $6 (24... Nf6 $142 25. Qd4 $16) 25. b5 $1 Ra5 26. Bxe5 dxe5 27. Rc6 $18 {And now the rest, just for the sake of completeness.} Rd8 28. Bc4 Qe7 29. Rxe5 Qh4 30. d6 Ra7 31. Qe2 Kf8 32. Rc7 Rxc7 33. dxc7 Rc8 34. Qd3 Bc2 35. Qd7 1-0


