1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O c6 7. Qc2 b6 8. Rd1 Bb7 9. Bf4 Nbd7 10. Ne5 Nh5 11. Bd2 Nhf6 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Nc6 Bxc6 (13... Qe8 $5 14. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {has been tested around 20 times before. It's definitely worth considering as an alternative.}) 14. Qxc6 Rc8 15. Qa4 {A rare move, which has previously been considered harmless due to 15...Rc4 16.Qxa7 Rxd4 as well as the game continuation.} (15. Qb5 {is by far the most common move both Pavlovic and Illingworth have analysed it for ChessPublishing.} Ne8 16. Qd3 Nd6 17. Nc3 Nf6 (17... f5 {is awarded an exclamation mark by Illingworth. I am less enthusiastic about it, though it is surely playable.} 18. Nb5 Nxb5 19. Qxb5 Qc7 {Now Black plans ...Qb7 so an interesting idea is} 20. Qa6 $5 Nb8 (20... Qc4 21. Qxa7 Rc7 22. b3 $1 $14 {White holds on to the extra pawn though Black is by no means losing after swapping queens.}) 21. Qd3 Qb7 22. a4 Nc6 23. Rdc1) (17... Nc4 18. Bc1 Nf6 $1 (18... Bb4 $6 19. e4 $1 $36 {was shown in Cheparinov - So (see Illingworth's annotations).}) 19. b3 Nd6 20. Bd2 {see 17.. .Nf6.}) 18. b3 (18. Be1 {has also been played by some strong GMs, including Wojtasek and Leko.} Qd7 19. Rac1 Rc7 20. Rc2 Rfc8 21. Rdc1 h5 22. e3 g6 23. Ne2 Kg7 24. Rxc7 Rxc7 25. Rxc7 Qxc7 26. h4 Nfe4 $11 {1/2-1/2 Leko,P - Giri,A chess24. com INT 2020}) 18... Qd7 19. f3 Nf5 20. e3 Rfd8 21. Ne2 h5 {This is a very popular counterattack, preparing to undermine the f3-pawn with ...g5-g4.} ({Illingworth dared to examine} 21... g5 $5 {in his notes to Cheparinov - So, but he ultimately decided that it was too risky. Actually, I think there's a lot of merit to the move, and he was probably too critical about his own idea here.} 22. a4 g4 23. fxg4 Nxg4 24. Bf3 Nf6 {Now he suggests that White is better after} 25. a5 $6 {but my engine gives Black an advantage after} Nd6 {among other moves.}) 22. Rac1 Ba3 23. Rxc8 Rxc8 24. Be1 Nd6 25. e4 Nb5 26. e5 Ne8 27. f4 g6 28. h3 Qc6 29. g4 Qc2 30. Kf1 Qxd3 31. Rxd3 hxg4 32. hxg4 f5 $11 {Helbich,J - Vesely,P ICCF email 2016}) 15... Qc7 {The most solid reply, and a good practical decision by Duda, considering that his opponent probably spent most of his time exploring 15...Rc4.} (15... Rc4 16. Qxa7 Rxd4 17. Nc3 Rc4 18. Rac1 {This position is definitely more interesting than it is credited to be. White has decent prospects of an advantage in the long run as the asymmetrical pawn structure favours the two bishops.} Ne5 (18... Rc8 19. Qa4 h6 (19... Ne5 {Petruzzelli,R (2071)-Kozlowski,W (2425) ICCF email 2015} 20. Be1 Rc4 21. Qa6 Qc8 22. Qxc8 Rfxc8 23. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2f4]}) 20. b4 Rc4 21. Nb5 Nc5 22. Qa3 Nce4 23. Be1 Rxc1 24. Rxc1 Qa8 25. Qb3 Qa6 26. a4 Ra8 27. Qa3 Ne8 28. Ra1 {White had some pressure in Herman,T (2219)-Sazon,A (2251) ICCF email 2018}) 19. b3 Rc8 20. Nb5 Nc6 21. Qa4 Qd7 22. Nc3 $13) 16. Nc3 (16. e3 {in Ragger - Anand was met by} Qc2 $1 17. Qxc2 Rxc2 18. Bc3 $6 {1/2-1/2 (24) Ragger,M (2669) -Anand,V (2757) Germany 2019} Ne4 19. Bxe4 dxe4 {There is no way for White to take advantage of Black's 'trapped' rook on c2.}) 16... Qb7 17. e3 a6 18. Qb3 Rc7 19. Rdc1 (19. Rac1 {has also been played:} Rfc8 20. Ne2 Ne8 21. Rxc7 Rxc7 22. Rc1 Nd6 23. Rxc7 Qxc7 {(Lei,T - Saduakassova,D, 2021). Somehow Stockfish always claims that White is slightly better in these positions, but Black is very solid and has absolutely no weaknesses. I think this type of evaluation also obscures players' perspectives when preparing.}) 19... b5 20. Ne2 Nb6 21. Rxc7 Qxc7 22. Rc1 {As per the above text, I don't really think Black should be worried in these positions, since Stockfish's +0.50 evaluation is somewhat misleading. On the other hand, if White wants to try here, they have every right to press until the end, which is probably the only unpleasant aspect of these positions from Black's point of view (as Black cannot really hope to gain winning chances themselves).} (22. Nf4 Nc4 23. Be1 a5 24. Rc1 Qb6 25. Nd3 Rc8 26. Qd1 Rc7 $11) (22. Ba5 Rc8 23. Nf4 Qb8 24. Nd3 Nc4 25. Be1 a5 $11) 22... Nc4 23. Bb4 Rb8 24. Nf4 Bxb4 25. Qxb4 a5 26. Qe1 Qb6 27. Nd3 (27. Rc2 b4 $11) 27... b4 28. b3 Nd6 {Duda did all the right things to neutralise Vidit's hopes of an advantage.} 29. Nc5 (29. Ne5 Qb7 30. Rc5 Ra8 31. Qc1 Nb5 $11 {White gains control of the c-file in this variation, but since there are no access squares, the c-file is close to useless.}) 29... Rc8 30. Na4 Qd8 31. Bf1 Rxc1 32. Qxc1 g5 33. a3 1/2-1/2


