1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. c4 O-O 6. Ne5 $5 {An extremely rare move, which only appears 5 times in my database. Two of those games, however, appear in the Chess Publishing Archives, including a game by our own Tony Kosten! White's idea is to steer the game out of Catalan theory while maintaining a flexible and sound position. Instead, of course, White's main options are 6 d4 entering a mainline Catalan, or 6 b3 leading to the Reti double fianchetto setup. The latter has been covered many times on the Flank Opening section of this site.} c5 {Black has also played:} (6... Nbd7 7. d4 {which is officially classified under ECO code E07. This is very similar to standard closed Catalan setups, although this is not necessarily what Black wanted - perhaps he planned to play an "open" Catalan with 6 d4 dxc4, for example.} c6 {and now:} 8. Nd2 (8. Nc3 Nxe5 9. dxe5 Nd7 10. cxd5 exd5 (10... cxd5 11. e4 d4 12. Qxd4 Bc5 13. Qc4 {gave White a development lead in Iordachescu,V (2607)-Chernyshova,N (2030) Bad Wiessee 2009 1-0 (29)}) 11. f4 Re8 12. Be3 Bc5 13. Bxc5 Nxc5 {was played in Giri,A (2785)-So,W (2815) chess. com INT 2017 1-0 (32), and now} 14. b4 $1 Nd7 15. b5 {gives White a slight initiative.}) 8... Nxe5 9. dxe5 Nd7 10. Nf3 Nb6 11. cxd5 exd5 {was Kosten-Horvath, in the Archives}) 7. cxd5 exd5 8. e3 {White goes for central occupation. Instead:} (8. b3 Be6 9. Bb2 Qc8 10. d4 cxd4 11. Nd2 Nc6 12. Ndf3 Bh3 13. Rc1 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Qe8 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. Nxd4 {and White has good play against the hanging pawns, see Kurajica-Horvath in the Archives}) 8... Qd6 {A slightly awkward looking move, but Black wants to avoid the doubled pawns that would result after:} (8... Nc6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 {etc.}) (8... Re8 9. d4 Nc6 {looks like a cleaner approach, when Black is active enough to avoid major problems.}) 9. d4 cxd4 10. exd4 Be6 11. Nc3 {Despite the symmetrical (IQP vs IQP) pawn structure, White has the more promising position. His g2-bishop is more active than its e6-counterpart, and he has a slight lead in development.} Qb6 12. Re1 Nc6 13. Na4 Qd8 {Black has effectively lost 3 tempi moving his queen around and then back to base.} 14. Nxc6 {White fixes the backward c6-pawn, and continues with natural developing moves.} bxc6 15. Bf4 Re8 16. Rc1 Bd7 17. Nc5 Bf5 18. Re5 Bc8 $2 {After this unfortunate retreat, Black can hardly avoid losing the c6-pawn. Black could limit the damage with, for example:} (18... Bxc5 19. Rxc5 Bd7 {or}) (18... Bg4 19. Qe1 Rc8 {although White retains a slight advantage}) 19. Qa4 Bd7 20. Nxd7 Nxd7 21. Re2 g5 $6 {The c6-pawn is falling, but this just makes matters worse.} 22. Bd2 Nb6 23. Qxc6 Rc8 24. Qh6 {White has a crushing position, with an extra pawn and badly exposed Black king. Vidit wraps up the win efficiently.} Rxc1+ 25. Bxc1 f6 26. Bh3 Bf8 27. Rxe8 {Black resigned in light of:} (27. Rxe8 Qxe8 28. Qxf6 {for example} Qe1+ 29. Kg2 Qe4+ 30. Kf1 Qd3+ 31. Kg1 Qd1+ 32. Kg2 {and Black's checks run out, while 33 Be6# is looming.}) 1-0


