1. e4 {[%emt 0:00:00] Game 07} c5 {[%emt 0:00:26]} 2. Nf3 {[%emt 0:00:00]} e6 {[%emt 0:00:29]} 3. d4 {[%emt 0:00:02]} cxd4 {[%emt 0:00:05]} 4. Nxd4 {[%emt 0:00:06]} Nf6 {[%emt 0:00:03]} 5. Nc3 {[%emt 0:00:09]} Nc6 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 6. Nxc6 {[%emt 0:00:20]} bxc6 {[%emt 0:00:05]} 7. e5 {[%emt 0:00:07]} Nd5 {[%emt 0:00:04]} 8. Ne4 {[%emt 0:00:08]} Qc7 {[%emt 0:00:03]} 9. f4 {[%emt 0:00:15]} Qb6 {[%emt 0:00:03]} 10. c4 {[%emt 0:00:36]} Bb4+ {[%emt 0:00:12]} 11. Ke2 {[%emt 0:00:09] Game 07: 'This is essential. Any awkwardness in White's position is only temporary, as he can easily neaten up his king position. In contrast, Black's weaker pawn structure tends to be a game-long problem.'} (11. Bd2 $2 {(Game 07) blunders a pawn to} Qe3+ 12. Qe2 Bxd2+ 13. Nxd2 Qxe2+ $17 {followed by ...Nxf4.}) 11... f5 {[%emt 0:02:17] Game 07: 'The only respectable try.'} (11... Ba6 $6 {(Game 07) This used to be a main line, but then it was hit hard by a forcing line.} 12. Kf3 $1 f5 ({Black has no choice as} 12... Ne7 $2 13. a3 {is fatal. For example:} Bc5 14. b4 Bd4 15. c5 $18) 13. exf6 Nxf6 14. c5 $1 {This is the punch that killed the line.} Qa5 {What else?} (14... Bxc5 15. Nxc5 Bxf1 16. Na4 $1 Bxg2+ 17. Kxg2 $16 {leaves Black a piece down for just two pawns.}) 15. Nd6+ Ke7 16. Bxa6 Qxa6 {Again the only chance.} (16... Bxc5 $2 17. Nb7) ({and} 16... Qxc5 $2 17. Nb7 {both lose to the same resource.}) 17. Be3 $16 {White is close to winning, with a beast of a knight on d6 and an insecure black king to harass; his score in the database is 7/8 and it should have been more. A key point is that the apparently active} Nd5 $6 {is crushed by} 18. Qd4 $1 $18 {with the idea} Rhg8 19. f5 $1) 12. exf6 {[%emt 0:01:23] Game 07: 'A forcing and effective line.'} (12. Nf2 {(Game 07) is a common alternative.}) 12... Nxf6 {[%emt 0:00:18]} 13. Be3 {[%emt 0:00:08]} Qd8 {[%emt 0:02:55] Game 07: 'One of two commonly played moves.'} (13... Qa5 {(Game 07) is another important option which we will see in the next illustrative game.}) (13... Qc7 {(Game 07) is rare.} 14. Nxf6+ gxf6 15. Kf2 $16 {is similar to the next game, though the queen is more passive on c7 than a5.}) 14. Nd6+ {[%emt 0:00:11] Game 07: 'Of course this is the right path'} ({rather than allowing Black's idea of} 14. Nxf6+ $6 {Game 07} Qxf6) 14... Bxd6 {[%emt 0:00:38]} 15. Qxd6 {[%emt 0:00:03]} Qe7 {[%emt 0:00:19] Game 07: '?!' Game 07: 'Krasenkow is a Four Knights expert, so his choice should be taken seriously'} ({Game 07: 'but the more common alternative seems stronger.'} 15... Bb7 16. Rd1 {Game 07: 'White's plan of development is Rg1 and g2-g4, gaining space and clearing a path for the f1-bishop; the white king is fine where it is.'} Rc8 {Game 07: 'Preparing ...c6-c5 to free the bishop.'} ({The same advance as a gambit is unconvincing:} 16... c5 {Game 07} 17. Qxc5 {For example:} Be4 18. Ke1 Rc8 19. Qa3 $16 {Sanz Algarrada - Troia, email 2013.}) 17. g4 (17. Rg1 {(Game 07) transposes after} c5) ({Instead} 17. c5 {(Game 07) stops one of Black's plans, but allows another:} Ba6+ 18. Kf3 Bxf1 19. Rhxf1 Nd5 $11 {As a general guideline, c4-c5 becomes an effective plan only after there is no black knight to settle on d5.}) 17... c5 18. Rg1 {Game 07: 'Black has many possible plans, so I would not suggest trying to anticipate and memorize every possible line. I will however give a few important lines. a)'} Rf8 {Game 07: 'A rare move, but chosen in a high-class encounter, so worth a look:'} ({b)} 18... Qb6 {Game 07} 19. g5 {White is happy to exchange queens, just not on b6 when Black can recapture with ...axb6.} Qxd6 ({Also pleasant for White is} 19... Nd5 20. Qxb6 Nxb6 21. b3 $14 {as in Martin Sanchez - Soltau, email 2013; the hanging knight meant Black could not recapture with the a7-pawn.}) 20. Rxd6 {The bishop pair should give White a edge. For example:} Ne4 21. Rd3 d5 22. Ra3 $14) ({c)} 18... Rc6 {(Game 07) Forcing, and the usual choice; this is one line White certainly should remember.} 19. Qe5 O-O 20. g5 Nh5 21. Bh3 $1 {Threatening Bg4 or the less obvious g5-g6, which is a common theme.} ({The immediate} 21. g6 $2 {fails to} Rf5 $17) 21... d6 $1 {This excellent move has been played in all four games in my database, which tells you they were all correspondence games.} ({Instead} 21... Qc7 $6 {allows White to show his idea with} 22. g6 {when the g1-rook springs to life.}) 22. Bxe6+ $1 {The following line leaves Black little choice along the way:} ({Instead} 22. Qxe6+ Kh8 23. Rgf1 {may look tempting, but Black has irritating counterplay after:} Rb6 24. b3 Ra6 $13) 22... Kh8 23. Qc3 Nxf4+ 24. Bxf4 Rxf4 25. Rdf1 $1 Re4+ 26. Kd1 Rxe6 27. Rf7 $14 {Recovering the sacced minor piece, leading to a major-piece ending where White has greater activity. My engine and I had this line ready, then Kotronias & Semkov published their book first, with exactly the same line; such things happen in forcing lines.}) 19. f5 {Game 07: '' Game 07: 'was interesting but messy in Karjakin - Yu Yangyi, Baku 2015.'} (19. g5 $5 $146 {(Game 07) I like recommending a consistent plan, unless there is good reason to vary.} Ne4 {The critical test.} (19... Nh5 20. Bh3 Qc7 21. Rgf1 Qxd6 22. Rxd6 $14 {gives White a pleasant endgame edge.}) 20. Qd3 Rc7 $1 {Preparing a defence to White's idea of Bg2.} ({Instead} 20... Qe7 $6 21. Bg2 d5 22. Bxe4 dxe4 23. Qc3 $16 {leaves Black with a deadened bishop and a weak structure.}) 21. Bg2 $5 Qa8 22. Rde1 Ke7 23. b3 $5 $14 {A generally useful little move; White retains some pressure. For example:} Nd6 $2 24. Rd1 $18 {wins, with the point} Nf5 25. Bxc5+) ({The white king could become exposed if we go pawn-grabbing, so avoid} 19. Bxc5 $2 {(Game 07) when} Rf7 {renews the threat of ...Ne4. And following} 20. Bxa7 Rxc4 $15 {the previously passive rook on c8 is now hyperactive.}) 19... Qb6 20. fxe6 dxe6 21. g5 Nd5 22. Qxb6 Nxb6 23. Ke1 Nd7 24. Be2 Ke7 25. Rd3 Be4 26. Ra3 Rc7 27. Kd2 e5 28. Rf1 Rb8 29. Kc3 Rb6 30. Rd1 Rbc6 31. Bg4 Nb6 32. Ra5 g6 33. b3 Bf5 34. Be2 Nd7 35. a3 Be6 36. h4 Bf7 37. Bf3 Rb6 38. Rxd7+ Kxd7 39. Bxc5 e4 40. Bg4+ {1-0 (40) Karjakin,S (2762)-Yu,Y (2721) Baku 2015}) 16. Bc5 {[%emt 0:11:37]} Qf7 $146 {[%emt 0:26:31] Game 07: '?' Game 07: 'Keeping the queens on and threatening ...Ne4, but White has superb resources in the middlegame.'} (16... Qxd6 17. Bxd6 Kf7 (17... Ne4 {Game 07} 18. Ba3 (18. Be5 $5 {is equally good}) 18... d5 19. Ke3 a5 20. Rc1 $16 {In Martin Gonzalez - Li Zunian, Biel 1985, White had the bishop pair, the initiative and an active king.}) 18. Kf3 Ne8 19. Ba3 d5 20. Bd3 Nf6 21. Rac1 Ba6 22. Rhe1 Rhd8 23. Re3 Bb7 24. f5 Bc8 25. g4 Re8 26. g5 Ne4 27. cxd5 exf5 28. Rxc6 Nxg5+ 29. Kf4 Rxe3 30. Kxe3 Nh3 31. Rc7+ Kf6 32. Kd4 Ng1 33. Be7+ Kf7 34. Ke3 Nh3 35. Bc5+ {1-0 (35) Ahmed,A (2346)-Ayyad,M (2123) Muscat 2015}) 17. Ke3 {[%emt 0:00:41] Game 07: 'The funny thing is that any king move that covers ...Ne4 is good enough. So 17.Kd3 or 17.Kf3 are both winning.'} g5 {[%emt 0:05:42] Game 07: '?!' Game 07: 'This does not work, but the desperation is justified.'} (17... Ng4+ {(Game 07) achieves nothing after} 18. Kd2 Qf6 19. Kc2 $18 {when White can simply complete development with a crushing bind.}) 18. Be2 {[%emt 0:33:25] Game 07: 'Logical and effective'} ({but also strong was} 18. fxg5 {Game 07} Ng4+ 19. Kd2 Nf2 20. Bd3 $1 {with the idea of} Nxh1 21. Rxh1 {then Rf1, when Black is finished.}) 18... g4 {[%emt 0:09:31] Game 07: 'Now the advance of the g-pawn has achieved nothing other than weakening Black's kingside'} ({but instead after} 18... gxf4+ {Game 07} 19. Qxf4 {the open f-file helps White.}) 19. Rac1 {[%emt 0:06:58] Game 07: '+-' Game 07: 'White simply needs to shuffle his pieces towards the exposed black king; it takes a few moves, but there is no rush as Black lacks any counterplay.'} h5 {[%emt 0:09:24]} 20. Rc3 {[%emt 0:06:24]} Qg7 {[%emt 0:03:33]} 21. Bd3 {[%emt 0:03:49]} Kf7 {[%emt 0:02:49]} 22. Kd2 {[%emt 0:00:52]} Re8 {[%emt 0:00:50]} 23. Re1 {[%emt 0:00:48]} Qh6 {[%emt 0:01:46]} 24. Kc2 {[%emt 0:04:24] Game 07: 'Taking his time.'} ({The immediate} 24. Re5 {(Game 07) was possible, as} Qxf4+ 25. Be3 Qxh2 {loses to the same tactic we shall see in a moment.}) 24... a5 {[%emt 0:08:24]} 25. Re5 {[%emt 0:08:37] Game 07: '!'} Nh7 {[%emt 0:03:59]} ({Taking the pawn loses the queen:} 25... Qxf4 $2 {Game 07} 26. Be3 Qxh2 27. Bg6+ $1 Kxg6 28. Rg5+) 26. Rf5+ {[%emt 0:12:21]} Kg8 {[%emt 0:00:44]} 27. Qe5 {[%emt 0:01:07] Game 07: 'Black's position is collapsing; it's notable that his c8-bishop and a8-rook never moved - the frozen bishop in particular is a sign of a Four Knights gone very wrong for Black.  The game was a disaster for Black, so 15...Qe7 is unlikely to become popular. The critical line is 15...Bb7, but with precise play White keeps the better chances.'} 1-0


