1. d4 {[%emt 0:00:00] Fernandez,D} d5 {[%emt 0:00:08]} 2. c4 {[%emt 0:00:15]} dxc4 {[%emt 0:00:07] Possibly a psychological choice- White is unlikely to go for the riskiest lines when a draw is so likely to give him first place.} 3. e3 {[%emt 0:00:35]} Nf6 {[%emt 0:00:19]} (3... e5 4. Bxc4 exd4 5. exd4 Nf6 {is a bit more imbalanced, thanks to the isolated queen's pawn.}) 4. Bxc4 {[%emt 0:00:07]} e6 {[%emt 0:00:07]} 5. Nf3 {[%emt 0:00:10]} c5 {[%emt 0:00:06]} 6. O-O {[%emt 0:00:39]} Nc6 {[%emt 0:00:07]} (6... a6 {might have with hindsight given Black a few perks, assuming White plays the endgame anyway, and plays it in a similar style:} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Bd2 Ke7 $11 {Black will set up with ...b5, ...bd7, ...b7. The position is equal.}) 7. Nc3 {[%emt 0:01:17]} a6 {[%emt 0:00:10]} 8. dxc5 {[%emt 0:00:25]} Qxd1 {[%emt 0:00:11]} 9. Rxd1 {[%emt 0:00:04]} Bxc5 {[%emt 0:00:10]} 10. Bd2 {[%emt 0:00:06]} O-O {[%emt 0:00:47]} (10... Ke7 {is less advisable here thanks to} 11. Bd3 $5 $14 {and Black faces a few problems completing development.}) 11. Rac1 {[%emt 0:00:22]} Bd7 {[%emt 0:00:09]} 12. Be2 {[%emt 0:00:12] The idea is clearly enough a4-c5, but right now there is an issue with playing it, so Black can safely ignore the idea.} (12. Ne2 Bb6 13. Bc3 {was more forcing, but also didn't give much:} Rfd8 14. Ne5 Be8 $1 $11) 12... Rfd8 {[%emt 0:00:06]} 13. Na4 {[%emt 0:04:11]} Ba7 {[%emt 0:00:06]} 14. Be1 {[%emt 0:00:38]} (14. Nc5 Bxc5 15. Rxc5 Ne4 {equalises, unless White can somehow mount a convincing claim that his opponent's bishop is genuinely bad.}) 14... Be8 {[%emt 0:08:04]} 15. Rxd8 {[%emt 0:09:57]} (15. Nc5 Rxd1 16. Bxd1 Rb8 $11) 15... Nxd8 {[%emt 0:06:24]} 16. b3 {[%emt 0:00:28]} (16. Nc5 Rc8 $11) 16... Nd5 {[%emt 0:03:19]} 17. Kf1 {[%emt 0:00:41]} Nc6 {[%emt 0:15:52]} (17... Bb5 $5 {was most principled, and would have been an interesting way for Black to remind his opponent that the draw is subject to good play from both sides and is not a God-given right.} 18. Ne5 (18. Bxb5 axb5 19. Nc3 Nxc3 20. Bxc3 f6 $132) 18... f6 19. Nd3 Ne7 20. Nab2 Rc8 $11 {Black has kept his equality without making any concessions.}) 18. Nc5 {[%emt 0:01:29]} Rb8 {[%emt 0:00:11]} 19. a3 {[%emt 0:08:33]} Nce7 {[%emt 0:08:37]} 20. Ne5 {[%emt 0:08:26]} Rc8 {[%emt 0:07:11]} 21. Ned3 {[%emt 0:00:33]} Rc7 {[%emt 0:02:03]} 22. b4 {[%emt 0:05:24] Maybe not the most precise way to prosecute the advantage.} ({White could have had something following} 22. e4 Nf6 23. f3 Bb5 24. Bg3 $1 $14) 22... Bxc5 {[%emt 0:09:07]} 23. Rxc5 {[%emt 0:11:25]} Bb5 {[%emt 0:00:21]} 24. Rxc7 {[%emt 0:07:36] Here the draw was agreed, so we assume White could not really be bothered pressing but was fine to halve out as soon as the draw margin was large enough for Black to completely forget about winning himself.} (24. e4 Bxd3 25. Bxd3 Rxc5 26. bxc5 Nf6 $132 {is probably not that dangerous for Black anymore.}) 1/2-1/2


