1. d4 {My opponent has a rich opening repertoire and usually comes up with various fresh ideas. This time I decided to employ a line which had never occurred in my practice before.} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 Be7 (6... a5 {is what I previously played in this position.}) 7. O-O O-O 8. Nc3 c6 9. Bf4 d5 10. Qd3 $5 {I analyzed this interesting continuation long time ago, but during the game didn't manage to refresh anything in my memory. Obviously, White's main idea is pushing e2-e4 at some point.} Na6 $6 {Quite a risky decision - the knight is located rather awkwardly.} ({The more natural} 10... Nbd7 11. Rfd1 ({For some reasons, nobody tried} 11. e4 $5 dxc4 12. Qxc4 b5 13. Qb3 b4 14. e5 {, though it looks promising.}) 11... Ba6 12. b3 dxc4 13. bxc4 Nd5 14. a3 (14. Rac1 $5 Nxf4 15. gxf4 Qc7 16. e3 {also might be an improvement.}) 14... Nxf4 15. gxf4 Qc7 16. e3 Rfd8 $132 {led to double-edged play in Anton Guijarro,D - Narayanan,S Sharjah 2017}) 11. a3 dxc4 12. Qxc4 Nd5 $146 {This innovation definitely doesn't make Black's position look more attractive. Somehow, I was hoping to slowly neutralize the pressure along h1-a8 diagonal, but this isn't realistic.} ({The only preceding game saw} 12... c5 13. Ne5 ({It looks like after} 13. Rfd1 $1 Qc8 14. Rac1 {Black is under strong pressure - the misplaced a6 causes serious problems.}) 13... Bxg2 14. Kxg2 cxd4 15. Nc6 Qd7 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Qxd4 Rfd8 {Black was fine in Jumabayev,R -Tiviakov,S Tashkent 2010}) 13. Ne5 Rc8 14. Rfd1 {In general, this pawn structure is acceptable for Black in case the knight can be placed on d5. Alas, this time it cannot get there.} Nb8 $6 {This inaccurate move invites fresh troubles.} ({Correct was} 14... Qe8 15. Rac1 Nxf4 16. gxf4 Kh8 17. e3 f6 18. Nd3 Nc7 {Black is clearly worse, but it is still playable.}) 15. Qa4 $1 Nxf4 $2 {Surprisingly, this is already a decisive mistake!} ({Admitting the mistake by means of} 15... Na6 {wouldn't change much, since after} 16. Rac1 b5 17. Qb3 Nxf4 18. gxf4 {White's position is practically winning.}) ({The lesser evil was} 15... a5 16. Qb3 Nd7 17. Rac1 $16) 16. gxf4 a5 17. Qb3 {All White's moves are very natural and strong. This time he provokes another weakening advance.} b5 18. Rac1 Rc7 19. Ne4 Na6 ({Equally bad was} 19... Nd7 20. Nc5 Nxe5 21. dxe5 Qa8 {, and now White can even afford} 22. Rd6 $5 {, reaching full domination.}) 20. Nc5 Nxc5 21. dxc5 Qa8 22. Be4 {Black's position looks so depressing that the rest does not have too much value for chess.} g6 23. Qg3 Rd8 ({More stubborn was} 23... Qc8 24. b4 axb4 25. axb4 Rd8 26. h4 {, but also then the king would be helpless.}) 24. f5 {Alas, this game can be considered as a typical opening disaster.} (24. f5 exf5 25. Nxg6 hxg6 26. Qxc7 $18) 1-0


