1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 e6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. exd4 b6 6. h3 ({Far from essential at this early stage and we considered} 6. Nbd2 Be7 7. c3 O-O 8. Bd3 Ba6 {in J.Van Foreest-Van den Doel, Dutch Championship, Amsterdam 2017,}) ({while coverage of} 6. Bb5 $5 Be7 7. h3 O-O 8. O-O Bb7 (8... Ba6 9. a4 $1 {is an important idea}) 9. Re1 d6 10. a4 {can also be found in the Archive - look for Grischuk-Leko, European Team Championship, Hersonissos 2017.}) 6... Be7 7. a4 $5 {I dare say that many a club player would not have advanced both rook pawns so early, but this advance is ever tempting against an early ...b6.} O-O 8. Nbd2 d6 9. Bb5 {Consistent with his last, and now Black plays along with White's plan.} Ba6 ({A big decision. Instead,} 9... a6 10. Bd3 Bb7 11. c3 Nbd7 {would be all quite normal, when an important question is: can Black meet} 12. O-O {with} e5 $5 {? It seems that he can, as} 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Bxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Bd6 16. Ndf3 Re8 17. Nc4 Bc5 {must offer lasting compensation based on the two bishops, with which side to prefer here likely a matter of taste.}) (9... Bb7 10. O-O Nbd7 {is, of course, also possible, although it would be a surprise if Black could resist the ...a6 prod for too long.}) 10. O-O Bxb5 $6 ({Vidit played very well in the first half of Prague, but I still don't like this decision. Instead,} 10... Bb7 11. Re1 a6 12. Bd3 Nbd7 {reaches a position we've considered before. Now} 13. Bh2 {was Gata Kamsky's choice, albeit only in a blitz game,} ({while} 13. c3 Re8 14. Bh2 Nf8 15. Nc4 Nd5 (15... Ng6 $5 {might improve, and only if} 16. Qe2 {then} Nd5) 16. Nfd2 $1 b5 17. axb5 axb5 18. Rxa8 Bxa8 19. Na3 b4 20. Nb5 {left Black slightly worse, with c3-c4 on its way in Van den Doel-Kryakvin, Hoogeveen 2018.})) 11. axb5 Nd5 ({Fighting for space. Otherwise after something like} 11... Nbd7 12. c3 Qc7 13. Qe2 {it's not hard to imagine Black struggling to free his position, while White perhaps goes Ne1-d3-b4 and/or expands on the kingside.}) 12. Bg3 Nc7 $1 {Recognising his early error, Vidit is determined to make amends as best he can, by at least getting in the ...a6 break.} 13. c4 a6 14. bxa6 (14. Qb3 $1 {would have been a forcing alternative. Then} Qd7 (14... axb5 15. Rxa8 bxc4 $2 16. Qa2 {wins a piece}) 15. Ne4 $1 ({stronger than} 15. Rfc1 Rc8) 15... axb5 {(before White goes Nc3 to maintain his grip)} 16. Rxa8 Nxa8 17. Qxb5 Qxb5 18. cxb5 f5 {exploits the white bishop's position on g3, as opposed to h2, but even so after} 19. Neg5 Nc7 20. Rc1 {Black remains under heavy pressure and set to have to lose a pawn.}) 14... Rxa6 15. Qb3 Qd7 16. Rxa6 (16. Ne4 $1 {was again a more direct approach, refusing to fear} f5 (16... d5 17. Ne5 Qd8 18. Nc3 dxc4 19. Qxc4 Rxa1 20. Rxa1 {is also good for White, whose activity more than offsets the IQP}) 17. Nc3 f4 {on account of} 18. Rxa6 Nbxa6 19. Bh4 Bxh4 20. Nxh4 {when Black's position remains quite ragged. There are too few pieces left for him to contemplate ...f3 followed by an exchange sacrifice, but something like} d5 21. cxd5 exd5 22. Nf3 Qd6 23. Rc1 {just leaves him positionally clearly worse.}) 16... Nbxa6 17. Ra1 (17. Qxb6 Rb8 18. Qa5 Rxb2 19. Ra1 Rb7 {feels quite solid for Black, who might next regroup with ...Nb8.}) 17... Rb8 18. Ne4 ({Finally, but} 18. Qc3 $5 {to meet} b5 {with} 19. b3 {might have retained an edge.}) 18... h6 $2 ({Now Black gets into trouble all over again when he might have liberated his position with} 18... b5 $1 {. Presumably Vidit disliked} 19. c5 $1 dxc5 20. dxc5 Nxc5 21. Nxc5 Bxc5 22. Ne5 {, but after} Qe8 $1 23. Rc1 Bb6 {the machine fails to discover anything especially scary for Black whose pieces are just well enough coordinated.}) 19. Nc3 $1 {Clamping down on b5 and so reminding Black of his out-of-play knight on a6.} Bf8 20. Qa4 $6 ({Electing to force the pace, although White might also have manoeuvred, such as by improving his king's knight after} 20. Ne1 $5 {.}) 20... Qxa4 21. Rxa4 Rb7 22. b4 {The point of Vitiugov's play, but again something slower might have been more appropriate as Black is now able to roll up into a ball.} Nb8 $1 23. b5 Nd7 24. Kf1 f5 25. h4 {White has plenty of time to suppress ...g5 and manoeuvre, but the issue remains the same: how to break through Black's solid defences, with the invasion squares down the a-file covered and b6 secure?} Be7 26. Bf4 Kf7 27. Na2 $6 ({Heading for c6, but something slower like} 27. Ke2 {would have been preferable.}) 27... e5 $1 {Vidit doesn't miss his chance to break out.} 28. dxe5 Nc5 29. Ra3 d5 {I wonder if Vitiugov missed this from afar. Black is a pawn down, but is very active and it's White's b-pawn which is now weak.} 30. cxd5 Nxd5 31. Bd2 Ne4 32. Rd3 Ra7 33. Nc1 $1 {Calm and good defence from White who manages to avoid drifting into trouble.} Nc7 34. Be3 Ra1 35. g3 Nc5 36. Rd1 Nxb5 {Regaining the pawn, but White is fairly well coordinated after his next and exchanges quickly follow.} 37. Re1 Ke6 38. Ne2 Rxe1+ 39. Kxe1 g5 (39... g5 40. hxg5 hxg5 41. Nfd4+ Nxd4 42. Nxd4+ Kxe5 43. Nc6+ Ke6 44. Nxe7 Kxe7 45. Bxg5+ {would, of course, but be extremely drawish.}) 1/2-1/2


