{I think this line is a reasonable option for those who want to create some pressure without much risk. Black should be fine, but some precision is required.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qb3 {Only the fifth most played move, but probably it's not worse than the main alternatives.} c5 6. dxc5 Nc6 7. Bg5 Qa5 (7... dxc4 8. Qxc4 Qa5 9. Rc1 (9. Bxf6 gxf6 {transposes to the game.}) 9... Qxc5 10. Qxc5 Bxc5 11. e3 {Nakamura,H (2779)-Aronian,L (2785) London Classic 8th 2016 (8) 1/2-1/2 was tried by Nakamura recently, but Black has no problems.}) 8. Bxf6 dxc4 9. Qxc4 gxf6 10. Rc1 Qxc5 {Reaching the basic structure of this position. Black's king is less safe and White's pawns are slightly better. On the other hand, Black has the bishop pair and a development advantage. If White manages to finish getting out his pieces, he could claim a small advantage, so Black needs to be quick and precise.} (10... Bxc5 {was seen in some games, but I think it's not as good as the main line, the game could continue:} 11. e3 Be7 12. g3 $5 {the bishop usually does well on the long diagonal} (12. Be2 {is also possible.}) 12... O-O 13. Bg2 Bd7 14. O-O Rfd8 15. Qh4 {and White's position is easier to play, as seen in 1-0 (25) Krysa,L (2491) -Peralta,F (2574) Lorca 2016}) 11. Qf4 $5 {Less played, but in some positions the queen is better centralized on f4. Also it provokes ...e5, which is not necessarily a bad move, but is always committal.} (11. Qh4 Ke7 12. g3 {is the usual way to play, and after} Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 (13. Rxc3 {does not bring any advantage} Qb4 14. Qxb4+ Nxb4 15. e4 Bd7 {was soon drawn in 1/2-1/2  (30) Kacheishvili,G (2590)-Swiercz,D (2649) Saint Louis 2017}) 13... b6 14. Bg2 Bb7 (14... Ba6 {I don't think the bishop is better on this diagonal} 15. Nd2 Rac8 16. Ne4 Qf5 $6 (16... Qe5 17. O-O h5 18. Rfe1 $14) 17. g4 {and White has good pressure, Rapport,R (2701)-Gajewski,G (2650) HUN-POL m Budapest 2014 (2.3) 1-0}) 15. O-O Rac8 (15... h5 16. Nd4 Rac8 17. Nb3 Qb5 18. Rfd1 Rhd8 $11) 16. Rfd1 h5 {White's queen is not doing much on h4, so in a top level game White just went} 17. Qf4 {1/2-1/2 (39) Dominguez Perez,L (2723)-Cheparinov,I (2687) Varadero 2016}) 11... Ke7 12. g3 {Now the plans with ...b6 are not working because of the check on c7.} e5 13. Qh6 (13. Qe4 {could be interesting, keeping the queen in the center looking at both h7 and b7} Be6 14. Bg2 Bxc3+ 15. bxc3 Bxa2 {not forced, but why not?} (15... Rac8 16. O-O b6 17. Nh4 $14) 16. Nd4 $5 (16. O-O Be6 17. Ne1 h5 18. Nd3 Qc4 19. Qe3 {with compensation.}) 16... Nxd4 (16... Be6 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. O-O $16 {the king is too exposed.}) 17. Qxb7+ Kf8 18. Qxa8+ Kg7 19. Qe4 Nb3 20. Qg4+ Kf8 21. Rd1 Qxc3+ 22. Kf1 {with a big mess, but I think White should be better.}) 13... Bxc3+ $6 {There are many possible moves, but it's early to take the knight.} (13... Be6 14. Bh3 (14. Bg2 {is always a solid option.}) 14... Bxh3 15. Qxh3 Nd4 16. O-O Bxc3 17. Nxd4 exd4 {Bruzon Batista,L (2691)-Lenderman,A (2617) WchT 10th Tsaghkadzor 2015 (9.2) 0-1} 18. e3 $5 Qa5 19. Qg2 Kf8 20. bxc3 dxc3 21. Qf3) (13... Rd8 14. Bg2 Nd4 15. O-O Bxc3 16. Nxd4 exd4 17. bxc3 dxc3 18. e4 Be6 19. e5 fxe5 20. Qg5+ Kf8 21. Bxb7 Rab8 22. Bg2 Rd4 23. Qf6 {Black's pieces are well placed, so White will eventually look for some perpetual.}) (13... Nd4 14. a3 (14. Bg2 Nf5 {is a funny way to bother White's plans} 15. Qh5 Ng7 16. Qh4 Nf5 17. Qe4 Nd6 18. Qb1 Bf5 19. Qa1 {doesn't look like the way to get any advantage.}) 14... Bxc3+ 15. Rxc3 Nc2+ $1 16. Kd1 Qd5+ 17. Kxc2 (17. Qd2 Nd4 18. Rg1 Rd8 19. Nxd4 Qxd4 20. Qxd4 Rxd4+ 21. Kc1) 17... Bf5+ 18. Kc1 Rac8 19. Bh3 Rxc3+ 20. bxc3 Bxh3 21. Qxh3 Qb3 22. Qg4 Qxc3+ 23. Kb1 Qb3+ $11) 14. bxc3 Be6 15. Bh3 (15. Bg2 {is also good} Rad8 (15... Na5 16. Nd2 Bd5 17. Bxd5 Qxd5 18. O-O Rhd8 19. Nf3 {with advantage.}) (15... Bxa2 16. O-O Rad8 17. Ra1 Be6 18. Rfb1 {with a Benko style position. White has pressure all over the board and Black's plan is not clear.}) 16. O-O Bxa2 17. Ra1 (17. c4 {is unclear} Bxc4 18. Nd2 Rxd2 19. Qxd2 b5) 17... Be6 18. Rfb1 $14) 15... e4 (15... Bxh3 16. Qxh3 Nd4 17. Nxd4 exd4 18. Qg2 {wins a pawn.}) 16. Bxe6 exf3 17. Bg4 fxe2 18. Rc2 Ne5 (18... Nd4 19. Qe3+ Ne6 20. Qxc5+ Nxc5 21. Rxe2+ Kf8 22. O-O {was the best way for Black to follow, without the queens Black can try to double rooks on the c-file and hold the endgame.}) (18... Qg5 19. Rxe2+ Kd6 20. Rd2+ Kc5 21. Qh3 {and Black's king is not exactly safe.}) 19. Bxe2 {Now White is going to castle and Black's position will collapse. The pawns are weak, the king is under attack and the knight has no good squares to go to.} Rad8 20. O-O Rd6 21. Re1 Re6 (21... Kd8 22. c4 Kc8 23. Rb1 $16) 22. Rd1 Rd6 23. Rxd6 Qxd6 24. Qe3 Kf8 (24... Qb6 {could be the last chance to hold, going for a rook and minor piece endgame with a pawn down} 25. Qxb6 axb6 26. Rb2 Ra8 27. Rxb6 Rxa2 28. Rxb7+ Kf8 29. Bh5 $16) 25. Qxa7 Qc6 26. f4 Nd7 27. Rb2 b6 28. Rd2 Ke7 29. a4 Rc8 30. Bb5 Rc7 31. Bxc6 Rxa7 32. Bxd7 Rxd7 33. Rxd7+ Kxd7 34. Kf2 Kc6 35. Ke3 Kc5 36. Ke4 Kc4 37. Kf5 Kxc3 38. Kxf6 Kb4 39. Kxf7 Kxa4 40. f5 b5 41. f6 b4 42. Kg7 1-0


