{China had been our main competitor in the Asian championship and needless to say this was a very crucial match for the final standings.} 1. e4 {Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R Vidit,S} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. d3 Nf6 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d5 {Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R: '!?' The most direct and concrete attempt to equalise against the Italian. The resulting position leads to the e5-point becoming the main battlefield. Most of the following moves from both sides either directly or indirectly influence control of the e5-point.} 7. exd5 Nxd5 {White already has a choice to make here. He has a wide variety of options at his disposal, leading to various kinds of strategically complex, yet balanced positions.} 8. Nbd2 (8. a4 {The space seizing move has been in fashion lately in the Italian.} a6 (8... Nb6 9. Bb5 Bd6 (9... Ne7 10. a5 $14) 10. a5 Nd5 11. a6 $14 {Demchenko,A (2596)-Jakovenko,D (2745), 2014}) (8... Nf6 9. Nbd2 Bf5 10. Qe2 Qe7 11. Ne4 Nxe4 12. dxe4 Be6 13. b4 Bd6 14. a5 f6 15. Be3 Nd8 16. Rfd1 Nf7 17. Nd2 Rfd8 18. Bxe6 Qxe6 19. Qc4 Qxc4 20. Nxc4 a6 {Shankland(2656)-Nakamura(2814), Baku 2015, with a slight, but secure edge.}) 9. Nbd2 Kh8 $5) (8. Re1 Bg4 9. h3 Bh5 10. Nbd2 Nb6 (10... Bb6 11. Ne4 f6 {is an additional option for Black in this move order though}) 11. Bb5 Bd6 {would tranpose to the text.}) (8. b4 Be7 9. Re1 (9. b5 Na5 10. Bxd5 Qxd5 11. c4 Qd7 12. Bd2 e4 13. Bxa5 exf3 14. Qxf3 a6 $44) 9... Bf6 10. a4 a6 11. Nfd2 Bf5 12. Ne4 Be7 {leads to a different kind of interesting position.}) (8. h3 Nb6 9. Bb5 Bd6 10. Re1 Ne7 $1 {[%csl Rb5]} 11. d4 exd4 12. cxd4 (12. Nxd4 c5 13. Nf3 Bf5 $11) 12... c6 13. Bd3 Bf5 $11) 8... Nb6 {Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R: '!'} 9. Bb5 Bd6 10. Re1 (10. Ne4 Bf5 11. Re1 Re8 12. Bd2 (12. Bg5 {Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R} Qd7) 12... Bg6 13. a4 a6 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. a5 Nd5 16. Qa4 Qd7 $11 {Kryvoruchko,Y (2706)-Tomashevsky,E (2714) Doha 2014}) 10... Bg4 11. h3 Bh5 {Vidit,S: 'would tranpose to the text.'} 12. Ne4 f5 {Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R: '!?' Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R: 'Quintiliano - I think this is an ambitious move for Black.'} ({Quintiliano - Grischuk scored a nice win with a more solid approach recently:} 12... Re8 {Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R} 13. Bg5 (13. Ng3 Bg6 14. Bg5 Qd7 15. Nh4 {½-½ Annaberdiev,M (2496)-Le,Q (2739) Asia-chT KO rapid 5th 2017 (1.1)} f6 $5 $146 16. Be3 Bf7 $11) 13... f6 14. Be3 a6 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Ng3 (16. g4 $5 {is recommended by Roiz in the notes to the game as a more active option} Bf7 17. c4 Bf8 18. Kh2 a5 19. Rg1 {with double-edged play. Maybe Black can bring the knight back now} Nc8 $5 20. Nh4 Nd6 21. Qe2 Kh8 22. Rad1 Rb8 $13) 16... Bf7 {[%csl Yd6,Yf7] We have a similar position to those reached in Fedoseev-Shirov and Anand-So, but as we saw, the bishop pair is valuable compensation for Black's damaged structure on the queenside} 17. c4 {[%csl Yd5] again playing to prevent d5} (17. d4 $6 {½-½ Carlsen,M (2855)-Aronian,L (2792) Leuven GCT blitz 2016 (1)} exd4 18. Nxd4 Bxg3 19. fxg3 Nc4 20. Bc1 Qd5 $15) 17... Bb4 $1 {This is a nice motif when White plays c3-c4, slightly disrupting his pieces} 18. Re2 Bf8 19. b3 c5 $1 {Now Black prevents d3-d4} 20. Qe1 a5 $1 21. Rd1 a4 $15 {0-1 Nakamura,H (2777)-Grischuk,A (2766) Sinquefield Cup 6th 2018 (3) we have a similar situation to the game Anand-So. Black achieved slight pressure on the queenside, but as Nakamura displayed a better defence, in the end Grischuk won by advancing the kingside pawns, after meticulous preparation -}) 13. Ng3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Qd7 {Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R: 'Quintiliano - This position looks somehow balanced, but still tense for both sides. Black has lost the bishop pair, but obtained a free development and more space in the centre. On other hand, it is not easy to figure out how White should continue his development.'} ({Quintiliano -} 14... Ne7 $6 {Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R was played by Giri, but I'm not sure about the objective value of this move} 15. Qxb7 c6 16. Bc4+ (16. Bxc6 $2 Rb8 {is the trick}) 16... Nxc4 17. Qb3 $1 Kh8 18. Qxc4 Qd7 19. Bd2 Nd5 {½-½ Vachier Lagrave,M (2789)-Giri,A (2782) Leuven GCT blitz 2018 (11) Black had some compensation for the pawn, what sometimes is enough in a blitz game -}) 15. a4 {Played after a long think. I already had a huge time advantage. Also, maybe it is better to leave the queenside untouched. Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R: 'Played after a long think. I already had a huge time advantage. Also, maybe it is better to leave the queenside untouched. /Quintiliano - Actually, this is the most played, but as the game went, Vidit is probably right, as the weaknesses on the queenside proved helpful only for Black.'} ({Quintiliano -} 15. Bd2 {Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R right now looks a bit risky} e4 $5 16. Qe2 (16. dxe4 $2 Bxg3 {[%csl Rd2]}) 16... Rae8 {with some pressure for Black} 17. Nf1 (17. dxe4 $2 f4 18. Nf1 f3 $40) 17... a6 18. Bxc6 Qxc6 $36) ({Quintiliano -} 15. Bxc6 {Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R} bxc6 16. c4 Rae8 {this is also fine for Black} 17. b3 Bc5 18. Qe2 $2 {0-1 Kapnisis,S (2510)-Cheparinov,I (2660) Gibraltar Masters 8th 2010 (10)} f4 19. Ne4 Bd4 20. Rb1 f3 $40) ({Quintiliano -} 15. d4 $6 {½-½ Smirin,I (2676)-Melkumyan,H (2640) Warsaw Najdorf Memorial op-A 14th 2016 (8) Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R} e4 16. Qd1 a6 17. Bf1 Rae8 {[%cal Ye4e3] once more Black's position seems very promising}) ({Quintiliano -} 15. b3 $5 {Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R} Rae8 16. Bb2 {1-0 Van Kampen,R (2646)-Perez Ponsa,F (2553) PRO League Stage rapid 2018 (8)} e4 $1 {this gives a strong initiative for Black} 17. Qe2 (17. dxe4 fxe4 18. Qg4 e3 $1 $17) 17... Re6 $5 $40 {[%cal Ge6g6]}) ({Quintiliano - the regroupment suggested by Vidit later is likely the safest option for White, but there too I didn't find problems for Black} 15. Nf1 {Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R} Rae8 16. Be3 (16. a4 {is once more met by} a6 $1 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Bd2 Nd5 19. a5 $2 {waste of time} Kh8 20. Rab1 $2 e4 21. dxe4 fxe4 22. Qg4 Qf7 $36 {[%cal Ye8e6,Ye6g6];0-1 Berend,E (2287)-Bellia,F (2435) Francophone-ch 5th 2017 (5) and Black had a dangerous initiative -}) 16... a6 $5 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. c4 (18. Nd2 Nd5 19. Nc4 Re6 $13) 18... Bb4 $1 19. Red1 {There is a nice way to improve the pieces now for Black} Na4 $1 20. Rab1 (20. a3 Be7 {[%cal Ye8b8]} 21. b3 $2 Nb2 $19 {[%csl Rd3]}) 20... f4 $1 21. Bd2 a5 22. Bxb4 (22. a3 Bxd2 23. Nxd2 Rb8 {[%csl Yb2] wins the pawn}) 22... axb4 23. Nd2 Nc5 $11 {and Black is at least OK}) 15... a6 {Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R: '!'} 16. Bxc6 bxc6 {White has managed to weaken Black's queenside pawn structure a bit, but this has come at the cost of space in the centre and piece activity for Black.} 17. c4 {Somehow I didn't like White mixing up a4 and c4. Maybe slow regrouping with f1 d2 is the way to play the position Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R: 'Somehow I didn't like White mixing up a4 and c4. Maybe slow regrouping with f1 d2 is the way to play the position. /Quintiliano - This committal decision by Wey Yi can be explained by the fact that usually, when White exchanges on c6, he continues with c3-c4 in order to deprive the knight of coming back to the centre via d5. Still, the inclusion of a2-a4 in this case only helps Black.'} ({Quintiliano -} 17. Bd2 $2 {Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R} e4 $1 {is still good for Black}) ({Quintiliano -} 17. Nf1 {Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R} Rae8 18. a5 Nd5 19. Bd2 Re6 $1 {This seems again easier for Black, he has space and promising ideas on the kingside, like e5-e4, f5-f4 or e6-g6. White does not have a clear plan and should be constantly aware of these threats}) 17... Rab8 $1 {The appropriate place for the rook! I felt quite comfortable at this point.  Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R: 'The appropriate place for the rook! I felt quite comfortable at this point. /Quintiliano - I found this move very impressive. It shows a profound understanding of the changes provoked by a2-a4 in this position. With the pawn still on a2, this move would be just useless, but now White has no easy way to face the pressure in the b-file, thus making his development more difficult.  '} 18. a5 Nc8 19. c5 {Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R: '!?' Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R: 'Quintiliano -' Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R: 'Wey Yi realizes he must do something to change the course of the game, and quickly.'} ({Quintiliano -} 19. Rb1 {Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R} c5 20. Nf1 Ne7 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Ye7c6] is simply pleasant for Black}) 19... Bxc5 20. Rxe5 Bd4 21. Re1 (21. Rxf5 {fails to} Ne7 22. Rf4 Ng6 $1 $17) 21... Nd6 {Black is in control. However, Black's position is not without its weaknesses, especially the queenside pawn formation. In this position, White needs to find the precise way to play against these pawn weaknesses.} 22. Ne2 $6 {This move cramps White's position and uncoordinates his pieces.} (22. Qd1 $142 $1 Rfe8 (22... Bxb2 23. Bxb2 Rxb2 24. Qc1 Rb5 25. Ne2 {[%csl Ra6,Rc6,Rc7]}) (22... f4 23. Ne2 Bxb2 24. Bxb2 Rxb2 25. Nd4 {[%csl Ra6,Rc6,Rc7]}) 23. Rxe8+ Rxe8 24. Ne2 Bf6 25. Be3 Nb5 {with an interesting and complicated position.}) 22... Rfe8 {The point. White's pieces get into a tangle now, but his problems can be solved if the queen could somehow get to d1.} 23. Bf4 $2 {I was very surprised to see this move. White loses a pawn for no compensation.} (23. Rd1 Nb5 $15) (23. Rb1 $142 Nf7 24. Rd1 Bf6 25. d4 Qd5 $15 {[%csl Ra5]}) 23... Bxb2 24. Rab1 Nb5 $1 {Black is just a pawn up and controls the important squares. White is going nowhere in the pursuit to counter-attack against Black's weak pawns.} 25. Ng3 Bc3 26. Rxe8+ Rxe8 27. Be3 g6 28. Qd1 {I thought for more than half hour in this position. As Kramnik once said, if you think for more than 20mins in a position you usually end up playing a bad move :) Vidit,S/Quintiliano,R: 'I thought for more than half hour in this position. As Kramnik once said, if you think for more than 20 mins in a position you usually end up playing a bad move :)'} Bxa5 (28... f4 {doesn't work because of} 29. Qb3+) ({I was also considering} 28... Qd5 29. Ne2 Bxa5 30. Ra1 Bb6 31. Bxb6 cxb6 32. Rxa6 {But this didn't look that easy to convert}) 29. Ra1 Bb6 $2 {A bad move. Luckily it wasn't punished.} (29... f4 $142 {I saw this but I misevaluated the position with} 30. Bxf4 (30. Rxa5 fxe3 31. Qb3+ Qd5 32. Qxd5+ cxd5 $19) 30... Re1+ 31. Qxe1 Bxe1 32. Rxe1 Nc3 {but Black should be winning here as it isn't easy to stop the a-pawn.}) 30. Bxb6 cxb6 31. Rxa6 f4 32. Ne2 (32. Nf1 Nd4 33. Rxb6 {The position looks menacing, but amazingly, White still manages to hold this position.} f3 34. Ng3 Ne2+ 35. Kh2 $1 fxg2 36. Qb3+) 32... f3 33. Nf4 $2 {A terrible square for the knight. I wasn't sure how good Black's position is after g3.} (33. Ng3 Nd4 (33... fxg2 34. Qb3+ Kh8 35. Qb2+ Qd4 36. Qxd4+ Nxd4 37. Rxb6 $11) 34. Rxb6 h5 {was my original plan. Although it looks a bit scary, with a few accurate moves White holds the balance:} 35. Qb1 Ne2+ 36. Kh2 $1 $11) 33... Nd4 34. Ra1 Rf8 {With the score of 3-1 we managed to defeat our main rivals, China! After this we won all our remaining games and secured the gold medal again after a wait of 7 years! :)} 0-1


