{Before this game I had 6/8 and I needed a win to score a decent place. The good thing about Dubai open was that even the final round began at 17:30! So unlike the last rounds in other opens I felt quite fresh and ready to fight!  Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Before this game I had 6/8 and I needed a win to score a decent place. The good thing about Dubai open was that even the final round began at 17:30! So unlike the last rounds in other opens I felt quite fresh and ready to fight! ''} 1. Nf3 {Postny,Evgeny Postny,Evgeny Postny,Evgeny Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Vidit,S''} Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. a3 Bc5 7. Nb3 Bb6 {A relatively new move in the a3 system. The direct approach was pioneered by Sutovsky. This move prepares for direct confrontation in the centre with d5. Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'A relatively new move in the a3 system. The direct approach was pioneered by Sutovsky. This move prepares for direct confrontation in the centre with d5.''} (7... Be7 {Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi'} 8. e4 O-O 9. Be2 b6 10. O-O {was the way the games used to go previously here.}) 8. Bf4 (8. c5 {Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi' was tried by Laznicka, impeding Black's d5-break} Bc7 9. Bg5 b6 10. e3 h6 (10... bxc5 11. Nxc5 Be5 12. Rc1 Qa5 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 (13... gxf6) 14. N5e4 Rb8) 11. Bh4 Be5 12. Rc1 Rb8 $132) (8. e4 {Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi' doesn't exactly prevent ...d5.} O-O (8... d5 {is also possible} 9. exd5 exd5 10. c5 (10. cxd5 Ng4 11. Be3 Nxe3 12. fxe3 Ne5 13. Bb5+ Bd7 14. Qh5 O-O 15. Bxd7 Nxd7 16. O-O-O Bxe3+ 17. Kb1 $132) 10... Bc7 11. Be2 O-O 12. Be3 Be5 $11 {½-½ (41) Kovalyov,A (2616)-Caruana,F (2808) Baku 2015}) 9. Be2 d5 10. cxd5 exd5 11. exd5 Ne7 12. Bf3 Nexd5 $1 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Qxd5 Qe8+ 15. Be2 Bg4 16. Be3 Bxe2 17. Kxe2 Rd8 $11) 8... d5 9. e3 (9. cxd5 $6 {Postny,Evgeny} Nxd5 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. e3) 9... O-O (9... d4 $2 {Postny,Evgeny} 10. exd4 Nxd4 11. Nxd4 Bxd4 12. Nb5 Bxb2 $6 (12... e5 13. Nxd4 exf4 14. Qe2+ Qe7 15. O-O-O {and it will be a game for two results, White's pawn majority on the queenside is a serious factor.}) 13. Nc7+ (13. Bd6 Bxa1 14. Qxa1 {was also very promising for White.}) 13... Ke7 14. Qb3 e5 15. Qxb2 Qxc7 16. Bxe5 Qb6 17. O-O-O $16 {½-½ (40) Lenic,L (2637)-Sutovsky,E (2700) Plovdiv 2012}) 10. Be2 (10. cxd5 {Postny,Evgeny} Nxd5 11. Nxd5 exd5 {Postny,Evgeny: 'would transpose to the game Antoniewski-Navara, mentioned below.'} 12. Bd3 d4 (12... Qf6 13. Qc2 h6 14. O-O Be6 15. Nc5 Nd4 16. exd4 Qxf4 $11 {0-1 (45) Skalkotas,N (2114)-Lekic,D (2374) Aghios Kirykos 2016}) 13. exd4 Re8+ 14. Be3 Nxd4 15. O-O Nxb3 16. Qxb3 Bxe3 17. fxe3 Be6 18. Bc4 Bxc4 19. Qxc4 Qe7 $15 {½-½ (42) Antoniewski,R (2532)-Navara,D (2744) Poland 2016}) 10... h6 {A useful move to get in. I can sometimes go e5-d4 without fearing g5.  Postny,Evgeny: 'A useful prophylactic move. Black wants to play e6-e5, meanwhile robbingWhite's bishop of the g5-square.' Postny,Evgeny: 'A useful prophylactic move. Black wants to play e6-e5, meanwhile robbingWhite's bishop of the g5-square. Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'A useful move to get in. I can sometimes go e5-d4 without fearing g5. ''} (10... dxc4 {Postny,Evgeny} 11. Bxc4 Na5 12. Nxa5 Bxa5 13. b4 Bc7 14. Qxd8 Bxd8 15. O-O-O Bd7 16. Kb2 a6 17. Bd6 Re8 18. f3 Rc8 19. Bb3 $14 {1-0 (60) Mareco,S (2625)-Nihal,S (2351) Stockholm 2016}) (10... d4 $6 {Postny,Evgeny} 11. exd4 Nxd4 12. O-O h6 13. Be5 Nxb3 14. Qxb3 Bc7 15. Rad1 Qe7 16. Bxc7 Qxc7 17. Nb5 $14 {0-1 (66) Tan,Z (2495)-Muzychuk,M (2545) Chengdu 2016}) (10... e5 $6 {Postny,Evgeny} 11. Bg5 d4 12. Nd5 Be6 13. e4 {and Back's structure on the kingside will be permanently damaged.}) 11. Bg3 {Postny,Evgeny: 'Otherwise Black will comfortably push e6-e5, followed by d5-d4.'} dxc4 12. Bxc4 (12. Nd2 {Postny,Evgeny} Na5 13. Nxc4 Nxc4 14. Bxc4 {and here Black can choose either to play ...d7 immediately, or to swap queens first. In both cases the position is equal.}) 12... Bd7 {Black has emerged out of the opening phase with no problems. But the nature of the position got me worried. It was the last round and I had to win in order to end the tournament with a decent place.  Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Black has emerged out of the opening phase with no problems. But the nature of the position got me worried. It was the last round and I had to win in order to end the tournament with a decent place. ''} 13. O-O Na5 14. Nxa5 (14. Be2 {Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi' I was more worried about this move, but Black should be totally fine after} Rc8 15. Nd2 Bc7 $11) 14... Bxa5 15. Rc1 $6 {Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '?!'' This move doesn't exactly set Black any problems and passes over the initiative. Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'This move doesn't exactly set Black any problems and passes over the initiative.''} (15. Be5 {Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi'} Rc8 16. Bxf6 (16. Be2 Bc6 $11) 16... Qxf6 17. Qxd7 Bxc3 18. bxc3 Rxc4 $11) (15. Bd6 {Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi' it is important to provoke Black's rook to e8 to set some problems.} Re8 16. Be5 Bxc3 (16... Bc6 17. b4 Bc7 18. Qxd8 Bxd8 19. b5 $36) (16... Rc8 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. Qxd7 {[%csl Re8] the point of provoking ...e8.}) 17. Bxc3 Rc8 18. Bxf6 (18. Ba2 Ne4 19. Be5 Bb5 $11) 18... gxf6 {is just equal anyway, but d6 was probably White's most promising try.}) (15. b4 {Postny,Evgeny} Bc7 16. Be2 Rc8 17. Rc1 Bxg3 18. hxg3 Qb6 $11 {½-½ (30) Deac,B (2501)-Banusz,T (2621) Zalakaros 2016}) 15... Rc8 16. Qe2 Bxc3 17. Rxc3 Ne4 18. Rcc1 Nxg3 19. hxg3 {After a lot of exchanges the position looks very dull. It should be completely equal, but White still needs to play a few decent moves. Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'After a lot of exchanges the position looks very dull. It should be completely equal, but White still needs to play a few decent moves.''} Qb6 {Postny,Evgeny: 'Black equalised easily and in the forthcoming positional battle even managed to prevail. '} 20. b3 $6 {Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '?!'' Although this doesn't change the equilibrium, fixing the pawns on light squares doesn't look right. Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Although this doesn't change the equilibrium, fixing the pawns on light squares doesn't look right.''} (20. Rc3 {Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi'} Rc7 21. Rfc1 Rfc8 22. Qd2 $11 {looked like the most simple and straightforward way.}) 20... Rc7 21. Rfd1 (21. Rcd1 {Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi' I couldn't find a way to pose White problems if White just moves the rook from the c-file. The position is too symmetrical for any tricks.}) 21... Rfc8 22. Qb2 $4 {Postny,Evgeny: '?' '?' '?' Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '??'' This move just loses a pawn directly. Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'This move just loses a pawn directly.''} (22. Rd4 {Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi'} Bb5 23. Qd3 {just keeps things equal.}) 22... Ba4 {Postny,Evgeny: '!' '!' '!'} 23. Rb1 (23. Be2 {Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi'} Qxb3 24. Qxb3 Bxb3 25. Rd8+ Rxd8 26. Rxc7 Bd5 $17) (23. Bxe6 {Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi'} fxe6 24. Rxc7 Rxc7 25. Rd8+ Kh7 26. Qb1+ g6 27. Qa1 Rg7 $1 $19) 23... Rxc4 24. bxa4 Qxb2 25. Rxb2 R8c7 26. Rb4 Rc3 27. Ra1 b6 {Black has a clear advantage now. One of the a-pawns is doomed to fall, and White doesn't have a completely smooth pawn structure on the kingside either.  Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Black has a clear advantage now. One of the a-pawns is doomed to fall, and White doesn't have a completely smooth pawn structure on the kingside either. ''} 28. g4 Kf8 29. Kh2 Ke7 30. Kg3 R7c5 {Not allowing any mess with a5. My plan was to bring the king to the queenside and attack one of the a-pawns with the rooks. White's pieces are too passive for any counterplay.  Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Not allowing any mess with a5. My plan was to bring the king to the queenside and attack one of the a-pawns with the rooks. White's pieces are too passive for any counterplay. ''} 31. Kf3 Rd5 32. Rb5 Rc4 33. Rb4 (33. Rxd5 {Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi'} exd5 34. a5 b5 35. Rb1 a6 $19) 33... Rc3 34. Ra2 (34. Rb5 Kd6 {Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi' was my intention.}) 34... Kd6 35. Rf4 f6 36. Rb4 Kc6 37. Re4 Kd6 38. Rb4 Kc6 39. Re4 e5 40. Rb4 Rd4 (40... Rdc5 {Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi' is probably cleaner, but during the game it looked simpler to stop e4-f5.}) 41. a5 (41. Ke2 {Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi' might've put up a more stubborn defence, but I don't think it would change the evaluation of the position by much.} Rdc4 42. Kd2 Rxb4 43. axb4 Rc4 44. b5+ Kc5 45. f3 Kb4 46. Kd3 e4+ (46... Rc3+ 47. Ke4 Ra3 48. Rc2 Rxa4) 47. fxe4 Rc3+ 48. Ke2 Ra3 49. Rb2+ Ka5 $19 {[%csl Ga7,Rb5,Gb6][%cal Ga3a4,Ga4b4] would eventually win.}) 41... b5 42. Rab2 a6 43. Ke2 Rd5 44. a4 Ra3 45. axb5+ axb5 46. Kf3 Rxa5 {The rest is pretty easy.  Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'The rest is pretty easy. ''} 47. R4b3 Ra4 48. Rc3+ Rc5 49. Rcb3 Ra8 50. Rd2 Rc4 51. Rdb2 Rb8 52. Ra3 b4 53. Ra6+ Rb6 54. Ra8 Rb7 55. Rd8 Kb5 56. Ra8 Rc3 57. Ke2 b3 58. Rb1 Kb4 59. Rb2 Rc5 60. Kd3 Rd7+ 61. Ke4 Kc3 62. Re2 Rd2 63. Re1 Rxf2 64. Rd8 b2 65. g5 Rc4+ {After an unexpected Round 6 loss with White I scored 3/3 in the end with a decent shared 2nd place. It was nice to end the tournament on a positive note and also to break into the top 100 :) Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'After an unexpected Round 6 loss with White I scored 3/3 in the end with a decent shared 2nd place. It was nice to end the tournament on a positive note and also to break into the top 100 :)''} (65... f5# {Postny,Evgeny: 'Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi' was a bit prettier? ;)}) 0-1


