{[%evp 0,97,58,32,75,55,67,59,72,34,8,2,18,20,12,12,-6,-1,23,3,46,4,11,24,24,-4,50,71,69,27,26,23,25,34,42,28,69,56,80,27,81,78,94,107,139,112,112,100,100,55,64,64,66,71,85,98,104,109,145,141,162,121,107,130,130,146,146,144,143,146,153,148,148,96,103,103,105,92,94,87,110,131,141,141,135,134,134,169,191,201,201,201,259,288,313,259,309,407,719,553]} {This game occurred in the 4th round of the 2016 World Rapid Championships that Vassily won. It's even a greater accomplishment to win such an event with the World Champion in the field! Among other superb games by Ivanchuk in this event, this particular one impresses me for his pressure play in simple positions, and accurate judgment of the resulting positions.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 $5 {Back then this trendy "Endgame Variation" against the Caro-Kann was not so well-known and studied which is good against a theoretically prepared opponent like Vidit. Ivanchuk is still showing us his originality and creativity in the opening!} dxe4 4. dxe4 Qxd1+ 5. Kxd1 Bg4 6. Be3 ({Recently, the other bishop has been preferred by GMs in practice:} 6. Be2 Nd7 7. Ne1 Bxe2+ 8. Kxe2 Ngf6 9. f3 O-O-O (9... g6 10. Nd3 Bg7 11. a4 O-O 12. Be3 Rfd8 13. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Ga4a5,Gg2g4,Gh2h4,Gc2c3] with a more pleasant ending for White.}) 10. Be3 e6 11. Nd3 Bd6 12. Nd2 Kb8 (12... Ne5 $2 13. Bxa7 $18 {1-0 (24) Chigaev,M (2631)-Berkovich,M (2326) Lichess.org INT 2021}) 13. Nc4 Bc7 14. a4 $14 {with a better structure and piece placement for White.}) 6... Nd7 7. Nbd2 e5 8. Bc4 ({In the same year, the only other game here went:} 8. Bd3 Bc5 9. Ke2 Bxe3 10. Kxe3 f6 11. Nc4 Ke7 12. Na5 Rb8 13. b4 Kd6 14. Nd2 $1 Kc7 15. f3 Bh5 (15... Be6 16. Bc4 Nf8 17. Nab3 {[%cal Ga2a4,Gb3c5,Ga4a5]}) 16. a4 {1-0 (72) Danielsen,H (2481)-Nasshan,D (2321) Boeblingen 2016, with nagging pressure on the queenside.}) 8... Bc5 9. Ke2 Bxe3 10. Kxe3 Ngf6 11. h3 ({It is also worth considering manoeuvring the knight to d3 which I have no doubt also crossed Vassily's mind.} 11. Ne1 $5 Ke7 12. Nd3 Ne8 {but maybe he didn't see anything special if Black tries the same! Let's check it:} 13. f3 Be6 14. Bxe6 Kxe6 15. a4 a5 16. g4 Nd6 17. h4 f6 {The engine is giving a slight edge probably due to the space on the kingside but I think it's simply symbolic as Black should be able to hold.}) 11... Bxf3 $1 (11... Bh5 {is a positional mistake as the bishop will be cut off from the action.} 12. g4 $1 Bg6 {Now at least White will have a better version of the lines examined earlier. In fact, it's even worse for Black as the engine points out a strong dynamic idea:} 13. Bd3 $1 {planning to hit e5 quickly.} Ke7 (13... Ng8 14. Nc4 f6 15. h4 $1 (15. Nd6+ $6 Ke7 16. Nxb7 a5) 15... h5 (15... h6 16. h5 Bf7 17. Nd6+ Ke7 18. Nxb7 a5 19. Nh4 {[%csl Rd6,Rf5]}) 16. Rhg1 $36) 14. Nc4 Ke6 15. Rad1 Rad8 16. Rhg1 $1 Ne8 17. Be2 f6 18. Nh4 Ke7 19. Na5 {[%cal Gg4g5]} Rb8 20. g5 $1 $40 {with strong pressure on all fronts of the board.}) 12. Nxf3 Ke7 13. Rhd1 {While the position simply looks equal and all engines would give 0.00, Black still has not achieved full equality in practical play due to one problem: the pressure on e5 doesn't allow him to improve his knights.} Nb6 $2 {Vidit tries to solve problems using a little tactic.} ({Simple development of either rook should hold the balance.} 13... Rhd8 14. a4 a5 {but there is the question of how move the knights as the pressure on e5 is quite annoying...} 15. Bb3 $5 Nc5 (15... Ne8 $2 16. Rxd7+ $1 Rxd7 17. Nxe5 Rdd8 18. Nxf7 Rd7 19. f4 $16) 16. Nxe5 Nfxe4 17. Bxf7 Nd6 18. Bh5 {White wins a pawn.}) (13... Rad8 $1 {seems more accurate} 14. a4 a5 15. Rd3 Rhe8 16. Rad1 (16. Bb3 Nc5) 16... Nb6 17. Nxe5 (17. Bb3 $11) 17... Nfd7 {now this idea works.}) 14. Nxe5 Nfd7 {This is the tactical idea that Black was counting on. However, not all tactics are good! And it's here that Ivanchuk shows his experience and skill in evaluating the resulting positions.} 15. Rxd7+ $1 Nxd7 16. Nxf7 Rhf8 17. Ng5 {[#] Let's take stock. For the exchange, White has 2 connected pawns, active minor pieces, and a clear plan to slowly roll down the pawns, whereas Black's rooks can only wait on the baseline. Therefore, Black's tactical idea has backfired and White is better.} b5 18. Bb3 a5 {It's logical for Black to quickly create counterplay and disturb White's rhythm.} 19. a3 Ne5 $2 {the second mistake. It has the idea of creating counterplay with a future c4, b8, a4/b4 but it's a bit too slow.} ({More natural and effective is} 19... Nc5 {which covers e6} 20. Ba2 b4 $1 (20... h6 21. Nf3 b4 22. Nd4) 21. Bc4 {and now it's important to keep disrupting White} ({To keep the advantage, the engine says that it's better to ignore Black's queenside play but it doesn't look as clear to the human eyes:} 21. f4 Rfb8 22. Nf3 b3 (22... Na4 23. Ne5) 23. cxb3 Nxb3 24. Rb1 a4 25. Ne5 Rb6 $14 {I think White needs to play some precise moves at some point to increase any real advantage here.}) 21... Na4 $1 22. b3 Nb2 $1 23. Be2 a4 $132) 20. Ne6 $1 (20. Nxh7 $2 {gives Black time to demonstrate his idea:} Rfb8 21. f4 Nc4+ 22. Bxc4 bxc4 23. Rb1 Rb5 $1 (23... Ra7 24. Kd4 Rab7 25. Kc3) 24. Kd4 c3 $1 {the point} 25. Kxc3 Rc5+ 26. Kd3 Rd8+ 27. Ke3 Rxc2 {and clearly White let things out of control.}) 20... Rfb8 21. Nxg7 a4 22. Nf5+ Kf6 23. f4 $1 {I like this counter-attacking move as it defuses Black's initiative.} ({The engine's top choice is a bit abstract to me:} 23. Ba2 Nc4+ 24. Kf4 Rd8 {I think White still has to be careful with Black's rooks flying around.} (24... Nxb2 25. g4 Nc4 (25... b4 26. axb4 Rxb4 27. g5+ Kg6 28. h4 {a mating net is forming around the black king.}))) 23... axb3 24. fxe5+ Kxe5 25. cxb3 c5 26. Rc1 c4 27. Nd4 $1 {A classy move, which puts out the fire in Black's counterplay.} Rc8 28. b4 $18 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gg2g4,Gh3h4,Gg4g5,Gd4f3]} c3 {A sign of desperation which is normal in rapid play.  The rest of the game doesn't need much commentary as both players were in mutual time trouble where errors are bound to happen. There was only one lapse from Ivanchuk, still it's impossible to defend such an ending in short time controls!} 29. bxc3 Rxa3 30. Nxb5 Ra2 31. Rf1 $1 {Giving back some material to push back enemy pieces and gain piece harmony!} (31. g4 $2 Rh2 {allows Black to cause great confusion.}) 31... Rxg2 32. Rf5+ Ke6 33. Rh5 Rg7 34. Nd4+ Kf6 35. Rf5+ Ke7 36. Kd3 $6 (36. Ne2 $1 Rf7 {And many roads lead to Rome from here.} 37. Rh5 $18 {[%cal Gb4b5,Ge4e5]} (37. Rxf7+ Kxf7 38. Kd4 Rd8+ 39. Kc5 Re8 40. b5 Rxe4 41. Nd4 $18)) 36... Rg3+ 37. Rf3 Rxf3+ 38. Nxf3 Rg8 (38... Rd8+ $1 {can give Black some holding chances.} 39. Kc4 (39. Ke3 Rc8) (39. Nd4 Kd6) 39... Rc8+ 40. Kb3 Kd6) 39. h4 Rg3 40. Ke3 Rg4 41. c4 h5 42. c5 Kd8 43. b5 Kc7 44. e5 {Just watch these pawns go!} Rc4 45. Nd4 {A nice small tactic to support the pawns.} Rc3+ 46. Ke4 Rh3 47. Nf5 Rb3 48. b6+ Kb7 49. e6 {Such rapid play by Ivanchuk reminds us all of what a skillful and dangerous player he is in various situations!} 1-0


