{[%evp 0,131,29,-19,26,19,12,12,12,14,31,30,29,30,39,6,1,-16,-23,-23,-47,-47,-47,-46,-30,-30,-30,-61,-55,-48,-48,-53,-53,-53,-53,-53,-34,-124,-86,-86,-63,-71,-71,-71,-67,-59,-73,-52,-54,-59,-27,-33,-33,-57,-63,-55,-38,-38,-62,-31,0,0,92,98,121,71,98,79,69,69,69,70,58,58,90,99,99,99,131,91,193,208,224,224,219,217,219,224,238,223,244,217,239,227,258,286,275,275,275,275,287,287,287,287,300,262,300,292,292,268,350,123,123,123,126,134,132,128,130,127,207,188,408,399,833,972,1229,1237,1292,1314,1334,1431,1576,1720] I had lost the previous game due to a stupid blunder, so I was hoping to fix my mistake today! Also previously I had never won in a must-win situation in the World Cup before, so I was looking forward to changing my destiny!!} 1. c4 {This looked like an interesting choice!} ({Of course, people might have expected to see my recent favorite with} 1. b3) 1... c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e5 5. d4 exd4 6. exd4 d5 {I wasn't expecting this, now I realized that high chances for the game to end in a draw :)!} 7. Bg5 $5 {[%cal Gg5d8] I managed to pull myself together and found a line where I couldn't see any clear way to forced equality!} cxd4 8. Nxd5 (8. Bxf6 {was another line, But I didn't like} Qxf6 9. Nxd5 Bb4+ $1 {An important check, not wasting time retreating the queen.} 10. Nxb4 Nxb4 11. Be2 O-O {with an equal game for Black and I felt my chances to win in this position were rather slim due to Black's central passed pawn.}) 8... Be6 {Greedy VD :), I couldn't believe that he wanted to win the d5-pawn :).} 9. Qb3 {[%cal Gb3d5] I wanted to fight for my equal rights :).} Bxd5 10. cxd5 Bb4+ (10... Qxd5 {looked very interesting and it was a complete mess after} 11. Qxb7 Bb4+ 12. Kd1 O-O 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Rc1 {I wasn't sure who was better here, but at least my king was kind of safe on d1 for the time being.}) 11. Kd1 {[%csl Gd1] I felt the king is doing fine on d1, due to the shelter provided by the d4-pawn.} Qxd5 12. Bc4 Qd7 13. Bb5 $5 {[%csl Yb4][%cal Gh1e1] The computer didn't like this decision, but to be honest I don't think it understood my play for quite a while :) in this game!} Qd6 14. a3 {Trying to remove the bishop from the a5-e1 diagonal, so that I can prepare Re1.} Ba5 15. Bxf6 ({My first intention was} 15. Qa4 {to continue to bully the bishop but...} O-O $1 16. Bxf6 (16. Bxc6 Qxc6 17. Qxa5 Rac8 {also looks bad.}) 16... Qxf6 17. Bxc6 Qxc6 18. Qxa5 Rac8 {looked horrible for me with a winning attack for Black.}) 15... gxf6 (15... Qxf6 {was safer maybe} 16. Bxc6+ $1 Qxc6 (16... bxc6 17. Qa4 $1 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Ga4a5,Gh1e1]} O-O 18. Qxa5 {Now the situation is completely different, but still I wasn't sure and wanted to avoid this if possible :).}) 17. Rc1 {[%csl Ya4,Yc6][%cal Gb3a4] Black queen can't stop Qa4 anymore!}) 16. Qa4 {[%cal Ga4a5,Ga4e8,Gh1e1] GO BACK SIMON!} Bb6 17. Rc1 ({My original intention was} 17. Re1+ {but then thought that Black can go} Kd8 $1 {Just like my king which is very safe thanks to the d-pawn as a shelter...Black can also do the same :)!} 18. Rc1 Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c7,Gd8b8] followed by Rc7 and Kc8 if needed!}) 17... Rc8 18. Kc2 $3 {[%cal Ge8d8,Gc2b1] I was very proud of this move! My main concern was the king's safety and If I can get it to safety then I can play for attack without any concern!} O-O {I was happy to see this, as I felt the king would be nicely placed on d8! On the kingside, I can create some play against his majesty!} 19. Kb1 {Now that my king is safe, it is time to begin the onslaught!} Ne5 20. Nxe5 fxe5 21. Bd3 {I have a clear target... The Black king!!} Rxc1+ {I was happy to see this, as I felt it was going to take some effort to win the fight for the key open file!} 22. Rxc1 f5 {This I felt weakens his king even more!} 23. f3 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gf3e4] Firmly stopping the pawn advance and Black is left with too many weaknesses to defend.} Kh8 24. Qb5 $1 {[%cal Rb5b7,Gb5e5,Gc1e1] A very nice preparing the deadly Re1 and also trying to provoke a6!} Qe7 (24... a6 25. Qb3 {[%csl Rb6,Rb7][%cal Gb3b7] Now the b6-bishop will constantly need the supervision of the queen!}) 25. Qd5 $1 {Continuing the act of provocation, I guess VD didn't understand what I was up to... (In my defence I also didn't know myself :), neither does the computer :)).} ({I rejected} 25. Re1 {due to} Bc5 $1 {I didn't want to allow the bishop to come back! (of course stupid comp doesn't understand this simple concept and recommends 25.Re1!)}) 25... Rd8 26. Qb3 e4 27. fxe4 fxe4 28. Re1 {Forcing e3!} e3 29. Rf1 $1 {[%cal Gf1f7] Finally the plan is clear, I am going to play for domination and Black's pawns are useless :)!} Kg7 (29... Rf8 30. Rxf8+ Qxf8 31. Qe6 {Surprisingly Black is going to find out that the attack is very difficult to defend against...while the bishop and the pawns are silent spectators!}) 30. Qd1 $1 {[%cal Gd1g4,Gg4h5] The queen is coming to h5 or g4 with a lot of destructive power!} e2 {Panic! This only prolongs the inevitable :)!} 31. Bxe2 Rf8 32. Rh1 $3 {[%csl Gh1][%cal Ge2d3] Keeping the rooks at any cost!! I think VD didn't expect this epic rook move which keeps the tension and now things are hopeless for Black!} (32. Rxf8 Kxf8 {The king is a bit safer here than on h8 still, it should be very good for white...But I felt the game continuation was stronger!}) 32... Kh8 33. Bd3 {Preparing Re1, if the rook joins the fight then it's over!} Ba5 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Gd1h5] Desperately trying to stop the rook from getting activated!} 34. Qa4 Bb6 35. Rc1 {One step at a time! c1 is better than h1.} Qe3 36. Rd1 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Gd1d3] Now the queen has to retreat to stop Qd7 penetration.} Qe6 {An error allowing me to get what I wanted!} (36... Qe7 {[%cal Ge7b4] was the way to fight!}) 37. Qb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4f8,Gd1e1] Attacking the rook and preparing Re1!} Re8 38. Rf1 {Now f-file is equally destructive!} Qe7 39. Qb5 $1 {[%cal Gb5h5] Preparing to go Qh5 and Rf7.} Bc5 40. Qb3 {[%csl Rb7] This was the idea behind Qb5, now Rf8 loses the b7-pawn!} Rf8 41. Rxf8+ Qxf8 42. Qxb7 {Channeling Greedy VD against the Master :)!} Qe7 43. Qc8+ Kg7 44. Qf5 {Keeping the king locked in!} Kh8 45. g4 {Time to improve the pawn structure and create a mating net around the black king!} Bd6 46. g5 {[%csl Rh8]} Bxh2 47. Qc8+ Kg7 48. Qh3 $1 {[%cal Gh3h7,Gh3h2] A cute retreat winning the h7-pawn.} Be5 49. Qxh7+ Kf8 {I already saw that the bishop endgame was winning, but wanted to get it in the most ideal scenario and also felt maybe I can win keeping the queens on the board!} 50. Qf5+ Ke8 51. g6 Kd8 52. Qe4 Kc7 53. Qd5 {[%csl Gd5] A dominating post for the queen!} Bg7 54. Be4 Qd7 55. Qxd7+ Kxd7 56. b4 $1 {I just wanted to get this move in to avoid any saving chances for Black!} Ke6 57. Kc2 {[%csl Yd4,Gg6][%cal Ge4g6,Ge4d3] The endgame is easily winning due to the same diagonal principle where the bishop supports the pawn and also stops the enemy passed pawn!} Bh6 (57... Ke5 58. Bd3 Kf4 59. Kb3 Ke3 60. Kc4 {[%cal Gb4b8] and the queenside pawn shall promote :)!}) 58. Kb3 {I just had to make sure not to blunder like in the first game :)!} Bc1 59. Bd3 Kf6 60. a4 Kg7 61. Kc4 Bd2 62. Kb5 Be1 63. Ka6 Bxb4 64. Kxa7 Ba5 65. Ka6 {I will win the bishop for the a-pawn and then collect the d4-pawn leading to a win.} Bc7 66. Kb5 {I was very happy to pull off this epic win taking the match into tiebreaks! Winning in a must-win situation always gives you special happiness and also I was proud of the level I showed in this game :)!} 1-0


