{[%evp 0,111,19,29,23,12,37,14,-4,4,9,5,-21,-26,-4,-67,-22,-41,-28,-2,-12,-35,-30,-1,36,-37,-25,-40,-26,-13,13,-18,-18,-18,-18,-15,-30,-19,-35,-47,-37,-62,4,-16,-7,-20,-20,12,-14,-49,-5,-47,-5,6,14,-36,-57,-97,-23,-23,40,45,43,21,45,-8,86,0,-1,2,22,0,0,0,1,-17,-15,0,0,0,0,0,27,21,12,39,40,42,42,16,42,43,43,0,43,35,33,540,839,934,1022,1032,1075,1092,1105,1122,1157,1281,1283,1330,1330,1300,1894,1894]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 c5 3. c4 d4 4. exd4 cxd4 5. Bd3 $5 {A reversed Schmid-Benoni! To be honest, I had never seen it.} Nc6 6. O-O Nf6 (6... g6 {went very well for Black in another game:} 7. Re1 Bg7 8. a3 a5 9. Bc2 (9. Qe2 $5 {and then c2 might be the right solution}) 9... d3 $1 10. Ba4 Nh6 $1 11. Nc3 O-O $15 {0-1 (39) Agayev,N (2350)-Stupak,K (2586) Baku AZE 2017}) 7. Bc2 Bg4 8. Ba4 Nd7 {The most solid move.} (8... e5 9. h3 (9. d3 Bd6 $132) 9... Bxf3 10. Qxf3 e4 11. Qb3 Rb8 12. d3 $36) 9. h3 Bh5 10. d3 e5 11. Re1 Be7 12. Nbd2 (12. g4 Bg6 13. Nxe5 Ndxe5 14. Rxe5 O-O {would give Black full compensation for the pawn.}) 12... O-O 13. Ne4 Qc7 14. a3 a5 15. Ng3 Bg6 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. Nxd4 exd4 18. Rxe7 Qd6 19. Re2 Nc5 {Here as well Black has more than enough compensation!} 20. Ne4 (20. Rd2 $6 a4 $17) (20. a4 $1 {in order to play Ra3, or answer Nxd3 or Bxd3 with Rd2, was perhaps what White had to do.}) 20... Nxe4 (20... Bxe4 $5 21. dxe4 Rfe8 22. f3 a4 $15) 21. dxe4 Rfe8 22. f3 a4 23. c5 Qxc5 24. Bf4 Qb6 25. Rc1 c5 (25... f5 $5 26. e5 d3+ 27. Rf2 Qd4 28. Qd2 c5 $15) 26. Rc4 f6 27. Qc1 $2 ({Some timid move like} 27. Rd2 {was better. The a4-pawn is hanging, by the way...}) 27... Ra5 $1 28. Rec2 f5 $2 (28... Bf7 $1 29. Rxc5 d3 30. Bc7 $8 (30. R2c3 Rxc5 31. Rxc5 Rc8 32. Be3 Rxc5 33. Bxc5 d2 $1 $19) 30... Rxc5 31. Bxb6 Rxc2 {would surely have brought Black the full point.}) 29. Rxc5 Rxc5 30. Rxc5 fxe4 31. fxe4 d3 32. Be3 Qe6 33. Rc7 Qxe4 34. Bd2 {Suddenly, it's unclear who is playing for a win!} h6 35. Qc5 Bf7 36. Bc3 Qg6 37. Re7 Rxe7 38. Qxe7 Kh7 39. Qe5 Be8 40. Kf2 {Unbelievably enough, Black never took a decision to swap queens. True, it was hard to see Levon's winning idea coming.} Bf7 ({But} 40... Qf6+ {was an easy draw:} 41. Qxf6 gxf6 42. Bxf6 Bf7 (42... Bc6 $5 43. g4 Kg6 44. Bc3 h5 $11) 43. Ke3 (43. b4 axb3 44. a4 Kg6 45. Bc3 Bd5 $11) 43... Bb3 44. Kxd3 Kg6 $11) 41. g4 Bb3 42. Ke3 Bc2 $2 (42... Qg5+ $11) 43. Kd2 Bb3 ({It's now too late for} 43... Qg5+ $4 44. Qxg5 hxg5 {because of} 45. b4 $3 axb3 46. Bb2 {and White wins!}) 44. Ke3 Bc2 (44... Qg5+ $1 $11) 45. Kd2 Bb3 46. Qe7 Bc2 $4 47. b4 $3 {Finally Levon has got what he wanted, and it's a masterpiece! He's going to queen one of his queenside pawns, as Black is totally paralysed on the kingside, while his bishop is stuck on c2!} axb3 (47... h5 $5 48. g5 Bb3 49. b5 Bf7 50. b6 Qf5 51. Qe5 $18) 48. Bb2 h5 49. g5 h4 50. a4 Kg8 51. a5 Kh7 52. a6 Bd1 53. Kxd1 d2 54. Qxg7+ Qxg7 55. Bxg7 Kxg7 56. Kxd2 {A tough one for Vidit!} 1-0


