{[%evp 0,51,29,27,27,27,27,-16,-16,-15,-1,21,27,3,26,21,28,28,2,12,27,27,59,40,61,63,99,89,135,61,174,174,154,34,138,126,113,134,134,49,188,183,224,173,29989,29990,29991,29992,29995,29996,29997,29998,29999,-30000]} 1. d4 {Leitao,Rafael} Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bg5 {One of Duda's weapon in blitz games. Sinking into theory would be too long, but let's see some of his victories!} Ne4 (3... e6 4. Nbd2 Be7 5. e3 O-O 6. Bd3 h6 7. Bh4 c5 8. c3 Nc6 9. O-O b6 10. Ne5 Bb7 11. f4 Nd7 12. Bg3 Rc8 13. a4 Ndb8 14. Qh5 Ba6 15. Bb5 Bb7 16. f5 Nxe5 17. Bxe5 Bg5 18. fxe6 fxe6 19. Qg6 Qe7 20. Bd3 Bxe3+ 21. Kh1 Rf5 22. g4 $18 {1-0 (30) Duda,J (2734)-Moussard,J (2608) chess24.com 2020}) (3... c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6 6. Qc1 Bf5 (6... Ne4 7. Bf4 Bf5 8. Nbd2 e6 9. Be2 Be7 $11 {was also not very convincing for White, although once more, Duda won: 1-0 (75) Duda,J (2753)-Harikrishna,P (2719) chess24.com 2020.}) 7. Nbd2 e6 8. Be2 Be7 9. Nh4 Bg6 10. O-O Rc8 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Nf3 Bd6 13. dxc5 Qxc5 14. Bf4 Bxf4 15. exf4 O-O {The position is equal, but Duda nevertheless won the game within 7 moves:} 16. Qd2 Rfd8 17. Bd3 b5 18. Rac1 a6 19. Qe2 Qb6 (19... Qd6 $5) 20. Bxg6 $1 fxg6 21. Qxe6+ Kf8 $2 (21... Kh8 22. Ne5 $40) 22. Ne5 {1-0 Duda,J (2753)-Harikrishna,P (2719) chess24.com INT 2020}) 4. Bh4 (4. Bf4 {Leitao,Rafael}) 4... Qd6 $5 (4... c5 {Leitao,Rafael: '- 12/86'} 5. e3 Nc6 6. c3 Qb6 7. Qc1 Bf5 8. Nbd2 e6 9. Be2 Rc8 10. O-O Be7 11. Bxe7 Nxe7 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. Nd2 Bg6 14. Nb3 cxd4 15. exd4 O-O $11 {Again Duda got no advantage, but he seems to love this line anyway! 0-1 (51) Duda,J (2737)-So,W (2780) chess.com 2018}) (4... h5 $5 5. Bg3 (5. h3 $5 f6 6. Nfd2 g5 7. Nxe4 dxe4 8. Bg3 $1) 5... g5 6. h3 Nxg3 7. fxg3 Qd6 8. Kf2 g4 9. hxg4 Bxg4 10. Nc3 Nc6 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Qb4 13. c3 $5 Qb6 $2 (13... Qxb2+ 14. Be2 $44) 14. Qb3 $16 {1-0 (30) Sjugirov,S (2650)-Cheparinov,I (2710) Riyadh 2017}) 5. Nbd2 Qh6 {Leitao,Rafael: '!' Leitao,Rafael: 'Diagram [#]'} 6. Qc1 {Leitao,Rafael: '!'} (6. e3 $2 {Leitao,Rafael} g5 $1 7. Nxe4 (7. Bg3 Nxg3 8. fxg3 g4 $19) 7... dxe4 8. Bxg5 Qg6 9. Nd2 Qxg5 10. Nxe4 Qg6 $19) 6... g5 $6 {Leitao,Rafael: '!?'} (6... Qh5 $5 {looks to me like better move - simply answering c1 in a funny way and preventing xe4.}) (6... Nc6 {Leitao,Rafael} 7. c3 Qh5 8. h3 f5 $13) 7. Nxe4 dxe4 8. Bxg5 Qh5 (8... Qg7 9. Nh4 $1 $146 (9. Ng1 $6 Qxd4 10. Bd2 Qb6 11. Bc3 Rg8 12. e3 Nc6 13. Ne2 Bg4 14. h3 Bxe2 15. Bxe2 Bg7 16. Bxg7 Rxg7 17. O-O O-O-O $15 {0-1 (27) Hauke,C (2295)-Schlindwein,R (2440) Germany 1996}) 9... Qxd4 10. c3 Qg7 11. g3 e5 12. Bg2 f6 13. Be3 f5 14. Bh3 Qf7 15. f3 {and Black's position is awful.}) 9. Ng1 $1 {This time the knight would do better to retreat to g1.} Bg7 (9... c5 {Leitao,Rafael}) 10. c3 c5 {Leitao,Rafael: 'N'} (10... e5 {Leitao,Rafael} 11. dxe5 Bxe5 (11... Nc6 12. g3 Nxe5 13. Bg2 f5 14. h4 Bd7 15. Nh3 $16) 12. Qe3 $16 (12. g3 $16)) 11. Bd2 $1 {Leitao,Rafael: '!?'} (11. dxc5 $5 Na6 (11... Nc6 $13 {Leitao,Rafael}) 12. Qd2 Nxc5 13. Rd1 $1 (13. O-O-O Be6 $132) 13... Be6 14. Nh3 $1 {would also be great for White.}) 11... Nc6 {Leitao,Rafael: '?!'} (11... cxd4 12. cxd4 Bxd4 $4 (12... O-O {Leitao,Rafael} 13. e3 e5 14. d5 $1 (14. dxe5 Nc6 15. Ne2 Nxe5 16. Nf4 Qh4 17. Be2 Bg4 $44) (14. Ne2 exd4 15. Nxd4 Bg4 (15... Nc6 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. Bc3 Qg6 $14) 16. Bc3 Rc8 17. Qd2 Nc6 18. Be2 Ne5 19. Bxg4 Qxg4 20. h3 Qxg2 21. O-O-O Nd3+ 22. Kb1 Qxf2 23. Rhf1 Qxd2 24. Rxd2 $14) 14... Qg6 (14... Bg4 15. Be2 Qg6 16. Bxg4 Qxg4 17. Ne2 Nd7 18. Bb4 Rfc8 19. Qd2 $16) 15. Ne2 $16) 13. Qxc8#) 12. e3 Bg4 {Otherwise 13.e2 and White is much better.} 13. Ne2 {Anyway!} O-O-O {Leitao,Rafael: 'Diagram [#]'} (13... O-O {[%cal Rg1g8]}) (13... Bxe2 14. Bxe2 Qg6 15. O-O $18) 14. b4 $1 cxb4 (14... c4 $6 15. Nf4 $18 {The c4-pawn is lost.}) 15. cxb4 Kb8 16. b5 $5 {Leitao,Rafael: '!' A typical but excellent pawn sacrifice.} (16. Ng3 $5) 16... Qxb5 17. Rb1 Qd5 $8 18. Nc3 {Leitao,Rafael: ''} Qe6 (18... Qd7 19. Nxe4 $18) 19. Na4 Ka8 $2 (19... Qd6 {was better, but after} 20. Bc4 {or 20.Nc5, Black's position remains awful.}) 20. Rxb7 $1 {Now it's over.} (20. Nc5 $18 {Leitao,Rafael}) 20... Qd6 (20... Nxd4 21. Qc7 Nc2+ 22. Qxc2 Rc8 23. Nc5 $5 Rxc5 24. Rxa7+ Kxa7 25. Qxc5+ $18) 21. Nc5 Nxd4 22. Rxa7+ {Leitao,Rafael: '!'} Kxa7 23. Qa3+ Kb6 24. Qb4+ Kc6 25. Qb7+ Kxc5 26. Bb4# {Leitao,Rafael: '#' Allowing mate on the board is usually a sign of respect! What a crushing game by Artemiev.} 1-0


