1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bg5 {Long semi-condemned by theory, but as we've seen before, this version of the Torre may have been slightly underestimated.} Ne4 4. Bh4 ({Earlier in the competition Artemiev had preferred} 4. Bf4 {when it would be very interesting to know how he intended to counter} c5 $1 {- see the Archive for detailed coverage.} ({Instead, no less a game than Artemiev-Caruana, Internet (rapid) 2020, continued} 4... Bf5 5. e3 e6 6. Nbd2 Bd6 7. Nxe4 Bxe4 8. Bd3 $5 Bxf4 9. exf4 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 g6 11. h4 h5 12. O-O-O Qd6 13. Rhe1 Nc6 14. Bb5 $1 O-O-O {when the position continued to remain pretty level.})) 4... Qd6 {Vidit responds in a critical manner, but this is by no means forced, of course. See Eric's coverage for details of the alternatives.} 5. Nbd2 Qh6 6. Qc1 $1 g5 $6 ({This just doesn't really work after White's last, so Black should settle for} 6... Nxd2 7. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 8. Kxd2 {when the issue is how small (or large) is White's edge - see Yusupov-Wirthensohn, Hamburg 1991, in the Archive.}) 7. Nxe4 dxe4 8. Bxg5 Qh5 $6 (8... Qg7 {is a better try when after} 9. Nh4 $1 (9. Ng1 Qxd4 {is now fine for Black}) 9... Qxd4 10. c3 Qg7 ({Eric also looked at} 10... Qd5 $5 11. g3 Rg8 12. Be3 Nd7 13. Bg2 Nf6 {, which he thought was unclear, but after} 14. f3 $1 {the position should open to White's advantage}) 11. Be3 $1 ({Eric's suggested improvement over} 11. Qd2 $6 {which is likely too slow, as shown in the notes to Von der Loo-Nurbekoglu, correspondence 1998}) ({prospective white players might also look into} 11. g3 $5) 11... Nc6 (11... e5 $5 12. Qc2 f5 13. g3 Be7 {is probably a better try when White might go} 14. Bh3 $5 Bxh4 15. gxh4 Be6 16. f3 {when at least he has the two bishops}) 12. Qc2 f5 {I would only now improve over Eric's generally excellent analysis with} 13. g3 $5 {, and if} e5 14. Bh3 Qf6 15. O-O $1 {, since the king will be quite safe after f2-f4 or} f4 16. Bxc8 Rxc8 17. Bd2 Rg8 18. Kh1 Rd8 19. Rad1 {followed by picking up e4.}) 9. Ng1 {Back to base, but White is a clear pawn to the good.} Bg7 10. c3 c5 ({Black also suffered after} 10... e5 11. dxe5 Bxe5 12. Bf4 Nc6 {in Vlasov-Bejnerovich, St. Petersburg 1998, when} 13. g3 {would have been logical, and strong.}) 11. Bd2 ({Vidit wants his bishop safe inside his pawn chain.} 11. dxc5 $5 Nd7 12. g3 Nxc5 13. Bg2 {also looks quite effective, again so long as White quickly breaks with f2-f3.}) 11... Nc6 (11... cxd4 12. cxd4 O-O $1 13. e3 Rd8 {followed by ...e5 would at least have given Black a bit of Grünfeld-like compensation.}) 12. e3 Bg4 13. Ne2 O-O-O $2 {Vidit was far from his best in this event and here rather than trying to seize the initiative, allows White to do just that.} 14. b4 $1 cxb4 15. cxb4 Kb8 16. b5 $1 {Returning the extra pawn to obtain a strong attack. White can manage just fine without his rook no h1.} Qxb5 17. Rb1 Qd5 18. Nc3 Qe6 19. Na4 {White's pieces continue to flow to good squares.} Ka8 $2 ({Missing a straightforward tactic.} 19... Qd6 20. Nc5 Bc8 {was necessary when after} 21. Bc4 Ka8 22. Nxe4 ({or} 22. O-O e5) 22... Qg6 23. Ng3 h5 24. h4 f5 {Black would at least have been fighting, albeit two pawns down.}) 20. Rxb7 $1 Qd6 (20... Nxd4 $5 {was arguably worth a try, not that Black has anything good after} 21. Qc7 $1 {.}) 21. Nc5 {White intends Qb1 followed by Ba6. There's simply no good defence, in part because Black cannot move his knight.} Nxd4 22. Rxa7+ $1 {Finishing crisply. Mate is forced.} Kxa7 23. Qa3+ Kb6 24. Qb4+ Kc6 25. Qb7+ $1 Kxc5 26. Bb4# 1-0


