1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 d5 4. Bd3 b6 5. O-O Bb7 6. Nbd2 Bd6 {Black holds back his c-pawn for the time being.} 7. Ne5 ({Of course, there's nothing wrong with} 7. b3) ({or} 7. c4 {here, but the text is both fairly tempting and quite critical.}) 7... O-O ({Instead,} 7... Nbd7 8. f4 c5 {might be met by} 9. c3 {,} ({but notably leading Colle authority Artur Yusupov has preferred} 9. b3 {here, returning play to Colle-Zukertort waters.})) 8. f4 c5 ({A common reaction to the Stonewall at all levels is} 8... Ne4 {followed by ...f5. This was actually seen in another Yusupov game, Yusupov-Drasko, Sarajevo 1984, where} 9. c4 $1 {(White strives to undermine the intruder and to generate some pressure)} Nd7 (9... f6 {is quite critical, but after Yusupov's line} 10. cxd5 Nxd2 11. Qh5 $1 f5 12. Bxd2 Bxe5 13. fxe5 Qxd5 {I quite like White and now} 14. Qe2 {still seems very sensible, as given in a certain Starting Out work}) 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Nxe4 $1 dxe4 12. Bc4 Nf6 13. Qb3 {took aim at d5 and f7, with a pleasant edge.}) 9. c3 ({Standard, but} 9. Qf3 $5 {is more ambitious, fighting for the e4-square. Still, after} Nc6 (9... Qc8 {and ...Ba6 is a thematic alternative}) 10. c3 Rc8 11. Qh3 Ne7 $1 12. Ndf3 Ne4 {Black had absolutely no reason to complain in Abergel-Kryvoruchko, German Bundesliga 2013. I'm quite a fan of an early Qf3-h3 in both the Colle-Zukertort and the London, but it rarely seems to cut the mustard in a Stonewall formation. I guess a question one might ask is how often do you see Black's queen appear on h6 in the Dutch Stonewall?}) 9... Ne4 {By no means obligatory just yet, but Vidit can't resist invading the hole.} 10. Nxe4 ({Before Bakre White had generally moved his queen here, but} 10. Qf3 f5 {doesn't really give him a huge amount to write home about.}) 10... dxe4 11. Be2 ({A possible improvement on his game from the very previous round (clearly they're well prepared in this chess version of the IPL), where} 11. Bb5 a6 12. Be2 Qc7 13. Bd2 Nd7 14. Be1 $1 Nxe5 $1 15. fxe5 Be7 16. Bg3 Rad8 {had been pretty level, eventually drawn in Bakre-Karavade, Pune (rapid) 2014.}) 11... Nc6 12. Bd2 Qc7 13. Be1 {The standard Stonewall plan to improve the potentially bad bishop, but Black too can improve his pieces.} Ne7 $1 {The knight prepares to eye e3 as Vidit rightly doesn't fear losing the bishop-pair.} 14. Nc4 ({Going for the bishop, but had he been playing a lower-rated opponent, I suspect Bakre would have played more gently, perhaps beginning with} 14. Bf2 Nd5 15. a4 $5 {.}) 14... cxd4 15. Nxd6 Qxd6 16. cxd4 Nd5 17. Qb3 a5 18. a4 {White has managed to hold e3 and his own on the queenside, but is clearly too tied down to ever pretend to any advantage. Already a draw is looking rather likely.} f5 ({Vidit was clearly happy with a solid half as Black, but many would have been sorely tempted to try} 18... Ba6 $5 19. Bxa6 ({and not} 19. Bb5 $2 Bxb5 20. axb5 a4 $1) 19... Rxa6 20. Rc1 Raa8 21. Bd2 Rac8 {, hoping to gradually grind White down with good knight against bad bishop. I suspect Bakre would have held (Black does lack great pawn breaks and White is very solid), but the defence could have been a lengthy one.}) 19. Rc1 Rfc8 20. Bd2 Rxc1 21. Rxc1 Rc8 22. Rxc8+ Bxc8 23. Qc2 {Now White even has the c-file and after Black's next the draw becomes inevitable.} Qc7 24. Qxc7 Nxc7 (24... Nxc7 25. b4 axb4 26. Bxb4 Nd5 27. Bd2 Bd7 28. Bd1 Kf7 29. Kf2 {followed by a4-a5 will liquidate yet further.}) 1/2-1/2


