1. Nf3 {Sagar Shah/Amruta Mokal Ding Liren wants to begin with a positional game, perhaps?!} c5 2. e4 $5 {Change of plan! The Caro-Kann is avoided and Ding Liren switches to 1.e4!} d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 {Vidit works as a second of Anish Giri. Hence, it doesn't come as a surprise that he goes for the Najdorf.} 6. h3 e6 7. g4 Be7 8. g5 Nfd7 9. Be3 b5 (9... Bxg5 $2 10. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 11. Qh5+ $16 {and White is clearly better.}) 10. a3 Bb7 11. h4 Nc6 12. Rg1 {White's idea is to support the g5-pawn and prepare h5 and g6. Also he gets the rook off the long diagonal of the b7-bishop.} (12. Nxc6 {is a possibility} Bxc6 13. Qd4 O-O 14. O-O-O Rb8 15. h5 Nc5 16. h6 e5 17. Qd2 g6 18. f3 a5 19. Rg1 Qc7 20. Bxc5 dxc5 21. Nd5 Bxd5 22. exd5 Bd6 23. Rg4 Rfe8 24. Re4 $13 {with a complicated opposite coloured bishop position.}) (12. Qd2 {is the main move}) 12... Nc5 13. f3 O-O {Vidit is brave and doesn't fear the pawn storm against his king.} (13... Ne5 {is possible to delay 0-0 a bit longer} 14. Qd2 Nc4 {is not as strong because the b7-bishop is already blocking the b-file so it will be a slow process to increase pressure on b2.} 15. Bxc4 bxc4 16. O-O-O $14) 14. Qd2 {The first new move of the game.} (14. h5 Na4 15. Nxa4 bxa4 16. Nxc6 Bxc6 17. Qd2 Qc7 18. O-O-O d5 19. h6 dxe4 20. Qc3 e5 21. Bc4 g6 22. Rd7 Bxd7 23. Bxf7+ Rxf7 24. Qxc7 exf3 25. Qxd7 Bxg5 26. Qd3 Bxe3+ 27. Qxe3 Rf5 28. Qe4 Raf8 29. Qc4+ Kh8 30. Rd1 Rh5 31. Qc5 Rg8 32. Qe7 {1-0 (32) Quesada Perez,Y (2624)-Li,R (2571) Philadelphia 2017}) 14... Rb8 (14... d5 $5 {It is said that in the Sicilian if Black is able to execute the move d5, he should be doing fine.} 15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. exd5 (16. O-O-O dxe4 17. Qf2 Nd7 {double defence} 18. Nxe4 Bxe4 19. fxe4 $14 {White can claim a small edge thanks to his bishop pair.}) 16... exd5 17. O-O-O {if White tries to win the pawn, then} d4 $1 {is the saving grace!} 18. Bxd4 (18. Qxd4 Bxf3 19. Be2 Qxd4 20. Bxd4 Bxe2 21. Nxe2 $11) 18... Ne6 $1 (18... Bxf3 19. Be2 Bxe2 20. Qxe2 $16 {There are too many scattered weaknesses which cannot be taken care of by Black}) 19. Bf2 (19. f4 $4 {Trying to save the pawn would land up in disaster on the dark squares.} Qxd4 20. Qxd4 Nxd4 21. Rxd4 Bc5 $19) 19... Bxf3 $11) (14... f5 15. O-O-O $1 $14) 15. h5 (15. O-O-O {this natural move doesn't seem to be the best here because of} b4 16. axb4 Nxb4 {with immediate counter-attack by Black.}) 15... Qc7 16. Qh2 $6 (16. O-O-O b4 17. axb4 Nxb4 18. g6 {Here White is pretty quick.} Bf6 19. gxh7+ Kxh7 (19... Kh8 20. Kb1 {It is not so easy to see how Black will continue his attack on the queenside.} Ba8 21. Bg5 $1 $16 {Eliminating the key defender of Black's kingside.}) 20. Kb1 $14 {Though still complicated, White has more attacking prospects than his opponent.}) 16... Nxd4 17. Bxd4 e5 $6 {A common logical move to limit the activity of White's bishop. It also releases the pressure on the d6 weakness, and one must not forget the knight maneouvre via e6. But because White has delayed 0-0-0, Black could have taken advantage of this fact that at the moment there is no pressure on d6 by playing...f5!} (17... f5 $1 {A move which follows the simple principle - when an opponent is underdeveloped, open the centre.} 18. gxf6 (18. O-O-O fxe4 19. fxe4 Nxe4 20. Nxe4 Bxe4 {White loses a pawn for no substantial compensation.}) 18... Bxf6 {With White's 0-0-0 this would not be possible as Black would lose his d6-pawn! But here it's completely fine.} 19. Bxf6 Rxf6 20. h6 g6 21. O-O-O e5 $11 {Just like the game, but a better version, as Black has been able to get rid of his passive dark-squared bishop.}) 18. Be3 f5 {This time the move is not as well timed as the previous move, but still needed as it gives Black counterplay down the f-file.} 19. gxf6 Bxf6 20. O-O-O {It's a complicated position. How do we assess ?t. Let's try to make a simple comparison of the pieces. White's knight is excellently placed on c3 looking at the d5-square. White's bishops are also quite active. The f1-bishop can go to h3 and look at an important diagonal. On the other hand I am not so sure about Black's bishops. The f6-bishop is passive, and the b7 one is limited by the f3-e4 pawns. Black has a weakness on d6, but it is compensated for by White's weakness on f3. Overall, the position is complex, but there is no doubt that Ding Liren is better.} Ne6 21. Kb1 Nf4 (21... Nd4 $142 22. Bxd4 (22. Qg2 $1 $14) 22... exd4 23. Ne2 (23. Nd5 Bxd5 24. exd5 Be5 $11) 23... Be5 24. Qg2 d5 $132 {and the position opens up for Black's bishop pair.}) 22. Bh3 Bc6 (22... Nxh3 23. Qxh3 $16) 23. Bxf4 $5 {This exchange is quite counter-intuitive as it opens up the bishop on f6 and places it on a powerful diagonal. However, concretely White is also able to get his light-squared bishop activated. Ding Liren assessed that as an improvement over the current position. But I am not so sure about that. Somehow Black's play becomes easier from this point onwards.} (23. Bf5 {with the idea of h6. White has some real pressure on the position.}) 23... exf4 24. Be6+ Kh8 25. Nd5 Bxd5 26. Bxd5 {Which bishop is better? The bishop on d5 looks great, but so does the bishop on f6. As of now, somehow the white king looks much safer, but things can turn 180 degrees pretty soon in such sharp positions.} b4 27. a4 Qe7 $1 {Good play by Vidit. His queen will come to e5 and target the weakest point in White's camp.} 28. Qd2 Qe5 29. Qc1 h6 $1 {This weakens the light squares, but White is not able to make use of it because of the pressure on the b2 point.} (29... Qxh5 {Although this might be objectively fine, this is not a pawn that you want to be taking. Especially when the g8-square is covered by the bishop on d5.} 30. Rh1 Qe5 (30... Qxf3 {is not at all possible because of} 31. e5 $16) 31. Bb3 h6 32. Rd5 $16) 30. Bb3 {Planning to play d5.} Qxh5 {Now the f3-pawn is hanging so there is no time for h1.} 31. Rg4 (31. Rxd6 Qxf3 {and White will be in trouble}) (31. Rh1 Qxf3 $17) 31... Qe5 32. Rd5 Qe7 33. Ra5 (33. Rxf4 Be5 $13) 33... Qa7 34. Rxf4 Be5 35. Rh4 (35. Rf5 {was a possiblity} Rxf5 36. exf5 Qf2 37. Rxa6 Qxf3 38. a5 Qxf5 $6 (38... Kh7 $1 $11) 39. Qh1 $3 {An important idea for the rest of the game} Qf4 40. Ra8 Rxa8 41. Qxa8+ Kh7 42. Qe8 $1 $18) 35... Rxf3 36. Rxa6 $1 Qe7 (36... Qxa6 37. Rxh6+ gxh6 38. Qxh6#) 37. Rh1 Rc8 38. Qd2 Qf6 39. Ka2 Rb8 (39... Bxb2 40. Rxd6 $18) 40. Qd5 Kh7 41. Ra8 Qd8 42. Ra7 (42. Rxb8 $1 {Exchanging this rook would have helped White because it gets rid of an important defender and the a-pawn can start thinking of moving towards becoming a queen.} Qxb8 43. a5 $16 {A very unpleasant position to defend for Black.}) 42... Qb6 43. Rd7 Qe3 44. a5 Qe2 45. Qe6 Qe3 46. a6 $2 {The pawn is moving too fast, without any backup from its pieces.} Ra8 $1 47. Kb1 Rff8 (47... Rxa6 $4 48. Qg8+ Kg6 49. Qe8+ Kg5 50. Qh5+ Kf4 51. Qh4#) (47... Rg3 $3 $17 {Going for the same principle which White had on move 42: eliminating the back rank defender! Quite a difficult move to find.}) 48. Qc4 Rfc8 (48... Qb6 $1 {would have given Vidit a chance to continue playing for a win.} 49. Qe6 Rf6 50. Qc4 (50. Qg4 Rg6 $19) 50... d5 $1 {A strong move opening up the rook on f6 to look at the a6-pawn.} (50... Qxa6 51. Qxa6 Rxa6 $17 {is also a pleasant endgame.}) 51. Qxd5 (51. exd5 Qxa6 $1 52. Qxa6 Rfxa6 {is just winning.}) 51... Qxa6 52. Rxg7+ Kxg7 53. Rg1+ Rg6 54. Qxe5+ Kh7 55. Qe7+ Kh8 56. Qe5+ Qf6 57. Qxf6+ Rxf6 $17 {and Black has chances to win this.}) 49. Qf1 Rf8 50. Qc4 Rfc8 51. Qf1 Rf8 {Vidit doesn't risk it and the game ends in a draw. A typical Najdorf game - complex and full of interesting moments.} 1/2-1/2


