{Ding Liren was in great form in the World Cup and he had a splendid tournament. As they say, in such tournaments you need some luck and here is where I played my part! After playing a great game and reaching a winning position I gifted him a half point.} 1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Nc7 7. a3 g6 8. h4 Bg4 {Tadic,Branko: 'N' Here he started thinking. Not so surprising as this hadn't been played before. ...h6 and ...g7 have been played quite often.} (8... h6 9. d3 Bg7 10. Be3 Ne6 11. O-O (11. Rc1 {- 88/22}) 11... Bd7 12. Ne4 b6 13. b4 $5 $36) 9. d3 Bg7 10. Be3 Nd4 11. Bxd4 (11. Nh2 $5 Bc8 12. Rc1 h5 (12... O-O 13. h5 $36) 13. O-O O-O 14. b4 $36) 11... cxd4 12. Ne4 O-O {After a series of logical moves, we reached this position. White has the c-file and some play on the queenside. Whereas Black has two bishops and more space.} 13. O-O b6 $1 {Controlling the c5-square and limiting the scope of the e4-knight.} 14. Rc1 Qd7 {Here Ding went into deep thought.} 15. Nh2 {He played this and offered a draw. It was clear by his time management and body language that he didn't like his position. And in any case, I liked my position so I decided to continue.} Bf5 16. Ng5 Nd5 (16... Rac8 {was my original plan but I didn't like the possibility of him exchanging the light-squared bishops.} 17. Bc6 Qd6 18. Ne4 (18. Bb7) 18... Qd8 19. Qa4 {with some play on the queenside.}) 17. Qb3 Rfd8 {This looked a bit weird. Leaving the rook on a8 under the pin and leaving the f7 undefended. Although it didn't look natural, I played this for concrete reasons.} (17... Rad8 18. Qxd5 Qxd5 19. Bxd5 Rxd5 20. Rc7 {Now the a7-pawn is undefended.}) 18. g4 $6 {I was shocked by this move. I expected him to take on d5 and try to save the slightly worse endgame.} (18. Qxd5 Qxd5 19. Bxd5 Rxd5 20. Rc7 h6 21. Ne4 (21. Ngf3 Rb5 22. Rb1 e5 23. Nd2 Be6) 21... Rb5 22. Rb1 {and it's not so easy to progress. It will probably be a draw after the eventual exchanges in the center.}) 18... Be6 (18... Bxg4 $2 19. Qxd5 $18) 19. Nxe6 Qxe6 20. Rc2 {Tadic,Branko: '?!' '!?' Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#]' White does have clear control of the c-file and a powerful bishop but probably Ding underestimated the only but important factor which is in Black's favour, 'Weak king'! It was probably wise to go back and ask me to show my cards!} (20. Kh1 $5) 20... Be5 $1 {Tadic,Branko: '!'} 21. Nf3 Bg7 (21... Bb8 {Tadic,Branko: '!' This seemed very strange. To put the bishop on b8 and box in the rook on a8 voluntarily? Although the pieces are awkward, it disrupts White's kingside.} 22. g5 Qg4 {Tadic,Branko: ''} 23. Kh1 Nf4 24. Rg1 Nxg2 25. Rxg2 Qh3+ 26. Kg1 Bf4) 22. g5 (22. Nh2 {It was probably wise to go back and ask me to show my cards!}) 22... Qf5 $1 $17 {Getting rid of the pin. Now White can't stop Black from landing a knight on f4.} 23. Rfc1 {Tadic,Branko: '?!' This was a big surprise. I was only expecting h2 which at least temporarily prevents ...f4} (23. Nh2 $1 {Tadic,Branko: ''} e6 (23... Be5 24. Nf3) 24. e4 $1 {desperate counterplay!} dxe3 25. fxe3 Qe5 26. Rf3 Rac8 $15) 23... Nf4 {Tadic,Branko: '!'} 24. Bf1 (24. Kh1 h6 25. Rg1 Rac8 $19) 24... h6 25. Rc7 Nd5 $1 26. Rb7 hxg5 27. hxg5 Rdb8 $4 {Tadic,Branko: '?' Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#]' An inexplicable blunder! I hallucinated and didn't play the best move, even after seeing it.} (27... Qg4+ 28. Kh1 Be5 $1 {Bringing another piece into the attack. Now Black simply plays d6-e6 or g7-h8. Black is winning in multiple ways as you can see from the lines.} (28... Kh7 29. Bg2 Rac8 30. Rxc8 Nf4) 29. Bg2 (29. Nxe5 Qh5+ (29... Qh4+ 30. Kg1 (30. Bh3 Qxh3+ 31. Kg1 Qh5 $19) 30... Qxg5+ 31. Bg2 Qxc1+ $19) 30. Bh3 Qxh3+ 31. Kg1 Qf5) (29. Rxe7 Qh5+ 30. Kg1 Nxe7) 29... Bf4 (29... Kg7 30. Nxe5 Qxg5 $19) (29... Rac8 30. Rxc8 Rxc8 $19) (29... Bb8 $19 { Kg7}) (29... Nf4 $2 30. Qxf7+ Kh8 (30... Kxf7 31. Nxe5+ $18) 31. Bf1 $13) 30. Rc4 (30. Rc6 Kg7) 30... Kg7 31. Rxd4 Ne3 $1 32. fxe3 Rh8+ 33. Kg1 Bxe3+ 34. Kf1 Qg3 $19) (27... Rac8 {Even the simple inclusion of the last piece in the game was giving a decisive advantage.} 28. Rxc8 Rxc8) 28. Rxb8+ Rxb8 {Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#]'} 29. Bh3 $1 {I was shocked to see this! Black has not even a hint of advantage after this as his pride, the knight on d5, is exchanged!} Qxh3 (29... Qf4 30. Rc6 Rd8 31. Qc4 e6 $11) 30. Qxd5 Rc8 31. Rxc8+ Qxc8 32. Kg2 Qg4+ 33. Kf1 Qh3+ 34. Kg1 Qg4+ 35. Kf1 Qh3+ 36. Kg1 Qg4+ {I offered a draw here but Ding seemed optimistic to maybe even win this game.} 37. Kh2 Qf4+ 38. Kg2 (38. Kh3 Qc1 39. Qd8+ Bf8 40. Qxd4 Qf1+ 41. Kg3 Qxe2) 38... Qg4+ 39. Kh2 {Eventually, he decided to be objective and take a draw. Needless to say, this game gave me many sleepless nights, but it was a good lesson :) I hope to come back to the next World Cup even stronger.} 1/2-1/2


