{[%evp 0,99,80,16,61,8,62,20,45,-92,-38,-147,-95,-63,-51,-55,9,7,75,70,75,-54,62,-20,6,-11,-28,0,-24,43,31,32,21,26,24,26,32,28,27,21,10,10,14,7,5,10,3,9,9,7,7,9,19,26,5,13,13,2,33,26,17,13,9,16,10,0,38,61,71,70,144,104,95,0,72,25,100,-44,369,411,497,497,497,495,505,505,505,505,505,893,901,893,893,938,938,952,982,982,29995,29996,29997,29998] 'FIDE WORLD CUP 2021 – RETURN OF THE OTB CHESS The Chess World Cup 2021 was the 9th edition of the World Cup that took place in Sochi, Krasnaya Polyana, Russia, beginning 12 July and ending 6 August 2021 with the participation of 206 players. It marked the return of over-the-board chess on a global scale after the COVID-19 pandemic forced the cancellation of many sporting events. Elite players from all over the world competed for the $1, 892,500 prize fund and two spots in the 2022 Candidates Tournament. The top seeds were: Magnus Carlsen (World Champion), Fabiano Caruana (World Championship finalist), Sergey Karjakin (World Championship finalist), Levon Aronian (two times Winner of the World Cup), Anish Giri, Alexander Grischuk, Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, Maxime Vachier-Lagrave and Alireza Firouzja. However, the winner of the tournament was the Polish GM Jan-Krzysztof Duda, who won without losing any games either in classical chess or in the rapid tiebreakers. Duda, and the tournament runner-up Sergey Karjakin thus qualified for the FIDE Candidates Tournament 2022. In this volume of Informant we bring you a detail coverage of this prominent event with the contributions by Jan-Krzysztof Duda, Velimir Ivic, Miodrag Perunovic, Rafael Leitao and Milos Perunovic. *** Jan-Krzysztof Duda wins the FIDE World Cup and qualifies for the Candidates The Polish chess superstar finished the tournament undefeated and knocked out none other than World Champion Magnus Carlsen in the semifinals. Eventually, Carlsen beat Vladimir Fedoseev in the match to claim the third place.  Jan-Krzysztof earned his title the hard way, knocking out top class opposition: Alexander Grischuk, Vidit Gujrathi, Magnus Carlsen and Sergey Karjakin in the final four rounds of the marathon event. Right after the final game against Karjakin Duda called this the tournament of his life "at least in classical chess", being both excited and exhausted, but also extremely gracious and modest. World Champion Carlsen provided perhaps the best description of Duda's magnificent performance in Krasnaya Polyana: "Huge congratulations to Duda for winning the World Cup. Considering the line of opponents he beat in the last four rounds, never losing a game - then obviously never being in a must-win or desperate situation - is a massive achievement. So, he is a richly deserved winner." Jan-Krzysztof won a generous $110.000 first prize and 18.2 rating points, but also gained a spot in the next edition of the Candidates Tournament. He now stands as a worthy contender to become the next challenger to the world crown. When asked about his ambitions and chances to win the Candidates, always confident Duda responded: "Yeah, why not? If I have such a good form like here, I'm probably unstoppable in such case." Indeed, why not?! Dear readers, here we present you two of the most interesting games analysed by the Tournament Champion himself, with exclusive annotations for this edition of Informant. Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'FIDE WORLD CUP 2021 – RETURN OF THE OTB CHESS The Chess World Cup 2021 was the 9th edition of the World Cup that took place in Sochi, Krasnaya Polyana, Russia, beginning 12 July and ending 6 August 2021 with the participation of 206 players. It marked the return of over-the-board chess on a global scale after the COVID-19 pandemic forced the cancellation of many sporting events. Elite players from all over the world competed for the $1, 892,500 prize fund and two spots in the 2022 Candidates Tournament. The top seeds were: Magnus Carlsen (World Champion), Fabiano Caruana (World Championship finalist), Sergey Karjakin (World Championship finalist), Levon Aronian (two times Winner of the World Cup), Anish Giri, Alexander Grischuk, Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, Maxime Vachier-Lagrave and Alireza Firouzja. However, the winner of the tournament was the Polish GM Jan-Krzysztof Duda, who won without losing any games either in classical chess or in the rapid tiebreakers. Duda, and the tournament runner-up Sergey Karjakin thus qualified for the FIDE Candidates Tournament 2022. In this volume of Informant we bring you a detail coverage of this prominent event with the contributions by Jan-Krzysztof Duda, Velimir Ivic, Miodrag Perunovic, Rafael Leitao and Milos Perunovic. *** Jan-Krzysztof Duda wins the FIDE World Cup and qualifies for the Candidates The Polish chess superstar finished the tournament undefeated and knocked out none other than World Champion Magnus Carlsen in the semifinals. Eventually, Carlsen beat Vladimir Fedoseev in the match to claim the third place.  Jan-Krzysztof earned his title the hard way, knocking out top class opposition: Alexander Grischuk, Vidit Gujrathi, Magnus Carlsen and Sergey Karjakin in the final four rounds of the marathon event. Right after the final game against Karjakin Duda called this the tournament of his life "at least in classical chess", being both excited and exhausted, but also extremely gracious and modest. World Champion Carlsen provided perhaps the best description of Duda's magnificent performance in Krasnaya Polyana: "Huge congratulations to Duda for winning the World Cup. Considering the line of opponents he beat in the last four rounds, never losing a game - then obviously never being in a must-win or desperate situation - is a massive achievement. So, he is a richly deserved winner." Jan-Krzysztof won a generous $110.000 first prize and 18.2 rating points, but also gained a spot in the next edition of the Candidates Tournament. He now stands as a worthy contender to become the next challenger to the world crown. When asked about his ambitions and chances to win the Candidates, always confident Duda responded: "Yeah, why not? If I have such a good form like here, I'm probably unstoppable in such case." Indeed, why not?! Dear readers, here we present you two of the most interesting games analysed by the Tournament Champion himself, with exclusive annotations for this edition of Informant.'''} 1. e4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof'' Jan-Krzystztof Duda is not known to be going down long forcing lines, but in this game it was exactly what happened. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Jan-Krzystztof Duda is not known to be going down long forcing lines, but in this game it was exactly what happened.''} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 {Vidit has previously shown a few of his weapons against 1.e4 and the Archangelsk was the latest and the most succesful one, as he managed to beat Vasif Durarbeyli with it, in the previous round. It obviously wouldn't come as a surprise any longer and JKD goes on to blitz out the next few moves.  Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Vidit has previously shown a few of his weapons against 1.e4 and the Archangelsk was the latest and the most succesful one, as he managed to beat Vasif Durarbeyli with it, in the previous round. It obviously wouldn't come as a surprise any longer and JKD goes on to blitz out the next few moves. ''} 7. a4 {Clever to start with this and not after 7.c3 d6, because now 8.a4 allows the option of 8...Bg4 as well. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Clever to start with this and not after 7.c3 d6, because now 8.a4 allows the option of 8...Bg4 as well.''} Rb8 8. c3 {Durarbeyli, who is a very experienced and a very strong Grand Master, with an excellent track record, went for the 8.Nxe5 variation, which also shows up at the highest level a lot. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Durarbeyli, who is a very experienced and a very strong Grand Master, with an excellent track record, went for the 8.Nxe5 variation, which also shows up at the highest level a lot.''} d6 9. d4 Bb6 10. a5 {This has been very trendy for a while. The point is that 10...Nxa5? loses to 11.Rxa5! Bxa5 12.dxe5!, while if Black goes 10...Ba7, then after 11.h3 0-0 12.Be3, Black has to deal with some tactics as the a7 bishop is under protected. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'This has been very trendy for a while. The point is that 10...Nxa5? loses to 11.Rxa5! Bxa5 12.dxe5!, while if Black goes 10...Ba7, then after 11.h3 0-0 12.Be3, Black has to deal with some tactics as the a7 bishop is under protected.''} Ba7 (10... Nxa5 $2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish'} 11. Rxa5 $1 Bxa5 12. dxe5 $1 Ng4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof} 13. Bg5 $36 {- 80/362}) 11. h3 (11. Be3 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) Duda,Jan Krzysztof'} Bg4 {- 108/(91)}) 11... Bb7 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '!?''Vidit had played the Neo-Archangelsk in the previous match, and in the most trendy 10.a5 variation he played this interesting sideline. It wasn't a big surpise for me though, as his friend Anish Giri had played it in Zagreb GCT before, the tournament I had participated in as well. I decided to play in the most forcing way, and test my opponent's memory, even if objectively the very line is probably close to the so-called "forced draw". Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '!?' '!?' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Vidit had played the Neo-Archangelsk in the previous match, and in the most trendy 10.a5 variation he played this interesting sideline. It wasn't a big surpise for me though, as his friend Anish Giri had played it in Zagreb GCT before, the tournament I had participated in as well. I decided to play in the most forcing way, and test my opponent's memory, even if objectively the very line is probably close to the so-called "forced draw".''' This is the latest trend, intending to go for the direct complications with 12.Be3 Nxe4!?. On the black side we have games of Grischuk, Dubov, Caruana, Aronian and the last one before this game, was actually played by myself against Grischuk in the Zagreb rapid.  Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'This is the latest trend, intending to go for the direct complications with 12.Be3 Nxe4!?. On the black side we have games of Grischuk, Dubov, Caruana, Aronian and the last one before this game, was actually played by myself against Grischuk in the Zagreb rapid. ''} 12. Be3 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'This move was introduced by the young Russian player Gregory Oparin in 2011, but only gained popularity recently. The ideas behind the move are simple-13.d5 and 13.dxe5.''' White could also start with 12.Re1, which is what Harikrishna did against Fabiano in Wijk aan Zee this year. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'White could also start with 12.Re1, which is what Harikrishna did against Fabiano in Wijk aan Zee this year.''} ({Earlier this year we considered} 12. Re1 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) (Giri,Anish) Vachier Lagrave,M (2784)-Dubov,D (2702) chess24.com INT 2021 [Mikhalevski,V]}) 12... Nxe4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'Black accepts the challenge. This move leads to a complex unbalanced position by force.''' That's the point. These complications have existed for a few years already, but it was only this year that the line has exploded and people stopped avoiding this with both colours. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'That's the point. These complications have existed for a few years already, but it was only this year that the line has exploded and people stopped avoiding this with both colours.''} 13. d5 {The most direct test, but 13.Re1 has been played here too. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'The most direct test, but 13.Re1 has been played here too.''} (13. Re1 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) (Giri,Anish) is an interesting alternative which scored pretty well recently.}) 13... Bxe3 14. dxc6 Nxf2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'The only move, since two pieces were hanging.''' Forced complications. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Forced complications.''} (14... Bxf2+ $2 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) (Giri,Anish) runs into} 15. Rxf2 Nxf2 16. Qd5 $1 $18) 15. Qe2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'A contribution of the Indian GM Adhiban, who presented the move in 2013.''' The consensus is that this is the best. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'The consensus is that this is the best.''} (15. Qd5 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) - 111/157 Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) (Duda,Jan Krzysztof) - 111/157'}) (15. Rxf2 $2 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) (Giri,Anish) was a mistake.} Bxf2+ 16. Kxf2 Bxc6 {with a serious material advantage for Black, who has rook and three pawns for two minor pieces. Pratyusha,B (2180)-Monnisha, G (2051) Lucknow 2013}) 15... Nxh3+ {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'Black has no choice due to the two hanging pieces.'''} 16. Kh1 Nf2+ {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'All Black's moves are forced.'''} 17. Rxf2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'White has no choice either.'''} Bxf2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'We have arrived at a junction. White can choose which bishop to capture.''' And here White is at a principled crossroad. There are two attempts, as there are two bishops that can be captured. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'And here White is at a principled crossroad. There are two attempts, as there are two bishops that can be captured.''} 18. Qxf2 $5 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Diagram [#]''Diagram [#] Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'Concrete play continues after' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Diagram [#]'''} ({'Move in the text line is a small surpise, as Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Move in the text line is a small surpise, as'''} 18. cxb7 {'is the main line, and was played in the aforementioned Anish's game. I must confess that I didn't find any real improvement over Russian's play. Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!?' Mikhalevski,V: 'This move was played in at least three recent games.' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'is the main line, and was played in the aforementioned Anish's game. I must confess that I didn't find any real improvement over Russian's play.'''} Ba7 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!''' is how my game with Grischuk went and a few prepared moves down the line, he picked a move repetition. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'is how my game with Grischuk went and a few prepared moves down the line, he picked a move repetition.''} 19. Bd5 Qd7 20. Nd4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!'''} Qe7 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!'''} 21. Bc6+ Kf8 22. Nf3 {'Diagram [#] Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Diagram [#]'''} d5 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '!''Very strong, and holding! Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '!' '!' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Very strong, and holding!'''} 23. Qxe5 Qxe5 24. Nxe5 Ke7 25. Bxb5 (25. Nd3 $5 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) Giri,Anish} Kd6 26. Nb4 Bc5 27. Nxa6 Kxc6 28. Nxc5 Kxc5 29. a6 {is worth a try.}) 25... axb5 26. a6 Kd6 27. Nxf7+ Kc6 {'- and Alexander choose to repeat here: Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '- and Alexander choose to repeat here:'''} 28. Ne5+ Kd6 29. Nf7+ Kc6 30. Ne5+ Kd6 31. Nf7+ {½-½ (31) Grischuk,A (2778)-Giri,A (2776) Zagreb 2021'1/2 : 1/2 Grischuk,Alexander 2778 - Giri,Anish 2776, Zagreb (rapid) 2021 Giri,Anish: '½-½ (31) Grischuk,A (2778)-Giri,A (2776) Zagreb 2021 Mikhalevski,V: 'with a repetition in Grischuk,A (2778)-Giri,A (2776) Zagreb 2021' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '1/2 : 1/2 Grischuk,Alexander 2778 - Giri,Anish 2776, Zagreb (rapid) 2021'''}) 18... Bxc6 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'N!' 'N!''- and of course he knew about this radical solution. Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'N!' 'N!' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '- and of course he knew about this radical solution.''' In 2013, in the game betweed Adhiban and Ashwin, Black wasn't aware of this forced line just yet and played 18...Bc8?. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'In 2013, in the game betweed Adhiban and Ashwin, Black wasn't aware of this forced line just yet and played 18...Bc8?.''} (18... Bc8 $2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof''} 19. Nxe5 O-O 20. Nd3 $16 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'was clearly better for White in Adhiban,Baskaran 2587 - Ashwin,Jayaram 2461, India 2013 Giri,Anish: 'was clearly better for White in Adhiban,Baskaran 2587 - Ashwin,Jayaram 2461, India 2013''}) 19. Nxe5 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!'''} Bxg2+ $1 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '!' Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'The only move again.''' The crucial intermezzo, intending to throw out the d8 queen with a check. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'The crucial intermezzo, intending to throw out the d8 queen with a check.''} 20. Kg1 $1 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '!' Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'White also has no choice again.''' Forced as well. Now Black has no checks. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Forced as well. Now Black has no checks.''} (20. Kxg2 $2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) Duda,Jan Krzysztof'} Qg5+ 21. Kf1 (21. Kh1 $2 Qh5+ 22. Kg2 dxe5 $19) 21... Qxe5 22. Qxf7+ Kd8 23. Be6 Qf6+ $17) (20. Qxg2 $2 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) (Giri,Anish) is bad due to} Qh4+ 21. Kg1 Qe1+ 22. Qf1 Qg3+ 23. Kh1 ({or} 23. Qg2 Qxe5) 23... Qh4+ 24. Kg1 Qg5+ 25. Kh1 Qh5+ 26. Kg1 dxe5 $19 {After protecting the f7-pawn with a check Black captures the knight and obtains a huge material advantage.}) 20... Qf6 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'One of a few equalisers.''' After the game JKD said that he expected Vidit to follow a correspondence game with 20...0-0 which leads to a draw. There seems to be nothing wrong with Vidit's solution either. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'After the game JKD said that he expected Vidit to follow a correspondence game with 20...0-0 which leads to a draw. There seems to be nothing wrong with Vidit's solution either.''} ({'I expected my opponent to know the following line: Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'and' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'I expected my opponent to know the following line:'''} 20... O-O $5 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '!?' Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'transpose into each other after'''} 21. Nxf7 Qe7 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '='''} 22. Nd2 {here Black has to know a couple of important moves to reach the desired 0.00. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'here Black has to know a couple of important moves to reach the desired 0.00.''} d5 $1 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '!''} 23. Qxg2 Qe3+ 24. Kh1 {'Diagram [#] Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Diagram [#]'''} Kxf7 $3 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '!' '!''Giri,Anish: '!!' Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '!' '!''' and the complications end in a draw. Unfindable stuff, but possible to memorize. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'and the complications end in a draw. Unfindable stuff, but possible to memorize.''} 25. Bxd5+ {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof''} Ke7 26. Nf3 Qh6+ {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'when I actually intended to make a draw after 27.Kg1, alternatively Giri,Anish: 'when I actually intended to make a draw after 27.Kg1, alternatively''} 27. Nh2 Rf4 $8 $13 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '''is a total mess, but I think in general it's a perspective position for Black. Giri,Anish: 'is a total mess, but I think in general it's a perspective position for Black. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: ''''}) (20... Qe7 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) Giri,Anish}) 21. Nxf7 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!''' The best. Now we reach an endgame by force. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'The best. Now we reach an endgame by force.''} (21. Qxf6 $2 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) Giri,Anish} gxf6 22. Ng4 Bb7 {still yields Black sufficient material advantage.}) 21... Qxf2+ 22. Kxf2 Rf8 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'The most accurate.'''} (22... O-O $6 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) (Giri,Anish) is less accurate in view of} 23. Kxg2 Rxf7 24. Nd2 Kf8 25. Bxf7 Kxf7 {and White gained a tempo compared to the game.}) 23. Kxg2 Rxf7 24. Bxf7+ Kxf7 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'I'm pretty sure both players analysed this position at home. Black has three pawns for a piece, but only two extra pawns on the kingside.''' This is an endgame both players went for. White has a knight for 3 pawns which is a very fine material allocation for the second player, but he does have to watch out a little bit, as the a6 pawn is fixed by the a5 pawn and if the knight is ever to land on b4, Black could get under pressure.  But that will never happen... or will it?  Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'This is an endgame both players went for. White has a knight for 3 pawns which is a very fine material allocation for the second player, but he does have to watch out a little bit, as the a6 pawn is fixed by the a5 pawn and if the knight is ever to land on b4, Black could get under pressure.  But that will never happen... or will it? ''} 25. Nd2 {'- and so after a forced variation we have the ensuing endgame. Objectively it's level, but in practical terms I think only White can pull it off. Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '- and so after a forced variation we have the ensuing endgame. Objectively it's level, but in practical terms I think only White can pull it off.'''} Re8 {I didn't like this particular solution, although it is not a bad move objectively, as the game stays well within the drawable margin. It felt more practical to include 25...b4 26.c4, to get some counterplay with Re8-Re5, or alternatively go for 25...g5!?, giving the king a nice square on g6 behind the pawns and not in front of them.  Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'I didn't like this particular solution, although it is not a bad move objectively, as the game stays well within the drawable margin. It felt more practical to include 25...b4 26.c4, to get some counterplay with Re8-Re5, or alternatively go for 25...g5!?, giving the king a nice square on g6 behind the pawns and not in front of them. ''} (25... b4 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) might be an improvement for Black, to damage White's queenside.} 26. c4 {Giri,Anish} Re8 (26... g5 $5) 27. Kf3 Re5 (27... g5 {was still good.}) 28. Nf1 Rf5+ 29. Ke2 Rh5 30. Kd3 Rh1 31. Re1 c6 {and a draw was agreed in the just finished tournament. Nihal,S (2655)-Arjun,K (2503) Riga 2021}) 26. Rf1+ {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'A clever intermediate move, which tries to force Black's king to the g-file''' An annoying check. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'An annoying check.''} Kg6 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!''' Allowing the rook trade and going for a very concrete knight vs pawns endgame is not something you want to be dealing with this early in the game, but now the king is somewhat awkwardly placed in front of its pawns. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Allowing the rook trade and going for a very concrete knight vs pawns endgame is not something you want to be dealing with this early in the game, but now the king is somewhat awkwardly placed in front of its pawns.''} 27. Kf2 $1 {'The combination of my last two moves looks a bit weird, but at least now Black can't play g5 anymore. From now on, both sides could deviate in several moments, but what we did certainly made sense. Giri,Anish: '!' Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'Now Black's king is in front of the g-file and so the advance of the kingside pawns is slowed down.' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'The combination of my last two moves looks a bit weird, but at least now Black can't play g5 anymore. From now on, both sides could deviate in several moments, but what we did certainly made sense.''' Strong. The g-file is free for the rook and the king takes it upon himself to stop the invasion of the rook. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Strong. The g-file is free for the rook and the king takes it upon himself to stop the invasion of the rook.''} h5 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!''' Black wants to slowly start pushing his kingside pawns.  Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Black wants to slowly start pushing his kingside pawns. ''} (27... Rf8+ $6 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) (Giri,Anish) is met by} 28. Nf3) 28. Rg1+ Kf6 29. Kf3 $5 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '!?'' 29.Nf3 may seem automatic at first, but this is a much more clever way to stop the pawns, intending Ne4+. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '29.Nf3 may seem automatic at first, but this is a much more clever way to stop the pawns, intending Ne4+.''} g6 (29... Re5 $5 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) (Giri,Anish) also deserved attention.} 30. Ne4+ Kf7 31. Kf4 g6 {and Black doesn't mind trading rooks, as after} 32. Rg5 Rxg5 33. Kxg5 {he activates his king by means of} ({or} 33. Nxg5+ Kf6 $11) 33... Ke6 $11) 30. Ne4+ Kg7 {'Diagram [#] Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Diagram [#]'''} (30... Kf7 $2 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) (Giri,Anish) would be wrong due to the following manoeuvre of the white knight.} 31. Nf2 $1 Kf6 (31... Kg7 32. Nd3 $1 Kh6 33. Re1 $1 Rf8+ (33... Rxe1 34. Nxe1 $18 {is hopeless due to the weak queenside pawns.}) 34. Kg3 $16) 32. Nh3 Kf5 33. Nf4 Re4 34. Nd5 $1 $16 ({After} 34. Nxg6 b4 {Black creates sufficient counterplay.})) 31. Nf2 $1 {'Directing to the green b4-square. Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'The knight is heading to d3 from where it can get to either f4 or b4.' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Directing to the green b4-square.''' Duda makes one nasty move after the other. Here already I started feeling the heat for Vidit, but the engine still pointed out a cleacut solution- 31...Kh6! 32.Nd3 g5!. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Duda makes one nasty move after the other. Here already I started feeling the heat for Vidit, but the engine still pointed out a cleacut solution- 31...Kh6! 32.Nd3 g5!.''} Rf8+ $6 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '?!'' Fishing for a move repetition is tempting, but it just doesn't bring Black the desired result. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Fishing for a move repetition is tempting, but it just doesn't bring Black the desired result.''} ({It would be more accurate to play} 31... Kh6 $1 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) Giri,Anish} 32. Nd3 g5 {Black creates fast counterplay.} 33. Re1 g4+ 34. Kg2 Rf8 35. Nb4 h4 36. Nxa6 h3+ {and the game may continue} 37. Kg3 Kg5 38. Nxc7 Rf3+ 39. Kh2 Kh4 40. Nd5 g3+ 41. Kg1 h2+ 42. Kh1 Kh3 43. Ne3 Rf4 $1 44. a6 Ra4 45. Ng2 Rxa6 46. Nf4+ Kg4 47. Nd5 Ra2 $11) 32. Kg2 Re8 $2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '?' Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '?!''' Continuing with the wrong intention. White doesn't have to take the draw and this only gives White more time. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Continuing with the wrong intention. White doesn't have to take the draw and this only gives White more time.''} (32... Rf4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish' Keeping control of the f4 square was much better, with the direct 32...Rf5 or first this.} 33. Ra1 Rf5 34. Nd3 c5 {and Black manages to keep the knight at bay and wants to start pushing his kingside. The position is still very much drawish.}) (32... Rf5 $5 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof} 33. Nd3 c5 $11 {'Giri,Anish: '!' Giri,Anish: 'restricting the knight was better. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '=' '='''}) 33. Nd3 $1 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' Now Black is suddenly in serious trouble. He has to allow either Nb4 or Nf4. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Now Black is suddenly in serious trouble. He has to allow either Nb4 or Nf4.''} g5 {Correct, as 33...c5 34.Nf4! was just losing, with Kf3 coming next and Black's kingside pawns not able to move. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Correct, as 33...c5 34.Nf4! was just losing, with Kf3 coming next and Black's kingside pawns not able to move.''} ({'Now Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Now'''} 33... c5 $2 {'is no longer good, as after Giri,Anish: '?' Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'is no longer good, as after'''} 34. Nf4 $1 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '''Black can hardly defend his weaknesses. Giri,Anish: '!' Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '' 'Black can hardly defend his weaknesses.'''}) 34. Nb4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Diagram [#]''Diagram [#] Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Diagram [#]''' Black has to answer very hard questions, but objectively this seems to still be within the drawing margin of the game. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Black has to answer very hard questions, but objectively this seems to still be within the drawing margin of the game.''} Re2+ $2 {'A very natural and tempting check, but at the same time the losing mistake! Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'This is the decisive mistake.' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'A very natural and tempting check, but at the same time the losing mistake!''' Very tempting, but Vidit has missed JKD's strong sequence. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Very tempting, but Vidit has missed JKD's strong sequence.''} ({'He should have opted instead for Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'After the correct' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'He should have opted instead for'''} 34... c5 $1 {leads to a defendable position. Black gives up a pawn, but gets rid of the main issue, the passed a5 pawn. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'leads to a defendable position. Black gives up a pawn, but gets rid of the main issue, the passed a5 pawn.''} 35. Nxa6 (35. Nd5 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) Duda,Jan Krzysztof'} Kg6) 35... Ra8 36. Nc7 Rxa5 {'when White can win an additional pawn in different ways, but the reduction of material plus activity of Black's rook are sufficient for equality e.g. Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'when White can win an additional pawn in different ways, but the reduction of material plus activity of Black's rook are sufficient for equality e.g.''' Black holds. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Black holds.''} 37. Ne8+ {There are also other tries. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'There are also other tries.''} (37. Kf3 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) Giri,Anish} Kf6 38. Rd1 Ke7 {Black retains good chances for a draw.}) 37... Kg6 38. Nxd6 Ra2 39. Rb1 b4 40. c4 b3 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '=!' '!''Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '=!' '=!''' and Black is apparently ok, as he can combine the relative instability of White's queenside pawns with the advance of his own kingside soldiers. This wasn't easy to go for, but it had to be done, as the move in the game just loses by force. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'and Black is apparently ok, as he can combine the relative instability of White's queenside pawns with the advance of his own kingside soldiers. This wasn't easy to go for, but it had to be done, as the move in the game just loses by force.''} 41. Ne4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) Duda,Jan Krzysztof'} Ra4 42. Nxc5 Rxc4 43. Nxb3 h4 $44) 35. Kh1 $1 {'Now White is winning in a forcing way, and I managed to calculate it almost to the end. Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '+-!' Mikhalevski,V: 'Surprisingly, after this retreat Black is in trouble. White wins the a6-pawn and creates a strong passed pawn.' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Now White is winning in a forcing way, and I managed to calculate it almost to the end.''' The king is now not in the way of any checks, neither by the pawns nor by the rook. A very aesthetically pleasing solution. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'The king is now not in the way of any checks, neither by the pawns nor by the rook. A very aesthetically pleasing solution.''} (35. Kf3 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) Duda,Jan Krzysztof'} Rxb2 36. Ra1 g4+ 37. Ke3 h4 38. Nxa6 h3 39. Nxc7 h2 40. a6 Ra2 $1) 35... Rxb2 36. Ra1 $1 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' Grabbing the a-file before collecting the a6 pawn. The a5 pawn is now unstoppable and Black is just losing by force. Note that with the king on f3 Black would now have counterplay thanks to g4+ and Rb3-xc3 check, but now that the king is on h1, the counterplay is much too slow. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Grabbing the a-file before collecting the a6 pawn. The a5 pawn is now unstoppable and Black is just losing by force. Note that with the king on f3 Black would now have counterplay thanks to g4+ and Rb3-xc3 check, but now that the king is on h1, the counterplay is much too slow.''} (36. Nxa6 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) Duda,Jan Krzysztof'} Ra2 37. Rxg5+ Kf6 38. Rxb5 c6 39. Rxh5 Kg6 40. Rh3 Rxa5 41. Nb8) 36... c5 (36... Rb3 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof} 37. Nxa6 Rxc3 38. Nb4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '+-' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'and there is no stopping the a-pawn.'} Rc4 {Diagram [#] Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) (Duda,Jan Krzysztof) Diagram [#]'} 39. Nd3 $1 (39. a6 $2 Rxb4 40. a7 Rh4+ 41. Kg2 Rg4+ 42. Kf3 Rf4+ 43. Ke3 Rf8 44. a8=Q Rxa8 45. Rxa8 Kf6 46. Rb8 Ke5 47. Rxb5+ c5 48. Rb8 d5 $13) (39. Nd5 $2 b4 $1 40. a6 $140 b3 41. a7 b2 42. a8=Q Rc1+ $17) 39... Re4 40. a6 Re8 41. a7 Ra8 42. Nb4 Kf7 43. Nd5 $18) (36... g4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'was another attempt, where I had seen a following line: Giri,Anish: '(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) was another attempt, where I had seen a following line:''} 37. Nxa6 h4 38. Nxc7 g3 39. a6 h3 40. a7 Rh2+ 41. Kg1 Rg2+ 42. Kf1 Rf2+ 43. Ke1 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'is winning, as after 43...h2 there is 44.a8Q protecting h1-square, and after Giri,Anish: 'is winning, as after 43...h2 there is 44.a8Q protecting h1-square, and after''} Rf8 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'there is'} 44. Ne6+ $18) 37. Nxa6 b4 {The last attempt, but JKD is merciless.  Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'The last attempt, but JKD is merciless. ''} (37... Rc2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) Duda,Jan Krzysztof'} 38. Nxc5 $18) 38. Nxb4 $1 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' Leads to a major piece endgame in which White gets to check first and Black's king has nowhere to hide. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Leads to a major piece endgame in which White gets to check first and Black's king has nowhere to hide.''} (38. cxb4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) is also enough for a win.'} cxb4 39. Nc7 b3 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof'} (39... Rc2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof} 40. a6 $1 Rxc7 ({or} 40... b3 41. Ne6+ $1 Kg6 42. Nd4 Rc8 43. Nxb3 $18 {with an easily won position.}) 41. a7 Rc8 42. a8=Q Rxa8 43. Rxa8 $18) 40. Ne6+ $1 (40. a6 Ra2) 40... Kf6 41. Nd4 $18) 38... cxb4 39. a6 bxc3 40. a7 c2 41. a8=Q Rb1+ 42. Kg2 c1=Q {'Tragicomedy Black has three extra pawns at the moment, but an extremely poor placement of his pieces means he is getting checkmated by force. Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'It seems that Black did as much as he could, but White's attack is decisive.' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Tragicomedy Black has three extra pawns at the moment, but an extremely poor placement of his pieces means he is getting checkmated by force.''' All forced so far. Now White starts checking and the king just ends up getting mated. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'All forced so far. Now White starts checking and the king just ends up getting mated.''} 43. Ra7+ Kf6 44. Qf8+ Ke5 45. Re7+ Kd5 (45... Kd4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof''} 46. Qf2+ Kd3 47. Qf3+ Kd4 48. Qe4+ $18) 46. Qf3+ Kc5 47. Rc7+ Kb4 48. Qb7+ Ka5 (48... Ka3 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) (Giri,Anish) doesn't save Black.} 49. Qa7+ Kb3 50. Qb8+ Ka2 51. Ra7+) 49. Qa7+ Kb5 50. Qb8+ {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'A well-played game by Duda! Strong opening preparation and good endgame technique made their deal. Black's main mistake came on move 34, when Vidit played 34...Re2?, instead of the correct 34...c5. Black's play can also be improved by means of 31...Kh6. Also 25...b4 and 29...Re5 make sense.''' A crucial win, for the eventual World Cup winner. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'A crucial win, for the eventual World Cup winner.''} 1-0


