1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 (4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6. f3 d5 {This will be our move-order}) 4... d5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. dxc5 Qa5 {One of the mainlines of the entire line} 9. e4 Nf6 10. Be3 O-O 11. Qb3 Nfd7 12. a4 Qc7 (12... Nxc5 $2 13. Qb4 $1 $16) 13. Qa3 {Simply defending the pawn.} b6 14. a5 {Our idea is to let black take back on c5 with the pawn so that our pawn on c3 doesn't become weak.} Bb7 (14... bxc5 {This is the mainline}) 15. Ne2 {This use to be the reason why black players shifted towards bc5} Nxc5 16. Nd4 {Simple development} Nbd7 17. Be2 {We have two bishops more space, the only concern is the weak c3 pawn but it won't be easy for black to even attack it.} Ba6 18. Nb5 $1 {Ofcourse not exchanging any pieces when black lacks space.} Qc6 19. c4 f5 $6 {Black was lacking counterplay but this is simply bad as now white can shift his pieces towards black's king} 20. exf5 exf5 21. O-O Rfe8 22. Rfe1 bxa5 23. Rad1 a4 24. Bf1 Bxb5 25. cxb5 Qc7 26. Bc4+ $1 {Another good move, we want to put this bishop right in the throat of black's position which is on c6.} Kh8 27. Bd5 Rad8 28. Bc6 Ne6 29. Bf2 Nef8 30. Rxe8 (30. Re7 $1 {This was good as well but I wanted to keep everything simple.} Ne5 31. Rxc7 Rxd1+ 32. Be1 Nxc6 33. bxc6 Rdxe1+ 34. Kf2) 30... Rxe8 31. Qxa4 Nb6 32. Qc2 Rd8 33. Re1 Qf7 34. h4 h6 35. Re5 f4 36. Rf5 Qc7 37. Qe4 Qd6 38. Rf7 Ne6 39. Qg6 Qd1+ 40. Kh2 Qf1 41. Be4 {1-0 (41) Gupta,A (2625)-Vidit,S  (2508) Aurangabad 2011} 1-0


