[PlyCount "92"]

1. d4 {I have chosen this game as a model game because I think it shows how black should play in the StartFENr2q1rk1/pb1nbppp/1pp1pn2/3p4/2PP1B2/5NP1/PPQ1PPBP/RN1R2K1 w - - 2 11EndFEN 11.Ne5 mainline, where we go StartFENr2q1rk1/pb1nbppp/1pN1pn2/3p4/3P4/6P1/PPQBPPBP/RN1R2K1 b - - 1 14EndFEN 14...Qe8! . It was played in a decisive match, USA vs India in this year's Online Olympiad.} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Nf3 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 {The move order I recommend in the course. We are flexible against the sidelines that White can play. Though, if White just wants to play the mainline, it makes no difference to 7...c6 .} 8. Qc2 c6 9. Rd1 b6 10. Bf4 Bb7 11. Ne5 Nh5 {An important move, harassing the dark-squared bishop.} 12. Bd2 Nhf6 13. cxd5 {Vidit goes for the line where he wins the two bishops.} cxd5 14. Nc6 Qe8 {The move I think is best. As I explain in the course, I do not like 14...Bxc6 . The resulting positions can be hard, and I often found myself weakening my own light squares too much.} 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. Qc7 {A very rare move. The move played exclusively is 16.Nc3 . Perhaps Vidit had studied those arising positions and realized that the queen was a problem on either c2 where it was on the c-file and Ne4 motives came- or on d3 where a5-Ba6 comes with tempo as we saw inGrischuk-Anand.} Ba6 17. Nc3 Rfc8 {The depth of this move will be shown after:} 18. Qf4 {Vidit argues that since we have given away the dark-squared bishop, we can not really drive away the queen from f4. Here Robson plays a very strong move, showing the flaw in White’s strategy:} Nf8 {The knight on f8 is going to g6 where it wins a tempo. From g6 the knight can go to e7-f5, where it will stand very well.} 19. h4 h6 {We are always happy to include h6, as one day h6-g5 is on the cards.} 20. Bf3 Ng6 21. Qe3 Qd8 {Giving way for the knight to come to e7.} 22. Rac1 Rc4 23. b3 Rc7 {The best square for the rook. On c6 it is unprotected, so we are ready to double on the c-file from here.} 24. a4 Rac8 {Black is doing very well in my opinion. Vidit plays on the queenside in this game, but Black is very well coordinated and soon takes over.} 25. Na2 {25.h5 Ne7 26.g4 was perhaps what Vidit should have tried, though it can lead to more weaknesses in the king safety for White in the future. 26...Qd7 27.Kg2 Nh7 , followed by Ng5. Black is not getting mated.} Bb7 {Prophylaxis versus Nb4.} 26. Rxc7 Rxc7 27. Nc3 Ba6 {The bishop is doing a good job from a6, as it protects the b5-square from the knight on c3. Note that the bishops for White are not really doing so much.} 28. h5 Nf8 {28...Ne7 would have been more active, but it is understandable that in such an important game, Robson wanted to make sure his king was as safe as possible. 29.g4 The knight does not get to f5 and the attack could start for White.} 29. Rc1 N8h7 {The point behind Nf8. As White weakened the g5-square, this is justified.} 30. Qe5 Qc8 {Making sure that the c-file is in Black's hand.} 31. Na2 Rxc1+ 32. Nxc1 Nd7 33. Qd6 Ng5 {Giving White a choice. White is already in some trouble, as 34.Bg2 fails to 34...Nf6 . The knights are coming to e4!} 34. Bxg5 {The knight was a source of big problems for White, so he took it off.} hxg5 35. Na2 Nf6 {Intending g4, when Black would win space and the e2-pawn could fall. Black is doing so well because of having the c-file and the active bishop on a6 and knight on f6.} 36. g4 {36.Qe5 was the best move, though Vidit maybe did not want to give Black 36...g4 .} Qc2 {Suddenly, White is lost. The knight on a2 is under fire, and if 37.Nb4 , then 37...Qd1+ wins the game as e2 is falling!} 37. Qb8+ {The only try:} Kh7 38. Qxa7 Bxe2 {Material might be equal, but look at the difference in the pieces! Also, all of Black's pieces are directly attacking White's king. So far Robson has played perfectly, and he does not disappoint in delivering the checkmate either!} 39. Bxe2 Qxe2 40. Qxf7 Qxg4+ 41. Kf1 Qd1+ 42. Kg2 Nxh5 {The strongest. Now the knight comes to f4 with check. White is hopelessly lost, as the knight on a2 is on the side of the board doing nothing.} 43. Nc3 {Trying to get it into the game but Black is accurate:} Qg4+ {43...Nf4+ would lose, due to 44.Qxf4! .} 44. Kf1 Qh3+ 45. Ke2 Nf4+ 46. Kd2 Qd3+ {The knight on c3 falls with check.  A model game that shows how Black should play in the Nc6 ...Qe8 middlegame if White goes for the Qc7-Qf4 rare idea. Now this game shows also the general idea of Black as a whole, as Black was occupying the c-file, playing with active pieces and constantly trying to improve. White did have the bishop pair on paper, but when a player like GM Vidit has a hard time making any use of them, it shows that it is not easy for White.  This game was decided after Vidit played the move StartFEN2q3k1/p4pp1/bp1Qpn2/3p2pP/P2P4/1P3BP1/N3PP2/6K1 w - - 2 36EndFEN 36.g4 , as now 36...Qc2! came, and in the resulting mating attacks, the f4-square was critically weak. But Robson had a good game either way and could have continued gaining space on the kingside with g4. A game to learn from!} *


