1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 {Continuing a bizarre fashion from the World Championship match, though it must be said that trying to find an advantage in this position is a thankless task. Therefore, you have to respect Nepomniachtchi (also a pioneer of the 5.Bd3 Petroff) for trying.} e6 {Likewise. I'm not certain what's wrong with ...Nf6 or ...c6.} 7. Qd2 Be7 8. O-O-O Nxd4 9. Qxd4 a6 10. f4 {Usually something has gone wrong if White has gained tempi and achieved d5 in such positions. The Petroff is so solid that Black is fine anyway, though. The problem, rather, lay in what happened if White didn't rush d5.} (10. Be2) (10. Bc4) 10... O-O (10... b5 11. Bxf6 gxf6 (11... gxf6 12. Bd3 (12. f5 Qa5 13. Kb1 b4 14. Ne2 e5 15. Qe3 Bb7 16. Ng3 d5 17. Bd3 O-O-O 18. Qe2 h5 19. exd5 h4 20. Ne4 Rxd5 21. Bc4 Rxd1+ 22. Rxd1 Rd8 23. Rd2 Kb8 24. Qe3 Kc7 25. g4 Qb6) 12... Qc7 (12... O-O 13. e5 d5 14. Ne4) 13. Qe3 Qc5 14. Qg3 b4 15. Ne2 a5 16. Kb1 Kf8 17. Qh3 h5 18. Rc1 d5 19. exd5 Qxd5 20. f5) (11... Bxf6 12. e5 dxe5 13. Qc5 Bd7 14. Nxb5 axb5 15. Rxd7)) 11. Be2 (11. Bc4 b5 12. Bb3 Qc7 13. Kb1 Re8 14. e5 dxe5 15. fxe5 Nd7 16. Bxe7 Rxe7 17. Ne4) (11. Bd3) 11... b5 {Black is fine now.} (11... Qa5 12. e5 dxe5 13. Qxe5 b5 14. Bf3 Ra7 15. Kb1 Rc7) 12. Bxf6 (12. e5 dxe5 13. Qxd8 (13. Qxe5 Qb6) 13... Bxd8 14. fxe5 (14. Rxd8 Rxd8 15. fxe5 h6) 14... Nd7 15. Bxd8 Rxd8 16. Bf3 Ra7) (12. Bf3) 12... gxf6 (12... Bxf6 13. Qxd6) 13. Bf3 (13. f5 Qa5 14. fxe6 fxe6 15. Nd5 Bd8 16. Rd3) 13... Bb7 $5 {Sacrificing this pawn does not seem to have been entirely needed, though it is in principle fine.} 14. f5 Rc8 15. Kb1 (15. fxe6 $11 fxe6 16. Qd3 (16. Bg4 f5 17. exf5 Rc4 18. Qa7 Bxg2 19. f6 Rxf6 20. Be2 Rc7)) 15... Rc4 16. Qd3 Qc7 17. Ne2 (17. fxe6 fxe6 18. Ne2) 17... e5 18. Ng3 Kh8 19. Nh5 $1 Rc8 20. Rc1 {Now this is a little hard to play for Black, mostly because of the imminent mate threats.} b4 $1 {Black recognises that the priority is to exchange off the knight on d4.} 21. g4 a5 $1 22. Qd2 Qd8 23. h4 Bxe4 (23... a4 24. Rhe1 (24. Qh6 Qf8 25. Qxf8+ Rxf8 26. Rhe1 $11) 24... a3 25. b3 Rc3 26. Bh1 $16 {with an extremely original mess in Ganguly,S-Abasov,N Ulaanbaatar 2018}) 24. Bxe4 Rxe4 25. g5 (25. Qd5 {and now one high-level game went} Rxg4 $5 26. Qxf7 Qf8 27. Qe6 Rcc4) 25... fxg5 (25... Rd4 26. Qe3 $44 (26. Qg2 fxg5 {is probably no worse a version than the next note.} 27. Rcf1 $5 (27. f6 Bxf6 {regains the pawn.} 28. Rcf1 Be7 29. Rxf7 Qe8) (27. hxg5 $11 Bxg5 {doesn't leave Black many good options for development. The main one that makes sense is} 28. f6 h6 29. Rcg1 Qc7 $14 {but here I would award White a little something, mostly because he does still have ways to force through the d5-break, at a moment of his choosing.} 30. Ng7 (30. Nf4 {would be my choice.}) 30... Rd2)) 26... fxg5 27. f6 Bxf6 28. Qf3 Be7) 26. Qd5 (26. f6 Bxf6 (26... Bf8 $16 {Black's king lacks a flight-square on d7 and probably perishes.} {Bizarrely, the key to Black's position probably lay in the classy} 27. Qxg5 $1) 27. Qd5) 26... Rxh4 $2 27. Qxf7 (27. Rxh4 $13 {Black's pieces have acheived a measure of co-ordination.} gxh4 $14 {In the similar line} 28. f6 Bf8) 27... Qf8 28. Qe6 Rcc4 29. f6 Bd8 30. Rhf1 $1 $16 {When playing Kb7, Black must have underestimated this quiet move.} (30. f7 Rxh1 31. Ka1 (31. Rxh1 Rh4 32. Rxh4 gxh4)) 30... Rc7 31. Ng7 Rf7 32. Ne8 Rf4 33. Rfd1 Bxf6 34. Nxd6 Re7 $2 {Now the position becomes definitely lost, due to immediate Rb8 and Bb8-type tactics.} 35. Qd5 $1 e4 36. Re1 e3 37. Qxa5 {The bishop is lost.} Bg7 (37... Bxb2 $14 {is dangerous, but nowhere near as dangerous as the game.}) (37... Rd7 {is just misguided:} 38. Nb5 $11 {The even calmer response} Qb8 39. Rxe3 Rf5 $1 {was needed in order to fully neutralise White's advantage. White cannot give mate with a single rook, and there isn't time to keep both rooks AND double them.}) 38. Qxg5 Re6 (38... Re5 39. Qg3 Rd4 $18 {Black can prevent White's king from reaching the kingside, but cannot simultaneously prevent tactics based on Kc5 and perhaps Rb6xc6.} {Engines start speaking of wins which begin} 40. Nb7 Qe7 41. Qf3 Rd7) 39. Nb5 $18 {is not really worth playing on} (39. Nb7 e2 40. Qd5 Re7) 39... Re5 40. Qg3 Rxb5 41. Rxe3 Re5 1-0


