1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 e6 6. e4 Bb4 7. e5 {This is a relatively rare move at this juncture. White modestly develops while hoping that his extra bishop will grant him chances for an advantage when the position later opens up.} Ne4 (7... Nd5) 8. Qc2 Qd5 9. Be2 c5 (9... O-O 10. O-O Nxc3 11. bxc3 Be7 12. Nd2 c5 13. Bxc4 Qd8 14. Qe4) (9... b5 10. O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 O-O 12. Ne1) 10. O-O Nxc3 (10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 Nc6 12. Bxc4 Qxc4 13. Qxe4 Qxc3 14. Bd2) 11. bxc3 cxd4 12. cxd4 (12. Nxd4 Bc5 (12... Be7) (12... Qxe5 13. cxb4 Qxd4 14. Bb2) 13. Nf3 Nd7 14. Rd1 Qc6 15. Bxc4) (12. cxb4 d3 13. Bxd3 Qxd3 14. Qxd3 cxd3 15. Rd1 Bd7 16. Rxd3 Bc6 17. Nd4) 12... c3 (12... Nc6 13. Bxc4 (13. Bb2 Na5) 13... Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Qxd4 15. Rb1 Qc3 (15... Be7 16. Bb5+ Kf8 17. Rd1 Qxe5 18. Ba3) 16. Qe2 Be7 17. Rb5 a6 18. Bb2) 13. Bd2 Qa5 (13... Nc6 14. Bxc3 Bxc3 15. Qxc3 O-O 16. a5) 14. Bxc3 Bxc3 {Black resolves the central tension but willingly saddles himself with the famous insolated d-pawn. As compensation, he is ahead in development and his major pieces will be quick to find good squares.} (14... Nc6 15. Rab1 Bxc3 16. Rb5 Qc7 17. Qxc3 O-O 18. Ng5) 15. Ra3 Nc6 (15... Bd7 16. Rxc3 Bxa4 17. Bb5+ (17. Rc8+ Kd7 18. Bb5+ Nc6)) (15... O-O 16. Rxc3 Bd7 17. Ng5) 16. Rxc3 Bd7 (16... O-O 17. Rb1 (17. Rc5 Qd8 18. Rc1) 17... Qc7 18. Ng5) 17. Rb1 O-O (17... Rb8 {are both far more common. I have tested both of these moves recently, but Black appears to have worked out some convincing replies.} 18. Rc5 Qd8 19. Qe4) (17... Qc7) 18. Rc5 (18. Rxb7 Nb4 19. Rc5 Nxc2 20. Rxa5 Bc6 21. Rbxa7 {with an equal position.} Rab8 {and}) 18... Qd8 (18... Qc7 19. Ng5) 19. Rxb7 Bc8 20. Rb1 Nxd4 ({moves such as} 20... Ne7 $5 {were also on the radar.} 21. Ng5 $2 {would be met strongly by:} Ng6 $1 $17 22. Bf3 {featured in the game Nakamura-Anand, Norway Chess 2015:}) 21. Nxd4 {Commital, and true to Fedoseev's style. White hints at a kingside attack though in truth this move is aimed at limiting the scope of Black's knight.} Qxd4 {This feels slightly too passive.} 22. Bf3 $1 {Further restricting the black knight.} Bd7 23. Bxa8 Rxa8 24. a5 (24. Rd1 Qxa4 $6 25. Qxa4 Bxa4 26. Rdc1 $14) 24... g6 25. Rd1 Qb4 $1 26. Qc4 Rb8 $11 {Now play is balanced.} 27. Qxb4 Rxb4 28. h3 (28. Rc7 Ba4 {changes nothing:} 29. Rd8+ Kg7 30. h3 $1 $14 {would keep an eye on the e6-knight and prevent Black's next.} a6 {would have been an immediate attempt to liquidate the centre:} 31. Ra8 Bb5 $132 {There was no reason to refrain from} 32. Raa7 $11 {with the simple idea of bringing the knight round to the newly-created outpost on e4.} Rf4 {might have been enough for a small (if somewhat symbolic) advantage:} 33. g3 Rf5 34. f4) 28... Bb5 29. Rd8+ Kg7 30. Rcc8 Rb1+ 31. Kh2 Rb2 32. Kg3 (32. g4 Rxf2+ $19 {and with a safe king the path to victory should be straightforward.} (32... g5 33. Kg3 Rb3+ 34. Kg2 Bd3 {with perpetual check.}) 33. Kg3 {was safer, blockading the a-pawn.} {It would have been pragmatic to try and force an immediate draw:} Ra2 34. g5) 32... Rb3+ (32... Re2 33. f4 $1 {(preventing Qe8+ ideas and attacking f5)} Ra2 34. Rg8+ Kh6 35. Rc7) 33. f3 Rb2 34. Rg8+ Kh6 35. Rc7 Bf1 36. Rxf7 (36. f4 Rxg2+ 37. Kf3 Rb2 38. Rxf7 Bg2+ 39. Kg3) 36... Rxg2+ (36... g5 37. f4 gxf4+ $1 {wins due to a strange type of zugzwang. White cannot give perpetual check, while it is impossible to keep both his king and bishop on the correct squares. One sample variation:} 38. Kh4) 37. Kf4 g5+ 38. Ke3 Re2+ 39. Kd4 Rd2+ 40. Ke3 Re2+ 41. Kd4 Rd2+ 42. Kc3 Rd3+ 43. Kc2 $6 {Knowing Fedoseev, he was still habouring hopes of a victory here. However Black's queen and knight are simply too active.} Ra3 (43... Rd5 44. Rxa7 Bxh3 (44... Rxe5 45. Rgg7 Rc5+ 46. Kd2 Rd5+ 47. Ke3 $11 {and now, as opposed to the variation with 60...Qb4!, Black cannot gain time by checking the white king.} Bd3 48. Rgd7) 45. a6 Ra5 (45... Bf5+ 46. Kc3) 46. Kb3 $1 {Now Black has no checks so he must abandon the a-pawn. Fedoseev now defends accurately to ensure the draw.} Bf1 47. Rc7 (47. Rf8 Bd3 48. Rd7 Bf5 $19 49. a7 $1 {draws, but once again this is difficult for the untrained human eye:}) 47... Bxa6 (47... Rxa6 48. Rc2 Rb6+ 49. Ka4 Ra6+ 50. Kb4 Rb6+ 51. Kc5 Rb5+ 52. Kd6 Rb4 53. Rh2+ {should also eventually lead to a draw, although Black can press forever.} Rh4 {would win} {while} 54. Rxh4+ {is similar to the variations above:} gxh4 55. Rg1 Bh3 56. Rh1 Bf5 57. Rxh4+) 48. Rc1 Rb5+ 49. Ka4 Rxe5 50. Rh1#) 44. f4 gxf4 $1 $15 {Vidit prevents any checks and prepares to push his a-pawn.} 45. Rxf4 Be2 (45... Bd3+ $2 {Letting the win slip for good.} 46. Kb2) 46. Rf6+ $6 Kh5 $17 47. Kd2 Bc4 (47... Bd3 {It is hard to criticise this, as Vidit has played superbly over the past dozen moves. Black could now have converted his advantage although the winning concept is still difficult to comprehend, even with engine assistance:} 48. Rf3 $2 {allowing Black another chance.}) 48. Rg7 h6 49. Rgg6 Rd3+ (49... Rxa5 50. Rxh6+ Kg5 51. Rfg6+ Kf5 52. Rg4) 50. Kc2 Rd8 51. Rxh6+ Kg5 52. Kc3 Bd5 53. Kd4 Bh1+ 54. Ke3 Bd5 55. Rhg6+ Kh5 56. Kf4 Rh8 57. h4 1/2-1/2


