1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nc6 3. d3 Bc5 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. c3 d6 6. O-O $6 O-O 7. Nbd2 a6 8. Bb3 Ba7 9. Re1 (9. h3 h6 10. Re1 Nh5 11. Nc4) (9. Nc4 h6 10. Be3 Be6 11. Re1 Re8 12. Bxa7 Rxa7 13. Ne3 Ra8 14. Bxe6 Rxe6 15. Nd5 Ne7 16. Nxf6+ Rxf6 17. d4 Ng6 18. dxe5 dxe5 19. Qxd8+ Rxd8 20. Rad1 Rfd6 21. Rxd6 Rxd6) 9... Ng4 $1 10. Re2 Kh8 11. h3 {As we have seen in the previous games, White should not rush to castle, so this seems the best continuation.} Nh6 $1 {Still, this move forces the white queen to an awkward position.} 12. Nf1 $8 f5 $1 {Now this check forces more concessions from White.} 13. Bxh6 $8 {Although it seems tempting for White to cover the check with a piece, this is probably the safest option.} gxh6 $1 {Compared to the 10.0-0? line, White is unlikely to be going to castle to the kingside here, as for now the queen is stuck on f1 and after h3-g4 this option seems even less attractive. Therefore, the bishop has no great utility on d6, but keeping the d-file opened can be useful as Black has plans to undermine the centre with moves like ...b7-b5 or ...c7-c6.} 14. exf5 Bxf5 15. Bd5 Qf6 $1 {A very nice manoeuvre, taking advantage of White's weak d3-square but also threatening to advance the f-pawn, which would give a big advantage to Black.} (15... Ne7 16. Be4 Ng6 {[%cal Yd3f3]} 17. Bxf5 $5 (17. Ng3 Bxe4 $1 {Preventing b4.} (17... Bxh3 18. gxh3 d5 19. Bf5) 18. Rxe4 (18. dxe4 Rxf3 19. gxf3 Nf4 20. Re1 Qh4) 18... d5 19. Rg4 (19. Rg4 Nf4 20. Nxe5 (20. Ne2 Nxh3+) 20... Bxf2+ 21. Kxf2 Nxd3+ 22. Kg1 Nxe5 23. Qd4 Qd6 24. Re1 Rae8 25. b4 Qb6)) (17. d4 Nf4 18. Re1 Bxh3 19. gxh3 Qd7) {because} 17... Rxf5 {seems natural, and indeed this was the best option:} 18. Re4 Nf4 {[%csl Yc6,Ye5] I like Black's position here, as the knights are stuck defending each other, Black keeps his nice d3 there and the queenside always offers attacking chances in view of the open b-file; here are some illustrative lines:} 19. Ng3 $5 Qg8 $1 {A good move to preserve the bishop and attack the knight with ...f7-f6 at some point.}) (15... Qd7 16. Kh2 Ne7 17. Bxb7 Rab8 18. Be4 Ng6 19. Rd2 Nf4 20. Bxf5 Rxf5 21. Ng3 Rg8) 16. Ng3 $8 Bd7 {would transpose to the game.} 17. d4 (17. Be4 Rg8 18. Kh2 Bxf2 19. Nh5 Qf7 20. Rxf2 Qxh5 $2 21. d4 {[%csl Rg7] Black has no satisfactory way to defend g7 now} exd4 22. cxd4 $18 {But here} d5 $5 {was better:} 23. Bc2 Raf8 24. Qd2 Bxh3 {Black is better organised than in the game.} 25. gxh3 $1 Rxf3 26. Rxf3 $1 $17 {is indicated by the computer as the best continuation, but I think it is a very non-human way to play.} Qxf3 $2 {would make White's life easier.}) 17... exd4 18. Bxc6 {White managed to castle just in time, but Black is able to pose new problems now.} bxc6 {Always a pleasant square to put the knight on.} 19. Nxd4 Rae8 $1 {A typical idea to shake White's centre.} 20. Rd2 $1 {White also finds the best reaction.} (20. Rc1 Rxe2 21. Qxe2 Bxd4 22. cxd4 Qxd4 23. Rc4 Qf6) (20. Rxe8 Qxf2+) 20... c5 21. Nc2 c4 22. Nd4 d5 23. Qf1 $5 $146 {Believe it or not, all these moves had been played before! I don't know when White's (and Black's) preparation finished, but this is the first new move, trying to solve the problems by force with the clear threat of f4-f5.} h5 $6 {Vidit didn't react well to White's idea, I'm not sure if he may have missed something in the variations,} 24. Qd1 (24. Nxh5 Qg5 25. Qd1 Bxh3 26. Ng3 Bg4 27. Qc2 c5) (24. Re1 h4 25. Rxe8 (25. Nge2 Bxh3) 25... Rxe8) 24... h4 25. Nf1 {White's pieces were hanging but this move keeps everything defended.} Bxd4 $1 {Vidit finds the best way to keep the tension.} (25... Bxh3) 26. cxd4 Bxh3 {White still has to deal with many pieces under attack.} 27. Ne3 (27. gxh3 Rg8+ 28. Kh2 Qf4+ 29. Kh1 Re1) 27... Qg5 {It is hard to blame Black for playing the most natural continuation.} 28. Kh1 Bd7 29. Rc1 h3 30. g3 c5 31. dxc5 $1 {A precise answer.} d4 32. Nxc4 Qd5+ 33. f3 Rxf3 $1 34. Kh2 Rxg3 35. Qh1 (35. Kxg3 Rg8+ 36. Kf2 Rg2+ 37. Kf1 Qf5+ 38. Ke1 Rg1+ 39. Ke2 Qe4+ 40. Kf2 Qg2#) 35... Rg2+ $1 {The game remained tense until the very end, and although Vidit managed to win, it was the kind of endgame that is decided by one small mistake.} 36. Rxg2 hxg2 37. Qxg2 Qh5+ 0-1


