{Before this game I had 6/8 and I needed a win to score a decent place. The good thing about Dubai open was that even the final round began at 17:30! So unlike the last rounds in other opens I felt quite fresh and ready to fight!} 1. Nf3 {Postny,Evgeny} d5 2. c4 c6 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. O-O Nbd7 6. Qc2 Nb6 7. a4 a5 {A relatively new move in the a3 system. The direct approach was pioneered by Sutovsky. This move prepares for direct confrontation in the centre with d5.} 8. Na3 Nfd5 9. Nxc4 Nb4 10. Qb3 Nxc4 {A useful move to get in. I can sometimes go e5-d4 without fearing g5.  Postny,Evgeny: 'A useful prophylactic move. Black wants to play e6-e5, meanwhile robbingWhite's bishop of the g5-square.'} 11. Qxc4 {Postny,Evgeny: 'Otherwise Black will comfortably push e6-e5, followed by d5-d4.'} Be6 12. Qc3 Nd5 {Black has emerged out of the opening phase with no problems. But the nature of the position got me worried. It was the last round and I had to win in order to end the tournament with a decent place.} 13. Qe5 (13. Qd4 $11 Nb4 {it is important to provoke Black's rook to e8 to set some problems.}) 13... Nb4 14. Ra3 (14. b3 Bxb3 15. Qc3 Bd5 16. Re1 f6 (16... e6 17. e4 Ba2 $11 18. d4) 17. Ba3 e5 18. e4 $1 $19 Bf7 19. d4 exd4 {just keeps things equal.} 20. Nxd4 {I couldn't find a way to pose White problems if White just moves the rook from the c-file. The position is too symmetrical for any tricks.} Bd6 (20... Be7 21. Rad1) 21. Rad1 Qc7 22. e5 fxe5 $11 {looked like the most simple and straightforward way.} 23. Nf5 O-O-O 24. Bb2) 14... Qd6 (14... Bd5 15. Re3 (15. d4 $19 e6 (15... f6 16. Qf4 g5 17. Qg4 $17 Qd7) 16. Bd2 Qd6 17. Qh5) 15... e6 16. b3 Qf6 17. Bb2 {is probably cleaner, but during the game it looked simpler to stop e4-f5.} Be7 18. Bc3 {was my intention.} Qxe5 19. Nxe5 f6 20. Nc4 Kf7) 15. Qc3 $6 {This move doesn't exactly set Black any problems and passes over the initiative.} Nd5 16. Qd4 Nb4 17. Qb6 Bc8 18. d4 Ra6 (18... f6 19. Bf4 Qd7 20. e4 $19 {[%csl Ga7,Rb5,Gb6][%cal Ga3a4,Ga4b4] would eventually win.}) 19. Qc5 {After a lot of exchanges the position looks very dull. It should be completely equal, but White still needs to play a few decent moves.} Qxc5 {Postny,Evgeny: 'Black equalised easily and in the forthcoming positional battle even managed to prevail. '} 20. dxc5 $6 {Although this doesn't change the equilibrium, fixing the pawns on light squares doesn't look right.} e5 21. Nxe5 Bxc5 22. Rd1 $4 {Postny,Evgeny: '?' This move just loses a pawn directly.} Be6 {Postny,Evgeny: '!'} 23. e4 (23. Nd3 Nxd3 24. Raxd3 O-O 25. Bd2) 23... Ra8 24. Rc3 b6 25. Bf1 Ke7 26. Rxc5 bxc5 27. Be3 Rhd8 {Black has a clear advantage now. One of the a-pawns is doomed to fall, and White doesn't have a completely smooth pawn structure on the kingside either.} 28. Rc1 f6 29. Bxc5+ Ke8 30. Bxb4 axb4 {Not allowing any mess with a5. My plan was to bring the king to the queenside and attack one of the a-pawns with the rooks. White's pieces are too passive for any counterplay.} 31. Rxc6 (31. Nxc6 Rdc8 32. Bb5 Bd7 33. Rc4 b3 34. Kg2) 31... Bb3 32. Nd3 Bxa4 33. Rb6 Rab8 34. Rxb4 Rxb4 35. Nxb4 Rd2 36. Nd5 Rxb2 37. Ne3 Bc6 38. Bd3 Rb4 39. e5 fxe5 40. Bxh7 Bf3 41. Bc2 g5 42. h3 Rd4 43. Kh2 Rd2 44. g4 e4 45. Kg3 Kd7 (45... Kf7 46. h4 gxh4+ 47. Kxh4 Kf6 48. Kg3 Kg5 49. Bb3 Rb2 50. Bf7 Rb1 51. Bd5 Rc1 {After an unexpected Round 6 loss with White I scored 3/3 in the end with a decent shared 2nd place. It was nice to end the tournament on a positive note and also to break into the top 100 :)} 52. Bc4 {was a bit prettier? ;)} Bxg4 {might've put up a more stubborn defence, but I don't think it would change the evaluation of the position by much.} 53. f4+) 46. h4 gxh4+ {The rest is pretty easy.} 47. Kxh4 Rxf2 48. Kg3 Rd2 49. Kf4 Bh1 50. Ke5 Rd6 51. Ba4+ Kc7 52. Bc2 Rd8 53. g5 Re8+ 54. Kd4 Re6 55. g6 Rxg6 56. Bxe4 Bxe4 57. Kxe4 Kd6 58. Kd4 Re6 59. Nc4+ 0-1


