1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 Nf6 7. f4 {In this variation the knight on c2 is a bit passive and also does not control the important c5-square.} Bb4 8. Bd3 d6 9. Nxc6 (9. Qf3) 9... bxc6 $1 {The isolated d-pawn structure is fine for Black who leads in development and controls d4 which stops White from establishing a blockade with d4. White is developed passively and after the aggressive development ...g4, Black has a slightly better position.} 10. O-O e5 $1 (10... c5 11. e5 $15 Bxc3 12. bxc3 $15 Nd5 {This recapture leaves a White with a weak c4 isolated pawn which is high price to play to get in the natural g2.} 13. Bf2 Bb7 14. Qg4 Ne7 15. Rad1) (10... O-O 11. e5 $17 dxe5 {likely transposes to the game, for example after} (11... Nd5 12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. Kh1 $1 Bc5 14. Bd2 $1 f6 15. exf6 Qxf6 16. Bc3 d4 17. Be1 $132 Bb7 18. Qg4) 12. fxe5 Nd5 13. Bd2 Qh4 14. Ne4 $1 {This an important move that allows Black to immediately equalise.} Bxd2 15. Qxd2 $1) 11. h3 $6 {A bad move. White now has several weak pawns and the bishop on g2 is blocked by the f3-pawn.} (11. fxe5 Ng4 12. Qf3 Nxe5) 11... O-O (11... exf4 12. Bxf4 $1 O-O (12... Nd7 13. Bc4) 13. e5 Bxc3 14. bxc3 $17 {Wei Yi-So Wesley, Internet 2018} dxe5 $6 {(Lubczynski-Gritsak, Legnica 2013)} 15. Bxe5 $1 {improves on the game for a couple of reasons. Black wants to use the open d-file (intending ..0-0, d8). Also after xc4 the light squared-bishop is misplaced, as normally the bishop would go to g2.} Nd5 16. Qh5 f5 17. Rae1 Qe8 18. Qh4 $17 Qd8 19. Qd4) 12. fxe5 $2 {The losing move.} (12. Qf3 exf4 13. Bxf4 Nd7 14. Bc4 (14. Qg3 Qe7 15. Kh1 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Ne5 17. Rab1 Qc7 18. Qe3 Be6 $11 19. Qb6 $6 Rfc8 20. a4 a5) 14... Qe7 {Followed by b2, the position is roughly equal.} 15. Qg3 {Black makes the thematic advance which liquidates the isolated pawn and after a long forcing computer variation, the position fizzles out to a draw.} Kh8 16. Bb3 Ne5 $1 17. Rad1 f6 $1 18. Kh1 Rb8 19. Ne2 Bd7 20. c3 Bc5 21. Bc1 Be6) (12. f5 d5) 12... dxe5 $1 13. Na4 Be6 $1 {Black makes the thematic advance to open the position and start a direct attack. The position is hopeless for White.} 14. Qe2 Nd7 15. Bc4 Re8 16. Rad1 Qc7 $19 17. Kh2 Bf8 18. b3 a5 19. Rf2 (19. Bxe6 Rxe6 $11 20. Rd3) 19... Rab8 20. c3 Nf6 21. Bg5 {This was the way to prolong the game but Black will still have a better position, with an extra pawn.} (21. Bxe6 Rxe6 $1 22. Nc5 Bxc5 23. Bxc5) 21... Bxc4 22. Qxc4 Be7 23. Be3 Qb7 24. Bb6 Bd8 25. Bxd8 Rexd8 $17 26. Rfd2 $1 {This is the only move, but eventually Black will have a slight advantage in the endgame.} Rxd2 27. Rxd2 Qb5 28. Qxb5 cxb5 29. Nc5 h5 $1 30. Nd7 Nxe4 $15 {Two minor pieces are usually better than a rook and a pawn and this position is no exception.} 31. Rd5 $2 Nxc3 $18 32. Rc5 $2 Rd8 $1 $16 33. Nxe5 {is a slightly passive move.} Rd5 34. Rxc3 {(Moroni-B.Szabo, Gabicce Mare 2013)} Rxe5 $1 35. a3 h4 $14 36. Kg1 {Avoiding the complications that would arise from giving up the d-pawn after 10...g4 11.xd5} Re1+ 37. Kf2 Rb1 38. Rc8+ Kh7 39. Ra8 Rb2+ 40. Kg1 $132 Rxb3 $2 {Taking the d-pawn fails because White is left with too many hanging pieces after} 41. Rxa5 Rb2 42. a4 $1 $19 {This is the nice tactical point, the rook escapes the attack and defends the d1, while White is left with two hanging knights.} bxa4 $2 43. Rxa4 g5 44. Ra5 Kg6 45. Rc5 $19 {[%csl Rc2,Rd3]} Rb1+ 46. Kf2 $17 0-1


