{[%evp 0,131,29,-19,26,19,12,12,12,14,31,30,29,30,39,6,1,-16,-23,-23,-47,-47,-47,-46,-30,-30,-30,-61,-55,-48,-48,-53,-53,-53,-53,-53,-34,-124,-86,-86,-63,-71,-71,-71,-67,-59,-73,-52,-54,-59,-27,-33,-33,-57,-63,-55,-38,-38,-62,-31,0,0,92,98,121,71,98,79,69,69,69,70,58,58,90,99,99,99,131,91,193,208,224,224,219,217,219,224,238,223,244,217,239,227,258,286,275,275,275,275,287,287,287,287,300,262,300,292,292,268,350,123,123,123,126,134,132,128,130,127,207,188,408,399,833,972,1229,1237,1292,1314,1334,1431,1576,1720] I had lost the previous game due to a stupid blunder, so I was hoping to fix my mistake today! Also previously I had never won in a must-win situation in the World Cup before, so I was looking forward to changing my destiny!!} 1. d4 {This looked like an interesting choice!} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 c6 {I wasn't expecting this, now I realized that high chances for the game to end in a draw :)!} (6... Ne4 7. Rc1 Nc6) (6... O-O 7. e3 Bf5 8. Qb3) 7. e3 $5 {[%cal Gg5d8] I managed to pull myself together and found a line where I couldn't see any clear way to forced equality!} Bf5 8. a3 (8. Qb3 Qb6) 8... Bd6 {Greedy VD :), I couldn't believe that he wanted to win the d5-pawn :).} (8... Be7 9. Nh4 Be6 10. Bd3) 9. Ne5 {[%cal Gb3d5] I wanted to fight for my equal rights :).} (9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. Nh4 Be6 11. Bd3) 9... Qe7 (9... Nbd7 10. Nxf7 Kxf7 11. Bxd6) (9... O-O 10. g4 Be6 (10... Bxe5 11. dxe5 Nxg4 12. h3 Nh6 13. Qf3) 11. Bd3 c5 12. g5 Ne8 13. dxc5 Bxe5 14. Bxe5 Qxg5 15. Bd4) 10. Qf3 Bg6 (10... Nbd7 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Qxf5) (10... g6 11. Bg5 h5 (11... Bxe5 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. g4) 12. Bd3 Bxe5 13. dxe5 Qxe5 14. Bxf5 gxf5 15. Bf4 Qe7 16. Ne2) (10... O-O 11. Nxc6 Nxc6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Qxf5) (10... Qe6 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. Nxd3 O-O 13. Bxd6 Qxd6) 11. h4 {[%csl Gd1] I felt the king is doing fine on d1, due to the shelter provided by the d4-pawn.} Nh5 12. Nxg6 fxg6 (12... hxg6 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. e4) 13. Bxd6 $5 {[%csl Yb4][%cal Gh1e1] The computer didn't like this decision, but to be honest I don't think it understood my play for quite a while :) in this game!} Qxd6 14. e4 {Trying to remove the bishop from the a5-e1 diagonal, so that I can prepare Re1.} dxe4 (14... Qf4 15. Qxf4 Nxf4 16. g3 Ne6 17. O-O-O) 15. Nxe4 (15. Qxe4+ Qe7) 15... Qe7 (15... Qxd4 16. Rd1 Qe5 17. Bc4 Nf6 18. O-O) 16. Bc4 {[%cal Ga4a5,Ga4e8,Gh1e1] GO BACK SIMON!} Nd7 (16... Nf6 17. O-O-O) 17. Bf7+ (17. O-O-O O-O-O 18. Ng5) 17... Kf8 18. Bxg6+ $3 {[%cal Ge8d8,Gc2b1] I was very proud of this move! My main concern was the king's safety and If I can get it to safety then I can play for attack without any concern!} (18. Bb3+ Nhf6 19. Bc2) (18. Ba2+ Ndf6 19. O-O Qxe4 20. Qb3 Nd5 21. Qxb7 Re8 22. Rae1 Qxe1 23. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 24. Kh2) 18... Nhf6 {I was happy to see this, as I felt the king would be nicely placed on d8! On the kingside, I can create some play against his majesty!} 19. Bf5 {Now that my king is safe, it is time to begin the onslaught!} g6 (19... Nxe4 20. Qxe4 Qxe4+ 21. Bxe4 Re8 22. f3 Nf6 23. O-O) 20. Bxd7 Qxe4+ 21. Qxe4 {I have a clear target... The Black king!!} Nxe4 {I was happy to see this, as I felt it was going to take some effort to win the fight for the key open file!} 22. Bg4 Kg7 {This I felt weakens his king even more!} 23. Rd1 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gf3e4] Firmly stopping the pawn advance and Black is left with too many weaknesses to defend.} Nf6 24. Be2 $1 {[%cal Rb5b7,Gb5e5,Gc1e1] A very nice preparing the deadly Re1 and also trying to provoke a6!} Rae8 25. Rh3 $1 {Continuing the act of provocation, I guess VD didn't understand what I was up to... (In my defence I also didn't know myself :), neither does the computer :)).} Nd5 26. Rf3 Re7 27. Kf1 Rd8 28. g3 {Forcing e3!} Red7 29. Rfd3 $1 {[%cal Gf1f7] Finally the plan is clear, I am going to play for domination and Black's pawns are useless :)!} Ne7 (29... h5 30. Bf3 Ne7 31. Be4 Rd6) 30. Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gd1g4,Gg4h5] The queen is coming to h5 or g4 with a lot of destructive power!} Nf5 {Panic! This only prolongs the inevitable :)!} (30... Rd6 31. Re1 Nd5) 31. Bxf5 gxf5 32. Re1 $3 {[%csl Gh1][%cal Ge2d3] Keeping the rooks at any cost!! I think VD didn't expect this epic rook move which keeps the tension and now things are hopeless for Black!} (32. Rf3 Rxd4 (32... Rd5 33. Rc1 Kf6 34. Rc5) 33. Rxd4 Rxd4 34. Rxf5) 32... f4 33. Re4 {Preparing Re1, if the rook joins the fight then it's over!} (33. gxf4 Kf6 34. Rb3 (34. Re4 c5) 34... Rc7 35. Re4 Rd5 36. Kg2) 33... fxg3 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Gd1h5] Desperately trying to stop the rook from getting activated!} 34. Rxg3+ Kf6 35. Rf3+ {One step at a time! c1 is better than h1.} Kg6 36. Rff4 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Gd1d3] Now the queen has to retreat to stop Qd7 penetration.} Rd6 {An error allowing me to get what I wanted!} 37. Ke2 $1 {[%cal Gb4f8,Gd1e1] Attacking the rook and preparing Re1!} Rf6 38. Rg4+ {Now f-file is equally destructive!} Kf7 39. Ke3 $1 {[%cal Gb5h5] Preparing to go Qh5 and Rf7.} Rdd6 40. Re5 {[%csl Rb7] This was the idea behind Qb5, now Rf8 loses the b7-pawn!} h6 41. Rge4 Rd7 42. h5 {Channeling Greedy VD against the Master :)!} a6 43. a4 Rfd6 44. a5 {Keeping the king locked in!} Rd5 45. Rxd5 {Time to improve the pawn structure and create a mating net around the black king!} (45. b4) 45... Rxd5 46. Re5 {[%csl Rh8]} Rd8 47. Ke4 Rg8 48. d5 $1 {[%cal Gh3h7,Gh3h2] A cute retreat winning the h7-pawn.} cxd5+ 49. Rxd5 Ke6 {I already saw that the bishop endgame was winning, but wanted to get it in the most ideal scenario and also felt maybe I can win keeping the queens on the board!} 50. Re5+ (50. f4 Rg2 51. f5+ Ke7 52. b4 Rg4+ (52... Rb2 53. Ke5 Re2+ 54. Kd4 Kf6 55. Rd6+) 53. Ke5 Rxb4 54. f6+ Kf8 55. Ke6 Re4+ 56. Kf5 Rb4 57. Kg6) 50... Kf6 51. b4 Rg1 52. Rc5 Re1+ 53. Kf4 {[%csl Gd5] A dominating post for the queen!} Rb1 54. Rc4 Rh1 55. Kg4 Rg1+ 56. Kf4 $1 {I just wanted to get this move in to avoid any saving chances for Black!} Rh1 57. Kg4 {[%csl Yd4,Gg6][%cal Ge4g6,Ge4d3] The endgame is easily winning due to the same diagonal principle where the bishop supports the pawn and also stops the enemy passed pawn!} Rg1+ 58. Kf3 {I just had to make sure not to blunder like in the first game :)!} Rg5 (58... Rb1 59. Ke4 Ke6 (59... Kg5 60. f4+ Kxh5 61. Kf5) 60. f4 Re1+ (60... Rb2 61. f5+ Kf6 62. Kd4 Kxf5 63. Kc5) 61. Kd3 {looked horrible for me with a winning attack for Black.} Rd1+ (61... Kd5 62. Rc7) (61... Kd6 62. Rd4+ Kc6 63. f5) 62. Ke3 Rb1 (62... Re1+ 63. Kd2 Rb1 64. Kc2 Rh1 65. Rc7) 63. Kd4 {also looks bad.} Kd6 {looked very interesting and it was a complete mess after} 64. Ke4 Rh1 (64... Ke6 65. f5+ Kf6 66. Kd5 Kxf5 67. Kc5) 65. Rc5 (65. Kf5 Rxh5+ 66. Kg6 Rh4) 65... Rb1 66. Kf5 Rxb4 67. Re5) 59. Rc5 Rxc5 ({My first intention was} 59... Rg7 {to continue to bully the bishop but...} 60. Ke4 $1) 60. bxc5 Kg5 61. Ke4 Kxh5 62. Kf5 (62. Ke5 Kg6 {[%cal Gc8c7,Gd8b8] followed by Rc7 and Kc8 if needed!} 63. f4 {was safer maybe} h5 $1 64. Ke6 Kg7 {[%csl Ya4,Yc6][%cal Gb3a4] Black queen can't stop Qa4 anymore!} 65. Ke7 Kg6 $1 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Ga4a5,Gh1e1]} 66. Ke6 Kg7 {Now the situation is completely different, but still I wasn't sure and wanted to avoid this if possible :).}) 62... Kh4 63. f4 h5 64. Ke5 (64. Ke6 {[%cal Ge7b4] was the way to fight!} Kg3 65. f5 {The king is a bit safer here than on h8 still, it should be very good for white...But I felt the game continuation was stronger!} h4 66. f6 h3 67. f7 {Surprisingly Black is going to find out that the attack is very difficult to defend against...while the bishop and the pawns are silent spectators!} {I rejected} h2 {due to} 68. f8=Q $1 {I didn't want to allow the bishop to come back! (of course stupid comp doesn't understand this simple concept and recommends 25.Re1!)} h1=Q 69. Qd6+ {[%csl Rb6,Rb7][%cal Gb3b7] Now the b6-bishop will constantly need the supervision of the queen!} {My original intention was} Kf2 {but then thought that Black can go} 70. Kd7 $1 {Just like my king which is very safe thanks to the d-pawn as a shelter...Black can also do the same :)!}) 64... Kg4 65. f5 {I will win the bishop for the a-pawn and then collect the d4-pawn leading to a win.} h4 66. f6 {I was very happy to pull off this epic win taking the match into tiebreaks! Winning in a must-win situation always gives you special happiness and also I was proud of the level I showed in this game :)!} h3 67. f7 h2 68. f8=Q h1=Q 69. Qg7+ {[%cal Gb4b8] and the queenside pawn shall promote :)!} 1-0


