{[%evp 0,99,80,16,61,8,62,20,45,-92,-38,-147,-95,-63,-51,-55,9,7,75,70,75,-54,62,-20,6,-11,-28,0,-24,43,31,32,21,26,24,26,32,28,27,21,10,10,14,7,5,10,3,9,9,7,7,9,19,26,5,13,13,2,33,26,17,13,9,16,10,0,38,61,71,70,144,104,95,0,72,25,100,-44,369,411,497,497,497,495,505,505,505,505,505,893,901,893,893,938,938,952,982,982,29995,29996,29997,29998]} 1. e4 {Jan-Krzystztof Duda is not known to be going down long forcing lines, but in this game it was exactly what happened.} c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e6 {Vidit has previously shown a few of his weapons against 1.e4 and the Archangelsk was the latest and the most succesful one, as he managed to beat Vasif Durarbeyli with it, in the previous round. It obviously wouldn't come as a surprise any longer and JKD goes on to blitz out the next few moves.} 7. f3 {Clever to start with this and not after 7.c3 d6, because now 8.a4 allows the option of 8...Bg4 as well.} b5 8. a3 {Durarbeyli, who is a very experienced and a very strong Grand Master, with an excellent track record, went for the 8.Nxe5 variation, which also shows up at the highest level a lot.} Nbd7 9. g4 h6 10. Qd2 {This has been very trendy for a while. The point is that 10...Nxa5? loses to 11.Rxa5! Bxa5 12.dxe5!, while if Black goes 10...Ba7, then after 11.h3 0-0 12.Be3, Black has to deal with some tactics as the a7 bishop is under protected.} Bb7 11. O-O-O Rc8 {This is the latest trend, intending to go for the direct complications with 12.Be3 Nxe4!?. On the black side we have games of Grischuk, Dubov, Caruana, Aronian and the last one before this game, was actually played by myself against Grischuk in the Zagreb rapid.} (11... d5 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 14. Bg2) (11... Ne5) 12. h4 {White could also start with 12.Re1, which is what Harikrishna did against Fabiano in Wijk aan Zee this year.} d5 {That's the point. These complications have existed for a few years already, but it was only this year that the line has exploded and people stopped avoiding this with both colours.} (12... Nb6) 13. Rg1 {The most direct test, but 13.Re1 has been played here too.} (13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Be2 Ne5 16. Kb1 Qc7 17. Rhe1 Nc4 (17... Be7 18. Bf4 Nc4 19. Bxc4 Qxc4) 18. Bxc4 Qxc4 19. b3 Qc7 (19... Qc3 20. Qxc3 Rxc3 21. Nxb5 axb5 (21... Rc8) 22. Rxd5 Rxb3+ 23. cxb3 exd5) 20. Bf4) 13... dxe4 14. g5 hxg5 {Forced complications.} 15. hxg5 {The consensus is that this is the best.} Nd5 16. Nxe4 (16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. g6 f5 (17... f6 $1) (17... exf3 18. gxf7+ Kxf7 19. Nxf3 Bxf3 20. Qf2 Qf6 21. Rxd7+ Ke8) 18. fxe4 fxe4 (18... Bxe4 19. Nxe6 Bxc2 20. Nxd8 Be4+ 21. Qc3 Rxc3+ 22. bxc3 {½-½ (31) Grischuk,A (2778)-Giri,A (2776) Zagreb 2021} Bxa3+ $2 23. Kd2 $1 Kxd8) 19. Kb1) 16... g6 (16... Qb6 $3 {and the complications end in a draw. Unfindable stuff, but possible to memorize.} 17. g6 f6 {is how my game with Grischuk went and a few prepared moves down the line, he picked a move repetition.}) (16... Nxe3 17. Qxe3 Qb6 (17... g6 18. Nxe6 fxe6 19. Nf6+) 18. g6 f6 19. Rg3) 17. Bf2 b4 {And here White is at a principled crossroad. There are two attempts, as there are two bishops that can be captured.} (17... Be7 $1 18. Kb1 Kf8 19. Bg2) 18. axb4 $5 Nxb4 {In 2013, in the game betweed Adhiban and Ashwin, Black wasn't aware of this forced line just yet and played 18...Bc8?.} (18... Bxb4 19. c3 Be7 (19... Nc5 20. Nxc5 Bxc5 21. Nxe6 fxe6 22. Bxc5 Qa5 {and Black is apparently ok, as he can combine the relative instability of White's queenside pawns with the advance of his own kingside soldiers. This wasn't easy to go for, but it had to be done, as the move in the game just loses by force.} (22... Rxc5 23. Qd4 {here Black has to know a couple of important moves to reach the desired 0.00.}) 23. Ba3 $2 Rxc3+ $1 24. bxc3 {Keeping control of the f4 square was much better, with the direct 32...Rf5 or first this.} Qxa3+ 25. Qb2 Qxc3+ 26. Qxc3 {and Black manages to keep the knight at bay and wants to start pushing his kingside. The position is still very much drawish.} Nxc3 $5 27. Rd4) 20. Kb1 Nc5 21. Nxc5 Bxc5 22. Bc4 (22. Nxe6 fxe6 23. Bxc5 Rxc5 {A crucial win, for the eventual World Cup winner.} 24. c4 $1 {leads to a defendable position. Black gives up a pawn, but gets rid of the main issue, the passed a5 pawn.} (24. Qd4 {Black holds.} Rh4 {There are also other tries.}) 24... Qb6 25. cxd5 Bxd5) 22... Qc7 23. Bb3) 19. Nxe6 Bxe4 $1 {The crucial intermezzo, intending to throw out the d8 queen with a check.} (19... fxe6 20. Qxd7+ $1 {Grabbing the a-file before collecting the a6 pawn. The a5 pawn is now unstoppable and Black is just losing by force. Note that with the king on f3 Black would now have counterplay thanks to g4+ and Rb3-xc3 check, but now that the king is on h1, the counterplay is much too slow.} Qxd7 21. Nf6+ Kf7 {The last attempt, but JKD is merciless.} 22. Rxd7+ $1 {Leads to a major piece endgame in which White gets to check first and Black's king has nowhere to hide.} Be7 23. Rxb7 Rxc2+ 24. Kb1 Rxf2 25. Ng4 Rd2 26. Bc4 Nc6 {All forced so far. Now White starts checking and the king just ends up getting mated.} 27. Rc7) 20. Nxd8 $1 {Forced as well. Now Black has no checks.} Rxc2+ {After the game JKD said that he expected Vidit to follow a correspondence game with 20...0-0 which leads to a draw. There seems to be nothing wrong with Vidit's solution either.} 21. Qxc2 {The best. Now we reach an endgame by force.} Bxc2 22. Nxf7 Rh2 23. Rd2 Nc5 (23... Kxf7 24. Rxd7+ $1 {Duda makes one nasty move after the other. Here already I started feeling the heat for Vidit, but the engine still pointed out a cleacut solution- 31...Kh6! 32.Nd3 g5!.} Ke6 $6 {Fishing for a move repetition is tempting, but it just doesn't bring Black the desired result.} 25. Rd2) (23... Bb3 $2 {Continuing with the wrong intention. White doesn't have to take the draw and this only gives White more time.} 24. Nh6 $1 {Now Black is suddenly in serious trouble. He has to allow either Nb4 or Nf4.}) (23... Bc5 {Correct, as 33...c5 34.Nf4! was just losing, with Kf3 coming next and Black's kingside pawns not able to move.} 24. Bxc5 {Black has to answer very hard questions, but objectively this seems to still be within the drawing margin of the game.} Nxc5 $2 {Very tempting, but Vidit has missed JKD's strong sequence.} 25. Bc4 $1 {The king is now not in the way of any checks, neither by the pawns nor by the rook. A very aesthetically pleasing solution.}) 24. Rd8+ Kxf7 {This is an endgame both players went for. White has a knight for 3 pawns which is a very fine material allocation for the second player, but he does have to watch out a little bit, as the a6 pawn is fixed by the a5 pawn and if the knight is ever to land on b4, Black could get under pressure.  But that will never happen... or will it?} 25. Rxf8+ Kg7 {I didn't like this particular solution, although it is not a bad move objectively, as the game stays well within the drawable margin. It felt more practical to include 25...b4 26.c4, to get some counterplay with Re8-Re5, or alternatively go for 25...g5!?, giving the king a nice square on g6 behind the pawns and not in front of them.} 26. Bd4+ {An annoying check.} Kxf8 {Allowing the rook trade and going for a very concrete knight vs pawns endgame is not something you want to be dealing with this early in the game, but now the king is somewhat awkwardly placed in front of its pawns.} 27. Bxc5+ $1 {Strong. The g-file is free for the rook and the king takes it upon himself to stop the invasion of the rook.} Ke8 {Black wants to slowly start pushing his kingside pawns.} 28. Bxb4 Bf5 29. Bc3 $5 {29.Nf3 may seem automatic at first, but this is a much more clever way to stop the pawns, intending Ne4+.} Rc2+ 30. Kd1 1-0


