{[%evp 0,76,5,27,40,40,39,13,8,-17,-22,-63,-36,17,17,-40,9,-13,37,13,67,70,63,-55,-4,-23,13,13,37,-1,-1,-18,8,13,11,-6,2,-42,-29,-29,-17,-34,-39,-39,-40,-40,-25,-31,-26,-54,-18,-63,-49,-71,-66,-71,-62,-62,-155,-207,-202,-204,-266,-279,-158,-229,-108,-223,-228,-265,-301,-301,-361,-545,-621,-675,-328,-429,-397] This was the 1st time in my World Cup experience that I had gone beyond Round 3. All the matches so far had been quite hard fought and this one was no exception. In the 1st game, after I missed a winning chance, I was lost for the most part but Durarbeyli hadn't been able to finish it off.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Ng5 Ngf6 6. Bd3 g6 {I hadn't played the Archangelsk before, but that didn't seem to surprise my opponent too much. He blitzed out his next moves anyways.} 7. N1f3 Bg7 8. Qe2 O-O 9. h4 h6 10. h5 gxh5 11. Nh3 Re8 12. Bf4 c5 13. O-O-O (13. c3 cxd4 14. cxd4 Nf8) 13... cxd4 $5 $146 {An interesting direct approach to target the dark-squared bishop. Also, a move which made my opponent finally stop and have a think.} 14. Ne5 (14. Bc4 e5 15. Bxe5 (15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. Bxe5 Bg4 17. f3 Nd5)) 14... Nc5 15. Bc4 Be6 16. Bxe6 Nxe6 17. c4 b5 {A slight inaccuracy. Starting directly with b4 would avoid some options.} (17... Qc8 18. Kb1 Ng4 19. Nxg4 hxg4 20. Qxg4 Nxf4 21. Qxf4 Qxc4) 18. cxb5 a6 (18... Qd5 19. Kb1 Ng4) 19. bxa6 {The position felt fairly equal. So far, I had played all my moves at a fast speed. I realized that if White manages to play c2-c3 and remove the bishop, he would be quite comfortable.} Qa5 $1 {A very tricky move, which I feel made me win the game! Vasif thought that e6-g4 was the only threat in the position. But, I had a cunning idea up my sleeve.} 20. a3 $6 Rxa6 $1 21. Kb1 Rea8 $1 (21... Nd5 22. Qxh5 (22. Nd3 Nc3+) 22... Nc3+) 22. Rd3 (22. Bd2) 22... Qd5 (22... Nd5 23. Bd2 Qb5) 23. Re1 Nc5 {Now we see the point of b6. I could have reached the same position without h3 & b6 included, but then White could have played a2 and freed the bishop.} 24. Rf3 Re6 {It's important to keep the bishop on b1 boxed in! Now if I manage to get my knight to c4-d2, it would just be winning. Although, it's not easy as my c3 pawn is constantly under pressure.} 25. Qb5 Ng4 $1 {Important decision. Initially I was trying all the queen moves to protect c3 and then bring the knight to d2. But, in all the lines White gets some sort of counterplay.} (25... Nfd7) 26. Nd3 {In order to play f4.} Rxe1+ {Defending the pawn in order to play c4-d2. Surprisingly, White had an unexpected defensive idea here.} 27. Nxe1 $6 {Missing the only chance in the game.} Qe4+ $1 {Now everything is secure. There is no way for White to stop the idea of e5-c4-d2.} (27... e5) 28. Nd3 Rc8 29. Qc4 Rc6 (29... e5 30. Bd2 Qg6) 30. Ka2 Nd7 31. Qb3 {The attack on the kingside looked dangerous, but it's harmless. The key for Black is not to hurry in capturing the bishop on b1, it's dead anyways. Once he brings back his  in defense, White is doomed.} (31. Qb5) 31... Rb6 32. Nb4 (32. Qc4 Qb7 33. Rg3 e5) 32... Nde5 $1 $19 33. Rg3 (33. Qd5 Qxd5+ 34. Nxd5 Rb5 35. Nxe7+ Kf8 36. Bxe5 Nxe5 37. Rf5 d3 38. f4 d2 39. Nf2 Kxe7 40. fxe5 Rc5 41. Rf3 Rxe5 42. Kb1 h4 43. Kc2 Rg5) 33... Nc6 34. Bd2 Qe2 (34... h4) 35. Qd3 Qe6+ 36. Qb3 Qe2 $1 {Finally the poor soul is captured!} 37. Qd3 Qe6+ (37... Nxb4+ 38. Bxb4 Qe6+ 39. Qb3 Qd7) 38. Kb1 Nce5 {My opponent resigned and I was through to Quarterfinals! I received many nice messages after the game, but the message of my coach Alon Greenfeld stood out: " Congrats,Vidit for the win, in my long career, I have never seen a pawn on the 1st rank!" That aptly summarizes the game! :)} (38... h4 39. Nf4 Nxb4 40. Bxb4 Qd7) 39. Qe4 (39. Qb3 Qg6+ 40. Qc2) 39... Nc4 $19 (39... h4 40. Nf4 (40. Rxg4 Qxg4) 40... hxg3 41. Nxe6 gxf2 42. Qa8+ (42. Qe2 Rxe6) 42... Kh7 43. Qe4+ Ng6) 40. Qxe6 Rxe6 {Direct.} 41. Bc1 Re1 {[%cal Gc4d2] doesn't lead to much} 42. Nd3 $3 Rf1 {It looks like the bishop on b1 is lost, but White gets unexpected counterplay on the kingside.} 43. Nhf4 $1 Nce5 $1 {Keeping an eye on the king.} (43... Nd2+ 44. Kc2 Ne4 45. Rf3 Ng5 46. Rg3 Nf6) 44. a4 h4 45. Rh3 $1 Nxf2 46. Nxf2 $1 Rxf2 47. a5 $1 $11 {And finally with a series of accurate moves, the white bishop gets a second life :)} Nc6 48. a6 $3 {followed by either Rd7 or f6.} e5 {White has an unexpected resource here as well. Chess is full of amazing ideas, sadly they usually are left behind the scenes as humans can't yet play like Stockfish!} 49. Nd5 Bf8 (49... Kh7) 50. Bxh6 $3 {Black has bank rank problems!} e4 (50... Bxh6 51. Ne7+ Nxe7 52. a7) 51. Rxh4 Rf1+ (51... Bxh6 52. Ne7+ Kg7 53. Nxc6 d3 54. Rxe4 d2 55. Rg4+ Kh7 56. Rd4 Be3 (56... Rf1+ 57. Ka2 Rf4 58. Rxd2 Ra4+ 59. Kb3 Rxa6 60. Nb4) 57. Rh4+ Kg7 58. Rh1 Rf6) 52. Ka2 Rf5 $1 53. Rg4+ Kh7 54. Bxf8 Rxd5 55. Rxe4 d3 56. Re1 Ra5+ 57. Kb3 Rxa6 $11 {leads to a crazy draw.} 58. Kc3 {with the same idea of e5-c4 was more effective.} Nd8 59. Kxd3 $1 Ne6 60. Rh1+ $1 {and the pin is really annoying.} Kg6 61. Bb4 Nf4+ 62. Kc4 Kf5 63. g3 Ne2 64. Rf1+ Kg6 {would win a piece, but it's not so clear.} 65. Re1 {was another way to keep the bishop tied in. In some lines the queen ends up on a1, which seemed a little odd to me.} Rc6+ {now loses a piece to} 66. Bc5 $1 $19 Re6 {is a type of move which is extremely difficult to make! Just look at the bishop on b1 :)} 67. b4 $1 {was the only way to avoid the trick in the game} f5 {followed by c3-e2,c3, b1-c2 would finally break free the bishop from the cage.} 68. Kd3 Nf4+ 69. Kd2 Rxe1 {doesn't help the bishop} 70. Kxe1 {Aronian, Anish & Fabi all had played this before. Although I didn't fancy the resulting positions.} Ne6 71. Bd6 Kf7 $14 72. Ke2 Ng5 73. Kd3 Ke6 74. Bf4 Nf3 75. Kc4 Kd7 76. Kb5 Nd4+ 77. Kc5 Nc6 78. b5 Nd8 79. Kb6 Kc8 80. Ka7 Ne6 81. b6 Nc5 82. Bd6 Nb7 83. Bb4 Nd8 84. Ka6 Nb7 85. Be7 Kb8 86. Kb5 Kc8 87. Kc6 Na5+ 88. Kd5 Kd7 89. Bd6 Kc8 90. Bc7 Kd7 91. Ke5 0-1


