{[%evp 0,63,34,29,27,4,4,0,24,24,28,21,16,20,20,16,22,21,23,19,47,6,6,13,17,22,16,16,18,9,25,18,86,-20,94,91,91,112,112,112,112,104,114,114,92,112,140,140,135,132,132,130,244,269,255,237,237,237,216,289,420,425,496,496,747,808] At the opening ceremony, I was surprised to find out that 'Prague Masters' was a category 19 event, only one category short of the traditional Tata Masters tournament. It's rare to see closed tournaments for 2700-2740 rating, so I hope this fantastic initiative continues for many years!} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 (3. e4) 3... Nf6 (3... a6 $1 {Compared to exchange of the bishops on move 10, Black has more active pieces.} {The pawn is a taboo obviously:} 4. e3 $2 b5 5. a4 Bb7 $19 {The obvious alternative is} 6. b3 e6 7. bxc4 (7. axb5 axb5 8. Rxa8 Bxa8 9. bxc4 $5 bxc4 10. Bxc4 Nf6) 7... bxc4 {It doesn't seem much, but White clearly has a typical edge for this line. Or in modern terms they would say it's 0.10-0.20 :)} 8. Bxc4 Nf6 9. O-O c5 10. Nbd2) 4. e3 Bg4 5. Bxc4 (5. h3 {In fact, Black is even better. White is uncoordinated and Black can just roll ahead with the pawns.} Bh5 6. Bxc4 e6) 5... e6 6. Nc3 (6. Qb3 Bxf3 $1 7. gxf3 c5 $132 8. Qxb7 Nbd7 $132 {But suddenly I noticed that} 9. Nc3 $1 {is very powerful:} cxd4 10. exd4 Bd6) 6... Nbd7 7. O-O Be7 8. e4 (8. h3 Bh5 9. e4 O-O 10. Bb3 {leads to small advantage for White. He can blockade on d4 or play around the IQP.}) 8... O-O 9. e5 (9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 $1 c5 11. e5 {and White's attack is irresistible} Ne8 12. Be3 $1 {Black defends the f7 pawn} cxd4 13. Bxd4 Nb6 14. Qd3 {would have been the normal continuation.} Nxc4 {was the alternative.} 15. Qxc4 {This looked like the most natural way to proceed.} {For example} Rc8) 9... Ne8 {Blitzed out instantly. On the other hand I was spending time on each move (don't ask why!).} 10. Be3 {A novelty. I didn't fancy the lines after 10.0-0 Bf8. In such lines if White doesn't know what he is doing, it can get messy.} c6 {It seems strange to play c6 which hinders the pawn advance c5. The point is to exchange the b4  in a way which will help Black to achieve counterplay or if White declines, then to keep the bishop.} 11. h3 Bh5 12. g4 $1 {Played after 18 minutes of thought. Usually it's stupid to be down to 47 minutes after move 12, but on that day it worked out fine. The idea is to expand on the side.} (12. Bd3 Nb6 13. Ne4 Nd5 {White is obviously better, but Black can resist.} 14. Ng3 {doesn't really stop e4:} Bxf3 $1 15. Qxf3 Nxe3 16. fxe3 f5 $1) (12. Ne4 Nc7 $18 13. Ng3 $1 Bg6 14. Bd3 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 $1 Nd5 16. Ne4 Nxe3) 12... Bg6 13. Ne1 Nb6 14. Bb3 {I started to blitz out my moves to cover the time difference.} Nc7 {The first think of the game for Sam. So far he had used only 3 minutes. The main problem in Black's position is the knight on c6. If he can reroute it, he should be fine.} 15. f4 f5 $4 {A typical idea for White in such position is to play a4-b5, which creates a bind on the side. Sam didn't want to allow that, but the downside is huge. White simply breaks through with e4, after which Black is in real trouble. I feel he missed that he can't play 16..e7 to stop e4} 16. Nd3 {Good but not the best.} (16. exf6 Bxf6 17. Nf3 Nbd5) 16... Nbd5 {Looks too slow to be good.} 17. Qd2 Qd7 18. Rac1 Rad8 19. Nxd5 Nxd5 20. Nc5 $1 {Very precise! It looks like it's just a normal move, but it has a subtle point. More often than not, such moves win the game!} (20. g5 {Black will play Ra7 next and things don't seem so bad for him.} Nxe3 21. Qxe3 {Although White's position looks really active, I didn't see a clear way to improve.} Qxd4 {sacrificing the pawn seemed like relatively the best defense.} 22. Bxe6+ Bf7) 20... Bxc5 21. Rxc5 fxg4 22. hxg4 $1 {Another powerful move. I renew the threat of xc6 and don't give Black the time to regroup with e6-d5. After the last three precise moves, Black's position seems close to lost, as he is deprived of any play.} Be4 23. Qe1 $1 Qf7 {This loses material, but it was already inevitable.} 24. Bd2 $1 {Energetic! Tactics always work in good positions :)} Qg6 25. Qh4 Rd7 $2 {Loses immediately.} 26. Qh5 $18 {The rest is easy.} Qxh5 27. gxh5 Nc7 28. Be3 Bd5 29. Bd1 (29. Bc2 $18 {Initially it looked natural for me to play} b6 {with the idea to play e5, but I struggled to see a continuation after} 30. Rc3 Nb5 31. Rd3 Bc4) 29... Bxa2 30. Bg4 (30. b3 Bb1 31. Bf3 $1 $18 Bf5) 30... Bd5 31. f5 exf5 32. Rxf5 Rxf5 33. Bxf5 $1 Rf7 34. Bc8 Rf3 35. Bf2 {and the  is trapped.} Rb3 36. Bh4 Kf7 $1 (36... Rxb2 37. Bd8 Nb5 {White has} 38. e6 $1 Nd6 39. e7 Rb1+) 37. Rc2 Be6 38. Rf2+ Ke8 39. Rg2 {White's winning obviously, but he would still need to play well to convert.} {Also good is} Bxc8 $5 40. Rxg7 Nd5 (40... Ne6 $18 {Black can't develop the b8  ever :)} {The main point is after} 41. Rxh7 Nxd4) 41. Rg8+ Kd7 42. e6+ Kxe6 $40 43. Rxc8 Rh3 44. Bd8 Rxh5 {- here the  escapes.} (44... Rg3+ 45. Kf2 Rg8) 45. Rb8 Kd7 46. Ba5 $2 b6 47. Bd2 a5 $1 48. Kg2 Kc7 $11 49. Rh8 Kb7 1-0


