{[%evp 0,119,25,29,36,5,5,4,17,8,35,38,15,14,14,11,2,-6,2,0,72,53,38,-3,-11,-2,-5,-27,-24,-34,-33,-40,-33,-28,-44,-58,-14,-24,-40,-63,31,53,36,58,32,22,72,74,77,54,76,46,51,58,59,77,77,71,71,49,70,26,32,12,41,15,30,26,38,61,55,53,63,17,34,35,48,48,48,21,47,56,56,-3,76,89,76,81,94,85,91,87,87,92,97,104,113,95,104,93,113,120,120,121,115,127,131,131,133,145,150,150,176,176,302,306,312,294,317,317,1094,1115]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 {The Vienna Variation} b6 4. g3 Bb4+ $5 {Not the main move, but interesting.} 5. Nbd2 Bb7 $1 {Now the idea behind 4...b4 is clear} 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O d5 $1 8. a3 $1 {I find this the most challenging for Black here.} (8. Ne5 Re8) 8... Bxd2 (8... Be7 9. b4 c5 10. bxc5 bxc5 11. Rb1 Qc8 12. dxc5 Nbd7) 9. Nxd2 (9. Bxd2 $13 dxc4) 9... a5 $1 {A very cool reaction by Black. The point of this move is to delay short castling for a bit!} (9... Qc8 10. cxd5 $14 {with a comfortable position for White} Bxd5 {is the main move:} 11. e4 Bb7 12. b4) 10. b3 Ra7 11. cxd5 $5 {Trying too keep some chances.} (11. Bb2 dxc4 12. Bxb7 Rxb7 {and Black had a comfortable game in Nakamura-Giri 2020.} (12... c3 13. Bxc3 Rxb7) 13. Nxc4) 11... exd5 (11... Bxd5 12. e4 Ba8 13. Bb2 c5 14. dxc5 Rd7 15. Bxf6 $11 {with a fine game for Black.} Qxf6 16. cxb6 Qd8 17. Ra2) 12. Bb2 Re8 (12... Ne4 13. Nf3 Nd7) (12... Nbd7 $15 13. Rc1 {Is the logical move but...} c5) 13. Nf3 Nbd7 (13... Ne4 14. Ne5 f6 15. Nd3) 14. Rc1 c5 15. e3 {So here I was optimistic about my attacking chances. In this position the idea is to bring the queen to g3, the bishop to b2 and put pressure on the pawn on f6!} Ne4 (15... Ba6 $18 16. Re1 $1 {It was better to keep the advantage of the two bishops, but Black still has to solve some problems:} Rc7 17. dxc5 Rxc5) 16. dxc5 Ndxc5 $5 {Planning to attack the weaknesses of White's queenside structure by ...a4!} (16... bxc5 17. Nd4 Ra6 18. Nf5 Rg6) 17. Nd4 {First preventing the queen trade on g4!} (17. b4 axb4 18. axb4 Ne6 19. Nd4 Nxd4 20. Qxd4 $1 {giving up the a7-pawn for a very nice blockade on the light squares.} f6 $4 21. Ra1) 17... Qd7 18. b4 $5 {White should be careful to not lose the c2-pawn because after that the whole position would collapse.} axb4 19. axb4 $5 {A very tricky move both targeting the f6-pawn and maybe trapping the queen on a2!} Na4 {Here my opponent thought the queen was more important than the f6-pawn!} (19... Ne6 20. Nxe6 Qxe6 21. Qd4 f6 22. Rc7 Re7 23. Rxe7 Qxe7 24. Qxb6) 20. Ba1 Raa8 (20... Ba6 21. Re1 (21. b5 Bxb5 22. Nxb5 Qxb5 23. Qg4 f6 24. Bxe4 dxe4 25. Bxf6 Nc5) 21... Bc4 22. Qh5 {And now this is just a technical win.}) 21. Qh5 $16 {Now the bishop on b2 will be just a monster!} g6 (21... Nf6 $2 {A very big mistake. After this things just get tougher for Black.} 22. Qg5 $18 h6 23. Qf4 Bc8 24. Rfd1) 22. Qh6 f5 $1 {With the queens on the board Black will probably get mated on g7!} 23. Bxe4 (23. h4 Qf7 24. h5) 23... fxe4 (23... Rxe4 {So here we both were under time pressure, and Black still has to solve some problems.} 24. h4 Qf7 25. h5) 24. Nb5 {So now there still is a target on g7, and one on d6!} (24. f3) (24. f4) 24... Rac8 {Stopping f5} 25. Nd6 Rxc1 26. Nxe8 (26. Rxc1 Rf8 27. h4) 26... Rxf1+ 27. Kxf1 Kf7 28. Nf6 {Now all of my pieces are in the game.} Qb5+ 29. Kg2 Ba6 30. Qxh7+ Ke6 31. Qg8+ {Still trying to put pressure on the kingside.} Kd6 (31... Kf5 32. g4+ Kg5 33. Kg3) (31... Ke7 32. Nxd5+ Kd7 33. Nf6+ Kc6 $1 34. Qe8+) 32. Ne8+ 1-0


