{[%evp 0,51,29,27,27,27,27,-16,-16,-15,-1,21,27,3,26,21,28,28,2,12,27,27,59,40,61,63,99,89,135,61,174,174,154,34,138,126,113,134,134,49,188,183,224,173,29989,29990,29991,29992,29995,29996,29997,29998,29999,-30000]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 {One of Duda's weapon in blitz games. Sinking into theory would be too long, but let's see some of his victories!} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 $5 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3 e5 $6 7. Nde2 h5 8. g3 Be7 (8... Be6 9. Bg2 b5 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Be3 Nb6 12. b3 Be7 {The position is equal, but Duda nevertheless won the game within 7 moves:} 13. Qd2 Qc7 14. a4 bxa4 15. Nxa4 Nxa4 16. Rxa4 O-O 17. Rfa1 $1 Rfc8 18. c4) (8... Nbd7 $2) 9. Bg2 $1 {This time the knight would do better to retreat to g1.} b5 10. Nd5 Nxd5 (10... Nbd7 11. Nxe7 Qxe7 12. Bg5 Bb7 13. Nc3 Qe6 14. h4) 11. Qxd5 $1 Ra7 12. Be3 Rb7 {Otherwise 13.e2 and White is much better.} (12... Be6 13. Qd2 $18 {1-0 (30) Duda,J (2734)-Moussard,J (2608) chess24.com 2020} Rb7 14. f4 Nd7 15. b3 Nf6 16. O-O-O Qa8 17. g4) 13. O-O {Anyway!} (13. O-O-O Nd7 14. Qd2 O-O 15. g4 h4 16. f4) 13... Nd7 14. Qd2 $1 O-O 15. Nc3 Nf6 16. a3 $5 {A typical but excellent pawn sacrifice.} h4 17. g4 Be6 $8 18. f4 exf4 19. Bxf4 Nh7 $2 20. Rfd1 $1 {Now it's over.} (20. a4 b4 21. Nd5 Bg5) 20... Rd7 21. a4 b4 22. Nd5 Bxd5 23. Qxd5 Re8 24. e5 Nf8 25. exd6 Bxd6 26. Bxd6 {Allowing mate on the board is usually a sign of respect! What a crushing game by Artemiev.} Re6 27. Qc5 Rexd6 (27... a5) 28. Rxd6 Rxd6 29. Qxb4 $5 Ne6 30. Re1 (30. Rf1) 30... Rd4 31. Qb3 $18 Qd6 {was better, but after} 32. Qe3 {or 20.Nc5, Black's position remains awful.} (32. a5) 32... Rxa4 33. c3 $18 (33. b3 Ra2 34. Qc3 g6) 33... Ra2 $5 34. Qf2 $6 g5 $18 {The c4-pawn is lost.} 35. Bf1 {[%cal Rg1g8]} Nf4 (35... a5) 36. Rb1 Ra5 37. c4 $18 Ra4 (37... Re5 38. Re1 Rxe1 39. Qxe1 Qb6+ 40. Qf2 Qb3 41. c5 Nxh3+ 42. Bxh3 Qxh3 43. Qd4 Qg3+ 44. Kh1) 38. Rc1 Rb4 $4 39. c5 Qc7 $5 40. Qd2 (40. Rc3) 40... Rb3 41. Rc3 (41. Qd6 Rg3+ $1 42. Kh2 Qb7) 41... Rxc3 $1 42. Qxc3 a5 $1 {would also be great for White.} 43. c6 (43. Kh1 Qc6+ 44. Kh2 a4) 43... Qb6+ $132 44. Kh1 Qf2 $1 $146 45. Qc4 Qf3+ (45... Qxb2 $2 46. c7 $16 {1-0 (30) Sjugirov,S (2650)-Cheparinov,I (2710) Riyadh 2017} Qb7+ 47. Kg1 $44 Qc8 $5) 46. Kg1 Qe3+ 47. Kh1 Qf3+ 48. Kg1 Qg3+ 49. Kh1 Ne6 (49... Nxh3 50. Bxh3 Qxh3+ 51. Kg1 Qg3+ 52. Kh1 h3 53. Qc2 $5) 50. Qb5 Qf3+ {and Black's position is awful.} 51. Kg1 $6 Qe3+ 52. Kh1 Qc1 53. Kh2 Qf4+ 54. Kg1 Qe3+ 55. Kh1 Qc1 (55... Nd4 56. c7 Nxb5 57. c8=Q+ Kg7 58. Bxb5 Qxh3+ 59. Kg1) 56. Kh2 Kf8 57. Bg2 Qd2 58. Qb8+ Ke7 59. Qa7+ Kf6 $15 {0-1 (27) Hauke,C (2295)-Schlindwein,R (2440) Germany 1996} 60. Qb8 $5 {looks to me like better move - simply answering c1 in a funny way and preventing xe4.} Qb4 61. Qa7 (61. Qg8 $11 {Again Duda got no advantage, but he seems to love this line anyway! 0-1 (51) Duda,J (2737)-So,W (2780) chess.com 2018} Ke7 $5 62. Qa8) 61... Qxb2 62. Qxa5 Qe5+ 63. Qxe5+ Kxe5 64. Kg1 Kd6 65. Kf2 Nf4 66. Bf1 Kxc6 (66... Kxc6 67. Kf3 Kd5 68. Ke3 Ke5 69. Kf3 Kd4 70. Kf2 Ke4) 1-0


