{[%evp 0,76,5,27,40,40,39,13,8,-17,-22,-63,-36,17,17,-40,9,-13,37,13,67,70,63,-55,-4,-23,13,13,37,-1,-1,-18,8,13,11,-6,2,-42,-29,-29,-17,-34,-39,-39,-40,-40,-25,-31,-26,-54,-18,-63,-49,-71,-66,-71,-62,-62,-155,-207,-202,-204,-266,-279,-158,-229,-108,-223,-228,-265,-301,-301,-361,-545,-621,-675,-328,-429,-397] This was the 1st time in my World Cup experience that I had gone beyond Round 3. All the matches so far had been quite hard fought and this one was no exception. In the 1st game, after I missed a winning chance, I was lost for the most part but Durarbeyli hadn't been able to finish it off.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 {I hadn't played the Archangelsk before, but that didn't seem to surprise my opponent too much. He blitzed out his next moves anyways.} 7. a4 Rb8 8. Nxe5 {Mikhalevski,V: 'The third most popular move in the position. This line was tested by Svidler in two recent games, but probably what inspired the Azeri player was Nakamura's win over Carlsen in 2020.'} ({Earlier we considered the main line} 8. c3 {So,W (2770)-Dubov,D (2702) chess24.com INT 2020 [Mikhalevski,V]}) ({and} 8. axb5 {Vachier Lagrave,M (2757)-Nakamura,H (2764) Tashkent UZB 2014  [Mikhalevski,V]}) 8... Nxe5 9. d4 Bxd4 {Mikhalevski,V: 'Black has to part with this bishop.'} 10. Qxd4 d6 11. Bf4 {Mikhalevski,V: 'This line doesn't score well for White lately.'} ({Hikaru beat the world champion with} 11. f4 $5 Nc6 12. Qc3 Ne7 13. axb5 axb5 14. e5 (14. Ra7 {led to a quick draw in the following game.} c5 15. e5 Nfd5 16. Bxd5 Nxd5 17. Qf3 Qb6 18. Rxf7 Kxf7 19. Qxd5+ Be6 20. Qd1 Bf5 21. Qd5+ Be6 22. Qd1 Bf5 23. Qd5+ Be6 24. Qd1 {1/2-1/2 (24) Andreikin,D (2722)-Nakamura,H (2764) Tashkent 2014}) 14... Ne4 15. Qf3 (15. Qe1 {is more common.}) 15... Nc5 16. Ba2 O-O 17. Be3 Bb7 {Nakamura,H (2736)-Carlsen,M (2863) chess24.com INT 2020 and here White could set problems by means of} ({The most precise seems to be} 17... Nf5 $1 18. Bf2 Bb7 19. Qh3 Bc8) 18. Qg4 $1 Nd7 19. Nc3 b4 20. Ne2 $14) 11... c5 12. Qe3 ({White also tested} 12. Qd2) 12... c4 {Mikhalevski,V: 'Although Black created a backward pawn on d6 and weakened the d5-square with his last two moves he also restricted White's light-squared bishop, which later became White's main problem.'} 13. Ba2 Nh5 $5 $146 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'A strong novelty from the Indian Grandmaster. Black forces an exchange of the dark-squared bishop.' An interesting direct approach to target the dark-squared bishop. Also, a move which made my opponent finally stop and have a think.} ({Mikhalevski,V: 'Earlier Black only played'} 13... O-O {Aronian, Anish & Fabi all had played this before. Although I didn't fancy the resulting positions.} 14. Nc3 b4 (14... Nh5 {is still interesting.}) 15. Ne2 $14 Qc7 16. Rad1 $14 {0-1 (42) Svidler,P (2714)-Aronian,L (2781) Paris 2021} (16. h3 $1 Be6 17. Nd4 $14 {promised White the upper hand.})) 14. Nc3 {Mikhalevski,V: 'This provocative move looks a little risky, but playable.'} ({Mikhalevski,V: 'The bishop can't escape'} 14. Bg5 {Mikhalevski,V: '?!' '?!'} f6 15. Bh4 g5 {doesn't help the bishop} 16. Bg3 Nxg3 17. fxg3 bxa4 $15 {turns out to be better for Black.}) (14. Bxe5 $5 dxe5 15. axb5 axb5 16. b3 {is a good attempt to free the light-squared bishop. Black would have answered it with} Nf4 $1 17. bxc4 (17. Kh1 Qg5 18. Qg3 Qh6 19. bxc4 Rb6 $1 {with the initiative.}) 17... Bh3 $1 18. Nc3 $1 Bxg2 19. Rfd1 Qg5 20. Qg3 Qh6 21. cxb5 O-O {with a position of dynamic equality.}) 14... Nxf4 15. Qxf4 O-O {Mikhalevski,V: '!' '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'A safe move. Now White has to solve the problem of his bishop.'} (15... b4 16. Nd5 b3 17. cxb3 cxb3 18. Qg3 $1 {Probably Durarbayli hoped to play for an attack with this.} bxa2 19. Qxg7 Rf8 20. f4 {with sufficient compensation for the sacrificed piece for White.}) 16. axb5 axb5 17. Rad1 Be6 {Mikhalevski,V: '!?' '!?' A slight inaccuracy. Starting directly with b4 would avoid some options.} 18. Bb1 {Mikhalevski,V: 'White's idea is to move the knight and play c3 in order to free the bishop.'} (18. b4 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'would be nice prophylaxis against an advance of the b-pawn. Now White is planning to play Bb1 and then to move both his knight and the c-pawn to free the light-squared bishop. If he succeeds in this plan Black will stay with a backward pawn on d6.' followed by c3-e2,c3, b1-c2 would finally break free the bishop from the cage.} Qb6 {Objectively the position remains equal here.}) 18... b4 19. Ne2 {Mikhalevski,V: '?' '?' Mikhalevski,V: 'If the previous move was slightly inaccurate, the text is a serious mistake.' The position felt fairly equal. So far, I had played all my moves at a fast speed. I realized that if White manages to play c2-c3 and remove the bishop, he would be quite comfortable.} (19. Nd5 $5 {deserved attention. Although White seems to be under some pressure he seems to solve his problems with accurate play. For example,} Re8 20. Qg3 Bxd5 21. Rxd5 Qf6 (21... h5 22. h3 Qf6 23. Qe3 Ng6 24. Rd4 Nf4 25. Rfd1 c3 26. bxc3 bxc3 27. g3 $1 Ne6 28. Rxd6 Rb2 29. Ra6 {with roughly equal chances.}) 22. c3 bxc3 23. bxc3 Rb3 24. Bc2 Rb2 25. f4 $1 $11) 19... Qb6 $1 {A very tricky move, which I feel made me win the game! Vasif thought that e6-g4 was the only threat in the position. But, I had a cunning idea up my sleeve.} 20. h3 $6 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' '!'} (20. Qd2 $1 {was the only way to avoid the trick in the game}) ({Unfortunately for White} 20. c3 $2 {is strongly met by} bxc3 21. bxc3 Bg4 22. Qd2 (22. Rd2 $2 {is impossible due to} Qxb1 $19) 22... Qb2 $1 23. Rfe1 Qxd2 24. Rxd2 Bxe2 25. Rdxe2 g5 $1 $17 {The key move, which secures Black's advantage thanks to the strong position of the knight on e5.}) 20... c3 $1 {Mikhalevski,V: 'Nice play against the light-squared bishop.'} 21. bxc3 (21. b3 {Mikhalevski,V: 'looks suicidal, as the light-squared bishop can never get out of b1.' is a type of move which is extremely difficult to make! Just look at the bishop on b1 :)}) 21... Bc4 $1 22. Rfe1 Bxe2 23. Rxe2 bxc3 {Mikhalevski,V: '' '' Mikhalevski,V: 'The bishop is trapped on b1 and White is in trouble.' Now we see the point of b6. I could have reached the same position without h3 & b6 included, but then White could have played a2 and freed the bishop.} 24. Ree1 (24. Ba2 {Mikhalevski,V: '?' '?' Mikhalevski,V: 'loses to' now loses a piece to} Qa6 $1 $19 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'with a double attack on a2 and e2.'}) 24... Ra8 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'Vidit stops 25.Ba2 and reaches a virtually winning position.' It's important to keep the bishop on b1 boxed in! Now if I manage to get my knight to c4-d2, it would just be winning. Although, it's not easy as my c3 pawn is constantly under pressure.} (24... Qa6 {was another way to keep the bishop tied in. In some lines the queen ends up on a1, which seemed a little odd to me.}) 25. Qg3 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'The Azeri GM is trying to create counterplay on the kingside. Unfortunately for him he doesn't have enough resources.'} Rfc8 $1 {Important decision. Initially I was trying all the queen moves to protect c3 and then bring the knight to d2. But, in all the lines White gets some sort of counterplay.} (25... Qb4 26. Kh2 $1 Nc4 27. Rd4 $1 {and the pin is really annoying.}) (25... Qb2 26. Rxd6 Nc4 27. Rc6 Nd2 28. Qxc3 Qxc3 29. Rxc3 Rfb8 {would win a piece, but it's not so clear.}) 26. Kh2 {In order to play f4.} Ra3 {Mikhalevski,V: '?!' '?!' Mikhalevski,V: 'This move is inaccurate.' Defending the pawn in order to play c4-d2. Surprisingly, White had an unexpected defensive idea here.} (26... Qb4 {with the same idea of e5-c4 was more effective.}) (26... Qb8 $1 {was better, with the idea of} 27. f4 (27. Re3 Ra3 $19) 27... Nc4 28. Qxc3 Nb2 29. Qd4 Nxd1 30. Rxd1 g6 $19 {with a technically won position.}) 27. Re3 $6 {Mikhalevski,V: '?' '?' Mikhalevski,V: 'White misses a chance to set some problems.' Missing the only chance in the game.} ({Mikhalevski,V: 'After the correct'} 27. f4 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'Black would have to retreat the knight to g6 instead of c4.'} Nc4 {Mikhalevski,V: '?' '?' Direct.} (27... Ng6 $1 $17 28. h4 h5 29. Qg5 Ra5 30. f5 Ne5 31. Qxh5 Rb8 $17) 28. f5 (28. Rd3 $3 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' '!'} Nd2 {It looks like the bishop on b1 is lost, but White gets unexpected counterplay on the kingside.} (28... Ra1 {White has an unexpected resource here as well. Chess is full of amazing ideas, sadly they usually are left behind the scenes as humans can't yet play like Stockfish!} 29. Rxc3 Rxb1 30. Qg4 $3 {Black has bank rank problems!} Rc5 31. Rxb1 Qxb1 32. Rb3 h5 $1 33. Qd7 Qf1 34. Rb8+ Kh7 35. Qxf7 Ne3 36. Qg8+ Kg6 37. Qe8+ Kh7 $11 {leads to a crazy draw.}) 29. f5 $1 {Mikhalevski,V: 'and the bishop on b1 is untouchable.'} Qb8 $1 {Keeping an eye on the king.} (29... f6 30. e5 $3 {followed by either Rd7 or f6.}) (29... Nxb1 $2 30. Rxd6 Qb4 31. f6 g6 32. Qf4 $1 h6 33. Rxb1 $1 g5 34. Rxb4 gxf4 35. Rd7 $1 $18) 30. f6 g6 31. Qg5 $1 Kh8 32. Qd5 $1 {Mikhalevski,V: '=!' '=!' Mikhalevski,V: 'and the bishop suddenly escapes from a2.'} Rf8 33. Ba2 $1 $11 {And finally with a series of accurate moves, the white bishop gets a second life :)}) 28... f6 {[%cal Gc4d2] doesn't lead to much}) 27... Qb4 $1 {Mikhalevski,V: 'The Indian player protects the c3-pawn in order to bring the knight to c4.' Now everything is secure. There is no way for White to stop the idea of e5-c4-d2.} (27... Qb8 $1 $19 {was also strong. Mikhalevski,V: '-+' '!' '-+'}) 28. f4 Nc4 29. Qg4 ({or} 29. Red3 Nd2 30. e5 (30. f5 Ra1 $1 31. f6 g6 32. Qe3 Kh8 $1 33. e5 dxe5 34. Qxe5 Rxb1 35. Rxb1 Qxb1 36. Rxc3 Rg8 $19) 30... dxe5 31. fxe5 Ra1 $19) 29... Rb8 30. Rg3 g6 31. f5 {The attack on the kingside looked dangerous, but it's harmless. The key for Black is not to hurry in capturing the bishop on b1, it's dead anyways. Once he brings back his  in defense, White is doomed.} Nd2 {Mikhalevski,V: '-+!' '-+!' Mikhalevski,V: 'Black wins the b1-bishop.'} 32. Qf4 Qd4 $1 $19 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' '!'} 33. fxg6 (33. f6 Qe5 $19) 33... hxg6 34. Rg5 Ra1 35. Rd5 Qxe4 36. Qxd6 Raxb1 $1 {Finally the poor soul is captured!} 37. Rd4 Qe6 38. Qc7 Qb6 {Mikhalevski,V: 'A nice positional achievement for the Indian Grandmaster. 13.. .Nh5 looks like a strong novelty, which promises Black equal chances. Probably 11.f4 is a better attempt to fight for an opening advantage.' My opponent resigned and I was through to Quarterfinals! I received many nice messages after the game, but the message of my coach Alon Greenfeld stood out: " Congrats,Vidit for the win, in my long career, I have never seen a pawn on the 1st rank!" That aptly summarizes the game! :)} 0-1


