{[%evp 0,99,80,16,61,8,62,20,45,-92,-38,-147,-95,-63,-51,-55,9,7,75,70,75,-54,62,-20,6,-11,-28,0,-24,43,31,32,21,26,24,26,32,28,27,21,10,10,14,7,5,10,3,9,9,7,7,9,19,26,5,13,13,2,33,26,17,13,9,16,10,0,38,61,71,70,144,104,95,0,72,25,100,-44,369,411,497,497,497,495,505,505,505,505,505,893,901,893,893,938,938,952,982,982,29995,29996,29997,29998] 'FIDE WORLD CUP 2021 – RETURN OF THE OTB CHESS The Chess World Cup 2021 was the 9th edition of the World Cup that took place in Sochi, Krasnaya Polyana, Russia, beginning 12 July and ending 6 August 2021 with the participation of 206 players. It marked the return of over-the-board chess on a global scale after the COVID-19 pandemic forced the cancellation of many sporting events. Elite players from all over the world competed for the $1, 892,500 prize fund and two spots in the 2022 Candidates Tournament. The top seeds were: Magnus Carlsen (World Champion), Fabiano Caruana (World Championship finalist), Sergey Karjakin (World Championship finalist), Levon Aronian (two times Winner of the World Cup), Anish Giri, Alexander Grischuk, Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, Maxime Vachier-Lagrave and Alireza Firouzja. However, the winner of the tournament was the Polish GM Jan-Krzysztof Duda, who won without losing any games either in classical chess or in the rapid tiebreakers. Duda, and the tournament runner-up Sergey Karjakin thus qualified for the FIDE Candidates Tournament 2022. In this volume of Informant we bring you a detail coverage of this prominent event with the contributions by Jan-Krzysztof Duda, Velimir Ivic, Miodrag Perunovic, Rafael Leitao and Milos Perunovic. *** Jan-Krzysztof Duda wins the FIDE World Cup and qualifies for the Candidates The Polish chess superstar finished the tournament undefeated and knocked out none other than World Champion Magnus Carlsen in the semifinals. Eventually, Carlsen beat Vladimir Fedoseev in the match to claim the third place.  Jan-Krzysztof earned his title the hard way, knocking out top class opposition: Alexander Grischuk, Vidit Gujrathi, Magnus Carlsen and Sergey Karjakin in the final four rounds of the marathon event. Right after the final game against Karjakin Duda called this the tournament of his life "at least in classical chess", being both excited and exhausted, but also extremely gracious and modest. World Champion Carlsen provided perhaps the best description of Duda's magnificent performance in Krasnaya Polyana: "Huge congratulations to Duda for winning the World Cup. Considering the line of opponents he beat in the last four rounds, never losing a game - then obviously never being in a must-win or desperate situation - is a massive achievement. So, he is a richly deserved winner." Jan-Krzysztof won a generous $110.000 first prize and 18.2 rating points, but also gained a spot in the next edition of the Candidates Tournament. He now stands as a worthy contender to become the next challenger to the world crown. When asked about his ambitions and chances to win the Candidates, always confident Duda responded: "Yeah, why not? If I have such a good form like here, I'm probably unstoppable in such case." Indeed, why not?! Dear readers, here we present you two of the most interesting games analysed by the Tournament Champion himself, with exclusive annotations for this edition of Informant. Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'FIDE WORLD CUP 2021 – RETURN OF THE OTB CHESS The Chess World Cup 2021 was the 9th edition of the World Cup that took place in Sochi, Krasnaya Polyana, Russia, beginning 12 July and ending 6 August 2021 with the participation of 206 players. It marked the return of over-the-board chess on a global scale after the COVID-19 pandemic forced the cancellation of many sporting events. Elite players from all over the world competed for the $1, 892,500 prize fund and two spots in the 2022 Candidates Tournament. The top seeds were: Magnus Carlsen (World Champion), Fabiano Caruana (World Championship finalist), Sergey Karjakin (World Championship finalist), Levon Aronian (two times Winner of the World Cup), Anish Giri, Alexander Grischuk, Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, Maxime Vachier-Lagrave and Alireza Firouzja. However, the winner of the tournament was the Polish GM Jan-Krzysztof Duda, who won without losing any games either in classical chess or in the rapid tiebreakers. Duda, and the tournament runner-up Sergey Karjakin thus qualified for the FIDE Candidates Tournament 2022. In this volume of Informant we bring you a detail coverage of this prominent event with the contributions by Jan-Krzysztof Duda, Velimir Ivic, Miodrag Perunovic, Rafael Leitao and Milos Perunovic. *** Jan-Krzysztof Duda wins the FIDE World Cup and qualifies for the Candidates The Polish chess superstar finished the tournament undefeated and knocked out none other than World Champion Magnus Carlsen in the semifinals. Eventually, Carlsen beat Vladimir Fedoseev in the match to claim the third place.  Jan-Krzysztof earned his title the hard way, knocking out top class opposition: Alexander Grischuk, Vidit Gujrathi, Magnus Carlsen and Sergey Karjakin in the final four rounds of the marathon event. Right after the final game against Karjakin Duda called this the tournament of his life "at least in classical chess", being both excited and exhausted, but also extremely gracious and modest. World Champion Carlsen provided perhaps the best description of Duda's magnificent performance in Krasnaya Polyana: "Huge congratulations to Duda for winning the World Cup. Considering the line of opponents he beat in the last four rounds, never losing a game - then obviously never being in a must-win or desperate situation - is a massive achievement. So, he is a richly deserved winner." Jan-Krzysztof won a generous $110.000 first prize and 18.2 rating points, but also gained a spot in the next edition of the Candidates Tournament. He now stands as a worthy contender to become the next challenger to the world crown. When asked about his ambitions and chances to win the Candidates, always confident Duda responded: "Yeah, why not? If I have such a good form like here, I'm probably unstoppable in such case." Indeed, why not?! Dear readers, here we present you two of the most interesting games analysed by the Tournament Champion himself, with exclusive annotations for this edition of Informant.'''} 1. e4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof'' Jan-Krzystztof Duda is not known to be going down long forcing lines, but in this game it was exactly what happened. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Jan-Krzystztof Duda is not known to be going down long forcing lines, but in this game it was exactly what happened.''} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 {Vidit has previously shown a few of his weapons against 1.e4 and the Archangelsk was the latest and the most succesful one, as he managed to beat Vasif Durarbeyli with it, in the previous round. It obviously wouldn't come as a surprise any longer and JKD goes on to blitz out the next few moves.  Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Vidit has previously shown a few of his weapons against 1.e4 and the Archangelsk was the latest and the most succesful one, as he managed to beat Vasif Durarbeyli with it, in the previous round. It obviously wouldn't come as a surprise any longer and JKD goes on to blitz out the next few moves. ''} 7. a4 {Clever to start with this and not after 7.c3 d6, because now 8.a4 allows the option of 8...Bg4 as well. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Clever to start with this and not after 7.c3 d6, because now 8.a4 allows the option of 8...Bg4 as well.''} Rb8 8. c3 {Durarbeyli, who is a very experienced and a very strong Grand Master, with an excellent track record, went for the 8.Nxe5 variation, which also shows up at the highest level a lot. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Durarbeyli, who is a very experienced and a very strong Grand Master, with an excellent track record, went for the 8.Nxe5 variation, which also shows up at the highest level a lot.''} d6 9. d4 Bb6 10. a5 {This has been very trendy for a while. The point is that 10...Nxa5? loses to 11.Rxa5! Bxa5 12.dxe5!, while if Black goes 10...Ba7, then after 11.h3 0-0 12.Be3, Black has to deal with some tactics as the a7 bishop is under protected. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'This has been very trendy for a while. The point is that 10...Nxa5? loses to 11.Rxa5! Bxa5 12.dxe5!, while if Black goes 10...Ba7, then after 11.h3 0-0 12.Be3, Black has to deal with some tactics as the a7 bishop is under protected.''} Ba7 (10... Nxa5 $2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish'} 11. Rxa5 $1 Bxa5 12. dxe5 $1 Ng4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof} 13. Bg5 $36 {- 80/362}) 11. h3 (11. Be3 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) Duda,Jan Krzysztof'} Bg4 {- 108/(91)}) 11... Bb7 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '!?' '!?''Vidit had played the Neo-Archangelsk in the previous match, and in the most trendy 10.a5 variation he played this interesting sideline. It wasn't a big surpise for me though, as his friend Anish Giri had played it in Zagreb GCT before, the tournament I had participated in as well. I decided to play in the most forcing way, and test my opponent's memory, even if objectively the very line is probably close to the so-called "forced draw". Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '!?' '!?' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Vidit had played the Neo-Archangelsk in the previous match, and in the most trendy 10.a5 variation he played this interesting sideline. It wasn't a big surpise for me though, as his friend Anish Giri had played it in Zagreb GCT before, the tournament I had participated in as well. I decided to play in the most forcing way, and test my opponent's memory, even if objectively the very line is probably close to the so-called "forced draw".''' This is the latest trend, intending to go for the direct complications with 12.Be3 Nxe4!?. On the black side we have games of Grischuk, Dubov, Caruana, Aronian and the last one before this game, was actually played by myself against Grischuk in the Zagreb rapid.  Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'This is the latest trend, intending to go for the direct complications with 12.Be3 Nxe4!?. On the black side we have games of Grischuk, Dubov, Caruana, Aronian and the last one before this game, was actually played by myself against Grischuk in the Zagreb rapid. ''} 12. Be3 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'This move was introduced by the young Russian player Gregory Oparin in 2011, but only gained popularity recently. The ideas behind the move are simple-13.d5 and 13.dxe5.''' White could also start with 12.Re1, which is what Harikrishna did against Fabiano in Wijk aan Zee this year. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'White could also start with 12.Re1, which is what Harikrishna did against Fabiano in Wijk aan Zee this year.''} ({Earlier this year we considered} 12. Re1 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) (Giri,Anish) Vachier Lagrave,M (2784)-Dubov,D (2702) chess24.com INT 2021 [Mikhalevski,V]}) 12... Nxe4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'Black accepts the challenge. This move leads to a complex unbalanced position by force.''' That's the point. These complications have existed for a few years already, but it was only this year that the line has exploded and people stopped avoiding this with both colours. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'That's the point. These complications have existed for a few years already, but it was only this year that the line has exploded and people stopped avoiding this with both colours.''} 13. d5 {The most direct test, but 13.Re1 has been played here too. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'The most direct test, but 13.Re1 has been played here too.''} (13. Re1 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) (Giri,Anish) is an interesting alternative which scored pretty well recently.}) 13... Bxe3 14. dxc6 Nxf2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'The only move, since two pieces were hanging.''' Forced complications. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Forced complications.''} (14... Bxf2+ $2 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) (Giri,Anish) runs into} 15. Rxf2 Nxf2 16. Qd5 $1 $18) 15. Qe2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'A contribution of the Indian GM Adhiban, who presented the move in 2013.''' The consensus is that this is the best. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'The consensus is that this is the best.''} (15. Qd5 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) - 111/157 Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) (Duda,Jan Krzysztof) - 111/157'}) (15. Rxf2 $2 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) (Giri,Anish) was a mistake.} Bxf2+ 16. Kxf2 Bxc6 {with a serious material advantage for Black, who has rook and three pawns for two minor pieces. Pratyusha,B (2180)-Monnisha, G (2051) Lucknow 2013}) 15... Nxh3+ {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'Black has no choice due to the two hanging pieces.'''} 16. Kh1 Nf2+ {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'All Black's moves are forced.'''} 17. Rxf2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'White has no choice either.'''} Bxf2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'We have arrived at a junction. White can choose which bishop to capture.''' And here White is at a principled crossroad. There are two attempts, as there are two bishops that can be captured. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'And here White is at a principled crossroad. There are two attempts, as there are two bishops that can be captured.''} 18. Qxf2 $5 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Diagram [#]''Diagram [#] Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'Concrete play continues after' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Diagram [#]'''} ({'Move in the text line is a small surpise, as Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Move in the text line is a small surpise, as'''} 18. cxb7 {'is the main line, and was played in the aforementioned Anish's game. I must confess that I didn't find any real improvement over Russian's play.