i,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'The most accurate.'''} (22... O-O $6 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) (Giri,Anish) is less accurate in view of} 23. Kxg2 Rxf7 24. Nd2 Kf8 25. Bxf7 Kxf7 {and White gained a tempo compared to the game.}) 23. Kxg2 Rxf7 24. Bxf7+ Kxf7 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'I'm pretty sure both players analysed this position at home. Black has three pawns for a piece, but only two extra pawns on the kingside.''' This is an endgame both players went for. White has a knight for 3 pawns which is a very fine material allocation for the second player, but he does have to watch out a little bit, as the a6 pawn is fixed by the a5 pawn and if the knight is ever to land on b4, Black could get under pressure.  But that will never happen... or will it?  Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'This is an endgame both players went for. White has a knight for 3 pawns which is a very fine material allocation for the second player, but he does have to watch out a little bit, as the a6 pawn is fixed by the a5 pawn and if the knight is ever to land on b4, Black could get under pressure.  But that will never happen... or will it? ''} 25. Nd2 {'- and so after a forced variation we have the ensuing endgame. Objectively it's level, but in practical terms I think only White can pull it off. Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '- and so after a forced variation we have the ensuing endgame. Objectively it's level, but in practical terms I think only White can pull it off.'''} Re8 {I didn't like this particular solution, although it is not a bad move objectively, as the game stays well within the drawable margin. It felt more practical to include 25...b4 26.c4, to get some counterplay with Re8-Re5, or alternatively go for 25...g5!?, giving the king a nice square on g6 behind the pawns and not in front of them.  Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'I didn't like this particular solution, although it is not a bad move objectively, as the game stays well within the drawable margin. It felt more practical to include 25...b4 26.c4, to get some counterplay with Re8-Re5, or alternatively go for 25...g5!?, giving the king a nice square on g6 behind the pawns and not in front of them. ''} (25... b4 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) might be an improvement for Black, to damage White's queenside.} 26. c4 {Giri,Anish} Re8 (26... g5 $5) 27. Kf3 Re5 (27... g5 {was still good.}) 28. Nf1 Rf5+ 29. Ke2 Rh5 30. Kd3 Rh1 31. Re1 c6 {and a draw was agreed in the just finished tournament. Nihal,S (2655)-Arjun,K (2503) Riga 2021}) 26. Rf1+ {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'A clever intermediate move, which tries to force Black's king to the g-file''' An annoying check. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'An annoying check.''} Kg6 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!''' Allowing the rook trade and going for a very concrete knight vs pawns endgame is not something you want to be dealing with this early in the game, but now the king is somewhat awkwardly placed in front of its pawns. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Allowing the rook trade and going for a very concrete knight vs pawns endgame is not something you want to be dealing with this early in the game, but now the king is somewhat awkwardly placed in front of its pawns.''} 27. Kf2 $1 {'The combination of my last two moves looks a bit weird, but at least now Black can't play g5 anymore. From now on, both sides could deviate in several moments, but what we did certainly made sense. Giri,Anish: '!' Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'Now Black's king is in front of the g-file and so the advance of the kingside pawns is slowed down.' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'The combination of my last two moves looks a bit weird, but at least now Black can't play g5 anymore. From now on, both sides could deviate in several moments, but what we did certainly made sense.''' Strong. The g-file is free for the rook and the king takes it upon himself to stop the invasion of the rook. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Strong. The g-file is free for the rook and the king takes it upon himself to stop the invasion of the rook.''} h5 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!''' Black wants to slowly start pushing his kingside pawns.  Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Black wants to slowly start pushing his kingside pawns. ''} (27... Rf8+ $6 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) (Giri,Anish) is met by} 28. Nf3) 28. Rg1+ Kf6 29. Kf3 $5 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '!?'' 29.Nf3 may seem automatic at first, but this is a much more clever way to stop the pawns, intending Ne4+. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '29.Nf3 may seem automatic at first, but this is a much more clever way to stop the pawns, intending Ne4+.''} g6 (29... Re5 $5 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) (Giri,Anish) also deserved attention.} 30. Ne4+ Kf7 31. Kf4 g6 {and Black doesn't mind trading rooks, as after} 32. Rg5 Rxg5 33. Kxg5 {he activates his king by means of} ({or} 33. Nxg5+ Kf6 $11) 33... Ke6 $11) 30. Ne4+ Kg7 {'Diagram [#] Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Diagram [#]'''} (30... Kf7 $2 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) (Giri,Anish) would be wrong due to the following manoeuvre of the white knight.} 31. Nf2 $1 Kf6 (31... Kg7 32. Nd3 $1 Kh6 33. Re1 $1 Rf8+ (33... Rxe1 34. Nxe1 $18 {is hopeless due to the weak queenside pawns.}) 34. Kg3 $16) 32. Nh3 Kf5 33. Nf4 Re4 34. Nd5 $1 $16 ({After} 34. Nxg6 b4 {Black creates sufficient counterplay.})) 31. Nf2 $1 {'Directing to the green b4-square. Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'The knight is heading to d3 from where it can get to either f4 or b4.' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Directing to the green b4-square.''' Duda makes one nasty move after the other. Here already I started feeling the heat for Vidit, but the engine still pointed out a cleacut solution- 31...Kh6! 32.Nd3 g5!. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Duda makes one nasty move after the other. Here already I started feeling the heat for Vidit, but the engine still pointed out a cleacut solution- 31...Kh6! 32.Nd3 g5!.''} Rf8+ $6 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '?!'' Fishing for a move repetition is tempting, but it just doesn't bring Black the desired result. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Fishing for a move repetition is tempting, but it just doesn't bring Black the desired result.''} ({It would be more accurate to play} 31... Kh6 $1 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) Giri,Anish} 32. Nd3 g5 {Black creates fast counterplay.} 33. Re1 g4+ 34. Kg2 Rf8 35. Nb4 h4 36. Nxa6 h3+ {and the game may continue} 37. Kg3 Kg5 38. Nxc7 Rf3+ 39. Kh2 Kh4 40. Nd5 g3+ 41. Kg1 h2+ 42. Kh1 Kh3 43. Ne3 Rf4 $1 44. a6 Ra4 45. Ng2 Rxa6 46. Nf4+ Kg4 47. Nd5 Ra2 $11) 32. Kg2 Re8 $2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '?' Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '?!''' Continuing with the wrong intention. White doesn't have to take the draw and this only gives White more time. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Continuing with the wrong intention. White doesn't have to take the draw and this only gives White more time.''} (32... Rf4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish' Keeping control of the f4 square was much better, with the direct 32...Rf5 or first this.} 33. Ra1 Rf5 34. Nd3 c5 {and Black manages to keep the knight at bay and wants to start pushing his kingside. The position is still very much drawish.}) (32... Rf5 $5 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof} 33. Nd3 c5 $11 {'Giri,Anish: '!' Giri,Anish: 'restricting the knight was better. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '=' '='''}) 33. Nd3 $1 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' Now Black is suddenly in serious trouble. He has to allow either Nb4 or Nf4. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Now Black is suddenly in serious trouble. He has to allow either Nb4 or Nf4.''} g5 {Correct, as 33...c5 34.Nf4! was just losing, with Kf3 coming next and Black's kingside pawns not able to move. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Correct, as 33...c5 34.Nf4! was just losing, with Kf3 coming next and Black's kingside pawns not able to move.''} ({'Now Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Now'''} 33... c5 $2 {'is no longer good, as after G