tries. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'There are also other tries.''} (37. Kf3 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) Giri,Anish} Kf6 38. Rd1 Ke7 {Black retains good chances for a draw.}) 37... Kg6 38. Nxd6 Ra2 39. Rb1 b4 40. c4 b3 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '=!' '=!' '!''Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '=!' '=!''' and Black is apparently ok, as he can combine the relative instability of White's queenside pawns with the advance of his own kingside soldiers. This wasn't easy to go for, but it had to be done, as the move in the game just loses by force. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'and Black is apparently ok, as he can combine the relative instability of White's queenside pawns with the advance of his own kingside soldiers. This wasn't easy to go for, but it had to be done, as the move in the game just loses by force.''} 41. Ne4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) Duda,Jan Krzysztof'} Ra4 42. Nxc5 Rxc4 43. Nxb3 h4 $44) 35. Kh1 $1 {'Now White is winning in a forcing way, and I managed to calculate it almost to the end. Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: '+-!' Mikhalevski,V: 'Surprisingly, after this retreat Black is in trouble. White wins the a6-pawn and creates a strong passed pawn.' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Now White is winning in a forcing way, and I managed to calculate it almost to the end.''' The king is now not in the way of any checks, neither by the pawns nor by the rook. A very aesthetically pleasing solution. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'The king is now not in the way of any checks, neither by the pawns nor by the rook. A very aesthetically pleasing solution.''} (35. Kf3 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) Duda,Jan Krzysztof'} Rxb2 36. Ra1 g4+ 37. Ke3 h4 38. Nxa6 h3 39. Nxc7 h2 40. a6 Ra2 $1) 35... Rxb2 36. Ra1 $1 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' Grabbing the a-file before collecting the a6 pawn. The a5 pawn is now unstoppable and Black is just losing by force. Note that with the king on f3 Black would now have counterplay thanks to g4+ and Rb3-xc3 check, but now that the king is on h1, the counterplay is much too slow. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Grabbing the a-file before collecting the a6 pawn. The a5 pawn is now unstoppable and Black is just losing by force. Note that with the king on f3 Black would now have counterplay thanks to g4+ and Rb3-xc3 check, but now that the king is on h1, the counterplay is much too slow.''} (36. Nxa6 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) Duda,Jan Krzysztof'} Ra2 37. Rxg5+ Kf6 38. Rxb5 c6 39. Rxh5 Kg6 40. Rh3 Rxa5 41. Nb8) 36... c5 (36... Rb3 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof} 37. Nxa6 Rxc3 38. Nb4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '+-' '+-' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'and there is no stopping the a-pawn.'} Rc4 {Diagram [#] Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) (Duda,Jan Krzysztof) Diagram [#]'} 39. Nd3 $1 (39. a6 $2 Rxb4 40. a7 Rh4+ 41. Kg2 Rg4+ 42. Kf3 Rf4+ 43. Ke3 Rf8 44. a8=Q Rxa8 45. Rxa8 Kf6 46. Rb8 Ke5 47. Rxb5+ c5 48. Rb8 d5 $13) (39. Nd5 $2 b4 $1 40. a6 $140 b3 41. a7 b2 42. a8=Q Rc1+ $17) 39... Re4 40. a6 Re8 41. a7 Ra8 42. Nb4 Kf7 43. Nd5 $18) (36... g4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'was another attempt, where I had seen a following line: Giri,Anish: '(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) was another attempt, where I had seen a following line:''} 37. Nxa6 h4 38. Nxc7 g3 39. a6 h3 40. a7 Rh2+ 41. Kg1 Rg2+ 42. Kf1 Rf2+ 43. Ke1 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'is winning, as after 43...h2 there is 44.a8Q protecting h1-square, and after Giri,Anish: 'is winning, as after 43...h2 there is 44.a8Q protecting h1-square, and after''} Rf8 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'there is'} 44. Ne6+ $18) 37. Nxa6 b4 {The last attempt, but JKD is merciless.  Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'The last attempt, but JKD is merciless. ''} (37... Rc2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) Duda,Jan Krzysztof'} 38. Nxc5 $18) 38. Nxb4 $1 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: '!'' Leads to a major piece endgame in which White gets to check first and Black's king has nowhere to hide. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Leads to a major piece endgame in which White gets to check first and Black's king has nowhere to hide.''} (38. cxb4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: '(Giri,Anish) is also enough for a win.'} cxb4 39. Nc7 b3 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof'} (39... Rc2 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof} 40. a6 $1 Rxc7 ({or} 40... b3 41. Ne6+ $1 Kg6 42. Nd4 Rc8 43. Nxb3 $18 {with an easily won position.}) 41. a7 Rc8 42. a8=Q Rxa8 43. Rxa8 $18) 40. Ne6+ $1 (40. a6 Ra2) 40... Kf6 41. Nd4 $18) 38... cxb4 39. a6 bxc3 40. a7 c2 41. a8=Q Rb1+ 42. Kg2 c1=Q {'Tragicomedy Black has three extra pawns at the moment, but an extremely poor placement of his pieces means he is getting checkmated by force. Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'It seems that Black did as much as he could, but White's attack is decisive.' Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Tragicomedy Black has three extra pawns at the moment, but an extremely poor placement of his pieces means he is getting checkmated by force.''' All forced so far. Now White starts checking and the king just ends up getting mated. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'All forced so far. Now White starts checking and the king just ends up getting mated.''} 43. Ra7+ Kf6 44. Qf8+ Ke5 45. Re7+ Kd5 (45... Kd4 {Duda,Jan Krzysztof Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Duda,Jan Krzysztof''} 46. Qf2+ Kd3 47. Qf3+ Kd4 48. Qe4+ $18) 46. Qf3+ Kc5 47. Rc7+ Kb4 48. Qb7+ Ka5 (48... Ka3 {(Duda,Jan Krzysztof) (Giri,Anish) doesn't save Black.} 49. Qa7+ Kb3 50. Qb8+ Ka2 51. Ra7+) 49. Qa7+ Kb5 50. Qb8+ {Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'A well-played game by Duda! Strong opening preparation and good endgame technique made their deal. Black's main mistake came on move 34, when Vidit played 34...Re2?, instead of the correct 34...c5. Black's play can also be improved by means of 31...Kh6. Also 25...b4 and 29...Re5 make sense.''' A crucial win, for the eventual World Cup winner. Duda,Jan Krzysztof: 'Giri,Anish: 'A crucial win, for the eventual World Cup winner.''} 1-0


