{[%evp 0,119,25,29,36,5,5,4,17,8,35,38,15,14,14,11,2,-6,2,0,72,53,38,-3,-11,-2,-5,-27,-24,-34,-33,-40,-33,-28,-44,-58,-14,-24,-40,-63,31,53,36,58,32,22,72,74,77,54,76,46,51,58,59,77,77,71,71,49,70,26,32,12,41,15,30,26,38,61,55,53,63,17,34,35,48,48,48,21,47,56,56,-3,76,89,76,81,94,85,91,87,87,92,97,104,113,95,104,93,113,120,120,121,115,127,131,131,133,145,150,150,176,176,302,306,312,294,317,317,1094,1115]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 {The Vienna Variation} Nc6 4. d3 Bb4 $5 {Not the main move, but interesting.} (4... Na5 {is the main move:} 5. Nge2 Nxc4 6. dxc4 Bc5 $13) 5. Nge2 d5 $1 {Now the idea behind 4...b4 is clear} 6. exd5 Nxd5 7. O-O Be6 $1 (7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 Bd6 9. Ng3 O-O 10. Qh5 $14 {with a comfortable position for White}) 8. Bxd5 $1 {I find this the most challenging for Black here.} (8. a3 Bxc3 9. bxc3 O-O 10. Bxd5 Qxd5 11. Be3 b6 {and Black had a comfortable game in Nakamura-Giri 2020.}) 8... Bxd5 9. f4 f6 $1 {Mikhalevski,V: 'An obvious improvement, which has already been seen in modern practice.' A very cool reaction by Black. The point of this move is to delay short castling for a bit!} ({An old correspondence game saw a disaster after} 9... exf4 $2 10. Nxf4 Ne7 $4 11. Nfxd5 Nxd5 12. Qh5 $18 {Ale,C-Geus,R Correspondence 1983 [Paul Motwani]}) 10. fxe5 Nxe5 11. Nf4 $5 {Mikhalevski,V: '?!' '?!' Mikhalevski,V: 'A dubious novelty. It was unnecessary to leave Black with the bishop pair.' Trying too keep some chances.} (11. Nxd5 {Is the logical move but...} Qxd5 12. d4 Ng6 {Mikhalevski,V: 'is roughly equal.'} 13. Nf4 Nxf4 14. Bxf4 O-O-O 15. c3 Bd6 $11 {with a fine game for Black.}) 11... Bxc3 {Mikhalevski,V: '?!' '?!' Mikhalevski,V: 'Black shouldn't be afraid of the few active moves White could make after the correct 11...Bf7!'} ({Mikhalevski,V: 'After the natural'} 11... Bf7 $1 {It was better to keep the advantage of the two bishops, but Black still has to solve some problems:} 12. d4 Ng6 (12... Nc6 13. d5 (13. Re1+ Be7 $17) 13... Ne5 14. Qd4 Ba5 15. Qa4+ c6 $17 {Black is better.}) 13. Re1+ Be7 14. Ne6 Bxe6 15. Rxe6 Qd7 16. Re1 O-O-O 17. Be3 $15) 12. bxc3 O-O 13. c4 ({Both} 13. Nxd5 $5 Qxd5 14. Bf4) (13. Qe1 $5 Re8 14. Qf2 Bf7 15. h3 {deserved attention, although Black retains the slightly better chances thanks to his better pawn structure.}) 13... Bf7 {Mikhalevski,V: '' ''} 14. Rb1 b6 15. Qe1 {Mikhalevski,V: 'Firouzja is looking for activity and transfers the queen to g3.' So here I was optimistic about my attacking chances. In this position the idea is to bring the queen to g3, the bishop to b2 and put pressure on the pawn on f6!} (15. Qd2 $1 Qd7 16. h3 Rfe8 17. Qf2 {is more accurate.}) 15... Re8 16. Qg3 ({Now} 16. Qf2 {is answered by} Ng4 17. Qf3 Qd4+ 18. Kh1 Ne5 19. Qg3 Qc3 20. Qf2 Qa5 21. a3 Re7 $17 {and White is under pressure.}) 16... Qd7 $5 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' '!' Planning to attack the weaknesses of White's queenside structure by ...a4!} 17. h3 {First preventing the queen trade on g4!} Qa4 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'Vidit attacks White's pawn weaknesses.'} 18. Rb3 $5 {Mikhalevski,V: 'Alireza prefers activity over a pawn.' White should be careful to not lose the c2-pawn because after that the whole position would collapse.} (18. Rb2 {was objectively better, but Black's edge is already beyond doubt.} Re7 $17) 18... Qxa2 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' '!'} 19. Ne2 $5 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'A clever move, which shocked the Indian player.' A very tricky move both targeting the f6-pawn and maybe trapping the queen on a2!} Qa4 {Mikhalevski,V: '?' '?' Mikhalevski,V: 'Black panics.' Here my opponent thought the queen was more important than the f6-pawn!} ({Mikhalevski,V: 'Black realised that'} 19... Qxc2 $4 {Mikhalevski,V: 'runs into'} 20. Nd4 Qa2 21. Ra3 Qb1 22. Bh6 {Mikhalevski,V: 'and Black loses the queen.'} Qxf1+ 23. Kxf1 $18) ({Black had to stay cold-blooded and continue with} 19... Bg6 $1 20. Nd4 ({After} 20. Ra3 Qxc2 21. Nd4 Qb1 22. Rb3 Qa1 $1 $19 {the queen escapes.}) 20... Qa5 21. Nb5 a6 $1 22. Ra3 (22. Nxc7 $2 Qc5+) 22... Qb4 23. Rb3 Qe7 24. Nc3 Rac8 $17) (19... Rad8 $5 {covering the d4-square also deserved attention, although in this case White can win the f6-pawn back.} 20. Rb2 Qa4 21. Rxf6 Ng6 22. Rf2 Qa1 $17) 20. Rxf6 {Mikhalevski,V: 'After winning back the f6-pawn the dark a1-h8 diagonal will also be weak.'} Qd7 {Mikhalevski,V: '?' '?'} (20... Ng6 $1 {was necessary, in order to meet} 21. Rf2 {with} ({or} 21. Nc3 Qd7 22. Rf1 Qd4+ 23. Kh2 Qe5 {and Black is close to equality.}) 21... Qa5 $1) 21. Rf2 $16 {Now the bishop on b2 will be just a monster!} Ng6 22. Bb2 {Mikhalevski,V: '' '' Mikhalevski,V: 'The advantage changed hands quickly.'} Qd6 $1 {Mikhalevski,V: 'Vidit is looking for an escape in an endgame.' With the queens on the board Black will probably get mated on g7!} 23. Qxd6 cxd6 24. Ng3 {So now there still is a target on g7, and one on d6!} (24. Rb5 $1 $16 {stopping the advance of the d-pawn was better.}) 24... Be6 {Mikhalevski,V: '?!' '?!' Mikhalevski,V: 'Passive defence. Black's idea is to cover the f5-square.' Stopping f5} (24... Re1+ {deserved attention.} 25. Kh2 Ne7 {covering the f5-square in a much better version.} 26. Ba3 Rd8 $14) ({The immediate} 24... d5 $6 25. cxd5 Bxd5 26. Ra3 $16 {is better for White.}) 25. Nh5 Ne5 (25... Re7 $5) 26. Rb5 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' '!'} Bf7 27. Ng3 {Mikhalevski,V: '' '' Mikhalevski,V: '28.Nf5 is a threat again.'} Bg6 (27... Rad8 28. Nf5 Bg6 29. Nd4 $16 {is still better for White.} (29. Nxd6 $2 {is strongly met by} Nxd3 $1 30. Nxe8 Nxf2 31. Nxg7 Nd1 $11)) 28. Rd5 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' '!' Now all of my pieces are in the game.} Rad8 29. Bc3 {Mikhalevski,V: 'Too soft.'} ({The direct} 29. Ba3 {was stronger.} Re6 30. Re2 $16 (30. Ne2 $5 $16)) 29... h6 30. Rf1 Nc6 31. h4 {Still trying to put pressure on the kingside.} Rf8 32. Re1 Bf7 {Mikhalevski,V: '?!' '?!'} ({After a few unconvincing moves from White Black had a chance to equalise by means of} 32... Rf4 $1 33. h5 Bf7 34. Rf5 Rg4 35. Kh2 Rh4+ 36. Kg1 Rg4 37. Nf1 Rh4 $11) 33. Rb5 Rfe8 (33... Rd7 $5 {was more accurate.}) 34. Rxe8+ Bxe8 35. Nf5 Rd7 36. Rd5 (36. g4 $1 $16 {was stronger, as the text may lead to a drawish endgame with opposite-coloured bishops.}) 36... Ne7 $1 37. Nxe7+ Rxe7 38. Rxd6 Ba4 {Mikhalevski,V: '!' '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'Black has to counter attack White's pawns.'} 39. Bb4 Rf7 {Mikhalevski,V: '?!' '?!'} (39... Re2 $1 {Once again Black had to choose an active defence.} 40. c3 a5 41. Rd8+ ({or} 41. Ba3 Ra2 42. Rd8+ Kf7 43. Bd6 Bc6 {with counterplay.}) 41... Re8 42. Rxe8+ Bxe8 43. Ba3 Bg6 44. d4 Bd3 $11) 40. c3 {So here we both were under time pressure, and Black still has to solve some problems.} Rd7 41. c5 bxc5 (41... Rxd6 $1 42. cxd6 a5 43. Ba3 Kf7 44. Kf2 Ke6 45. Ke3 g5 46. hxg5 hxg5 {and Black shouldn't have problems to hold.}) 42. Rxd7 Bxd7 43. Bxc5 a5 $2 {Mikhalevski,V: 'This is an obvious mistake. Black had to force White's pawns to dark squares in order to blockade them.' A very big mistake. After this things just get tougher for Black.} (43... Bf5 {Mikhalevski,V: '!'} 44. d4 Kf7 $1 {giving up the a7-pawn for a very nice blockade on the light squares.} 45. Bxa7 Ke6 46. c4 ({or} 46. Bc5 h5 47. Bf8 g6 48. Kf2 Kd5 {with a dead draw.}) 46... Bd3 47. d5+ Ke5 48. Bb8+ Kd4 $11) 44. Kf2 $18 Kf7 45. Ke3 Ke6 46. c4 Bc6 47. g3 Bg2 48. Bf8 {And now this is just a technical win.} Kf7 49. Ba3 Bf1 50. Kd4 g5 51. hxg5 hxg5 52. Kc3 {Mikhalevski,V: '+-' '+-' Mikhalevski,V: 'Now White wins thanks to the kingside pawn on g3, as Black can give up the bishop for two connected passed pawns.'} Ke6 53. d4 g4 54. Bc1 a4 55. d5+ Kd6 56. Kd4 Bg2 57. c5+ Kc7 58. Ke5 Bf3 59. Ke6 Bg2 60. d6+ Kd8 61. Bg5+ Kc8 62. d7+ $18 {The dubious opening experiment with 11.Nf4?! Can't be recommended. Instead 11.Nxd5 is equal. Moreover, the entire line promises White no advantage, after 11...Bf7! Black is better.} 1-0


