{[%evp 0,51,29,27,27,27,27,-16,-16,-15,-1,21,27,3,26,21,28,28,2,12,27,27,59,40,61,63,99,89,135,61,174,174,154,34,138,126,113,134,134,49,188,183,224,173,29989,29990,29991,29992,29995,29996,29997,29998,29999,-30000] Leitao,Rafael: '*** BOSSA NOVA ***  No Limits For Creativity  We are going through difficult times and the shift has gone from over-the-board tournaments to online chess. Fortunately, our passion for the game remained more active than ever with many online tournaments being organized. In this article I will show some of my favourite games from these events, and these all have one common theme: creativity.  Almost all of the online events are played in the rapid format, which can lead to the never ending discussion about what is more important: to have good, nearly perfectly played games with many draws, or to have more drama, more winning results at the cost of many errors that are inherent to the rapid format. There is a case to be said for all points of view, but it is undeniable fact that rapid events suit the online world better. Also, in rapid chess the elite grandmasters have a little more freedom for creativity. Creativity can take many forms in a practical chess game (we exclude studies and compositions: this is a fascinating world on its own). For example: a nice combination, an unorthodox positional idea, or a new idea in the opening. We will see all of these in the model games. First of all let's see one of the most intriguing games I have seen in a long time. This is a game of the new era of computers, which I think would be completely misunderstood some 50 years ago. The machine has taught us a new way of comprehending the game, with far less preconceived ideas. This might come easily for players of the new generation, but it is still quite difficult for me. That is why I consider the following game a mistery and I must confess I still do not quite understand it. However, I love things I cannot understand!  WARNING: this game might be dangerous for your chess health since it contradicts everything most beginners learn when they enter the world of chess. We have the queen coming in play early, White grabbing a pawn and neglecting development, the same piece moving more than once in the opening. We even have a mating attack with several pieces (of the attacking side) still being in their initial positions! I was reminded of Sunye's masterpiece when I saw this game played in the Online Nations Cup last year. It took me a while to understand it and I couldn't believe how White managed to create such an attack even without development. It's also a fascinating game. *** BOSSA NOVA *** No Limits For Creativity We are going through difficult times and the shift has gone from over-the-board tournaments to online chess. Fortunately, our passion for the game remained more active than ever with many online tournaments being organized. In this article I will show some of my favourite games from these events, and these all have one common theme: creativity. Almost all of the online events are played in the rapid format, which can lead to the never ending discussion about what is more important: to have good, nearly perfectly played games with many draws, or to have more drama, more winning results at the cost of many errors that are inherent to the rapid format. There is a case to be said for all points of view, but it is undeniable fact that rapid events suit the online world better. Also, in rapid chess the elite grandmasters have a little more freedom for creativity. Creativity can take many forms in a practical chess game (we exclude studies and compositions: this is a fascinating world on its own). For example: a nice combination, an unorthodox positional idea, or a new idea in the opening. We will see all of these in the model games. First of all let's see one of the most intriguing games I have seen in a long time. This is a game of the new era of computers, which I think would be completely misunderstood some 50 years ago. The machine has taught us a new way of comprehending the game, with far less preconceived ideas. This might come easily for players of the new generation, but it is still quite difficult for me. That is why I consider the following game a mistery and I must confess I still do not quite understand it. However, I love things I cannot understand! WARNING: this game might be dangerous for your chess health since it contradicts everything most beginners learn when they enter the world of chess. We have the queen coming in play early, White grabbing a pawn and neglecting development, the same piece moving more than once in the opening. We even have a mating attack with several pieces (of the attacking side) still being in their initial positions!'} 1. d4 {Leitao,Rafael Leitao,Rafael} Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bg5 {Leitao,Rafael: 'Artemiev is fond of exotic openings with the white pieces and his results with these, apparently harmless systems are quite good. Artemiev is fond of exotic openings with the white pieces and his results with these, apparently harmless systems are quite good.' One of Duda's weapon in blitz games. Sinking into theory would be too long, but let's see some of his victories!} Ne4 (3... e6 4. Nbd2 Be7 5. e3 O-O 6. Bd3 h6 7. Bh4 c5 8. c3 Nc6 9. O-O b6 10. Ne5 Bb7 11. f4 Nd7 12. Bg3 Rc8 13. a4 Ndb8 14. Qh5 Ba6 15. Bb5 Bb7 16. f5 Nxe5 17. Bxe5 Bg5 18. fxe6 fxe6 19. Qg6 Qe7 20. Bd3 Bxe3+ 21. Kh1 Rf5 22. g4 $18 {1-0 (30) Duda,J (2734)-Moussard,J (2608) chess24.com 2020}) (3... c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6 6. Qc1 Bf5 (6... Ne4 7. Bf4 Bf5 8. Nbd2 e6 9. Be2 Be7 $11 {was also not very convincing for White, although once more, Duda won: 1-0 (75) Duda,J (2753)-Harikrishna,P (2719) chess24.com 2020.}) 7. Nbd2 e6 8. Be2 Be7 9. Nh4 Bg6 10. O-O Rc8 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Nf3 Bd6 13. dxc5 Qxc5 14. Bf4 Bxf4 15. exf4 O-O {The position is equal, but Duda nevertheless won the game within 7 moves:} 16. Qd2 Rfd8 17. Bd3 b5 18. Rac1 a6 19. Qe2 Qb6 (19... Qd6 $5) 20. Bxg6 $1 fxg6 21. Qxe6+ Kf8 $2 (21... Kh8 22. Ne5 $40) 22. Ne5 {1-0 Duda,J (2753)-Harikrishna,P (2719) chess24.com INT 2020}) 4. Bh4 (4. Bf4 {Leitao,Rafael Leitao,Rafael: 'is more common.'}) 4... Qd6 $5 {Leitao,Rafael: 'Vidit is a very agressive player and his reaction suits his style well. It is very rare to see the queen starting her adventure at move 4, especially with the black pieces! Vidit is a very agressive player and his reaction suits his style well. It is very rare to see the queen starting her adventure at move 4, especially with the black pieces!'} (4... c5 {Leitao,Rafael: '- 12/86'} 5. e3 Nc6 6. c3 Qb6 7. Qc1 Bf5 8. Nbd2 e6 9. Be2 Rc8 10. O-O Be7 11. Bxe7 Nxe7 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. Nd2 Bg6 14. Nb3 cxd4 15. exd4 O-O $11 {Again Duda got no advantage, but he seems to love this line anyway! 0-1 (51) Duda,J (2737)-So,W (2780) chess.com 2018}) ({Leitao,Rafael: 'I checked my openings book while preparing the analysis of the game, and noticed that one of the suggested moves was I checked my openings book while preparing the analysis of the game, and noticed that one of the suggested moves was'} 4... h5 $5 {Leitao,Rafael: ', with the idea of f6_f5. There are really no limits to what we can learn with computers. , with the idea of f6_f5. There are really no limits to what we can learn with computers.'} 5. Bg3 (5. h3 $5 f6 6. Nfd2 g5 7. Nxe4 dxe4 8. Bg3 $1) 5... g5 6. h3 Nxg3 7. fxg3 Qd6 8. Kf2 g4 9. hxg4 Bxg4 10. Nc3 Nc6 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Qb4 13. c3 $5 Qb6 $2 (13... Qxb2+ 14. Be2 $44) 14. Qb3 $16 {1-0 (30) Sjugirov,S (2650)-Cheparinov,I (2710) Riyadh 2017}) 5. Nbd2 {Leitao,Rafael: 'Diagram [#]'} Qh6 {Leitao,Rafael: '!' '!' Leitao,Rafael: 'Diagram [#]' Leitao,Rafael: 'This is the point of Black's play. Even though it all looks quite superficial, actually it is a very interesting way to pose problems. Black simply wants to play g5 and White's reaction, at move 6, is nearly forced. This is the point of Black's play. Even though it all looks quite superficial, actually it is a very interesting way to pose problems. Black simply wants to play g5 and White's reaction, at move 6, is nearly forced. This is the point of Black's play. Even though it all looks quite superficial, actually it is a very interesting way to pose problems. Black simply wants to play g5 and White's reaction, at move 6, is nearly forced. Diagram [#]'} 6. Qc1 {Leitao,Rafael: '!' '!' Leitao,Rafael: 'The only way to hinder Black's plans. The only way to hinder Black's plans.'} ({Leitao,Rafael: 'Of course'} 6. e3 $2 {Leitao,Rafael Leitao,Rafael: 'would be met by'} g5 $1 {Leitao,Rafael: 'and that would cost a piece for insufficent compensation (even for online rapid standards). and that would cost a piece for insufficent compensation (even for online rapid standards).'} 7. Nxe4 (7. Bg3 Nxg3 8. fxg3 g4 $19) 7... dxe4 8. Bxg5 Qg6 9. Nd2 Qxg5 10. Nxe4 Qg6 $19) 6... g5 $6 {Leitao,Rafael: '!?' '!?' Leitao,Rafael: 'Going for it! A pawn sacrifice in truly romantic style.'} (6... Qh5 $5 {looks to me like better move - simply answering c1 in a funny way and preventing xe4.}) (6... Nc6 {Leitao,Rafael Leitao,Rafael: 'is quite reasonable.'} 7. c3 Qh5 8. h3 f5 $13 {Leitao,Rafael: 'with complete mess on the board. with complete mess on the board.'}) 7. Nxe4 {Leitao,Rafael: 'The next moves are forced.'} dxe4 8. Bxg5 Qh5 (8... Qg7 9. Nh4 $1 $146 (9. Ng1 $6 Qxd4 10. Bd2 Qb6 11. Bc3 Rg8 12. e3 Nc6 13. Ne2 Bg4 14. h3 Bxe2 15. Bxe2 Bg7 16. Bxg7 Rxg7 17. O-O O-O-O $15 {0-1 (27) Hauke,C (2295)-Schlindwein,R (2440) Germany 1996}) 9... Qxd4 10. c3 Qg7 11. g3 e5 12. Bg2 f6 13. Be3 f5 14. Bh3 Qf7 15. f3 {and Black's position is awful.}) 9. Ng1 $1 {Leitao,Rafael: '!' Leitao,Rafael: 'Here we are.This must be one of the craziest openings ever. How to evaluate it properly? When I first thought about it could not believe it was good for White, but the computer (and Artemiev) disagreed. Apparently, I have to exercise my humility and accept I am not ready for these positions. Nearly all White's pieces are on the first rank and it seems Black can develop with tempo, putting pressure. But White is solid enough and, as we will see (spoiler alert!), he might not even need his kingside pieces. The good old Ng1 after a strange opening. No worries. Here we are.This must be one of the craziest openings ever. How to evaluate it properly? When I first thought about it could not believe it was good for White, but the computer (and Artemiev) disagreed. Apparently, I have to exercise my humility and accept I am not ready for these positions. Nearly all White's pieces are on the first rank and it seems Black can develop with tempo, putting pressure. But White is solid enough and, as we will see (spoiler alert!), he might not even need his kingside pieces. The good old Ng1 after a strange opening. No worries.' This time the knight would do better to retreat to g1.} Bg7 (9... c5 {Leitao,Rafael Leitao,Rafael: 'was worthy of consideration. was worthy of consideration.'}) 10. c3 c5 {Leitao,Rafael: 'N' 'N' Leitao,Rafael: 'The first new move of the game.'} (10... e5 {Leitao,Rafael} 11. dxe5 Bxe5 (11... Nc6 12. g3 (12. Bf6 {Leitao,Rafael} Bxf6 13. exf6 Be6 $44 14. g3 {The computer thinks White is much better. The computer thinks White is much better.}) 12... Nxe5 13. Bg2 f5 14. h4 Bd7 15. Nh3 $16) 12. Qe3 $16 (12. g3 $16) (12. Bf4 {Leitao,Rafael} Nc6 13. e3 Bxf4 14. exf4 Be6 $44 {Vlasov,Sergey - Beynerovich,Alexander, Russia 1998} 15. Qe3 O-O-O 16. g3 Rhe8 $13 {Vlasov,Sergey - Beynerovich,Alexander, Russia 1998})) 11. Bd2 $1 {Leitao,Rafael: '!?' '!?' Leitao,Rafael: 'This is just fantastic, breaking all the rules we learned when we started playing chess. White reagroups so he can play e3 and bring the pieces into play. Another curious move. Instead of trying to develop, White retreats another piece. But the idea is to play e3 and everything is solid. This is just fantastic, breaking all the rules we learned when we started playing chess. White reagroups so he can play e3 and bring the pieces into play. Another curious move. Instead of trying to develop, White retreats another piece. But the idea is to play e3 and everything is solid.'} (11. dxc5 $5 {Leitao,Rafael: 'was the most natural move and again we have a position where Black seems to have compensation, but the computer preferes White. was the most natural move and again we have a position where Black seems to have compensation, but the computer preferes White.'} Na6 (11... Nc6 $13 {Leitao,Rafael}) 12. Qd2 Nxc5 13. Rd1 $1 (13. O-O-O Be6 $132) 13... Be6 14. Nh3 $1 {would also be great for White.}) 11... Nc6 {Leitao,Rafael: '?!' '?!' Leitao,Rafael: 'This is an inaccuracy. Black should have exchanged the pawns right away and started some direct play. This is an inaccuracy. Black should have exchanged the pawns right away and started some direct play.'} (11... cxd4 {Leitao,Rafael: '!'} 12. cxd4 Bxd4 $4 (12... O-O {Leitao,Rafael} 13. e3 e5 {Leitao,Rafael: 'I think Black would have interesting compensation, at least in a practical game. But, it comes as a surprise to me that objectively White is much better. I think Black would have interesting compensation, at least in a practical game. But, it comes as a surprise to me that objectively White is much better.'} 14. d5 $1 {Leitao,Rafael: 'after this precise move it is hard to prove compensation.'} (14. dxe5 Nc6 15. Ne2 Nxe5 16. Nf4 Qh4 17. Be2 Bg4 $44) (14. Ne2 exd4 15. Nxd4 Bg4 (15... Nc6 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. Bc3 Qg6 $14) 16. Bc3 Rc8 17. Qd2 Nc6 18. Be2 Ne5 19. Bxg4 Qxg4 20. h3 Qxg2 21. O-O-O Nd3+ 22. Kb1 Qxf2 23. Rhf1 Qxd2 24. Rxd2 $14) 14... Qg6 (14... Bg4 15. Be2 Qg6 16. Bxg4 Qxg4 17. Ne2 Nd7 18. Bb4 Rfc8 19. Qd2 $16) 15. Ne2 $16) 13. Qxc8#) 12. e3 Bg4 {Otherwise 13.e2 and White is much better.} 13. Ne2 {Anyway!} O-O-O {Leitao,Rafael: 'Diagram [#]' Leitao,Rafael: 'Diagram [#] Let's take a look at the position and think about it as if explaining it to a beginner: all Black's pieces are developed, it is important to have the rooks connected, it is important to castle. Look at White's king stuck in the middle, and he has only a pawn. You should never be greedy! So, I do not know why you put yourself in this trouble. However, now you should desperately try to develop your pieces and place your king in safety.  This explanation seems quite reasonable, right? But it is totally wrong! White is much better here and it is time to start attacking. Black played in an enterprising way, sacrificing, developing, castling. The result? He is going to suffer the attack from White's underdeveloped army. Yes, life is really unfair. Diagram [#] Diagram [#] Let's take a look at the position and think about it as if explaining it to a beginner: all Black's pieces are developed, it is important to have the rooks connected, it is important to castle. Look at White's king stuck in the middle, and he has only a pawn. You should never be greedy! So, I do not know why you put yourself in this trouble. However, now you should desperately try to develop your pieces and place your king in safety. This explanation seems quite reasonable, right? But it is totally wrong! White is much better here and it is time to start attacking. Diagram [#] Black played in an enterprising way, sacrificing, developing, castling. The result? He is going to suffer the attack from White's underdeveloped army. Yes, life is really unfair. Diagram [#]'} (13... O-O {[%cal Rg1g8]}) (13... Bxe2 14. Bxe2 Qg6 15. O-O $18) 14. b4 $1 {Leitao,Rafael: 'Another fascinating move. White starts attack with his own pieces being underdeveloped. Another fascinating move. White starts attack with his own pieces being underdeveloped.'} cxb4 (14... c4 $6 15. Nf4 $18 {The c4-pawn is lost.}) 15. cxb4 Kb8 16. b5 $5 {Leitao,Rafael: '!' '!' Leitao,Rafael: 'Giving the pawn back to open the b-file. Giving the pawn back to open the b-file.' A typical but excellent pawn sacrifice.} (16. Ng3 $5) 16... Qxb5 17. Rb1 Qd5 $8 18. Nc3 {Leitao,Rafael: '' ''} Qe6 (18... Qd7 19. Nxe4 $18) 19. Na4 {Leitao,Rafael: 'Now everything is clear. It is not the white king that is in real danger here. Finally White's pieces start playing. No need to castle or to move the bishop from f1. It is a long range piece, afterall. Now everything is clear. It is not the white king that is in real danger here. Finally White's pieces start playing. No need to castle or to move the bishop from f1. It is a long range piece, afterall.'} Ka8 $2 (19... Qd6 {was better, but after} 20. Bc4 {or 20.Nc5, Black's position remains awful.}) 20. Rxb7 $1 {Now it's over.} (20. Nc5 $18 {Leitao,Rafael}) 20... Qd6 (20... Nxd4 21. Qc7 Nc2+ 22. Qxc2 Rc8 23. Nc5 $5 Rxc5 24. Rxa7+ Kxa7 25. Qxc5+ $18) (20... Kxb7 {Leitao,Rafael} 21. Nc5+ $18) 21. Nc5 Nxd4 22. Rxa7+ {Leitao,Rafael: '!' '!' Leitao,Rafael: 'The final combination. Notice that White's king, bishop and rook are still in their initial positions, while all Black's pieces are developed. But remember: checkmate ends the game! The final combination. Notice that White's king, bishop and rook are still in their initial positions, while all Black's pieces are developed. But remember: checkmate ends the game!'} Kxa7 23. Qa3+ Kb6 24. Qb4+ Kc6 25. Qb7+ Kxc5 26. Bb4# {Leitao,Rafael: '#' Leitao,Rafael: '# This game is a real puzzle and will remain one of my favourites for some time! # A wonderful game. # This game is a real puzzle and will remain one of my favourites for some time! # # A wonderful game.' Allowing mate on the board is usually a sign of respect! What a crushing game by Artemiev.} 1-0


