{[%evp 0,66,29,-14,14,2,9,9,9,9,10,-6,8,12,14,6,7,8,20,12,8,10,10,11,18,12,29,13,41,4,70,-9,-22,34,10,18,15,22,22,22,-12,15,13,24,60,40,53,29,38,42,30,6,4,0,11,8,21,21,7,2,0,-6,11,-12,-1,-3,11,-12,0]} 1. c4 {David Cummings} c5 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. b3 {David Cummings: 'A rare move - White's 7th most common try - and new to this site. Ding uses this as a precursor to the new idea he brought to this game. In the Archives, you can find many games with the mainline 5 Nf3 as well 5 e3, 5 a3, 5 e4, 5 d3 and 5 Rb1.'} e6 {David Cummings: 'Vidit goes for the Fischer setup with ...e7-e6 and ...Ng8-e7, which has proven to be a very reliable approach for Black in the Symmetrical English. Instead another logical response is to construct a dark-squared pawn chain with ..d7-d6 and ... e7-e5:'} (5... d6 {David Cummings} 6. Bb2 e5 7. e3 {leads to a typical closed English battle. Some examples of how play can proceed:} Nge7 (7... Bf5 8. Nge2 Nge7 9. O-O (9. d3 Qd7 10. h4 $5 {is worth considering, to avoid the early trade of light-squared bishops.}) 9... O-O 10. Ne4 {White tries to counter Black's plan of ...Qd8-d7 and ...Bf5-h3 by hitting Black's central pawns.} Qd7 11. f4 Rad8 12. d3 b6 (12... Bh3 {is also OK}) 13. N2c3 h6 $6 {too slow} (13... Bh3 $1 {following through with the bishop trade leaves Black with a position that it perfectly fine for him}) 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. cxd5 Ne7 16. Nf2 {Now Black's f5-bishop doesn't have any squares, and Black gets pushed back.} Qc8 17. e4 Bd7 18. Qd2 f5 19. Rae1 {and White is better co-ordinated, with pressure in the centre, Vachier-Lagrave,M (2780)-Tari,A (2625) Gibraltar Masters 2019 1-0 (36)}) 8. Nge2 {and now:} Be6 (8... O-O 9. O-O Rb8 {Black needs to play more actively in this line} (9... Be6 {followed by ...Qd8-d7 is called for}) 10. d3 a6 11. Qd2 b6 12. f4 Re8 13. Rad1 f5 14. Nd5 Bd7 {Black's last 3 moves don't fit together very well, and now White take over in the centre with} 15. d4 cxd4 16. exd4 e4 17. Ne3 {and White's better pawn structure give him an advantage, Predojevic,B (2614)-Ostenstad,B (2464) Norway 2015 1-0 (28)}) 9. O-O O-O {David Cummings: 'followed by ...Qd8-d7 is called for'} 10. Nd5 Qd7 {This is Black's most straightforward plan, and Black has generally not had problems in games where he got in ...Be6-h3.} 11. Re1 $5 Bxd5 12. cxd5 Nb4 13. d4 {White sacrifices a pawn to mix things up, Savchenko,B (2655) -Dominguez Perez,L (2721) Havana 2009 1/2-1/2 (48), and now} exd4 14. exd4 Nbxd5 15. Qd2 {when White's two bishops give him compensation for the pawn.}) 6. Ba3 $5 {David Cummings: 'And this is the novelty. Other players were quick to explore this new line, with Giri and Vachier-Lagrave trying 5 b3 White in games played soon after this one (see the notes above and below).'} d6 {David Cummings: 'By forcing Black to defend his c5-pawn, White is aiming to get an edge in the battle for the centre by inhibiting the ...d7-d5 break.'} 7. e3 Nge7 8. Nge2 O-O 9. O-O {Usually in the e6-line Black´s plan is to play ...d5, but here it is not possible due to the attack on c5. Vidit deals with the issue and forces ...d5 through. If he had done nothing White would have played d4 himself with good play. Or he could have prevented d4 with ...Nf5 as van Foreest did. Usually in the e6-line Black´s plan is to play ...d5, but here it is not possible due to the attack on c5. Vidit deals with the issue and forces ...d5 through. If he had done nothing White would have played d4 himself with good play. Or he could have prevented d4 with ...Nf5 as van Foreest did.} Qa5 {David Cummings: 'Black comes up with a sharp idea which enables him to get the d5-break in, although this comes at the cost of a slight lag in development. In a later round at Wijk aan Zee, another game saw:'} (9... Nf5 {David Cummings} 10. d3 Qd7 {Black maintains the symmetry for now. Here:} 11. Qd2 $1 {is White's most accurate, since he will be the first to get in the d-pawn thrust, for example} (11. Rc1 Rd8 12. Qd2 b6 13. d4 cxd4 14. exd4 d5 $1 15. cxd5 Ncxd4 16. dxe6 $5 {White sacs the queen to create some imbalance.} Nf3+ 17. Bxf3 Qxd2 18. exf7+ Kxf7 19. Bxa8 {Giri,A (2783)-Van Foreest,J (2612) Tata Steel Masters 2019 1/2-1/2 (30), and now after} Nd4 (19... Bf8 {was played in the game}) 20. Nxd4 Bxd4 21. Ne4 Qxa2 {and Black is no worse.}) 11... Rd8 12. Rad1 b6 13. d4 {and White "wins" the centre. The tactics from Giri-Van Foreest now don't work for Black since the d1-rook now protects White's queen.}) 10. Bb2 d5 11. cxd5 (11. a3 $5 {was an intelligent waiting move with the idea was an intelligent waiting move with the idea} d4 12. b4 $1 {with good play. with good play.}) 11... exd5 {David Cummings: 'The pin on the c3-knight means the d5-pawn cannot be captured.'} 12. Nf4 Rd8 {David Cummings: 'Black can also play:'} (12... Bf5 $5 {David Cummings} 13. Nfxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Rfd8 {with compensation for the pawn due to White's "Swiss cheese" pawn formation.}) 13. Qc1 (13. a3 $5 {Even here this was possible. Again Even here this was possible. Again} d4 14. b4 $1) 13... d4 14. Na4 {David Cummings: 'Black has a space advantage and is only one or two moves away from completing development, so White must quickly apply pressure to the vulnerable c5-pawn.'} c4 $1 {David Cummings: 'Black pushes forward, further heightening the complications. Instead:' A dynamic solution. A dynamic solution.} (14... b6 {David Cummings: '?!' David Cummings: 'defending the c5-pawn doesn't work well because of'} 15. exd4 Bxd4 16. Re1 {David Cummings: 'for example' with initiative. with initiative.} Rb8 {David Cummings} 17. Bc3 Bxc3 18. dxc3 {and Black's offside queen gives White good attacking prospects in the centre and on the kingside.}) (14... g5 $5 {(David Cummings) is the engine's suggestion, dislodging the well placed f4-knight. Now} 15. Nh5 Bh8 16. h3 (16. Nxc5 Bg4 {is also very messy}) 16... g4 17. Qxc5 Qxc5 18. Nxc5 gxh3 {leads to some kind of dynamic equality.}) 15. Re1 $1 {David Cummings: 'A far from obvious, but excellent move. White threatens to open the e-file with e3xd4, after which the e1-rook will be powerfully placed. As a result, Black is obliged to trade on the e3-square, giving White an improved grip on the centre.'} (15. Qxc4 {David Cummings: 'is much less effective. After'} b5 16. Qc1 bxa4 17. Bxc6 Nxc6 18. Qxc6 Ba6 {David Cummings: 'Black has at least enough for a pawn.' and Black gets out. and Black gets out.}) 15... dxe3 16. dxe3 Ne5 $1 (16... Bxb2 17. Nxb2 {and the knight gets to c4. and the knight gets to c4.}) 17. Bc3 Qb5 18. Qa3 N7c6 {David Cummings: 'Another critical moment.'} 19. bxc4 {David Cummings: 'After this move, the queens and some minor pieces are traded, and Black manages to solve his problems. Instead, White has good chances after keeping the tension with:' White simplifies too soon. White simplifies too soon.} ({The little move The little move} 19. h3 $1 {David Cummings: 'depriving the c8-bishop of squares makes it difficult for Black to unravel. If now' was very strong. It is hard for Black to ease the tension: was very strong. It is hard for Black to ease the tension:} Bf5 (19... Bf8 {David Cummings} 20. bxc4 Qxc4 21. Qb3 Qxb3 22. axb3 {White is more actively placed than in the game, and retains a slight edge.}) 20. Red1 (20. g4 $5 Bd3 21. Rac1 Rac8 22. Red1)) 19... Nxc4 20. Qb3 Qxb3 21. axb3 Bxc3 22. Nxc3 Nd2 $1 {Black keeps defending actively. Black keeps defending actively.} 23. Ncd5 {David Cummings: 'The pressure on the weak b3-pawn causes White to jettison it in search of activity. Instead after:'} (23. Ra3 Bg4 (23... Ne5 {(David Cummings) Black's knights give him sufficient counterplay.})) 23... Nxb3 24. Ra3 Nba5 25. Rea1 Nc4 26. Rc3 {David Cummings: 'White has good play for the pawn, but only enough to hold the balance.'} N4e5 27. Nc7 Rb8 28. Nfd5 Kg7 29. f4 Ng4 30. e4 Nf6 {David Cummings: 'Chances are level, and the players now go for a repetition.'} 31. Kf2 Ng4+ 32. Kg1 Nf6 {White has enough compensation for a pawn but nothing more. White has enough compensation for a pawn but nothing more.} 33. Kf2 Ng4+ 1/2-1/2


