{[%evp 0,107,10,-23,19,8,8,11,11,11,6,6,23,12,21,21,23,26,26,24,24,16,23,6,24,-29,-40,-37,6,-1,1,1,1,-38,-23,-3,76,57,100,39,69,64,124,133,131,131,127,127,124,122,122,127,130,133,140,148,126,104,115,125,140,122,198,163,198,205,183,187,177,114,175,182,159,127,126,95,212,180,155,123,138,67,108,107,86,81,144,123,119,120,113,113,113,122,134,156,127,127,127,114,361,200,461,395,470,490,486,499,501,522]} 1. c4 {David Cummings David Cummings} c5 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 e6 6. d4 {David Cummings: 'A well-known attempt to sharpen the game, this move has also scored best for White (around 60%) in my database.'} cxd4 (6... Nxd4 {(David Cummings) is a significant alternative, analyzed in Harika-Lahno in the Archives}) 7. Nb5 d5 8. cxd5 exd5 {David Cummings: 'Black goes for a setup where he holds an IQP. The position is reminiscent of a Tarrasch QGD, except that Black's dark-squared bishop has been fianchettoed, rather than being developed on the a3-f8 diagonal. Instead:'} (8... Qa5+ {(David Cummings) is a sharper alternative, for example} 9. Qd2 Qxb5 10. dxc6 Qb6 {is the continuation of Mamedov-Aravindh in the Archives.}) 9. O-O Nge7 10. Nbxd4 O-O 11. b3 {David Cummings: 'Slightly unusual. We have previously looked at:'} (11. Be3 {(David Cummings) in Melkumyan-Sivuk and a couple of earlier games in the Archives.}) 11... Nf5 (11... Bg4 12. Bb2 Qb6 (12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Qb6 14. Nxc6 bxc6 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Qd2 $14 {1-0 (33) Dizdarevic,E (2481)-Kosanovic,G (2383) Stara Pazova 2011}) 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Ne5 Be6 16. Rc1 $14 {½-½ (107) Haast,M (2381)-Nasuta,G (2516) Karlsruhe 2019}) (11... Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Nf5 (12... Bg4 13. Bb2 Qd7 14. Re1 Rfe8 15. Qd2 Rac8 16. e3 $14 {½-½ (46) Goczo,M (2276)-Farago,S (2262) Budapest 2005}) 13. Bb2 $14 {0-1 (42) Faizrakhmanov,R (2426)-Sychev,K (2415) Minsk 2015}) (11... Re8 12. Bb2 Bg4 13. Qd2 Qb6 14. e3 $14 {0-1 (43) Kudryavtsev,V (2147)-Rensch,D (2356) Agoura Hills 2006}) 12. Nxc6 {David Cummings: 'Artemiev tries to create some play by transitioning to a hanging pawns structure. Here:'} (12. Bb2 Qb6 13. e3 {David Cummings: 'allows Black to go for exchanges and symmetry with'} Nfxd4 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 Bxd4 16. exd4 (16. Qxd4 Qxd4 17. exd4 Be6 $11 {½-½ (30) Zaragatski,I (2486)-Babula,V (2581) Teplice 2013}) 16... Be6 {David Cummings: 'and now' White does have a better bishop, but everything else is symmetrical, so the game is very likely to end in a draw.} 17. Qd2 Rac8 {/= ½-½ (28) Valdes Romero,L (2398)-Munoz Pantoja,M (2471) Sabadell 2018} 18. Rfe1 {David Cummings} Rc6 19. Re5 Rd8 20. Rae1 {is only symbolically better for White, Valdes Romero,L (2398) -Munoz Pantoja,M (2471) Sabadell 2018 1/2-1/2 (28)}) 12... bxc6 13. Rb1 Qa5 $6 {David Cummings: 'This allows White to get a grip on the dark squares. Instead:'} (13... Re8 14. Bb2 d4 {David Cummings: '!' '!' David Cummings: 'is fine for Black. As is often the case, if Black can advance the IQP to the 5th rank with impunity, he gets pressure against the e2-pawn which balances out his own pawn weaknesses.' blocking the diagonal. Black has nothing to complain about.}) 14. Bb2 $1 {David Cummings: 'White had to calculate the consequences of Black grabbing the a2-pawn, but satisfied that this works for him, plays the most active move. Instead:' White can sacrifice the a2 pawn. Exchanging the dark-squared bishops is unfavourable for Black.} (14. Qc2 {David Cummings: 'is slower. Now'} Be6 $11 {½-½ (45) Oboladze,L (2340)-Nasuta,G (2517) Skopje 2019} 15. Bf4 {David Cummings} c5 16. Be5 f6 17. Ba1 Rac8 18. Rfd1 {was played in Oboladze,L (2340) -Nasuta,G (2517) Skopje 2019 1/2-1/2 (45), and now} d4 {would lead to a balanced game}) 14... Qxa2 $6 {David Cummings: 'This wasn't forced, but after normal moves White will be slightly better with play against the hanging pawns.' Accepting the challenge, but it's very risky.} (14... Bxb2 15. Rxb2 $14) 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 (15... Nxg7 $6 {is even worse.} 16. Ne5 Bb7 17. Nd7 Rfd8 18. Nf6+ Kh8 19. Qd4 $16 {[%cal Gd4h4]}) 16. g4 Ne7 {David Cummings: '?!' '?!' David Cummings: 'Trying to hold on to the c6-pawn but leaving the knight passively placed. Here:'} (16... Nd6 {(David Cummings) is preferable, although after} 17. Ne5 Ne4 18. Rc1 Qd2 19. Nxc6 {White is slightly for choice.}) 17. Qd4+ f6 18. Qc5 {Suddenly White achieved a strong initiative almost out of nothing.} Ng8 {David Cummings: 'Alternatively:'} (18... Rf7 {David Cummings} 19. g5 {gives White a strong initiative}) 19. Qxc6 Bxg4 20. Nd4 $16 {David Cummings: 'White will soon win the d5-pawn, restoring material equality. His pieces are also much more active than their counterparts, leaving White clearly better.'} Qa5 (20... Rac8 {(David Cummings) activating the rook, was more resilient}) 21. h3 Bf5 22. Ra1 Qb6 23. Nxf5+ gxf5 24. Qxd5 (24. Bxd5 {(David Cummings) was also very strong. After} Rae8 25. Qxb6 axb6 26. Bc4 {White is favourite to win this endgame with the better minor piece and better pawn structure.}) 24... Rae8 25. Qxf5 Re5 26. Qf3 {David Cummings: 'White is now a pawn ahead, but the conversion is not trivial with all the heavy pieces, and only a few pawns, left on the board.'} Rfe8 27. e3 a5 28. Rab1 Ne7 29. Rfd1 Ng6 30. Rd4 f5 31. Rd7+ R8e7 32. Rxe7+ Nxe7 33. Qg3+ Ng6 34. h4 h5 {David Cummings: '?!' '?!' David Cummings: 'A better chance was to go for activity with:'} (34... Qf6 {(David Cummings) and if} 35. h5 $2 f4 $1 {puts Black right back in the game}) 35. Rc1 Qf6 36. Rc7+ Re7 37. Rc6 {David Cummings: 'More accurate was:'} (37. Rc4 {David Cummings} Rd7 38. Bf3 {and Black struggles to defend all his weak pawns.}) 37... Re6 {David Cummings: '?!' '?!' David Cummings: 'Missing an opportunity for counterplay with:'} (37... f4 $1 {(David Cummings) for example} 38. exf4 Re1+ 39. Kh2 Qxh4+ 40. Qxh4 Nxh4 41. Bd5 Nf5 {with some drawing chances}) 38. Rxe6 Qxe6 39. Qc7+ Kh6 40. Qxa5 Nxh4 41. Qd5 {David Cummings: 'White's outside passed pawn should be decisive.'} Qe7 42. Bh1 {David Cummings: 'Allowing some opening of the position, although White doesn't spoil anything.'} (42. Qd4 $1 {(David Cummings) keeps full control}) 42... f4 43. Be4 fxe3 44. fxe3 Qg7+ 45. Kf2 Qb2+ 46. Ke1 Qc1+ 47. Ke2 Qb2+ 48. Qd2 Qe5 (48... Qxb3 {(David Cummings) is no help due to} 49. Qd6+ Kg7 50. Qe7+ {picking up the loose h4-knight}) 49. Qd4 Qe7 50. Bd3 Ng2 51. Qe4 Qf6 52. Qxg2 Qb2+ 53. Kf1 Qc1+ 54. Kf2 1-0


