{[%evp 0,79,25,40,28,-14,6,6,37,28,56,35,14,31,25,16,17,24,15,34,43,31,40,41,48,48,48,48,43,47,63,48,51,46,42,37,46,51,54,59,40,37,84,31,58,50,50,28,35,45,42,42,45,42,42,30,28,46,72,27,45,48,83,81,94,62,152,152,420,442,459,466,1400,1466,1493,1503,1503,1503,1503,1503,1156,1244] The Biel Grandmaster Event this time had a very unique format. It was a combination of classical, rapid and blitz. On the 1st day in the rapid section I didn't start well by losing to Cori Jorge. Eventually I managed to recovere, but was still trailing by 2 points. Hence, this game was extremely important to me from the tournament and personal point of view!} 1. d4 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Vidit, Santosh Gujrathi'} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ {The Bogo Indian! Cori Jorge hadn't played much in the last 6 months, so I wasn't sure what to expect. In fact, his last available game in my database was in December 2018.} 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 O-O (5... Nc6 {is more common.}) 6. Bg2 Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2 d6 8. O-O e5 9. Nc3 {Black hasn't played the Bogo Indian in the most principled way. White has the centre and the extra space advantage.} Nc6 10. Nd5 $5 {I thought for about 20 minutes to make this decision. I wanted to be precise and increase my advantage.} (10. dxe5 {was the other option that I considered. But it didn't feel right to give up the central control.} dxe5 11. Nd5 Nxd5 (11... Qd6 $5) 12. cxd5 Rd8 13. Rfd1 e4 {I only saw this far. Apparently, Tactically this line works.} 14. Ng5 $1 f5 15. Qc3 Nb4 16. Qb3 $16) (10. d5 {Closing the centre didn't appeal to me as black would play Nb8-a5-Na6 and would have easy play.}) 10... Qd8 (10... Nxd5 11. cxd5 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 exd4 13. Rfe1 Qe5 14. Rac1 Bf5 15. Rc4 $16 {White will collect the d4 pawn and the pile up the major pieces on the c-file. the c7 pawn is a clear target}) 11. Rfd1 Re8 (11... Bg4 $5 {looked more natural but then the pressure along the d-file would be annoying.} 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Qe3 Re8 14. Nb6 axb6 15. Rxd8 Raxd8 16. h3 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 e4 18. Bg2 Nd4 19. Rb1) 12. dxe5 Nxe5 (12... dxe5 13. b4 Qd6 14. b5 Ne7 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. a4 $16) 13. Nxe5 $1 (13. Rac1 {looks normal but runs into} Ne4 $1 {And now the queen doesn't have any good squares!} 14. Qd4 (14. Qf4 Ng6 $1) 14... Ng4 15. Rf1 c6 $132 {Clearly White has lost control.}) 13... Rxe5 (13... dxe5 {During the game this looked more critical. If Black gets c6 in, he will be fine.} 14. Qa5 $1 Nxd5 15. cxd5 Bg4 16. Rac1 $16 {White will exchange the e2 pawn for c7 and the passed d-pawn should give him a healthy advantage. But maybe practically this was a better choice as at least Black has some counterplay. In the game he is left with passive pieces.}) 14. Rac1 Bg4 15. Re1 {Keeping the pressure. Now the plan is simple. Just push e4-f4 and gain more space.} (15. Ne3 $5 {This looks highly tempting and I tried very hard to make the tactics work. In hindsight I feel this is also objectively better.} Qc8 16. Nxg4 (16. c5 $5 {I was mainly trying to use the trick of weak bank rank} Rxc5 $4 (16... dxc5 17. Nxg4 Nxg4 18. Qf4 g5 19. Qf3 c6 {I didn't see a follow up, but engine simply suggests doubling of the rooks on the d-file.} 20. Rd2 $16) 17. Rxc5 dxc5 18. Nxg4 Nxg4 19. Bxb7 $18) 16... Nxg4 17. Qd4 Nf6 18. c5 Rxc5 19. Rxc5 dxc5 20. Qxc5 {I felt that exchaning too many pieces will help ease the defense. Although even here due to bad rook on a8, White keeps a considerable edge.} c6 21. Qe7) 15... Re8 16. Rc3 {Threatening Nf6+ followed by Bxb7.} (16. b3) 16... Rb8 17. e4 Nd7 18. f4 $16 Be6 19. b3 a5 20. Rce3 {The last couple of moves were normal. Both sides just reshuffled the pieces. White has a decent advantage, but it's not easy to get any breaks in the centre yet. Black is quite solid.} Ra8 $6 (20... a4 $1 {Black should have used the opportunity to open up the a-file. During the game he struggled for the very same thing!}) 21. Qd4 Rb8 (21... a4 22. b4 c6 23. Nc3 (23. Bf1) 23... Qb6) 22. Nc3 f6 23. Nb5 {The knight on b5 locks black pieces and also it can re-route to d4.} Ra8 24. Qd2 {A subtle move. I indirectly prevent a4 as it is met with a central breakthrough.} Qc8 (24... a4 25. e5 $1 fxe5 26. Bxb7 Rb8 27. Bc6 $16) 25. Nd4 (25. g4 $5 {Engine's choice! This move didn't come to my mind!}) 25... Bf7 26. Qc3 $1 {This move might not look anything special, but I am quite proud of it. I could have started expanding on the kingside, but Black would have played a4 and got some counterplay. With Qc3 I support the c4 pawn and keep total control. The most important thing is to not allow unnecessary play.} Qb8 27. h4 Qa7 28. Bh3 ({Apparently the direct} 28. g4 {g4 was better}) 28... Rad8 (28... Nf8 {Cori didn't like e5 here. I would have probably played Kh2 preparing e5.}) 29. Kh2 Qc5 30. g4 $1 {Now it's not easy to meet the threat of g5.} Nf8 31. g5 Ng6 32. Rf1 $1 (32. gxf6 Nxf4 {is completely unnecessary!}) 32... Nxh4 33. gxf6 $18 {There are many moves for Black, but nothing satisfactory. It's completely winning for White now.} gxf6 (33... g6 34. Qd3 Kh8 35. Bg4) 34. Rg3+ Kf8 35. Ne6+ Bxe6 36. Qxf6+ Bf7 37. Qh6+ Ke7 38. Qxh4+ Kf8 39. Qh6+ Ke7 40. Rg7 $18 {It felt nice to avenge the loss in rapids!} 1-0


[Event "Bienne GM Tournament"]
[Site "Biel"]
[Date "2019.07.24"]
[Round "10.2"]
[White "Vidit, Santosh Gujrathi"]
[Black "Leko, Peter"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "A37"]
[WhiteElo "2703"]
[BlackElo "2674"]
[Annotator "David Cummings"]
[PlyCount "117"]
[EventDate "2019.??.??"]
[EventType "game"]
[EventCountry "SUI"]

{Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Before this game, Peter was leading by one point in the overall standings. Hence, this game was really important for me as it was my best chance to take the lead.'} 1. c4 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Vidit, Santosh Gujrathi' Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'One month ago, I used a very interesting novelty to win against Peter in a rapid game. This time, I decided to test him in the English opening, as I felt he would be more thoroughly prepared in the Catalan.'} c5 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 {In this game we see a typical theme in the Pure Symmetrical, where both players push their b-pawns. A related line (for comparison) is:} (5. a3 a6 6. Rb1 Rb8 7. b4 cxb4 8. axb4 b5 9. cxb5 axb5 10. Nf3 {which was a recommendation for White in Tony Kosten's book The Dynamic English. Now} e5 11. d4 {is analyzed in Thiede-Cox in the PGN Archives}) 5... d6 {A flexible move which has been quite popular in recent high-level games. The main alternatives are 5...e6, 5...e5 and 5...Nf6, which we have looked at many times on the site.} 6. O-O Rb8 {It is a little unusual to combine 5...d6 with the plan of ...Ra8-b8 and ...b7-b5, and in the game it doesn't work out well for Peter. Several other lines are covered in the Archives, for example: Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '!?' '!?' Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'The first interesting point of the game. Earlier they used to play the setup with e6-Nge7 which was considered solid, although recently the trend has been to play Bf5-Qd7 which is a more aggressive approach. The point of Rb8, as I understand, is quite clever. Black waits for White to commit with a plan & accordingly react with either Bf5-Qd7 or e6/e5 Nge7. I expect lot of new theory to develop in this direction.'} (6... e5 {- Giri-Lupulescu}) (6... Bf5 {- Kosten-Gordon} 7. h3 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi} Nf6 8. d3 O-O 9. Be3 a6 10. Qd2 {This was the most recent top level game, where Maxime quite dubiously sacrificed a pawn on the next move and struggled against Carlsen.} b5 $6 11. cxb5 axb5 12. Nxb5 Qa5 13. Nc3 Rab8 14. Rfc1 Rfc8 15. b3 $16 {1-0 (43) Carlsen,M (2845)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2773) Karlsruhe/Baden Baden 2019}) (6... Nh6 {- McShane-Carlsen}) (6... Nf6 {- Swiercz-Meier}) (6... e6 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi} 7. d3 Nge7) 7. a3 {Both sides proceed with immediate queenside expansion. Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'With hindsight, this a3-b4 idea looks a bit slow.'} (7. e3 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi might be the more critical approach, directly fighting in the centre.} Nf6 8. d4) 7... a6 8. Rb1 (8. b4 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi} cxb4 9. axb4 Nxb4) 8... b5 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '?!' '?!' Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'A pleasant surprise! With a clever intermezzo, Black could have won some tempi.'} (8... Bf5 $1 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi} 9. d3 b5 10. cxb5 axb5 {The point is that as Black has forced me to play d3, I can't continue with my b4 plan as the c3 knight will be left hanging.} 11. Bd2 Nf6 12. b4 cxb4 13. axb4 Qd7 14. Bg5 O-O 15. Qd2 Rfc8 $11 {Black looks completelty fine.}) 9. cxb5 axb5 10. b4 cxb4 11. axb4 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '' ''} Nf6 $6 {After this natural developing move, it turns out that the position is surprisingly tricky for Black, despite the symmetry. Instead: Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'A subpar move. Already at this point Peter was thinking for a long period of time, suggesting me that he felt quite uncomfortable.'} (11... Bf5 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'was more tricky, although White is still slightly better after'} 12. Rb3 Be6 {pushes White's rook to a more awkward post} (12... Qd7 13. d4 Bg4 {was played in Mandekic,I (2277)-Bistric,F (2494) Kastav 2002 0-1 (37), and now} 14. Be3 Nf6 15. d5 Bxf3 16. exf3 $1 {gives White an edge thanks to his two bishops and extra space.}) 13. Rb2 (13. Ng5 $1 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi} Bd7 14. Nge4 $1 Nh6 15. d4 Nf5 16. e3 $14) 13... Qc8 {looks playable for Black}) 12. d4 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '!' '!' Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'It's really unpleasant to meet the threat of d5.'} Bf5 {Or:} (12... O-O 13. d5 Ne5 14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. Qd3 Ne8 16. Be3 Nd6 17. Bc5 {was slightly better for White in Schmidt,A (2164)-Kapfer, U (1967) Germany 2015 1-0 (56)}) 13. Rb3 {White actually had a choice of good moves here, since:} (13. d5 {is also promising. Now Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '!' '!'} Bxb1 (13... Ne4 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Bb2 $1 {is excellent for White}) 14. dxc6 Bf5 15. Nd4 O-O 16. Ndxb5 {netted White an extra pawn in Ivanov,O (2425)-Orev,P (2245) Gyongyos 1995 1-0  (29)} (16. Bg5 $16 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi})) 13... d5 {Black prevents the d4-d5 thrust, but in setting up a symmetrical pawn structure, he has lost a tempo by playing ...d7-d6-d5 in two moves. Black is therefore a whole tempo down on comparable theoretical positions such as those mentioned in the note to White's 5th move above. An old game saw:} (13... Bg4 14. d5 Bxf3 15. exf3 {(again this is the best way to recapture)} Ne5 16. f4 Nc4 17. Ne2 O-O 18. Nd4 {with a typical pull for White with more space and the two bishops, Fernandez,J (2420)-Spiridonov,N (2420) Decin 1977 0-1 (42)}) 14. Ne5 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '!' '!' Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'I like this approach of directly putting pressure on Black. In order to meet with the threats, Black has to put his pieces in awkward positions.'} (14. Bf4 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi} Rb6 15. Qc1 O-O) 14... Qb6 (14... Rb6 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi} 15. Nxb5 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Rxb5 17. exf6 Bxf6 18. Bh6 $16) 15. Be3 {Another good setup for White is: Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '!' '!'} (15. Bf4 Rc8 16. e3 {with pressure.}) 15... Be6 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'An ugly looking move. It shows that Black really is in some trouble.'} (15... Rd8 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi I would have still preferred to move the rook and keep at least the bishop on f5 more active.} 16. Qc1 $1 $14 {With all kinds of threats like Nxd5/Nxb5.}) 16. Nd3 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '!' '!' Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'The key manouevre. Once the knight lands on c5. Black pieces are completely paralyzed.'} O-O (16... Nxd4 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi} 17. Ne5 $1 $18 {is the clever point. The d4 pawn is poisoned.}) 17. Nc5 {White has used his extra tempi to establish this powerful knight on the c5-square, and this makes a big difference.} Rfd8 18. Ra3 {Activating his rook. Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '!' '!' Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Using tactical tricks to improve the rook's position. Once White gets control of the a-file, he will have complete domination.'} Ra8 {Black cannot grab the b4-pawn, since:} (18... Nxb4 $2 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Now the b4 pawn is poisoned!'} 19. Qb1 Nc6 20. Ra6 Qc7 21. Bf4 {and White wins material. Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '+-' '+-' Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'wins material.'}) 19. Rxa8 Rxa8 20. Qb3 {White has pressure against both the d5- and b5-pawns, and it is hard for Black to keep both defended.} Qd8 (20... Rd8 {is well met by Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'would cede the control of the a-file:'} 21. Ra1 {and the rook joins the party Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '' ''}) 21. Rc1 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '!' '!' Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'The final precise move in the sequence starting with 14.Ne5! After this, strategically Black's position is lost. He can't avoid losing material as both pawns b5 and d5 are very weak.'} Rc8 (21... Rb8 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi} 22. Nxe6 fxe6 23. Nxd5 $18) 22. Nxb5 {White is a clear pawn up, and still has the more active pieces.} Qb6 (22... Bf5 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi} 23. Nc3 e6 24. h3 h5 25. b5 Na5 26. Qb4) 23. Nxe6 fxe6 24. Bh3 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '!' '!' Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Using tactics to keep my pieces active.'} Kf7 25. Rc5 Ra8 {Not: Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'White's position is completely winning. He is a pawn up and has better pieces. I had played really well in the last phase of the game, but I failed to land the final blow. Over the next few moves, I improved my pieces further but didn't make much progress.'} (25... Nd7 $2 {because of} 26. Bxe6+ {and White crashes through. Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '+-!' '+-!'}) 26. Bf4 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '!' '!'} Nd8 27. Bc7 Qb7 28. Qf3 {A convincing alternative was: Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '?!' '?!' Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'I wanted to stop the f6 knight from coming to e4. This doesn't lose the advantage, but practically Bxd8 would have won the game on the spot.'} (28. Bxd8 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '!' '!' Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Simplest.'} Rxd8 29. Nc7 Rd6 30. b5 {and Black is busted Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '+-' '+-' Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'and all of Black's pieces are tied up. Soon White will sacrifice on e6 and push the b-pawn.'}) 28... Bh6 29. Be5 Bg7 30. Kg2 (30. Nc7 $1 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi} Ra1+ 31. Kg2 Qxb4 32. Bxe6+ Nxe6 33. Nxe6 {This was a difficult tactics to see in timetrouble.}) 30... h5 31. g4 (31. Nc7 $1 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi}) (31. Qf4 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi} Ra4 32. Nc3 Rxb4 33. Rc7 Qb6 34. Bd6) 31... hxg4 32. Bxg4 Ra4 33. Qb3 {White doesn't spoil anything, but by playing a little statically he allows Black to keep going. Instead: Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '?!' '?!' Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Another indecisive move. White was still completely winning, but after this practically the task became tougher.'} (33. Bc7 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '!' '!' Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'It was possible to finish the game with brute force!'} Nc6 34. e4 {should win comfortably, for example Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '!' '!' Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Complete aggression!'} (34. Ba5 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi}) 34... dxe4 35. Bxe6+ {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '!' '!'} Kxe6 36. Qb3+ {picking up the a4-rook Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '+-' '+-'}) 33... Ra6 34. Bxf6 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'It's a pity to give the bishop. Already at this point I started to feel that I had lost considerable portion of my advantage and I might have to 'rewin the game'.'} Bxf6 35. e3 Rb6 36. Be2 Nc6 37. Qa4 Kg7 (37... Bh4 $5 {was more resilient, since} 38. f4 {can be met by} Be1 {activating the bishop}) 38. f4 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Stopping Black's counterplay ideas like ...e5.'} (38. Nc3 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi} Nxb4 39. Qe8 Rc6 40. Na4 $1 {is just too brilliant of a win!}) 38... Ra6 39. Qb3 Rb6 40. Bd3 Na7 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '?' '?' Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'So many times the 40th move is the critical mistake!'} (40... Qb8 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi It made more sense to just wait as it's not easy to remove the knight on b5 and convert the advantage.}) 41. Nc7 $1 {Going for the breakthrough Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Peter expected me to exchange the knights, but this counter intuitive knight jump practically wins the game.'} (41. Rc7 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi} Qb8) 41... Rxb4 42. Nxe6+ (42. Qd1 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi was also possible, but simplying to the endgame looked easier.} Rb2+ 43. Bc2 {with Qg4 next.}) 42... Kf7 43. Nd8+ Kg7 {Or:} (43... Ke8 44. Qxd5 Qxd5+ 45. Rxd5 {defends the d8-knight and White remains two pans up}) 44. Qxd5 Qxd5+ 45. Rxd5 Rb3 46. Ne6+ {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '!' '!'} Kh6 47. Nc5 {With two extra pawns, White eventually brings the point home. Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '!' '!' Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'I had to foresee in advance that I can defend the d3 bishop this way and avoid losing the e3 pawn. The position is winning but still needs precision.'} Rb2+ 48. Kg3 Nc6 49. Rd7 Nb4 50. Bc4 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '!' '!'} (50. Be4 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi} Re2 {Now White has to give up either the e3 or h2 pawn.}) 50... Nc2 (50... Rc2 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi} 51. Bb5 g5) 51. Nd3 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '!' '!' Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'The knight danced all the way from b5-c7-e6-d8-e6-c5-d3!'} Rb1 52. Kf3 g5 53. fxg5+ Bxg5 54. Ne5 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '!' '!' Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Again a very important move, using tactics to defend the e3 pawn.'} Kg7 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Now taking on e3 is threatened again.'} (54... Nxe3 55. h4 {wins a minor piece Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '+-!' '+-!'}) (54... Bxe3 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi} 55. Ng4+ $18) 55. Rd8 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: '!' '!'} Bxe3 56. Rg8+ Kh7 (56... Kf6 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi} 57. Ng4+ $18) (56... Kh6 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi} 57. Ng4+ $18) 57. Rg6 {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'Threatening mate with Bg8+-Nf7++. Black's pieces are too far and not coordinated.'} Rb8 58. Bd3 Rf8+ 59. Rf6+ {Vidit,Santosh Gujrathi: 'White will win the piece on c2. Black resigned. After this game I took the lead of the tournament and didn't let it go till the last! I was very happy to win such a prestigious even like the Biel GM, on top of that with a margin of 6 points!'} 1-0


