{[%evp 0,117,27,-10,23,21,27,12,21,18,5,5,12,5,12,7,25,27,4,-1,21,21,23,27,16,22,12,14,47,39,68,32,73,62,71,74,47,91,85,105,105,85,135,122,154,110,192,166,157,157,208,206,206,208,212,216,202,232,213,217,215,204,276,295,295,262,295,200,245,200,188,174,187,169,179,179,242,158,179,177,186,188,217,184,215,216,216,218,216,225,223,219,221,221,218,226,218,217,214,203,184,194,214,214,205,212,236,240,255,257,266,282,374,388,384,345,357,381,381,364]} {Before this game, Peter was leading by one point in the overall standings. Hence, this game was really important for me as it was my best chance to take the lead.} 1. c4 {David Cummings Vidit, Santosh Gujrathi One month ago, I used a very interesting novelty to win against Peter in a rapid game. This time, I decided to test him in the English opening, as I felt he would be more thoroughly prepared in the Catalan.} c5 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 {David Cummings: 'In this game we see a typical theme in the Pure Symmetrical, where both players push their b-pawns. A related line (for comparison) is:'} (5. a3 {David Cummings} a6 6. Rb1 Rb8 7. b4 cxb4 8. axb4 b5 9. cxb5 axb5 10. Nf3 {which was a recommendation for White in Tony Kosten's book The Dynamic English. Now} e5 11. d4 {is analyzed in Thiede-Cox in the PGN Archives}) 5... d6 {David Cummings: 'A flexible move which has been quite popular in recent high-level games. The main alternatives are 5...e6, 5...e5 and 5...Nf6, which we have looked at many times on the site.'} 6. O-O Rb8 $5 {David Cummings: 'It is a little unusual to combine 5...d6 with the plan of ...Ra8-b8 and ...b7-b5, and in the game it doesn't work out well for Peter. Several other lines are covered in the Archives, for example:' The first interesting point of the game. Earlier they used to play the setup with e6-Nge7 which was considered solid, although recently the trend has been to play Bf5-Qd7 which is a more aggressive approach. The point of Rb8, as I understand, is quite clever. Black waits for White to commit with a plan & accordingly react with either Bf5-Qd7 or e6/e5 Nge7. I expect lot of new theory to develop in this direction.} (6... e6 7. d3 Nge7) (6... Bf5 {David Cummings: '- Kosten-Gordon'} 7. h3 Nf6 8. d3 O-O 9. Be3 a6 10. Qd2 {This was the most recent top level game, where Maxime quite dubiously sacrificed a pawn on the next move and struggled against Carlsen.} b5 $6 11. cxb5 axb5 12. Nxb5 Qa5 13. Nc3 Rab8 14. Rfc1 Rfc8 15. b3 $16 {1-0 (43) Carlsen,M (2845)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2773) Karlsruhe/Baden Baden 2019}) (6... e5 {(David Cummings) - Giri-Lupulescu}) (6... Nh6 {(David Cummings) - McShane-Carlsen}) (6... Nf6 {(David Cummings) - Swiercz-Meier}) 7. a3 {David Cummings: 'Both sides proceed with immediate queenside expansion.' With hindsight, this a3-b4 idea looks a bit slow.} (7. e3 {might be the more critical approach, directly fighting in the centre.} Nf6 8. d4) 7... a6 8. Rb1 (8. b4 cxb4 9. axb4 Nxb4) 8... b5 $6 {A pleasant surprise! With a clever intermezzo, Black could have won some tempi.} (8... Bf5 $1 9. d3 b5 10. cxb5 axb5 {The point is that as Black has forced me to play d3, I can't continue with my b4 plan as the c3 knight will be left hanging.} 11. Bd2 Nf6 12. b4 cxb4 13. axb4 Qd7 14. Bg5 O-O 15. Qd2 Rfc8 $11 {Black looks completelty fine.}) 9. cxb5 axb5 10. b4 cxb4 11. axb4 $14 Nf6 {David Cummings: '?!' David Cummings: 'After this natural developing move, it turns out that the position is surprisingly tricky for Black, despite the symmetry. Instead:' A subpar move. Already at this point Peter was thinking for a long period of time, suggesting me that he felt quite uncomfortable.} (11... Bf5 {was more tricky, although White is still slightly better after} 12. Rb3 Be6 {David Cummings: 'pushes White's rook to a more awkward post'} (12... Qd7 {David Cummings} 13. d4 Bg4 {was played in Mandekic,I (2277)-Bistric,F (2494) Kastav 2002 0-1 (37), and now} 14. Be3 Nf6 15. d5 Bxf3 16. exf3 $1 {gives White an edge thanks to his two bishops and extra space.}) 13. Ng5 $1 (13. Rb2 {David Cummings} Qc8 {looks playable for Black}) 13... Bd7 14. Nge4 $1 Nh6 15. d4 Nf5 16. e3 $14) 12. d4 $1 {It's really unpleasant to meet the threat of d5.} Bf5 {David Cummings: 'Or:'} (12... O-O {David Cummings} 13. d5 Ne5 14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. Qd3 Ne8 16. Be3 Nd6 17. Bc5 {was slightly better for White in Schmidt,A (2164)-Kapfer, U (1967) Germany 2015 1-0 (56)}) 13. Rb3 {David Cummings: 'White actually had a choice of good moves here, since:'} (13. d5 $1 {David Cummings: 'is also promising. Now'} Bxb1 (13... Ne4 {David Cummings} 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Bb2 $1 {is excellent for White}) 14. dxc6 Bf5 15. Nd4 O-O 16. Bg5 $16 (16. Ndxb5 {(David Cummings) netted White an extra pawn in Ivanov,O (2425)-Orev,P (2245) Gyongyos 1995 1-0  (29)})) 13... d5 {David Cummings: 'Black prevents the d4-d5 thrust, but in setting up a symmetrical pawn structure, he has lost a tempo by playing ...d7-d6-d5 in two moves. Black is therefore a whole tempo down on comparable theoretical positions such as those mentioned in the note to White's 5th move above. An old game saw:'} (13... Bg4 {David Cummings} 14. d5 Bxf3 15. exf3 {(again this is the best way to recapture)} Ne5 16. f4 Nc4 17. Ne2 O-O 18. Nd4 {with a typical pull for White with more space and the two bishops, Fernandez,J (2420)-Spiridonov,N (2420) Decin 1977 0-1 (42)}) 14. Ne5 $1 {I like this approach of directly putting pressure on Black. In order to meet with the threats, Black has to put his pieces in awkward positions.} (14. Bf4 Rb6 15. Qc1 O-O) 14... Qb6 (14... Rb6 15. Nxb5 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Rxb5 17. exf6 Bxf6 18. Bh6 $16) 15. Be3 $1 {David Cummings: 'Another good setup for White is:'} (15. Bf4 {David Cummings} Rc8 16. e3 {with pressure.}) 15... Be6 {An ugly looking move. It shows that Black really is in some trouble.} (15... Rd8 {I would have still preferred to move the rook and keep at least the bishop on f5 more active.} 16. Qc1 $1 $14 {With all kinds of threats like Nxd5/Nxb5.}) 16. Nd3 $1 {The key manouevre. Once the knight lands on c5. Black pieces are completely paralyzed.} O-O (16... Nxd4 17. Ne5 $1 $18 {is the clever point. The d4 pawn is poisoned.}) 17. Nc5 {David Cummings: 'White has used his extra tempi to establish this powerful knight on the c5-square, and this makes a big difference.'} Rfd8 18. Ra3 $1 {David Cummings: 'Activating his rook.' Using tactical tricks to improve the rook's position. Once White gets control of the a-file, he will have complete domination.} Ra8 {David Cummings: 'Black cannot grab the b4-pawn, since:'} (18... Nxb4 {David Cummings: '?' Now the b4 pawn is poisoned!} 19. Qb1 Nc6 20. Ra6 Qc7 21. Bf4 $18 {David Cummings: 'and White wins material.' wins material.}) 19. Rxa8 Rxa8 20. Qb3 {David Cummings: 'White has pressure against both the d5- and b5-pawns, and it is hard for Black to keep both defended.'} Qd8 (20... Rd8 {David Cummings: 'is well met by' would cede the control of the a-file:} 21. Ra1 $16 {David Cummings: 'and the rook joins the party'}) 21. Rc1 $1 {The final precise move in the sequence starting with 14.Ne5! After this, strategically Black's position is lost. He can't avoid losing material as both pawns b5 and d5 are very weak.} Rc8 (21... Rb8 22. Nxe6 fxe6 23. Nxd5 $18) 22. Nxb5 {David Cummings: 'White is a clear pawn up, and still has the more active pieces.'} Qb6 (22... Bf5 23. Nc3 e6 24. h3 h5 25. b5 Na5 26. Qb4) 23. Nxe6 fxe6 24. Bh3 $1 {Using tactics to keep my pieces active.} Kf7 25. Rc5 Ra8 {David Cummings: 'Not:' White's position is completely winning. He is a pawn up and has better pieces. I had played really well in the last phase of the game, but I failed to land the final blow. Over the next few moves, I improved my pieces further but didn't make much progress.} (25... Nd7 {David Cummings: '?' David Cummings: 'because of'} 26. Bxe6+ $1 $18 {David Cummings: 'and White crashes through.'}) 26. Bf4 $1 Nd8 27. Bc7 Qb7 28. Qf3 $6 {David Cummings: 'A convincing alternative was:' I wanted to stop the f6 knight from coming to e4. This doesn't lose the advantage, but practically Bxd8 would have won the game on the spot.} (28. Bxd8 $1 {Simplest.} Rxd8 29. Nc7 Rd6 30. b5 $18 {David Cummings: 'and Black is busted' and all of Black's pieces are tied up. Soon White will sacrifice on e6 and push the b-pawn.}) 28... Bh6 29. Be5 Bg7 30. Kg2 (30. Nc7 $1 Ra1+ 31. Kg2 Qxb4 32. Bxe6+ Nxe6 33. Nxe6 {This was a difficult tactics to see in timetrouble.}) 30... h5 31. g4 (31. Nc7 $1) (31. Qf4 Ra4 32. Nc3 Rxb4 33. Rc7 Qb6 34. Bd6) 31... hxg4 32. Bxg4 Ra4 33. Qb3 $6 {David Cummings: 'White doesn't spoil anything, but by playing a little statically he allows Black to keep going. Instead:' Another indecisive move. White was still completely winning, but after this practically the task became tougher.} (33. Bc7 $1 {It was possible to finish the game with brute force!} Nc6 34. e4 $1 {David Cummings: 'should win comfortably, for example' Complete aggression!} (34. Ba5) 34... dxe4 35. Bxe6+ $1 Kxe6 36. Qb3+ $18 {David Cummings: 'picking up the a4-rook'}) 33... Ra6 34. Bxf6 {It's a pity to give the bishop. Already at this point I started to feel that I had lost considerable portion of my advantage and I might have to 'rewin the game'.} Bxf6 35. e3 Rb6 36. Be2 Nc6 37. Qa4 Kg7 (37... Bh4 $5 {(David Cummings) was more resilient, since} 38. f4 {can be met by} Be1 {activating the bishop}) 38. f4 {Stopping Black's counterplay ideas like ...e5.} (38. Nc3 Nxb4 39. Qe8 Rc6 40. Na4 $1 {is just too brilliant of a win!}) 38... Ra6 39. Qb3 Rb6 40. Bd3 Na7 $2 {So many times the 40th move is the critical mistake!} (40... Qb8 {It made more sense to just wait as it's not easy to remove the knight on b5 and convert the advantage.}) 41. Nc7 $1 {David Cummings: 'Going for the breakthrough' Peter expected me to exchange the knights, but this counter intuitive knight jump practically wins the game.} (41. Rc7 Qb8) 41... Rxb4 42. Nxe6+ (42. Qd1 {was also possible, but simplying to the endgame looked easier.} Rb2+ 43. Bc2 {with Qg4 next.}) 42... Kf7 43. Nd8+ Kg7 {David Cummings: 'Or:'} (43... Ke8 {David Cummings} 44. Qxd5 Qxd5+ 45. Rxd5 {defends the d8-knight and White remains two pans up}) 44. Qxd5 Qxd5+ 45. Rxd5 Rb3 46. Ne6+ $1 Kh6 47. Nc5 $1 {David Cummings: 'With two extra pawns, White eventually brings the point home.' I had to foresee in advance that I can defend the d3 bishop this way and avoid losing the e3 pawn. The position is winning but still needs precision.} Rb2+ 48. Kg3 Nc6 49. Rd7 Nb4 50. Bc4 $1 (50. Be4 Re2 {Now White has to give up either the e3 or h2 pawn.}) 50... Nc2 (50... Rc2 51. Bb5 g5) 51. Nd3 $1 {The knight danced all the way from b5-c7-e6-d8-e6-c5-d3!} Rb1 52. Kf3 g5 53. fxg5+ Bxg5 54. Ne5 $1 {Again a very important move, using tactics to defend the e3 pawn.} Kg7 {Now taking on e3 is threatened again.} (54... Nxe3 55. h4 $1 $18 {David Cummings: 'wins a minor piece'}) (54... Bxe3 55. Ng4+ $18) 55. Rd8 $1 Bxe3 56. Rg8+ Kh7 (56... Kf6 57. Ng4+ $18) (56... Kh6 57. Ng4+ $18) 57. Rg6 {Threatening mate with Bg8+-Nf7++. Black's pieces are too far and not coordinated.} Rb8 58. Bd3 Rf8+ 59. Rf6+ {White will win the piece on c2. Black resigned. After this game I took the lead of the tournament and didn't let it go till the last! I was very happy to win such a prestigious even like the Biel GM, on top of that with a margin of 6 points!} 1-0


[Event "Tata Steel-A 81st"]
[Site "Wijk aan Zee"]
