1. d4 {Paunovic,Tomislav} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qa4+ {In search of a new weapon against the Ragozin defence, White revisits the 1930's theory.} ({Both} 5. Bg5) ({and} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 {are topical.}) 5... Nc6 {It's all about the placement of the black knight ahead of its c-pawn, which according to the classical principles of the Queens Gambit puts Black in disadvantage. Vyacheslav Ragozin made an important contribution by arguing the point.} 6. e3 O-O 7. Qc2 {[#] Sooner or later White has to return the queen to her proper spot, so it can be done right away.} (7. Bd2 {is best answered by the immediate} dxc4 $1 8. Bxc4 Bd6 {getting ready for e6-e5, which is the main idea in the Ragozin.} 9. O-O e5 10. h3 a6 11. Qc2 exd4 12. exd4 b5 $1 13. Be2 Nb4 14. Qd1 Bb7 {Yermolinsky-D.Zilberstein, San Francisco 2007}) 7... Re8 {Vidit settles on one of the most popular choices.} ({Others include} 7... dxc4 {which may eventually transpose to the game,}) (7... Ne7 {which I view as admission of guilt, as Black is trying to reposition the "badly placed" knight,}) ({and, finally my personal favorite} 7... b6) 8. Bd2 Bd6 {Black's idea is to wait for the white light-squared bishop to come out before taking on c4. I wonder if it's worth the trouble.} 9. h3 ({The point of Black's early rook move is visible after} 9. c5 Bf8 {where the threat of e6-e5 forces White into} 10. Bb5 Bd7 11. Bxc6 Bxc6 12. Ne5 {which, incidentally, might not be so bad for him.}) 9... a6 10. a3 Bd7 11. Be2 dxc4 12. Bxc4 h6 {[#] So, Black has won a local battle for a tempo (Bf1-e2xc4), but what are his accomplishments? The Bd7 move might have made sense when the white queen was on a4, but now it looks like a waste of time. In the meantime, thanks to the Re8 move Black must guard the g5-square before moving the e-pawn forward.} 13. g4 $3 {Paunovic,Tomislav: 'N' No matter what your engines say I absolutely admire Radjabov's concept. If Black can be punished for his opening transgressions it must be done in a resolute fashion.} (13. O-O {Paunovic,Tomislav: '- 134/ 140'} e5 14. Rae1 Qe7 15. Nh4 {Aronian-Giri, 2017}) 13... e5 {A classic strategy of meeting a flank attack with counterstrike in the centre, but it's wrought with dangers of opening the diagonal for the white bishop.} (13... b5 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '!?'} 14. Ba2 b4 {deserved attention.} 15. Ne2 $13 {Paunovic,Tomislav}) 14. g5 b5 ({Here and on the next move Vidit should have tried a a piece sacrifice:} 14... Nxd4 15. exd4 exd4+ 16. Ne2 b5 17. Bd3 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '!'} hxg5 18. Nxg5 c5 19. O-O {Paunovic,Tomislav} (19. O-O-O $5 {Paunovic,Tomislav}) 19... Qb6 20. b3 $14) 15. Ba2 exd4 {Paunovic,Tomislav: 'Diagram [#]' This will meet with a devastating response. [#]} ({Still,} 15... Nxd4 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '!?'} 16. exd4 exd4+ 17. Ne2 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '- 14...b5'} Qe7 18. Nfxd4 hxg5 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '' Paunovic,Tomislav: ' c5' was there for the taking.}) 16. gxh6 $3 {Guess who's coming to dinner - White threatens Qg6!} (16. Rg1 $5 {Paunovic,Tomislav} Ne5 $1 (16... dxc3 $2 17. Bxc3 $18) (16... d3 17. Qxd3 hxg5 18. Nxg5 Ne5 19. Qc2 $16 {}) 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 18. gxf6 (18. g6 $5 Kh8 19. gxf7 Re7 20. Qg6 Qf8 21. Nd5 Rxf7 $13) 18... Qxf6 $8 19. Nd5 Qf3 $13) 16... dxc3 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '?!'} ({The only way to deal with it was} 16... Bf4 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '!'} 17. O-O-O Bxh6 (17... dxc3 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '?'} 18. exf4 cxd2+ 19. Rxd2 Qe7 20. Qg6 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '+-' is White's signature attacking line.}) 18. exd4 Bxd2+ 19. Qxd2 {and now counterattack -} b4 $1 20. axb4 {Paunovic,Tomislav} Nxb4 21. Bc4 $13) 17. Bxc3 Be6 ({Now} 17... Bf4 18. Qg6 Bxh6 {Paunovic,Tomislav: 'Diagram [#]' still saves the king, but at the cost of a piece.} 19. Rd1 $1 ({Not} 19. O-O-O {Paunovic,Tomislav: '?!'} Qe7 20. Bxf6 {as} Qc5+ {Paunovic,Tomislav: '!'} 21. Bc3 Be6 {turns the tables.} 22. Bxe6 {Paunovic,Tomislav} Rxe6 23. Qc2 b4 $15) 19... Qe7 20. Bxf6 Qxf6 21. Qxf6 gxf6 22. Rxd7 {with large advantage to White.} Re7 {Paunovic,Tomislav} 23. Rd5 $1 $16) 18. Bxe6 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '?!'} ({Aesthetically White doesn't want to put his rook on a2, but} 18. Rg1 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '!'} Bxa2 19. Rxg7+ Kf8 20. Rxa2 Be5 21. Ng5 {actually works for him.} Qd5 {Paunovic,Tomislav} (21... Bxc3+ {Paunovic,Tomislav} 22. Qxc3 Ne5 23. b3 $1 $18) 22. Rxf7+ Qxf7 23. Nxf7 Kxf7 24. a4 $16) 18... Rxe6 19. Rg1 {[#]} Ne8 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '?' Clearing out that square was one of the ideas of 17...Be6, but just focusing on the defense isn't going to cut it.} ({Black needed to introduce an element of counterplay:} 19... Nh5 20. Bxg7 {Paunovic,Tomislav: 'Diagram  [#]'} Bg3 $3 {albeit White has a choice of good responses to it, the most efficient being} 21. Rd1 Qe7 22. Ke2 (22. Rd5 {Paunovic,Tomislav} Rxe3+ 23. Kf1 Rxf3 24. Rxh5 $16) 22... Re8 23. Bc3 Rxe3+ {Paunovic,Tomislav: '?'} (23... Rxh6 {Paunovic,Tomislav} 24. Qf5 $16) (23... Rg6 {Paunovic,Tomislav} 24. Qf5 Ng7 25. Qd7 $16) 24. Kf1 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '+-'}) 20. Bxg7 Nxg7 21. Rxg7+ Kf8 22. Qh7 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '+-' From this point on White's attack is irresistable.} Qf6 23. Ng5 Rxe3+ 24. Kf1 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '!'} (24. fxe3 $2 {Paunovic,Tomislav} Bg3+ 25. Kd1 Qf1+ 26. Kc2 Qe2+ 27. Kb1 Qd1+ 28. Ka2 Nb4+ 29. axb4 Qa4+ 30. Kb1 Qd1+ $11) 24... Nd8 25. Qg8+ Ke7 26. h7 Bg3 {Paunovic,Tomislav: 'Diagram [#]' [#]} 27. Ne4 $1 {Still, Teimour had to see this one and keep his nerve in the face of time trouble.} Rxe4 (27... Qf3 28. Nxg3 {Paunovic,Tomislav}) 28. Rxg3 Rh4 29. Rd1 {A final stroke in this truly brilliant game. Black is forced to part with a rook.} Rxh7 30. Re3+ Ne6 31. Qxa8 (31. Qxh7 $5 {(Paunovic,Tomislav)  Re6}) 31... Rh8 32. Qc6 Kf8 33. Rxe6 Qxe6 34. Rd8+ Kg7 35. Qc3+ f6 36. Qxc7+ 1-0


