1. d4 {Perunovic,Milos} Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 c6 $5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 $5 {An interesting opening experiment. As Black will soon play ...c6-c5, he basically loses a tempo with respect to the normal Exchange System lines. His main aim is proving that b3 is not so useful, as it weakens the defence on d4 and exposes the queen to ...e6 or ...c6-a5. On the other hand, the queen defends c3, so White can play an early d4-d5 as a reaction to Black's typical centre undermining. So far, this line has been mainly used by lower rated players and this is a first high level practical test.} 7. e4 Nxc3 (7... Nb6 {(Perunovic,Milos) - 7/561}) 8. bxc3 O-O 9. Be3 {Perunovic,Milos: 'Diagram [#]' A natural developing move, but possibly not the strongest.} ({Intuitively I would say that the queen's development to b3 suits the plan based on} 9. Ba3 {as Black will need some time to prepare ...c6-c5, thus ensuring the prolonged stability of the queen on b3. Here are a few examples:} Nd7 (9... Qc7 10. Be2 Be6 {is not likely to offer Black enough counterplay:} 11. Qb2 Rd8 12. Ng5 Bc8 13. Qb3 $14 {Ivanisevic,I (2665)-Bitici,G (2068) Skopje 2016 (1-0, 36)}) 10. Bd3 ({A very old game went} 10. Be2 c5 11. O-O cxd4 {and now} 12. Nxd4 $2 $11 {Bogoljubow,E-Saemisch,F Lueneburg 1947 (½-½, 47) was clearly not what White should play,}) 10... c5 {Black has carried out his thematic break, but with the knight on d7 the queen has no worries.} 11. O-O b6 12. Rad1 e6 13. Bc4 Qe7 14. Rfe1 Bb7 15. Bc1 $14 {Leitao,R (2636)-Toth,C (2365) Joao Pessoa 2013 (1-0, 46)}) 9... c5 $146 {Obviously the critical continuation. In games between lower rated players Black has delayed his counterplay, allowing White to keep his space advantage.} (9... Nd7 {Perunovic,Milos}) 10. d5 {The most logical way of justifying b3.} ({But} 10. Be2 {has no obvious refutation.} cxd4 11. cxd4 Nc6 (11... Qa5+ $5) 12. Rd1 Bg4 13. d5 {Kumaran,D (2310)-Rojas Keim,L Guarapuava 1991 (½-½, 34)} Ne5 $5 14. Nxe5 Bxe2 15. Kxe2 Bxe5 {White's space advantage remains impressive but due to the slightly exposed king's placement on e2 Black has chances for counterplay.}) 10... Nd7 {Defending c5 with a developing move and creating a threat which White failed noticing.} 11. Bd3 $6 ({Abstractly, it makes sense preparing to consolidate the centre with c3-c4 by unpinning the c-pawn. But} 11. Rd1 {still allows} b5 {for instance} 12. Bxb5 Rb8) ({Therefore, the critical move is} 11. Rc1 $1 {defending and unpinning c3, when Black still needs to struggle finding a constructive plan.} Nf6 {Perunovic,Milos} 12. Qc2 Qa5 (12... e6 13. Bxc5 exd5 14. Bxf8 Qxf8 15. e5 Ng4 16. Be2 Nxe5 17. O-O $14) 13. Be2 e6 14. d6 Bd7 15. O-O Bc6 $13) 11... b5 $1 12. Qc2 (12. Bxb5 {Perunovic,Milos: '?'} Rb8 $17 {leaves White hanging to ...a7-a6 and ...xc3.} 13. Bf4 {Perunovic,Milos} Rb7 $17) 12... b4 $1 ({The slow approach} 12... c4 13. Be2 Nb6 14. Nd4 a6 {offers White a free hand to start a typical attack.} 15. h4) (12... f5 $5 {Perunovic,Milos} 13. exf5 $140 c4 14. Be2 Ne5 (14... Rxf5 $13) 15. fxg6 Bf5 16. gxh7+ Bxh7 17. Qd2 Nd3+ 18. Bxd3 Bxd3 $44) 13. Bd2 ({Had White anticipated what was going to happen in the game, he might have sacrificed the pawn with} 13. O-O {, when his strong centre and good development might have offered reasonable compensation for the pawn.}) 13... c4 $1 14. Bxc4 (14. Be2 Nc5 15. Bxc4 bxc3 $15 {leaves the e4-pawn hanging, offering Black the initiative partly based on the enemy king's presence in the centre.}) 14... Qc7 15. Be2 bxc3 $15 {The opening has ended in an obvious fiasco for White. His centre is immobile and the c3-pawn is very strong.} 16. O-O {Perunovic,Milos: 'Diagram [#]'} Ne5 {Perunovic,Milos: '!'} 17. Rfc1 ({The knight exchange favours Black, as he can coordinate his pieces better for sustaining the passed pawn, but White has no favourable way of avoiding it:} 17. Nd4 Ng4 18. Nf3 Bd7 $15) (17. Nxe5 {Perunovic,Milos} Qxe5 (17... Bxe5 18. Rac1 Bd7 19. Be3 Bxh2+ 20. Kh1 Be5 21. f4 Bg7 22. e5 $44) 18. Be3 f5 19. Bc4 f4 (19... Kh8 $15) 20. Bc5 Kh8 21. f3 Bd7 $15) (17. Rac1 {Perunovic,Milos} Nxf3+ 18. Bxf3 Ba6 19. Rfd1 Rfc8 20. d6 (20. Be3 Rab8 $17) 20... exd6 21. e5 Rab8 22. Qxc3 Qxc3 23. Bxc3 Bxe5 24. Bxe5 dxe5 $17) 17... Nxf3+ 18. Bxf3 Bd7 {Perunovic,Milos: '!' Perunovic,Milos: 'Diagram [#]'} 19. Bxc3 {A desperate attempt to save the game. White has to eliminate the dangerous pawn at any cost.} (19. Bg5 Rab8 20. Bxe7 Rb2 $19) (19. Rab1 Rfc8 20. Bg5 Rab8 $19 {[%cal Gb8b2]} 21. Bxe7 Rb2 22. Rxb2 cxb2 23. Qxc7 bxc1=Q+) (19. d6 $142 {Perunovic,Milos} Qxd6 (19... exd6 20. Bxc3 Rac8 (20... Rfc8 21. e5 Rab8 22. Qd2) 21. Bxg7 Qxc2 22. Rxc2 Rxc2 23. Bd1 $1 Rd2 24. Bxf8 Kxf8 25. Bb3 $15) 20. Bxc3 Rac8 21. Qb2 Rxc3 22. Rxc3 Rb8 23. Qc2 Qd4 24. Rd1 Qxc3 25. Qxc3 Bxc3 26. Rxd7 Rb2 27. g3 (27. a3 e5 $17) 27... Rxa2 28. Rxe7 Bd4 $17) 19... Rfc8 {Perunovic,Milos: ''} 20. Bxg7 (20. e5 {Perunovic,Milos} Bxe5 21. d6 Qxc3 22. Qxc3 Bxc3 23. Rxc3 Rxc3 24. Bxa8 exd6 $17) 20... Qxc2 21. Rxc2 Rxc2 22. Bd4 a5 ({Now or on the next move it would have been simpler to force White into passivity with} 22... Rac8 23. Be3 {White cannot allow the exchange of rooks.} f6 24. g4 (24. h4 {Perunovic,Milos} a5 $17) 24... a5 $17) 23. h3 Rb8 24. a3 (24. e5 {Perunovic,Milos} Rb4 25. Be3 Rcb2 26. Kh2 Rb1 $17) 24... f6 {Perunovic,Milos: '?!'} (24... Rc4 $1 $17 {Perunovic,Milos}) 25. e5 Rc4 26. Rd1 Ba4 ({White's saving chances are not obvious after} 26... fxe5 27. Bxe5 Rb3 28. d6 e6 {Perunovic,Milos: '' either, as the rook has no open files available, but of course it is not easy to allow him to have such an advanced passed pawn.}) 27. Rd2 Rc2 28. Rxc2 Bxc2 29. exf6 exf6 30. d6 {Possibly fruit of a misscalculation.} ({But Black's winning chances remain intact after} 30. Bxf6 Kf7 31. Bc3 (31. Be5 {Perunovic,Milos} Rb3 32. Bd6) 31... a4 $17) 30... Kg7 31. d7 {Perunovic,Milos: '?'} (31. Bc3 {Perunovic,Milos} Rd8 32. Bxa5 Rxd6 33. Bb4 Rd4 $17) 31... Ba4 {Perunovic,Milos: '-+'} 32. Bg4 {Perunovic,Milos: 'Diagram [#]'} Bxd7 $1 {Probably this is what White missed. But if so, this was a brilliant blunder from a practical point of view.} 33. Bxd7 Rd8 34. Bb6 Rxd7 35. Bxa5 Rd1+ 36. Kh2 Rd3 37. Bb4 Kf7 38. Bc5 Rd5 39. Bb4 Ke6 40. g3 f5 {Black's position is simply won. The a-pawn does not really count and with the actual pawn display White would have needed the light-squared bishop to retain saving chances.} 41. Kg2 Rd3 42. Bf8 Kd5 43. Be7 Ke6 {Perunovic,Milos: 'Diagram [#]'} ({The typical plan in the positions without the a-pawn would be a massive invasion starting with} 43... Kc4 {It would work perfectly fine here, too.} 44. Bb4 Kb3 45. g4 ({Passive defence would not do either:} 45. Bf8 Kc2 46. Bb4 Kd1 {Planning ...e2, ...f3 followed by preparing the pawn break ...f5-f4.} 47. Kf1 f4 $19) 45... Kc2 46. gxf5 gxf5 47. Bc5 Kd1 48. a4 Ke2 49. a5 Rc3 50. Be3 Ra3 51. Kg3 (51. Bb6 f4 $19) 51... Rxa5 52. Kf4 Rb5 {Putting White in some sort of zugzwang.} (52... Kf1 53. Kf3 {slightly complicates matters.}) 53. Ba7 (53. Kg3 Rb4 54. Bc5 Rb3+ 55. Be3 Rxe3+ 56. fxe3 Kxe3 $19) 53... Kf1 {[%cal Gf1g2]} 54. Kf3 Rb4 55. Bc5 Rc4 56. Bb6 h5 57. Ba7 h4 58. Be3 Kg1 $19) 44. Bf8 {Perunovic,Milos: '!'} g5 $6 45. Bc5 Rc3 46. Be3 $1 {Obviously underestimated by Black.} (46. Bb4 $17 {Perunovic,Milos} Rb3 $140 47. Bf8) 46... h6 ({I failed to find a winning plan for Black after} 46... g4 47. hxg4 fxg4 48. Bb6 Rxa3 {½-½ Cebalo,M (2515)-Nedev,T (2415) Cannes Martinez op 1996 (7) which seems to be a fortress. Please refer to}) (46... Rxa3 {Perunovic,Milos} 47. Bxg5 Kd5 48. Bf4 $11) 47. h4 {Perunovic,Milos: '!'} gxh4 48. Bxh6 hxg3 49. f3 $1 {The saving move. White will win the g-pawn and keep the favourable kingside structure.} (49. fxg3 $2 {leaves the light squares undefended.} Rxa3 50. Kh3 Ra7 51. Kg2 Ke5 52. Bf4+ Ke4 53. Bb8 Ra2+ 54. Kh3 Kf3 55. Kh4 Ra8 56. Be5 Rg8 57. Bd6 Kg2 58. Be5 Rg4+ 59. Kh5 Rxg3) 49... Rxa3 50. Kxg3 {Perunovic,Milos: '=' This is a theoretical draw already, as the bishop and the pawn complete their actions. The main thing White should avoid is pushing his pawn to f4.} Ra4 51. Bg5 Ke5 52. Bh6 Rc4 53. Bg7+ Kd5 54. Bh6 Kc6 55. Bg5 Kb5 56. Bh6 Kb4 57. Bg5 Kc3 58. Bh6 Kd3 59. Bg5 Ke2 60. Bh6 Rc3 61. Kf4 $1 Rxf3+ 62. Ke5 {[%cal Gh6f4]} Rh3 63. Bg5 $1 Rh5 64. Kxf5 1/2-1/2


