1. d4 {Marin,Mihail Marin,M Marin,Mihail Marin,Mihail Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 c6 {Flear,Glenn: 'A solid choice, but one that looks somewhat unambitious.' Marin,Mihail: '!?' '!?' '!?' Marin,M: '!?'} 6. cxd5 (6. Bf4 {was featured in Potkin, V - Kamsky, G Moscow 2010, which can be found in the archives.}) ({I always thought that} 6. Bg5 {was a good antidote as there is additional pressure on the d5-square, but Black can complicate matters, for example with} dxc4 7. Qxc4 Qb6 $5 8. e4 Qxb2 9. Rb1 Qa3 10. e5 Be6 11. Qb4 Qxb4 12. Rxb4 Nd5 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 14. Rxb7 Nd7 {Crouch, C - Gormally, D British league 1999, and it seems that Black has good chances, noting that ...c5 is threatened.}) 6... Nxd5 {Marin,Mihail: '!?' '!?' '!?' Marin,M: '!?' Marin,M: 'An interesting opening experiment. As Black will soon play ...c6-c5, he basically loses a tempo with respect to the normal Exchange System lines. His main aim is proving that Qb3 is not so useful, as it weakens the defence on d4 and exposes the queen to ...Be6 or ...Nc6-a5. On the other hand, the queen defends c3, so White can play an early d4-d5 as a reaction to Black's typical centre undermining. So far, this line has been mainly used by lower rated players and this is a first high level practical test.' Marin,Mihail: 'An interesting opening experiment. As Black will soon play ...c6-c5, he basically loses a tempo with respect to the normal Exchange System lines. His main aim is proving that b3 is not so useful, as it weakens the defence on d4 and exposes the queen to ...e6 or ...c6-a5. On the other hand, the queen defends c3, so White can play an early d4-d5 as a reaction to Black's typical centre undermining. So far, this line has been mainly used by lower rated players and this is a first high level practical test. '} ({After} 6... cxd5 {then this time} 7. Bg5 {is fairly effective e.g.} Nc6 8. e3 e6 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O h6 {(Black has to do something, as otherwise White's much smoother development is annoying)} 11. Bh4 g5 12. Bg3 Nh5 13. Rac1 Nxg3 14. hxg3 Bd7 15. Rfd1 g4 $5 16. Nd2 h5 17. Ne2 Rb8 18. Nf4 Qg5 19. Bb1 Rfd8 20. Qd3 f5 21. Nb3 {with the easier game for White, Bu Xiangzhi - Andriasian, Z Riyadh Blitz 2017.}) 7. e4 {Flear,Glenn: 'So we have a type of Exchange Variation with the additional moves Qb3 for White and ...c6 for Black.'} Nxc3 ({Flear,Glenn: 'As a rule, the retreat to b6 isn't 'dynamic' enough for my taste e.g.'} 7... Nb6 {- 7/561 Marin,Mihail: '(Perunovic,Milos) - 7/561'} 8. Be3 O-O 9. Rd1 Be6 10. Qc2 N8d7 11. Be2 Bg4 12. O-O {Mamedyarov, S - Areshchenko, A Eilat 2012, and White's central grip ensures an enduring pull.}) 8. bxc3 O-O 9. Be3 {Diagram [#] Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: 'Diagram [#]'' Marin,M: 'A natural developing move, but possibly not the strongest.' Marin,Mihail: 'A natural developing move, but possibly not the strongest.'} ({Practical examples are few and far between, but so far it seems that Marin,M: 'Intuitively I would say that the queen's development to b3 suits the plan based on' Marin,Mihail: 'Intuitively I would say that the queen's development to b3 suits the plan based on'} 9. Ba3 $5 {is White's best chance of an edge: Marin,M: 'as Black will need some time to prepare ...c6-c5, thus ensuring the prolonged stability of the queen on b3. Here are a few examples:' Marin,Mihail: 'as Black will need some time to prepare ...c6-c5, thus ensuring the prolonged stability of the queen on b3. Here are a few examples:'} Qc7 (9... Nd7 10. Bd3 ({Marin,M: 'A very old game went' A very old game went} 10. Be2 {Marin,Mihail} c5 11. O-O cxd4 {Marin,M: 'and now' and now} 12. Nxd4 $2 $11 {Bogoljubow,E-Saemisch,F Lueneburg 1947 (½-½, 47) Marin,M: 'Bogoljubow,E-Saemisch,F Lueneburg 1947 (½-½, 47) was clearly not what White should play,' was clearly not what White should play,}) 10... c5 {Marin,M: 'Black has carried out his thematic break, but with the knight on d7 the queen has no worries.' Marin,Mihail: 'Blac