1. d4 {Marin,Mihail Marin,Mihail Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 c6 {Flear,Glenn: 'A solid choice, but one that looks somewhat unambitious.' Marin,Mihail: '!?' '!?'} 6. cxd5 (6. Bf4 {was featured in Potkin, V - Kamsky, G Moscow 2010, which can be found in the archives.}) ({I always thought that} 6. Bg5 {was a good antidote as there is additional pressure on the d5-square, but Black can complicate matters, for example with} dxc4 7. Qxc4 Qb6 $5 8. e4 Qxb2 9. Rb1 Qa3 10. e5 Be6 11. Qb4 Qxb4 12. Rxb4 Nd5 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 14. Rxb7 Nd7 {Crouch, C - Gormally, D British league 1999, and it seems that Black has good chances, noting that ...c5 is threatened.}) 6... Nxd5 {Marin,Mihail: '!?' '!?' Marin,Mihail: 'An interesting opening experiment. As Black will soon play ...c6-c5, he basically loses a tempo with respect to the normal Exchange System lines. His main aim is proving that b3 is not so useful, as it weakens the defence on d4 and exposes the queen to ...e6 or ...c6-a5. On the other hand, the queen defends c3, so White can play an early d4-d5 as a reaction to Black's typical centre undermining. So far, this line has been mainly used by lower rated players and this is a first high level practical test. '} ({After} 6... cxd5 {then this time} 7. Bg5 {is fairly effective e.g.} Nc6 8. e3 e6 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O h6 {(Black has to do something, as otherwise White's much smoother development is annoying)} 11. Bh4 g5 12. Bg3 Nh5 13. Rac1 Nxg3 14. hxg3 Bd7 15. Rfd1 g4 $5 16. Nd2 h5 17. Ne2 Rb8 18. Nf4 Qg5 19. Bb1 Rfd8 20. Qd3 f5 21. Nb3 {with the easier game for White, Bu Xiangzhi - Andriasian, Z Riyadh Blitz 2017.}) 7. e4 {Flear,Glenn: 'So we have a type of Exchange Variation with the additional moves Qb3 for White and ...c6 for Black.'} Nxc3 ({Flear,Glenn: 'As a rule, the retreat to b6 isn't 'dynamic' enough for my taste e.g.'} 7... Nb6 {- 7/561 Marin,Mihail: '(Perunovic,Milos) - 7/561'} 8. Be3 O-O 9. Rd1 Be6 10. Qc2 N8d7 11. Be2 Bg4 12. O-O {Mamedyarov, S - Areshchenko, A Eilat 2012, and White's central grip ensures an enduring pull.}) 8. bxc3 O-O 9. Be3 {Diagram [#] Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: 'Diagram [#]'' Marin,Mihail: 'A natural developing move, but possibly not the strongest.'} ({Practical examples are few and far between, but so far it seems that Marin,Mihail: 'Intuitively I would say that the queen's development to b3 suits the plan based on'} 9. Ba3 $5 {is White's best chance of an edge: Marin,Mihail: 'as Black will need some time to prepare ...c6-c5, thus ensuring the prolonged stability of the queen on b3. Here are a few examples:'} Qc7 (9... Nd7 10. Bd3 ({A very old game went} 10. Be2 {Marin,Mihail} c5 11. O-O cxd4 {and now} 12. Nxd4 $2 $11 {Bogoljubow,E-Saemisch,F Lueneburg 1947 (½-½, 47) was clearly not what White should play,}) 10... c5 {Marin,Mihail: 'Black has carried out his thematic break, but with the knight on d7 the queen has no worries.'} 11. O-O b6 12. Rad1 e6 13. Bc4 Qe7 14. Rfe1 {(White's development is more rapid and threatening)} Bb7 15. Bc1 $1 {and now that White is fully mobilized, the bishop is redeployed to a more useful diagonal, Leitao, R - Toth, Chr Joao Pessoa 2013 Marin,Mihail: '' '' Marin,Mihail: 'Leitao,R (2636)-Toth,C (2365) Joao Pessoa 2013 (1-0, 46)'}) 10. Be2 Be6 {Marin,Mihail: 'is not likely to offer Black enough counterplay:'} 11. Qb2 Rd8 12. Ng5 Bc8 13. Qb3 {Marin,Mihail: '' '' Marin,Mihail: 'Ivanisevic,I (2665)-Bitici,G (2068) Skopje 2016 (1-0, 36)'} Rf8 {(another return to starters, but now White is ready to go for sharp play)} 14. Bc4 $1 Bxd4 $5 15. cxd4 Qa5+ 16. Kf1 Qxg5 17. h4 $1 {Ivanisevic, I - Bitici, G Skopje 2016, with a promising initiative (and in addition, Black can't even hold onto his e7 pawn).}) 9... c5 $146 {Flear,Glenn: 'Black has lost a tempo (...c6 followed by ...c5) over a 'Be3 Exchange Variation', but this extra tempo is Q-b3, an unusual choice. However one advantage of this bonus move (that doesn't escape Vidit's attention) is that it defends the c3-pawn, thus enabling White's next...' Marin,Mihail: 'Obviously the critical continuation. In games between lower rated players Black has delayed his counterplay, allowing White to keep his space advantage. '} (9... Nd7 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'}) 10. d5 {Flear,Glenn: '!' '!' Marin,Mihail: 'The most logical way of justifying b3.'} ({But} 10. Be2 {Marin,Mihail has no obvious refutation.} cxd4 11. cxd4 Nc6 (11... Qa5+ $5) 12. Rd1 Bg4 13. d5 {Kumaran,D (2310)-Rojas Keim,L Guarapuava 1991 (½-½, 34)} Ne5 $5 14. Nxe5 Bxe2 15. Kxe2 Bxe5 {White's space advantage remains impressive but due to the slightly exposed king's placement on e2 Black has chances for counterplay.}) 10... Nd7 {Marin,Mihail: 'Defending c5 with a developing move and creating a threat which White failed noticing.'} 11. Bd3 {Flear,Glenn: '?!' '?!' Marin,Mihail: '?!' '?!'} ({Flear,Glenn: 'With hindsight, I think that' Marin,Mihail: 'Therefore, the critical move is'} 11. Rc1 {Flear,Glenn: '!' '!' Flear,Glenn: 'was the correct move, keeping control for now.' Marin,Mihail: '!' '!' Marin,Mihail: 'defending and unpinning c3, when Black still needs to struggle finding a constructive plan.'} Nf6 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} 12. Qc2 Qa5 (12... e6 13. Bxc5 exd5 14. Bxf8 Qxf8 15. e5 Ng4 16. Be2 Nxe5 17. O-O $14) 13. Be2 e6 14. d6 Bd7 15. O-O Bc6 $13) ({Following} 11. Be2 {Black could consider} Nf6 12. Nd2 b6 {intending ...e6 to counter the white centre.}) ({Abstractly, it makes sense preparing to consolidate the centre with c3-c4 by unpinning the c-pawn. But} 11. Rd1 {Marin,Mihail still allows} b5 {for instance} 12. Bxb5 Rb8) 11... b5 $1 {Flear,Glenn: 'Creative play. Artemiev notices a negative side of the queen's position on the b-file, as either capture on b5 will give White some problems.'} 12. Qc2 (12. Bxb5 $2 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: '?''} Rb8 {Flear,Glenn: '!' '!' Flear,Glenn: 'and the threat of ...a6 along with the pressure along the long diagonal gives Black the 