hange favours Black, as he can coordinate his pieces better for sustaining the passed pawn, but White has no favourable way of avoiding it:} 17. Nd4 {Marin,Mihail} Ng4 18. Nf3 Bd7 $15) 17... Nxf3+ 18. Bxf3 Bd7 $1 {Diagram [#] Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: '!' Perunovic,Milos: 'Diagram [#]''} 19. Bxc3 {Flear,Glenn: '!?' '!?' Flear,Glenn: 'Sacrificing the exchange in order to avoid being 'worse without play'. The engine doesn't think much of this but, in practical terms, having a powerful dark squared bishop certainly offers White something for his sorrows.' Marin,Mihail: 'A desperate attempt to save the game. White has to eliminate the dangerous pawn at any cost.'} (19. d6 $142 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} Qxd6 (19... exd6 20. Bxc3 Rac8 (20... Rfc8 21. e5 Rab8 22. Qd2) 21. Bxg7 Qxc2 22. Rxc2 Rxc2 23. Bd1 $1 Rd2 24. Bxf8 Kxf8 25. Bb3 $15) 20. Bxc3 Rac8 21. Qb2 Rxc3 22. Rxc3 Rb8 23. Qc2 Qd4 24. Rd1 Qxc3 25. Qxc3 Bxc3 26. Rxd7 Rb2 27. g3 (27. a3 e5 $17) 27... Rxa2 28. Rxe7 Bd4 $17) (19. Bg5 {Marin,Mihail} Rab8 20. Bxe7 Rb2 $19) (19. Rab1 {Marin,Mihail} Rfc8 20. Bg5 Rab8 $19 {[%cal Gb8b2]} 21. Bxe7 Rb2 22. Rxb2 cxb2 23. Qxc7 bxc1=Q+) 19... Rfc8 $17 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: '''} 20. Bxg7 (20. e5 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} Bxe5 21. d6 Qxc3 22. Qxc3 Bxc3 23. Rxc3 Rxc3 24. Bxa8 exd6 $17) 20... Qxc2 21. Rxc2 Rxc2 22. Bd4 a5 ({Marin,Mihail: 'Now or on the next move it would have been simpler to force White into passivity with'} 22... Rac8 23. Be3 {Marin,Mihail: 'White cannot allow the exchange of rooks.'} f6 24. h4 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} (24. g4 {Marin,Mihail} a5 $17) 24... a5 $17) 23. h3 Rb8 {Flear,Glenn: 'The rooks are great but, in such open positions, bishops aren't too bad either!'} 24. a3 (24. e5 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} Rb4 25. Be3 Rcb2 26. Kh2 Rb1 $17) 24... f6 $6 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: '?!''} (24... Rc4 $1 $17 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'}) 25. e5 {Flear,Glenn: '!' '!' Flear,Glenn: 'Open lines are going to be necessary to keep the white bishops going.'} Rc4 26. Rd1 Ba4 ({Marin,Mihail: 'White's saving chances are not obvious after'} 26... fxe5 27. Bxe5 Rb3 28. d6 e6 $17 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: ''' Marin,Mihail: 'either, as the rook has no open files available, but of course it is not easy to allow him to have such an advanced passed pawn.'}) 27. Rd2 Rc2 ({Artemiev decides to trade White's rook at the cost of a pawn. Instead,} 27... Kf7 28. exf6 exf6 29. d6 {looks reasonable for White.}) 28. Rxc2 ({If} 28. Rd3 {Black could be insistant with} Rb3) 28... Bxc2 29. exf6 exf6 30. d6 {Marin,Mihail: 'Possibly fruit of a misscalculation.'} ({Flear,Glenn: 'For the record,' Marin,Mihail: 'But Black's winning chances remain intact after'} 30. Bxf6 Kf7 31. Be5 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} (31. Bc3 a4 {Marin,Mihail: '' ''} 32. Bd4 $15 {doesn't look too bad either.}) 31... Rb3 32. Bd6) 30... Kg7 31. d7 $2 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: '?''} (31. Bc3 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} Rd8 32. Bxa5 Rxd6 33. Bb4 Rd4 $17) 31... Ba4 $19 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: '-+''} 32. Bg4 {Diagram [#] Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: 'Diagram [#]''} Bxd7 $1 {Flear,Glenn: 'Safe, but perhaps not strong enough to win.' Marin,Mihail: 'Probably this is what White missed. But if so, this was a brilliant blunder from a practical point of view.'} 33. Bxd7 Rd8 34. Bb6 Rxd7 35. Bxa5 {Flear,Glenn: 'Without the a-pawn, such positions are considered to be book wins (I remember a Speelman-Kasparov endgame). However, now winning attempts are more problematic as, for example, Black can't threaten to head into a pure king and pawn endgame. In the game Vidit successfully uses his a-pawn as a decoy.'} Rd1+ 36. Kh2 Rd3 37. Bb4 Kf7 38. Bc5 Rd5 39. Bb4 Ke6 40. g3 {Flear,Glenn: 'Setting up his desired kingside fortress while he still has time.'} f5 {Marin,Mihail: 'Black's position is simply won. The a-pawn does not really count and with the actual pawn display White would have needed the light-squared bishop to retain saving chances.'} 41. Kg2 Rd3 42. Bf8 Kd5 43. Be7 Ke6 {Diagram [#] Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: 'Diagram [#]''} ({The typical plan in the positions without the a-pawn would be a massive invasion starting with} 43... Kc4 {Marin,Mihail It would work perfectly fine here, too.} 44. Bb4 Kb3 45. g4 ({Passive defence would not do either:} 45. Bf8 Kc2 46. Bb4 Kd1 {Planning ...e2, ...f3 followed by preparing the pawn break ...f5-f4.} 47. Kf1 f4 $19) 45... Kc2 46. gxf5 gxf5 47. Bc5 Kd1 48. a4 Ke2 49. a5 Rc3 50. Be3 Ra3 51. Kg3 (51. Bb6 f4 $19) 51... Rxa5 52. Kf4 Rb5 {Putting White in some sort of zugzwang.} (52... Kf1 53. Kf3 {slightly complicates matters.}) 53. Ba7 (53. Kg3 Rb4 54. Bc5 Rb3+ 55. Be3 Rxe3+ 56. fxe3 Kxe3 $19) 53... Kf1 {[%cal Gf1g2]} 54. Kf3 Rb4 55. Bc5 Rc4 56. Bb6 h5 57. Ba7 h4 58. Be3 Kg1 $19) 44. Bf8 $1 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: '!''} g5 {Flear,Glenn: 'This turns out to be committal, but I'm not confident enough to know if it's actually a mistake. What else could he try anyway, I'm thinking?' Marin,Mihail: '?!' '?!'} 45. Bc5 Rc3 46. Be3 {Flear,Glenn: '!' '!' Flear,Glenn: 'Oh, a surprise choice. The a-pawn is abandoned in order to trade some kingside pawns.' Marin,Mihail: '!' '!' Marin,Mihail: 'Obviously underestimated by Black.'} (46. Bb4 $17 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} Rb3 $140 47. Bf8) 46... h6 (46... Rxa3 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos'} 47. Bxg5 Kd5 48. Bf4 $11) ({One idea is Marin,Mihail: 'I failed to find a winning plan for Black after'} 46... g4 47. hxg4 fxg4 48. a4 (48. Bb6 {Marin,Mihail} Rxa3 {½-½ Cebalo,M (2515)-Nedev,T (2415) Cannes Martinez op 1996 (7) which seems to be a fortress. Please refer to}) 48... Ra3 49. a5 Rxa5 50. Bb6 Ra2 51. Be3 {and I can't see how Black will make progress.}) 47. h4 $1 {Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: '!''} gxh4 48. Bxh6 hxg3 49. f3 {Marin,Mihail: '!' '!' Marin,Mihail: 'The saving move. White will win the g-pawn and keep the favourable kingside structure.'} (49. fxg3 $2 {Marin,Mihail leaves the light squares undefended.} Rxa3 50. Kh3 Ra7 51. Kg2 Ke5 52. Bf4+ Ke4 53. Bb8 Ra2+ 54. Kh3 Kf3 55. Kh4 Ra8 56. Be5 Rg8 57. Bd6 Kg2 58. Be5 Rg4+ 59. Kh5 Rxg3) 49... Rxa3 50. Kxg3 $11 {Flear,Glenn: 'A book draw it seems.' Marin,Mihail: 'Perunovic,Milos: '='' Marin,Mihail: 'This is a theoretical draw already, as the bishop and the pawn complete their actions. The main thing White should avoid is pushing his pawn to f4.'} Ra4 51. Bg5 Ke5 52. Bh6 Rc4 53. Bg7+ Kd5 54. Bh6 Kc6 55. Bg5 Kb5 56. Bh6 Kb4 57. Bg5 Kc3 58. Bh6 Kd3 59. Bg5 Ke2 60. Bh6 Rc3 {Flear,Glenn: 'Artemiev has done all he can do, but Vidit's reaction shows why he can't win.'} 61. Kf4 {Flear,Glenn: '!' '!' Marin,Mihail: '!' '!'} Rxf3+ 62. Ke5 {Flear,Glenn: 'Threatening Bf4 and then Kxf5.'} Rh3 63. Bg5 $1 Rh5 64. Kxf5 1/2-1/2


