{I have played against Korobov countless number of times. Each game being very fighting but always ending in draw. In the last 4 games, 3 of them were over 80 moves! I was happy to finally break the 'tradition' with this game.} 1. e4 {Vidit,S} c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 {Roiz,M: 'Anton is an experienced and decent Najdorf player, but in this event he still lost two important games in this opening.'} 6. Be3 (6. Bg5 {was played by Ian a few days ago. That game is also covered in this Update.}) 6... e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. f3 h5 9. Nd5 Bxd5 10. exd5 Nbd7 11. Qd2 g6 12. O-O-O {Roiz,M: 'The most aggressive choice.'} Nb6 13. Kb1 Nbxd5 14. Bg5 Be7 {Roiz,M: 'This important position was examined in a few games in our PGN Archive.'} 15. Bd3 {Nothing new so far, though this is a rare move. Played only once before, by one of the most polite persons I know, Peter Leko.} (15. c4 Nf4 $1 16. Bxf4 exf4 17. Qxf4 O-O {was shown to be satisfactory for Black in Inarkiev,E (2693)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2794) Baden Baden GER 2017 [Roiz,M]}) (15. Na5 {is covered in Grischuk,A (2771)-Topalov,V  (2816) Saint Louis 2015 [Roiz,M] As I've mentioned before,} Qc7 $5 {seems to be an improvement over Veselin's play. Indeed, in the following correspondence game White managed to regain the pawn, but his king came under some pressure:} 16. g3 Rd8 17. Bg2 O-O 18. f4 Nb6 19. Nxb7 Rd7 20. Na5 d5 $132 {Broniek,M - Wurschner,M LSS email 2011}) 15... Rc8 {Roiz,M: 'This innovation doesn't seem to make Black's position more attractive.' An 'automatic' move. What does the rook do on c8? Black should either castle long or keep the rook on a8 to prepare b5-a5 ideas.} ({Roiz,M: 'After'} 15... Qc7 {Roiz,M: 'Black came under pressure in Leko,P (2679)-Areshchenko,A (2645) Schwaebisch Hall GER 2017 [Roiz, M], but Alexander's play could definitely be improved.'} 16. Rhe1 O-O-O 17. c4 Nb6 18. c5 dxc5 19. Nxc5 Qxc5 20. Rc1 Nc4 21. Rxc4 Qxc4 22. Bxc4 Rxd2 23. Bxd2 Rh7 24. Rxe5 $14 {½-½ (35) Leko,P (2679)-Areshchenko,A (2645) Schwaebisch Hall GER 2017}) 16. Rhe1 {Roiz,M: 'Now Black's king doesn't feel safe in the centre.' Preparing ideas like f4.} O-O ({The timid} 16... Qc7 $6 {runs into} 17. f4 $1 Nb6 18. f5 $40 {, and White's attack plays itself.}) ({Hardly better is also} 16... Kf8 17. g3 $1 {This 'patient' continuation seems to pose Black major problems.} ({Instead,} 17. f4 Nxf4 18. Bxf4 exf4 19. Qxf4 d5 20. Rf1 Kg7 21. Nd4 Qb6) 17... Kg7 18. f4 Qc7 19. f5 $1 ({Worse is} 19. c4 $6 Nb6 20. Rc1 Qd8 $1 $132 {, and Black is ready to push ...e5-e4, obtaining decent counterplay.}) 19... Nb6 20. Qg2 $36 {Black has no counterplay, while the extra pawn has little value.}) 17. h3 {For one pawn, I have all the compensation. Perfect pieces plus a very clear plan of breaking through on the kingside.} b5 ({Roiz,M: 'In case of'} 17... Qc7 18. g4 Rfe8 {is the engine's stone cold suggestion. White has various possibilites here. I like the look of c3-c2 threatening gxh5.} 19. c3 b5 20. Rf1 $1 $36 {Black can hardly stop the powerful f2-f4 breakthrough.}) 18. g4 h4 {Played after a lot of hesitation. It wasn't easy to parry the threat of gxh5.} ({I guess that} 18... Nb6 {could have been rejected by Anton in view of} 19. f4 (19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. gxh5 Nc4 21. Qg2 Nxb2 22. Kxb2 e4+ 23. Kb1 exd3 24. Rxd3 Kh7 {doesn't offer White anything special - the Kb1 is now exposed too.}) ({However, deserving of serious attention is} 19. Qa5 $5 Nc4 20. Qxa6 Qd7 21. Na5 {, and this might pose Black definite problems.}) 19... hxg4 20. hxg4 Nxg4 {, and this position looks too scary to a human player, even though it's not so clear. For instance,} 21. Bxe7 ({After} 21. Qg2 Bxg5 22. fxg5 Qxg5 23. Be2 f5 24. Rxd6 Rf6 $13 {Black manages to consolidate.}) 21... Qxe7 22. f5 Nc4 23. Qg2 Nce3 24. Qh3 e4 25. fxg6 fxg6 26. Rh1 Qg7 27. Bxe4 Rf4 $132) 19. Bxh4 $16 {Roiz,M: '!' Roiz,M: 'The Indian Grandmaster has managed to regain the pawn while keeping all the merits of his setup.' It's hard to say where Black actually went wrong. With a few sub optimal moves he already has a difficult game.} ({Instead, the tempting} 19. Bh6 Nf4 (19... Re8 20. g5 Nh5 21. Bxg6 Ndf4 22. Bxh5 Nxh5 23. Nc1 $16) 20. Bxf4 exf4 21. Qxf4 d5 $14 {looks less promising.}) 19... Nf4 20. Bg3 {Roiz,M: 'GM Vidit liquidates the opponent's most active piece.'} Nxd3 21. Qxd3 {Roiz,M: '' Roiz,M: 'White's pieces are much more active, while the Kg8 is exposed.'} Qc7 {White has a couple of plans. h4-h5, preparing f4, or simply re-routing the knight from d2. I was too confused to chose one of them so ended up playing a 4th idea! The luxury of good positions :)} 22. c3 {Roiz,M: 'This prophylactic move isn't bad,'} ({Roiz,M: 'but more energetic would be'} 22. h4 $1 {Roiz,M: '!?' Objectively this seems the best.} Qc4 23. Qd2 b4 (23... Qc6 24. Re3 $16) 24. h5 $16) 22... Qc4 23. Qd2 {Roiz,M: 'Of course, liquidating into the endgame should favor Black in this situation.'} Qc6 24. f4 $6 {Roiz,M: 'An impulsive decision - now Black manages to activate most of his pieces.' Although White keeps an edge. It allows some unnecessary complications.} ({Roiz,M: 'Much stronger is'} 24. Qe3 $1 {Slowly preparing f4 is more advisable.} Rfe8 (24... Nd5 25. Qd3 Nb6 26. h4 $40) 25. h4 Kg7 26. h5 $40 {with a powerful attack.}) 24... Ne4 {Roiz,M: 'The centralized knight interrupts the coordination between White's pieces.'} 25. Qd3 d5 $5 {Roiz,M: '?!' Roiz,M: 'Anton returns the favor.' A typical Korobov move! Anton never misses a chance to muddy the waters.} ({Roiz,M: 'After'} 25... Nxg3 {Roiz,M: '!'} 26. Qxg3 b4 $1 {I had missed this.} (26... Bf6 27. f5 $1 b4 $1 {Black would have sufficient counterplay. For instance,} 28. cxb4 Qc2+) (26... exf4 27. Qxf4 Rce8 28. Nd4 $16) 27. cxb4 Qc2+ 28. Ka1 Bf6 {was a brilliant way out. Suddenly Black has a lot of activity.} 29. f5 e4 30. Rb1 $14 Be5 31. Qe3 Rc3 32. Qxe4 Qxe4 33. Rxe4 Rxh3 $44 {with full compensation for the pawn.}) 26. fxe5 b4 {Roiz,M: '!?' Roiz,M: 'Perhaps this is the best attempt to complicate matters.'} (26... Qc4 27. Qe3 b4 28. Rd4 Qb5 29. cxb4 Bxb4 30. Red1 Bc5 31. Nxc5 Qxc5 32. Bf4 $16) 27. cxb4 Bxb4 {For a moment I thought that I had messed up. When I dug deeper, I realised that although Black's initiative with ...a5-...b6 etc is scary, it can be parried concretely.} 28. Re2 $1 a5 29. Bf4 $1 {Roiz,M: '?!' Roiz,M: 'This inaccurate retreat could have spoiled the advantage.' An important move. White threatens to take on d5} ({Much better was} 29. Bh4 g5 (29... a4 30. Qxd5 Qxd5 31. Rxd5 axb3 32. Rxe4 Rc1+ 33. Kxc1 bxa2 34. Ra5 Bxa5 35. Ra4 $18) 30. Bf2 a4 31. Nd4 $16 {, maintaining the material advantage.}) 29... Qb6 {Renewing the threat of ...a4.} (29... a4 30. Qxd5 $16) 30. a4 $1 {Roiz,M: 'Till now Anton was playing quite creatively and well, but his next move invites serious trouble.' Probably the most important move of the game. This caught Anton by surprise and he went into deep thought. If White manages to play b5 it's just winning. What should Black do? His entire play was dependent on dislodging the b3-knight.} (30. Qxd5 Rfd8 $1 $19) 30... g5 {Roiz,M: '?' A sign of desperation. Now White is completely winning. A normal person would convert this with good technique but I sometimes have a tendency not to do exactly that!} (30... Nc3+ 31. bxc3 Rxc3 32. Qxd5 Be7 {Preparing ...d8 and attacking the b3-knight at the same time} 33. Rd3 $1 {And White protects everything.}) (30... Bc3 $1 31. Qb5 $1 Rb8 $1 {The only move! During the game, we both underestimated this.} 32. e6 (32. Qxb6 Rxb6 33. Kc2 (33. Ka2 Rb4 $1 34. Rxd5 Rxa4+ 35. Kb1 Rb4 $11) 33... Rc8 $1 {would offer Black sufficient counterplay. For instance, the game might end like this:} 34. Rxd5 Bd4+ 35. Kd3 Rxb3+ 36. Kxd4 Nc5 37. Rxc5 Rb4+ 38. Kd5 Rd8+ 39. Kc6 Rc8+ 40. Kd5 Rd8+ $11 {with a draw by perpetual.}) 32... Qxb5 33. axb5 Rxb5 34. e7 Re8 35. Rxe4 $1 Rxb3 (35... dxe4 36. Rd8 $18) 36. Rxd5 f6 $1 (36... Rxb2+ 37. Kc1 f6 38. Rd8 Kf7 39. Bd6 $18 {with idea c4-cc8 etc}) 37. Kc2 Rb4 {After a series of only moves Black has some chances to draw this endgame.} 38. Re3 $14) 31. Be3 Qg6 32. Ka2 (32. Nd4 $5 $18) 32... Rfd8 33. Nd4 {Roiz,M: 'Eventually White managed to consolidate. The knight is heading to f5 or b5.' Black basically has no 'real' counterplay. He has to survive on some tricks.} Rc4 34. Rc2 $1 {Removing the only active piece.} Qa6 ({White should be able to convert the material advantage into full point after} 34... Rdc8 35. Rdc1 Rxc2 36. Rxc2 Nc3+ 37. Rxc3 Bxc3 38. Qxg6+ fxg6 39. bxc3 Rxc3 40. Bf2 $18) 35. Nb5 $6 (35. Rdc1 {would be game over for Black:} Rdc8 (35... Bd2 36. Rxd2 $1) (35... Bc3 36. Rxc3 $1) 36. Rxc4 Rxc4 37. Rxc4 Qxc4+ 38. Qxc4 dxc4 39. Nc6 $18) ({Simpler was} 35. Nf5 $1 Bc3 36. Rxc3 Nxc3+ 37. bxc3 Rxa4+ 38. Kb3 $18) 35... Be7 $1 {Posing some practical problems.} 36. Rxc4 (36. Na3 $5) 36... dxc4 37. Qc2 Rxd1 38. Qxd1 Qe6 39. Qd4 $1 {Roiz,M: 'Only this important resource leaves White in control.' Despite messing up the advantage a little, I managed to bring myself back to making good moves.} Nc5 (39... c3+ 40. b3 Qc6 41. Qc4 $18) 40. Nc3 $1 Nd3 41. Kb1 {Getting myself out of the fork. The main problem of Black's position is that, despite restoring material equality he has a tough time. Every endgame is bad for him due to the weak pawns (a5-c4-g5).} (41. Nd5 Qxd5 {A classic tactic.} 42. Qxd5 Nb4+) 41... Nxe5 {Roiz,M: 'Black even managed to regain the pawn, but his position is still bad.'} 42. Qe4 {Planning d5 or d4.} ({Roiz,M: 'Stronger was'} 42. Qd5 $1 {was much more forcing and cleaner. After exchanging queens White can easily collect one of the weak pawns on the queenside.} Qg6+ (42... Qxd5 43. Nxd5 Bd8 44. Kc2 $18) 43. Ne4 Nf3 44. Ka2 $18 {White's pieces are dominating the board.}) 42... Bb4 {Hard to suggest any alternatives. It's not so easy to avoid queen exchanges.} (42... Bf6 43. Qd5 $1) (42... Qd5) 43. Bd4 (43. Qd5 $5) 43... Bxc3 ({After} 43... f6 44. Nd5 Kg7 45. Ne3 Qc6 46. Qd5 {despite the major simplifications, White's advantage is decisive. Still, it was the most stubborn.}) 44. Bxc3 f6 45. Qa8+ Kf7 46. Qxa5 $1 {Roiz,M: '+-' Roiz,M: 'The rest is easy - the a4-passer decides the game.' It looks like Black can get some counterplay with d3-e4, but it's all illusory.} Nd3 47. Qb5 $1 Qe4 48. Ka2 $18 {White simply puts the king on a2. Black can't co-ordinate the knight and queen to create any problems. White's simple plan is to just push the a-pawn. The rest is easy.} Nc1+ 49. Ka3 Qe7+ 50. Qb4 Qc7 51. a5 Nd3 52. Qb6 Qe7+ 53. Ka2 Nc1+ 54. Kb1 Qe4+ 55. Kxc1 Qh1+ 56. Kd2 Qh2+ 57. Ke1 1-0


