1. c4 {David Cummings David Cummings} e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3 Bb4 5. Qc2 d6 {David Cummings: 'This used to be a sideline, and is new to this site. 5...d6 was played 3 times by Jon Ludvig Hammer in 2016-17, and although he lost all three games, the move was picked up by Magnus Carlsen, who scored a win over Ding Liren in a recent rapid game. The mainline alternatives are:'} (5... O-O 6. Nd5 {David Cummings} Re8 7. Qf5 {- see Giri-Sunilduth Lyna and other archived games.}) ({and} 5... Bxc3 {David Cummings: '- see Aronian-Matlakov and earlier games in the Archives' are the main continuations here. However, the text-move had quite a solid reputation until recently...}) 6. Ne2 $1 {David Cummings: 'A very surprising novelty! Karjakin's move (which was clearly part of his preparation) appears to lose precious development time. On the other hand, the move ...d6 cuts off the retreat of Black's dark squared bishop, which is now left "floating" on the b4-square and vulnerable to White's potential queenside pawn storm. A natural reply to 6 Ne2 would be 6...d5, but since Black has already moved the d-pawn, this would represent a further loss of a tempo in a reversed Sicilian setup. Meanwhile, White's knight would not be badly placed on the g3-square. White has also played:' A new and dangerous try.} (6. Nd5 {David Cummings: 'and here Black has tried both bishop moves:' is harmless:} Ba5 {David Cummings: '!' '!' David Cummings: 'This is an important improvement, pinning White's d-pawn for now, and avoiding tactics associated with placing the bishop on the c5-square (see note above).'} (6... Bc5 7. a3 {David Cummings: 'and now:'} a5 {David Cummings: 'with a further split:'} (7... Nxd5 {David Cummings} 8. cxd5 Ne7 {allows} 9. Nxe5) 8. b3 (8. Be2 {David Cummings} Be6 9. Nc3 h6 10. O-O Qd7 11. d3 O-O 12. Bd2 Rfe8 13. Rfd1 Bf5 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. cxd5 Nb8 16. Bc3 Bb6 17. Nd2 a4 18. Nc4 Na6 19. e4 Bg6 20. Nxb6 cxb6 21. b4 {gave White a better structure in Harsha,B (2394)-Akobian,V (2662) Douglas 2017 1-0 (48)}) 8... Bg4 (8... Be6 {David Cummings} 9. Nc3 Qd7 10. Bd3 h6 11. Bb2 O-O 12. O-O Ne7 13. Rfd1 Bg4 14. Be2 Bf5 15. e4 $6 (15. d3 {maintains a flexible structure}) 15... Bg6 16. d4 exd4 17. Nxd4 Nc6 18. Nxc6 bxc6 {with pressure against White's centre, Eljanov,P (2727)-Naroditsky,D (2633) Reykjavik 2015 1/2-1/2 (27)}) 9. Be2 Nxd5 10. cxd5 Ne7 11. Nxe5 Bxe2 12. Kxe2 dxe5 13. Qxc5 Qxd5 14. Qxd5 Nxd5 15. Bb2 f6 16. Rac1 O-O-O 17. Rc5 b6 18. Rc4 Rd7 19. Rhc1 Kb7 20. g3 Rhd8 21. R1c2 c5 22. f4 exf4 23. gxf4 Re8 $11 {Vilela de Acuna,J (2450)-Stohl,I (2405) Stary Smokovec 1984}) 7. a3 (7. Be2 $142 $5 O-O $11) (7. Nxf6+ {David Cummings} Qxf6 8. a3 {avoids the weak d5-pawn which White gets in the game}) 7... Nxd5 8. cxd5 Ne7 9. b4 Bb6 10. Bc4 O-O 11. Bb2 Bf5 12. d3 Ng6 13. h4 $2 {David Cummings: '?!' '?!' David Cummings: 'Black was already at least equal, but this makes matters worse for White, simply castling short looks best.'} ({It was high time to play} 13. O-O $13) 13... h6 14. h5 Ne7 15. Nd2 Rc8 {David Cummings: 'and Black is slightly better. After opening the c-file, his pieces are more active, while White doesn't have specific targets to aim at, Ding,L (2774) -Carlsen,M (2837) Saint Louis 2017 0-1 (27)'} 16. e4 Bg4 17. d4 exd4 18. f3 Bd7 19. Qd3 c6 $1 $17 {Ding,L (2774)-Carlsen,M (2837) Saint Louis rpd 2017}) (6. a3 Bxc3 7. Qxc3 Bg4 ({Opening the long dark diagonal is strategically risky:} 7... e4 8. Nd4 Ne5 9. b4 Nfg4 (9... O-O 10. Bb2 Re8 $5 {is less clear}) 10. h3 Qh4 11. g3 Qh6 12. Be2 Nf6 13. Bb2 Bd7 14. O-O-O O-O-O 15. g4 Rhe8 16. Rdg1 g5 17. h4 Bxg4 18. hxg5 Qxg5 19. c5 h5 20. c6 Kb8 21. cxb7 c5 {Oleksienko,M (2615)-Harikrishna,P (2733) Germany 2018} 22. Nb3 $5 $36) 8. b4 (8. d3 {Then the consistent move is} Bxf3 (8... O-O 9. Be2 a5 10. b3 Qe7 11. Bb2 Nd8 12. h3 Bd7 13. O-O Ne6 14. Rae1 Rfe8 15. Bd1 c5 16. d4 e4 17. Nd2 d5 18. f3 exf3 19. Bxf3 Bc6 (19... cxd4 $5 20. exd4 Bc6 $14) 20. dxc5 $36 {King,D (2535)-Stohl,I (2580) Germany 1997}) 9. gxf3 Qd7 (9... Qe7 $13) 10. Bd2 a5 11. Rg1 O-O $13 {½, Bernal Moro,L (2435)-Tkachiev,V (2661) La Massana 2015}) 8... O-O 9. Bb2 Re8 10. h3 Bxf3 11. gxf3 d5 $6 ({Too ambitious, Black won't be able to retain his .} 11... Nd4 12. Bg2 c6 $13) (11... a5 $5 $132) 12. O-O-O d4 13. Qc2 Qd7 14. Rg1 Rad8 15. b5 Ne7 16. f4 $1 d3 17. Qb3 Ne4 18. Bg2 Qf5 19. fxe5 Ng6 20. f4 $16 {Duda,J (2724)-Eljanov,P (2702) Brest 2018}) (6. Be2 {David Cummings} O-O 7. O-O Re8 {and now:} 8. Nd5 (8. d3 a5 9. b3 Bf5 10. Bb2 Ne7 11. Na4 (11. a3 Bc5 12. Rfd1 {is perhaps a better try for a slight edge}) 11... Ng6 12. Rfd1 Bc5 13. Nxc5 dxc5 {with roughly balanced chances, Granda Zuniga,J (2658)-Mareco,S (2655) Buenos Aires 2017 0-1 (40)}) 8... e4 9. Ne1 a5 10. b3 Bc5 11. Nxf6+ Qxf6 12. Bb2 Qg6 {was played in Smith,A (2506)-Hammer,J (2628) Sastamala 2016 1-0 (60), and now} 13. d4 {is Smith's recommendation, since after} exd3 14. Bxd3 {he claims White has the better bishops and better structure}) 6... a5 {David Cummings: 'Black opts to keep the position closed. Instead:'} (6... d5 7. a3 (7. cxd5 {David Cummings} Nxd5 8. Ng3 {looks like a decent reversed Sicilian for White}) 7... Be7 (7... Bd6 {doesn't lose a tempo, but after} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Ng3 O-O 10. b4 a6 11. Bb2 Be6 12. Bd3 ({or} 12. Rc1 {White gets a pleasant Sicilian with chances for an advantage.})) 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Ng3 a6 10. b4 O-O 11. Bb2 Bd6 12. Bc4 Nb6 13. Bd3 g6 14. h4 Qe7 15. h5 f5 16. hxg6 hxg6 17. O-O-O Be6 18. Rh6 Kg7 19. Rdh1 Rh8 20. Rxh8 Rxh8 21. Rxh8 Kxh8 22. Bxa6 $1 $14 {Harsha,B (2443)-Chizhikov,V (2313) Moscow 2018}) (6... e4 {David Cummings} 7. Ng5 {leaves the e4-pawn vulnerable}) 7. a3 (7. Ng3 $5 {is a plausible alternative:} a4 $142 $5 {requires further testing:} (7... h6 8. a3 Bc5 9. b3 O-O {is similar to our game and pleasant for White:} 10. Be2 (10. Bb2 Re8 11. d3 d5 12. cxd5 Qxd5 13. Ne4 (13. Be2 $142 {- 10.e2}) 13... Be7 14. Be2 Be6 15. Ned2 Nd7 16. O-O Bg4 17. h3 Bh5 18. d4 $6 exd4 19. Bc4 Qd6 20. Ne4 Qg6 21. Nxd4 Nce5 $132 {Wang,Y (2448)-Harikrishna,P (2727) China 2018}) 10... Re8 11. d3 (11. Bb2 $5 {} e4 12. Nh4 Ne5 13. O-O $36 {[%cal Rf2f4]}) 11... d5 12. cxd5 Qxd5 13. O-O Bf8 14. Bb2 Be6 15. Nd2 Rad8 16. Rfd1 (16. h3 $5 $14 {Kir.Georgiev}) 16... Bg4 (16... g6 17. Rac1 Bg7 18. h3 Qd7 19. Nge4 Nxe4 20. dxe4 Qe7 21. Bb5 Rd6 22. Rf1 Red8 23. Nc4 Bxc4 24. Bxc4 Nb8 25. Bc3 b6 26. b4 $36 {Harsha,B (2454)-Vocaturo,D (2617) Abu Dhabi 2018}) 17. Bxg4 Nxg4 18. Nde4 Qe6 19. Qc4 Nf6 20. Nxf6+ Qxf6 21. Rac1 Qe6 22. Qb5 Qc8 23. d4 exd4 24. exd4 Ne7 $1 25. Qxa5 Nd5 $44 {Harutyunian,T (2487)-Sargsyan,S (2461) Yerevan 2018}) 8. Be2 a3 9. O-O O-O 10. d4 (10. b3 d5 $13) (10. Qb3 $5 axb2 11. Bxb2 $13 {/ seems more promising}) 10... Re8 (10... exd4 11. exd4 d5 $132) 11. h3 h6 12. Qb3 axb2 13. Bxb2 Ba5 14. Rad1 exd4 15. Nxd4 Ne7 16. Nh5 Nxh5 17. Bxh5 Nf5 18. c5 Qe7 19. Nxf5 Bxf5 20. cxd6 cxd6 21. Bf3 $14 {Stocek,J (2570)-Zanan,E (2497) Teplice 2018}) 7... Bc5 8. b3 (8. d4 Bb6 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. c5 Ba7 12. Ng3 O-O 13. b4 c6 14. Bb2 Bb8 $11 {/ Kir. Georgiev}) 8... O-O $6 ({Here the engine indicates a suprising tactical resource} 8... e4 $142 9. Ng5 Qe7 10. Bb2 Bxa3 $1 (10... h6 11. Nh3 Bxh3 12. gxh3 Ne5 13. Ng3 $13 {/}) 11. Bxa3 (11. Rxa3 $2 Nb4) 11... Qe5 {regaining the piece:} 12. Nc3 Qxg5 13. Nxe4 Bf5 $5 $132) 9. Ng3 Re8 10. Bb2 Ba7 {David Cummings: 'Compared to some of the examples with a similar pawn structure given in earlier notes (such as Eljanov-Naroditsky and Granda-Mareco), I prefer this version for White, since the g3-knight is better placed that it was on the c3-square.'} 11. Be2 h6 12. O-O Be6 (12... d5 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Rac1 $36 {[%cal Yf1d1,Yd2d4]}) 13. Bc3 {David Cummings: 'White could also just centralize with:'} (13. d4 exd4 14. exd4 Bg4 $132) (13. h3 $5 {d4 Kir. Georgiev}) (13. Rad1 {David Cummings} Bd7 14. d4 {with a space advantage on the queenside}) 13... Ne7 14. d4 $16 exd4 15. Nxd4 Bd7 16. Qd2 {David Cummings: 'This 'semi-Maroczy' structure gives White a slight advantage, as Black is a little passive.'} (16. Nb5 $1 $36) 16... Bb6 17. Rad1 Nc6 18. Nf3 (18. Nxc6 Bxc6 19. Qb2 $36 {[%cal Ga1h8]}) 18... Ne5 19. Qb2 {} Qe7 20. b4 (20. h3 $1 {plans  and  expansion:} c6 21. Kh1 Rad8 22. Nd4 Qf8 23. e4 Bc8 24. f4 Ng6 25. Bd3 $16 {Kir. Georgiev}) 20... axb4 21. axb4 c5 {David Cummings: 'Burying his own bishop, but White was threatening 22 c5 himself'} 22. h3 Rab8 $6 (22... Qe6 $142 $5 {[%cal Yd7c6]}) 23. b5 Rbd8 24. Rd2 Bc7 25. Rfd1 b6 26. Nh4 {David Cummings: 'White has pushed his opponent further back and is now clearly better, although some Rapid game randomness soon takes place..'} Be6 27. Nf3 $2 $138 {David Cummings: '?!' '?!' White now loses the theead - this was a rapid game...} (27. Nhf5 Bxf5 (27... Qf8 28. f4 Nxc4 29. Bxc4 Bxc4 30. Bxf6 gxf6 31. Nh5 $18) 28. Nxf5 Qe6 29. Qc2 $16) (27. Ngf5 $1 {(David Cummings) forces the trade on the f5-square, since} Qf8 28. f4 Nxc4 29. Bxc4 Bxc4 30. Nxh6+ {gives White a winning attack}) 27... Nxc4 28. Bxc4 Bxc4 29. Nf5 Qe6 30. Nxh6+ gxh6 31. Bxf6 {David Cummings: 'The position is now just very messy.'} Ra8 32. Bh8 f6 (32... Qg6 $1 $15) 33. Bxf6 Rf8 (33... d5 $13) 34. Bc3 Rf7 35. e4 $2 {David Cummings: '?!' '?!'} (35. Nh2 d5 $44) 35... Raf8 $2 {David Cummings: '?!' '?!' David Cummings: 'Missing a good chance:'} (35... Rxf3 $1 36. gxf3 Kf7 $1 $40 {David Cummings: 'and suddenly White's king is badly exposed'} 37. Be5 Ra2 $17) 36. Nh2 Qxe4 37. Ng4 Qg6 38. Qc1 h5 $2 {David Cummings: '??' '??'} (38... d5 {David Cummings: 'and all is still to play for'} 39. Rxd5 Bf4 $13) 39. Rd5 $2 (39. Rxd6 $1 {David Cummings: 'wins on the spot, as'} Bxd6 40. Rxd6 $18 Qxd6 {David Cummings} 41. Qg5+ {leads to mate}) 39... Bxd5 (39... Rf4 $142 $1) 40. Rxd5 Rf5 41. Nh6+ Kh7 42. Nxf5 Rxf5 43. Qd1 Qf7 44. Rxf5 Qxf5 45. Qe2 $36 {[%csl Rh7] David Cummings: 'White's safer king gives him the advantage here' In the resulting endgame White still holds the initiative due to his safer king.} Qb1+ $2 (45... Qf7 $142 46. Qe4+ Kg8 47. Qc6 $36) (45... Kg6 {(David Cummings) is more tenacious}) 46. Kh2 d5+ 47. g3 {[%cal Re2e7,Re2h5]} d4 48. Bxd4 $2 (48. Qe7+ Kg6 49. Qe6+ Kg7 50. Qd7+ Kg6 51. Qc6+ $18) 48... cxd4 $2 (48... Bxg3+ 49. fxg3 cxd4 50. Qxh5+ Kg7 $14) 49. Qe7+ Kg8 50. Qe8+ Kg7 51. Qd7+ Kf6 52. Qxc7 d3 (52... Qxb5 $142 53. Qd6+ Kf7 54. Qxd4 $16) 53. Qxb6+ Ke5 54. Qc5+ {David Cummings: 'The queen endgame with two extra pawns is winning for White'} Ke4 55. b6 $18 Qb3 (55... d2 56. Qe3+) 56. Qe3+ Kd5 57. b7 Kc6 58. b8=Q Qxb8 59. Qxd3 Qe5 60. Kg2 Kc7 61. g4 hxg4 62. hxg4 Qf4 63. Qg3 1-0


