1. e4 {Vidit,S} c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. g3 {After suffering on the black side of this line in the previous game, I decided to play this line just before I went to sleep. I didn't have much time to prepare as the last round started early in the morning.} e5 7. Nde2 Be7 8. Bg2 b5 9. Nd5 Nxd5 {Roiz,M: '!?' Roiz,M: 'A new move for our PGN Archive.'} ({The more common continuation -} 9... Nbd7 10. Nec3 Bb7 (10... Nb6 {seems insufficient for equality, as was proved in Giri,A (2784)-Wojtaszek,R (2723) Doha QAT 2015  [Roiz,M]}) 11. a4 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Nf6 13. Nxe7 Qxe7 {is covered in Lu Shanglei  (2620)-Sjugirov,S (2667) Moscow RUS 2016 [Roiz,M]}) 10. Qxd5 Ra7 11. Be3 Rb7 {Roiz,M: '!' Roiz,M: 'A novelty. This move was mentioned by me in my notes to Lu Shanglei - Sjugirov as a possible improvement for Black, though I didn't trust it much then. However, the route of this game proves that Black's position is indeed very solid.' Until here my opponent was playing fast.} (11... Be6 12. Qd2 Rb7 13. Nc3 Nd7 14. Nd5 $14 {Fressinet,L - Gharamian,T Cap d'Agde FRA 2015}) 12. O-O {This retained some flexibility regarding the queen's position.} (12. Nc3 {is hardly more dangerous for Black:} Nd7 13. Qd2 Nf6 14. O-O O-O 15. Bg5 (15. a4 b4 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. Qxd5 Qc7 18. a5 Rb5 19. Qd2 Rxa5 20. Qxb4 Rb5 $11) 15... Be6 16. Rfd1 Rc7 {The pressure on the c-file offers Black sufficient counterplay. For instance,} 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Qxd6 Qxd6 19. Rxd6 b4 $11) 12... O-O {He played this after a long period of thought. From now on Areschenko played all the moves after thinking for a considerable amount of time.} 13. Qd3 Be6 ({Possible was also} 13... Nd7 $5 14. Nc3 Nf6 15. Bg5 Be6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Nd5 Bg5 18. h4 Bh6 19. c3 a5 20. a3 g6 {leads to typical play a la Sveshnikov. In my opinion, Black shouldn't face serious problems here.}) 14. b3 Nd7 (14... b4 {I remembered that this was the main move. But over the board, I was wondering why not the simple ...d7? And he indeed played ...d7!}) 15. Nc3 {Roiz,M: 'A typical approach - the knight is heading for d5.'} ({Roiz,M: 'The more aggressive'} 15. f4 {Roiz,M: 'might backfire:'} Nf6 16. f5 Bd7 17. h3 (17. Bf3 d5 $1 18. exd5 Bd6 $44 {, and Black has at least sufficient play for a pawn.}) 17... Bc6 18. c4 bxc4 19. bxc4 Nd7 {I was a bit hesitant to play like this. My kingside looks more vulnerable than dangerous.}) 15... Nf6 16. a4 {I wanted to open the a-file before I fought for the d5-square.} ({In case of} 16. f4 b4 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. exd5 Ng4 19. Qxa6 Qc7 20. Bd2 Ra7 {Black's position looks more attractive to the human eye.}) 16... Qb8 {Roiz,M: '!' Roiz,M: 'A multi-task move - Black is making the d8-spot vacant for the bishop and over-protecting the Pb5.'} (16... Qd7 17. axb5 axb5 18. Bg5 {The play would be similar to the game. Of course one can argue if the queen is better placed here than on b8.} b4 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Nd5 Bd8 21. Rfd1 Bxd5 22. Qxd5 Bb6 23. Qxd6 Bd4 24. Qxd7 Rxd7 25. Rd2 {seems drawish, but Black would have to suffer till the end of the game.}) 17. axb5 axb5 18. Bg5 ({Roiz,M: 'After'} 18. Ra5 b4 19. Nd5 {I always am a bit surprised to see the engine giving such positions as better.} Bxd5 20. exd5 Bd8 21. Ra6 Bb6 22. Bxb6 (22. Rfa1 Bxe3 23. Qxe3 Nd7 {The superiority of the knight over the bishop compensates for White's control of the a-file.}) 22... Rxb6 {I actually think Black is very comfortable here.}) 18... b4 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Nd5 {Roiz,M: 'The Nd5 is pretty strong, but Alexander can cope with it.'} Bd8 (20... Bxd5 21. Qxd5 Rc8 22. Ra2 $14) 21. Rfd1 (21. Ra6 {Later on I thought that this was probably a better way to play. To fight for the a-file immediately} Bd7 (21... Bb6 22. Nxb4 Bd7 $1 {I didn't see such cheeky moves!}) 22. Rfa1 Bb5 23. Qe3 Bxa6 24. Rxa6 Qc8 {Probably I over-estimated the compensation. Black has a fine position.}) 21... Bxd5 (21... Bb6 22. Nxb4 Qc8 23. Nd5 Bxd5 24. Qxd5 Rc7 25. Qxd6 Bd4 26. Bh3 Qb8 27. Ra8 $14) 22. Qxd5 Bb6 23. Bf1 ({Roiz,M: 'In case of'} 23. Qxd6 {was my original intention, but after ...c7 I didn't see a clear way to play and the moves were too easy for Black} Rc7 24. Rd2 (24. Ra6 Bd4 25. Rd2 Rd8 26. Ra8 Qxa8 27. Qxc7 g6 $11 {White's extra pawn only has symbolic value.}) 24... Bd4 $132) 23... Bc5 (23... Ra7 {I thought the best way was to not allow ...a6 and with it the control of the a-file, but apparently it's not that clear} 24. Rxa7 Qxa7 25. Qxd6 $1 Bxf2+ 26. Kh1 $14) 24. Ra6 {Roiz,M: 'White's pieces are somewhat more active, but it doesn't promise anything special at the moment.'} g6 ({Possible was also} 24... Rb6 25. Ra5 Qc7 26. Bc4 Rb7 27. Rda1 g6 $11) 25. Bc4 Kg7 26. Kg2 {I purposefully delayed da1. I wanted to provoke some kingside weakening!} (26. Rda1 Qc7 {and the queen comes to e7. I don't see a clear plan to improve my position.}) 26... f5 {Roiz,M: '?!' Roiz,M: 'The first step in the wrong direction - the king is very exposed now.' A questionable decision. It weakens the king more than providing any activity.} ({Roiz,M: 'It was better to simplify matters:'} 26... Ra7 $11 27. Rda1 Rxa6 28. Rxa6 Qd8 $11) 27. Rda1 {Roiz,M: '?!' Roiz,M: 'GM Vidit unnecessarily yields Black a chance to activate his rooks.' I missed a tactic in this line. Probably f3 or exf5 is stronger:} (27. f3 Rbf7 28. exf5 Rxf5 29. Rf1 $1 {White keeps a bind on the light squares} Qc7 30. h4 $14 {Black would be doomed to passive defence in an unpleasant position.}) ({Roiz,M: 'After the correct'} 27. exf5 {Roiz,M: '!' is probably even better than 27.f3:} Rxf5 (27... Rbf7) (27... gxf5 28. Rda1 Re7 29. Qf3 $36) 28. f3 Rbf7 29. Ra8 Qc7 30. Qe4 $14 Rf8 31. Rxf8 Rxf8 32. Ra1 $36) 27... Ra7 {Roiz,M: '?' Roiz,M: 'Alas, Alexander misses a great opportunity to solve all his problems at once.'} ({Roiz,M: 'I guess both players considered'} 27... fxe4 28. Ra8 Rxf2+ 29. Kh1 Qc7 30. Qxe4 $1 {Roiz,M: 'as dangerous for Black,' White has to be accurate!} ({Roiz,M: 'After'} 30. Rg8+ {Roiz,M: '?'} Kh6 31. Qxe4 (31. Re1 Rb8 $19) 31... Qe7 {Roiz,M: '' Roiz,M: 'White gets nothing for a pawn.'} 32. Bd3 {I thought this wins} Qf6 33. Qxb7 e4 $1 {I stopped my calculation one move too early! Now the tables are turned!}) {Roiz,M: ', but after'} 30... Rf8 ({Roiz,M: 'Now'} 30... Qe7 {Roiz,M: 'runs into'} 31. Re8 {Roiz,M: '!'} Qxe8 32. Qxb7+ Kf6 33. g4 $1 {Roiz,M: ', inviting the king to the centre.'} e4 34. h4 Ke5 $1 35. Qg7+ Kf4 36. Qf6+ Kg3 37. Rg1+ Kh3 38. Bf1+ Rxf1 39. Qxf1+ Kxh4 40. Qf6+ Kh3 { And it's a DRAW?!!?!!}) 31. Rxf8 Kxf8 32. Rf1+ Kg7 33. g4 (33. Rf7+ Qxf7 34. Bxf7 Rxf7 $11 {, there would be no danger at all.}) 33... Ra7 34. g5 Qb7 35. Bd5 Qc8) 28. exf5 Rxa6 29. Rxa6 {Roiz,M: 'Despite the major simplifications, White's position is much better due to his full control over the light squares.'} gxf5 ({Roiz,M: 'Or'} 29... Qc8 $1 {was a nice move} 30. Bd3 gxf5 (30... Rxf5 31. f3 Rf8 32. h4 $16) 31. f3 $14) ({Roiz,M: 'The alternative wouldn't change the unfavourable route of the game:'} 29... Rxf5 30. f3 $14 Rf8 31. h4 Qc8 32. Rc6 $16) 30. Ra5 $1 {Roiz,M: 'The rook penetrates into the opponent's camp with great effect.'} Kh8 (30... e4 31. Rb5 Qe8 32. Rb7+) ({Or} 30... Qe8 31. Rb5) 31. Rb5 Qe8 (31... Qa8 32. Rb7) 32. Rb7 {Roiz,M: 'The Bc5 protects the pawns well, but it cannot join the defence. Therefore, Black's king is in big danger!'} e4 {Roiz,M: 'Alexander is desperately trying to activate his pieces, but this move exposes the long diagonal.'} (32... Qg6 $5 33. Rc7 e4 34. Qb7 h5 35. Rc8 Rxc8 36. Qxc8+ Kh7 37. Be6 Kg7 38. Bxf5 Qf7 $16 {Black would lose a pawn, but swapping the rooks is a definite achievement.}) 33. Qd1 $1 {I am proud to find the strongest move and a nice trick which made me 2700! :)} f4 $2 {Roiz,M: 'A decisive blunder.'} ({Roiz,M: 'Black has to sit and wait:'} 33... Qg6 34. Bd5 Qf6 (34... Qh6 35. h4 Qg6 {it's hard for White to make any progress in the middlegame, whereas after} 36. Qa1+ Qf6 37. Qxf6+ Rxf6 38. f3 $16 {The limited material balance leaves Black some drawing chances.}) 35. h4 $16 {White keeps the pressure.}) 34. Rb8 {Roiz,M: '!!' Roiz,M: 'A simple, but very beautiful final touch.'} f3+ (34... Qxb8 35. Qa1+) 35. Kh1 {I was very happy to win this game and also crossing 2700! It's not a big deal of course, but it did give me a very nice feeling :)} 1-0


