{During my preparations for the game, I noticed that Yu played only Nimzo and Ragozin against 1.d4 and he had excellent preparation and results with them.} 1. d4 {Paunovic,Dragan Paunovic,Dragan} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 {So Nimzo it is!} d5 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 c5 8. dxc5 g5 (8... Be6 {was played by Yu on a couple of occasions.}) 9. Bg3 Ne4 10. e3 Qa5 11. Be5 {Although it was played by Kasparov against Short in 1993, this is a comparitively rare line nowadays.} O-O 12. Bd3 Nc6 13. Bxe4 Nxe5 14. Bxd5 Bf5 {The most direct.} (14... Bg4 {Paunovic,Dragan: '- 59/(593)' was Short's choice against Kasparov in their WCh match. He equalised easily in the game, though the position is still quite rich.}) 15. Qxf5 {Paunovic,Dragan: 'N' 'N'} (15. e4 {Paunovic,Dragan}) 15... Bxc3+ 16. Kf1 Rfd8 $1 {Played instantly by Yu. I was out of my book after this natural move. Engines don't show this move in the beginning and this came as a nasty surprise.} (16... Bxb2 {Paunovic,Dragan} 17. Rd1 Rfd8 18. Qc2 Qb5+ 19. Ne2 Rac8 20. Qb3 Qxb3 21. Bxb3 Rxd1+ 22. Bxd1 Rd8 23. Bb3 Nd3 24. c6 bxc6 25. g4 $11) 17. Rd1 {Played after a long 45 minute think. After losing the opening battle I was hoping to find the most stubborn defence. It wasn't easy to calculate the random lines in the position as Black clearly has the initiative and White's position looks very dangerous.} (17. Bxf7+ Nxf7 18. bxc3 Qb5+ (18... Qxc3 {Paunovic,Dragan} 19. Re1 Qc4+ 20. Ne2 Rd2 $44) 19. Ne2 Rd2 20. Re1 Rad8 {The engine's initial first line looks just hopeless for White!}) (17. e4 Bxb2 18. Re1 Qd2 19. Bb3 Qd3+ 20. Re2 {was one of the 'scary' ways to play the game.}) 17... Qxc5 $1 (17... Qxa2 {is an attractive looking move, but probably not the best.} 18. Qe4 $1 (18. e4 Qc4+ (18... Qxb2 19. Ne2) 19. Ne2 Bxb2 $36) (18. Bxa2 $4 Rxd1+ 19. Ke2 Re1#) 18... Qxb2 19. Ne2 {and White has untangled himself}) 18. e4 (18. Bxf7+ Kg7 19. Rxd8 Rxd8 20. bxc3 Rd1+ 21. Ke2 Rc1 {This is one of the positions where engines calculate & display the usual 0.00. But for human beings it seems impossible to enter such lines.} 22. c4 {Paunovic,Dragan} Rxc4 (22... Qa5 23. Nf3 Qxa2+ 24. Nd2 Rxh1 25. Qxe5+ Kxf7 26. Qd5+ Kg6 27. Qxb7 $14) 23. Bxc4 Qxc4+ 24. Kd1 Qd5+ 25. Kc2 Qc4+ $11) (18. Qe4 {is relatively the best way to play} Qb5+ 19. Ne2 Bxb2 20. g4) 18... Qc4+ {Played instantly and it is just too pretty!} (18... Qb5+ 19. Ne2 Bxb2 20. g4) 19. Ne2 (19. Bxc4 Rxd1+ 20. Ke2 Re1#) 19... Bxb2 20. g4 $6 {Paunovic,Dragan: '?' '?' I was already down to 45 minutes and I couldn't see a very clear way to defend against the annoying threat of ...c2. Here White has to play a series of accurate moves to equalise.} (20. Qh3 $142 $1 {Paunovic,Dragan: '!' '!'} Kg7 21. Qb3 $1 {Computer geometry :)} Qxb3 22. axb3 $11) 20... Qc2 21. Re1 {Paunovic,Dragan: 'Diagram [#]'} Rxd5 $1 22. exd5 Nd3 23. Kg2 Nxe1+ 24. Rxe1 Qd2 (24... Qxf5 25. gxf5 Re8 26. Kf1 b6 {Although Black is slightly better I think White has decent chances to put up tough resistance.}) 25. Kf1 (25. Qb1 Qxd5+) 25... Re8 {Paunovic,Dragan: '' '' White's pieces are completely stuck. I played my next moves fast as I didn't see many nice options :).} 26. Qd7 (26. Qf3 {I didn't like this passive defence. Black can slowly improve his position while White has no clear plan.} a5) 26... Kf8 $1 (26... Re5 27. Qxb7 $11 {Black can't play ...c3 because of the c8 check.} (27. d6 Qd5 $19)) 27. Qb5 {Although the position looks visually bad I didn't see a clear way for Black to increase the pressure.} Ba3 $1 {I was always thinking about  moves on the a1-h8 diagonal and missed this simple move.} (27... a6 28. Qb3 b5 (28... Bg7 29. a4) (28... Bf6) 29. d6 $132 {and White can hope to create some practical problems for Black.}) 28. Qc4 $1 {Trying to exchange s with ...d4 or ...c3.} (28. h3 b6 $19 {with ...b4 and ...c5 coming next, White's position looks hopeless.}) 28... Re5 29. Qd4 (29. Qc8+ Kg7 30. Qc3 Qxc3 31. Nxc3 Rxe1+ 32. Kxe1 Bb4 33. Kd2 Kf6 34. Kd3 Ke5 $17) 29... Qxd4 30. Nxd4 Rxd5 31. Nf5 {I was very happy to get my  to f5. At least White doesn't have to suffer passively now.} h5 (31... Rd2 32. Re2) 32. Ne3 {I played this instantly! Instead h3 would maintain the  on f5 but without the h-pawns White would lose slowly.} (32. h3 hxg4 33. hxg4 f6 34. Re3 Ra5 35. Rh3 Bc5 $17) 32... Re5 $5 (32... Rd2 {Paunovic,Dragan: '!?' '!?' I was more scared of this move} 33. gxh5 Rxa2 34. h6 $1 (34. Ng4 Bb2 $1) (34. Kg2 {Paunovic,Dragan} Bc5 $17) 34... Bc5 (34... Kg8 35. Ng4) 35. h4 $1 {A very nice resource! The point is to take away the option of ...xh2 after the exchange on e3.} (35. Ng4 Bd4 36. Re4 Ra4 $1 $17) (35. Rd1 Bxe3 36. fxe3 Rxh2 $19) 35... gxh4 36. Rd1 Kg8 37. Ng4 {and the position is still quite messy and White has decent activity for a draw.}) 33. gxh5 (33. Rb1 $5 Bc5 $1 (33... b5 34. gxh5 Kg7 35. Rd1) 34. Rxb7 (34. gxh5 Bxe3 35. fxe3 b6) 34... Bxe3 35. fxe3 hxg4 36. Rxa7 Rxe3 {Sooner or later White will exchange the a-pawn for the g-pawn. Although not easy maybe White can hold that ending?}) 33... Bc5 34. Rc1 $1 {This looked like the best practical try.} (34. Ng4 Rxe1+ 35. Kxe1 Kg7 {looks lost for White as after d4-f5 White will lose the h-pawn and with it the game.}) 34... Bxe3 35. fxe3 Rxe3 36. Rc8+ $5 {Generally it is not a good idea to activate the black king by force but here I had a concrete idea in mind which required the king to be on g7.} (36. h6 Rh3 37. Rc8+ Ke7 38. Rc7+ Ke8 39. Rxb7 Rxh6 (39... Rxh2 40. Rxa7 Rxh6 41. Kg2) 40. Rxa7 Rxh2) (36. Rc5 f6 {Here we see why it was important to provoke the king into going to g7.}) 36... Kg7 (36... Re8 37. Rc5 f6 38. h6) 37. Rc7 Rh3 {Paunovic,Dragan: '?' '?'} (37... Ra3 $5 {Paunovic,Dragan: '!' '!' was possibly the best try for Black.} 38. Rxb7 Rxa2 39. h6+ Kg6 (39... Kxh6 40. Rxf7 a5 41. h3 $1 (41. Ra7 {Paunovic,Dragan} g4 $19) 41... Kg6 (41... a4 42. Rc7 a3 43. Rc3 Kg6 44. Kg1 Kf5 45. Rb3 Ke4 46. Rg3 Kd4 47. h4 (47. Rf3) 47... gxh4 48. Rh3) 42. Rc7 a4 (42... Kf5 43. Rc4 a4 44. Rb4) 43. Rc4 {and White has a defensive fortress.}) 40. Kg1 Ra4 41. h7 Rh4 42. Rxa7 Rxh7 43. Kg2 f5 44. Ra6+ Kh5 45. h3 Rh6 46. Ra5 Rf6 47. Ra4 {This looks lost but the black king is not able to proceed further.}) 38. Kg2 Rxh5 39. Rxb7 a6 40. Rc7 (40. Ra7 {was my original intention but I chose the game continuation since it seemed more clear.} Rh6 41. a4 Re6 42. a5 Kg6 43. h4 $1 {A nice concept!} gxh4 44. Kh3 f6 45. Kxh4 Kf5 46. Kg3 Ke4 47. Rb7 Re5 48. Rb6 Rxa5 49. Rxf6 $11) 40... Rh4 {After this it is quite easy.} 41. Rc5 Ra4 42. Rxg5+ Kh6 43. Rf5 $5 {The point is to get h4-h5 with a check!} (43. Rc5 Rxa2+ 44. Kg3 a5 45. h4 a4 46. Rc7 Kg7 47. h5 a3 48. h6+) 43... Rxa2+ 44. Kg3 Kg6 45. Rc5 a5 46. h4 Ra1 47. h5+ {This was why f5 was included.} Kg7 48. Rf5 a4 49. h6+ Kxh6 50. Rxf7 Kg6 51. Rf8 {This looked like the easiest, keeping the king at bay.} (51. Ra7 Kf5 52. Kg2 Ke4 53. Rg7 Kd3 54. Rg4 {It is important to attack the passed pawn from the rank and then reach another theoretical draw.}) 51... Kg5 52. Rf3 Re1 53. Kf2 Re4 54. Rc3 Kf5 55. Rc5+ Ke6 56. Ra5 Kd6 57. Kf3 Rh4 58. Ke3 Kc6 59. Kd3 Kb6 60. Ra8 Kb5 {Although the opening was a total disaster, I was quite happy with the defence especially in the rook endgame.} 1/2-1/2


